[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "Introduction to Ferguson's Cannon"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to Ferguson's Cannon"]
[Black "Ferguson's Cannon: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 $5 { Greetings! My name is Gus Logozar (Ferguson being my alias) and it is with great pleasure that I present to you my latest project: Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation! You're probably wondering about the genesis of the title. I have designated it as such because there is no object more fitting to blast away one's opponents with than that of a cannon! Imagine an 18-lb cast iron ball barreling with lethal force straight toward the enemy, causing mayhem, destruction, and anguish all in its wake! That is how I envision the bold ...d5 advance. Black attempts to blast open the center, to occasion chaos and desolation, and to bewilder the opponent all at once! Moreover, there's no opening I would love to blast away more than that of the accursed Rossolimo, and I surmise many of you would sympathize with this sentiment! I therefore deem the appellation assigned to this opening a suitable one. I want to note that at the time of writing there is no substantive coverage of this response anywhere apart from this course! I searched far and wide and could only find two books which mentioned 3...d5. The first, The Modernized Antisicilians by Haria Ravi dismisses it rather quickly, recommending the engine's preference, 4.Nc3. Ravi analyzes a variety of continuations, but strangely neglects to consider Black's best response. As will be demonstrated later in this course, Black can induce complications which offer excellent practical chances. In addition, I was unable to find any games where White found the critical continuation. The final resource I could find which attends to 3...d5 is Rossolimo and Friends A Complete Repertoire vs. The Sicilian by Alexei Kornev. Kornev too issues a brief treatment of the move and subsequently fails to consider Black's best continuation in the line he considers. Needless to say, we will not be responding as these authors suggest Black should. Over the last two years I have been experimenting at the advanced level (2150-2350 online) with 3...d5, both in OTB and online games across all time controls. My results are surprisingly impressive: roughly 60% win / 10% draw / 30% loss — not bad at all considering I'm playing with the black pieces! Similar results are shared by the few whom I have shared my analysis with prior to the release of this course, some impressively scoring 75%+! Such is a testament to the surprising efficacy of the theory you will soon become acquainted with. Even though almost any decent-looking move is perfectly viable as a response, the sheer rarity of 3...d5 alienates White from the comforts afforded by the familiarity of positions in mainline theory, depriving them of their preparation and forcing them to improvise right from move four! Such has a tendency to take a psychological toll and often results in inaccuracy and loss of time, making 3...d5 a deadly surprise weapon. But what exactly does ...d5 accomplish? Concretely, ...d5 accomplishes a number of things. Firstly, many lines have opened up. Black's queen can navigate to the center should d5 be captured. Our bishop now has immediate access to d7 or g4 should the circumstances demand relocation. With the center potentially opening up, Black increases the chance that the game will evolve into a dynamic attacking middlegame, rather than a slow positional one. Second, ...d5 generates tension in the center. White now has a number of questions to answer. How will they address the threat on e4? Should they capture c6 immediately? Should they instead capture d5? Should they hold the tension? Or advance to e5? So many avenues have been opened up for creative and exciting play! This begs the question; what kind of game is Black in pursuit of here? The Rossolimo is widely detested by proponents of the 2...Nc6 Sicilian, and for good reason. I hope I don't merely speak for myself when I say that I play 2...Nc6 chiefly because it results in imbalanced and sharp dynamic middlegames! (e.g. Sveshnikov, Dragon, Dirty Harry, etc.) This is one reason as to why 3.Bb5 is so loathed by 2...Nc6 Sicilian players. The Rossolimo stomps on our dreams for dynamism, and often casts the game into a dry positional hell! Moreover, when the positions in the main lines take a sharp turn, White tends to be the primary instigator. Generally, it's just not a particularly enjoyable opening to oppose and it certainly does no justice to those of us with predilections for aggressive attacking chess! Therefore, my intention in developing this repertoire is to try to turn the tables! The strategic outlook I have adopted for the majority of this course is one of relentless aggression, one which prioritizes the pursuit of dangerous and chaotic complications, and one which often neglects to respect those dogmatic opening principles history has 'proven' to be worthy of the consideration of all serious players. However, this is not to say that Black will be making moves without due regard to reason. Black's ideas are mostly well-motivated, even if the reasons behind certain moves are not apparent at first glance. I have invested great efforts into understanding the intricacies of the bizarre positions Black stumbles into and hope to divine this understanding to my curious readers. However, I must forewarn that I cannot guarantee that Black will of necessity acquire a dynamic game after 3...d5. There are multiple situations where simplification into an endgame arrives quicker than expected and a few rare instances in which a dry, positional middlegame is too tricky to avoid, but for the most part I have pursued explosive complications whenever available. On another note, because the terrain is almost entirely uncharted, and because the ensuing complications are both expansive and difficult to navigate without proper acquaintance with the common structures and themes, I found myself conflicted about the scope of this course. While it is my wish to be as comprehensive as I can, I understand that no sensible person (apart from myself, of course!) would endeavor to commit to memory 400-ish variations of a potentially dubious opening. Therefore, I have fought to compress my analysis into a reasonably sized package and have managed to reduce the quantity of core drillable variations to around 200. I realize that for the casual student even this might be excessive, and so to accommodate this perspective I have configured the Quickstarter (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) chapter in such a way as to include coverage of only the most popular continuations. The content in this chapter should be sufficient to equip my readers to meet the responses they will encounter most of the time, and minimally will serve as a substantive introduction into the strategic themes we should be familiar with if we are to play this opening. Finally, before proceeding I want to recommend that students of this course pay attention to the detailed notes in each variation. I have packed many of the lines full of clickable subvariations outlining tactics and other deviations not included in the core drillables. If I have omitted a noteworthy continuation from the core drillables, there's a good chance it's included somewhere in the annotations. Moreover, the tactics included in the tactics chapter are primarily taken from these notes, so paying attention early on will equip you to handle this later chapter. I hope you enjoy what I have prepared! } * 

