3... d5 { I want to add a short notice here to temper my readers' expectations. 3...d5!? is dubious! Play this at your own risk! There are a number of lines following 3...d5 in which White is able to get the better end of the practical stick. In fact, almost every sensible looking response starting from 3...d5 is more than playable for White. Granted, most of these unfortunate lines are almost never played -- or at least analysis of the databases indicate as much at the time of writing (most especially those advantageous lines for White) -- and it seems that more often than not White errs rather quickly, but we should not therefore ignore the possibility of such unfortunate continuations simply because no one plays them. From my experience, nobody yet has managed to identify the best path through our confounding, dynamic labyrinth live at the board; in my hundreds of games experimenting with this opening, I have yet to encounter an opponent willing to pursue the most critical lines. However, while we might be justified in inferring that our opponents are unlikely to play the most critical continuations, we must be comfortable with the possibility of playing at a disadvantage straight out of the opening. Therefore, if we are to welcome the Ferguson's Cannon variation into our arsenal of openings, we must embrace the disposition of the player willing to take serious risks! Since there is more room for error in faster time controls, this repertoire is primarily suited for blitz and other faster time controls. I have employed this repertoire with moderate success in rapid and classical formats, as have a number of players (even up to the master level) who have equipped themselves with my analysis. However, I expect the risk involved extends beyond what most competitive players would be comfortable with. That should be it for preliminaries. Let's get to the chess! } * 

