1... d5 { The Essentials Welcome. The variations included in this chapter are duplicates of others found throughout the course and were selected mostly based on the frequency with which each respective continuation is played, per the lichess database. For the most part I have set the rating range of the database to 2000+, however I have also examined the frequency of continuations at the range of 1600+ to get a more comprehensive picture of what is being played. There is almost no data on this opening at the master level, so I have ignored what little is currently there. This course is not created specifically for masters anyway, but more so for club players and those at the advanced and expert level. As such, the variations selected for this chapter have been expressly done so for those interested only in memorizing the 'practical' portion of the course and will suffice for those interested in equipping themselves merely for those more frequent responses. Since the first five chapters cover those responses played 80-90% of the time, almost all of the sidelines will be omitted from this chapter. Of course, I do encourage exploration of the entire course. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "Quickstarter: 4.exd5 with 6.Qe2 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: 4.exd5 with 6.Qe2 #1"]
[Black "Quickstarter"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bc8d7,Bd8d5][%csl Re4]Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { [%cal Bd5c6][%csl Rc6]Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { [%cal Be6c6][%csl Rc6,Re1]Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Rc5]Taking on d4 would just improve White's pieces, so Black should instead focus on development. If White accepts the gambit, Black's initiative will more than compensate for the pawn. In most continuations White will be forced to return it anyway. } 9. dxc5 e6 10. Be3 { This is the most common continuation. Naturally, White would like to hold on to the pawn. However, now we have a new target to harass. } 10... Nd5 { [%csl Re3,Rc5][%cal Bd5e3,Bd5b4,Bb4c2][%csl Rc2]The knight leaps ahead! White would be wise to simply return the pawn and enjoy equality while it lasts. Endeavoring to defend c5 will only make White's position more difficult. } 11. Bxc6 { Making Bd4 possible. Retreating his dark squared bishop instead allows the immediate ...Bxc5, and most other moves allow ..Nxe3 along with a subsequent capture on c5. } 11... Bxc6 12. Bd4 $6 f6 $1 { The materialist will suffer for their greed! ...e5 is incoming and White's bishop simply has no good square to retreat to! This ...f6-e5 sequence is thematic. } 13. O-O-O $5 e5 $1 14. Rhe1 { White has nothing better than to sacrifice the bishop! If White retreats the bishop Black will simply capture it and then eliminate c5, acquiring a decisive advantage. Note also that moving the rook here is a very computer-ish move, meaning you can be confident that most of the time Black will emerge with a sizable advantage immediately after 13...e5. It's still good to come prepared though. If } ( 14. c4 $2 { Black can respond with } 14... Nb4 $146 15. a3 ( 15. Be3 { Nxc5! A similar idea appears in an earlier variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Here White is similarly much worse. } ) 15... Na6 $146 { and will take c5. } ) 14... exd4 { The more ambitious move. White actually has compensation for the piece if they can find a sequence of only-moves. This we will discuss shortly, but first it's worth mentioning that } ( 14... O-O-O { is a simple, yet effective alternative for those who wish to avoid the complicated mess which follows ...exd4. } 15. c4 { is White's only move, where after } 15... Nb4 $146 16. a3 Na6 $146 17. Bc3 Bxc5 { Black enjoys a small advantage. } ) 15. Nexd4+ $7 Kf7 16. Nxc6 $7 { Once again, the only move. If White tries something like } ( 16. c4 $2 { instead Black has time to consolidate. } 16... Ne7 $146 17. Nxc6 $146 Nxc6 $146 18. Rd7+ Be7 $19 { White has seventh-rank activity, but it's worth much less than the piece they lost. } ) 16... bxc6 17. c4 $7 { White needs to get a rook to the seventh rank to secure any compensation for the sacrifice. } 17... Nf4 18. Rd7+ $7 Kg6 $5 { ...Kg8 works too, but clogs up the back rank. We'll need to connect our rooks quickly in the event that White attempts to mobilize a queenside pawn storm. } 19. Rd4 $1 { Nearly forced. If instead } ( 19. Re4 $2 { Black wins with } 19... Kf5 $3 { hitting the rook with tempo } 20. Rdd4 g5 { and is in time to deal with all of White's threats. } ) ( 19. b4 $2 { can be met with } 19... a5 20. a3 axb4 21. axb4 { and here } 21... Nxg2 $2 $146 { actually works. These lines are all somewhat complex, but being a piece up Black has at least a practical advantage in each case. } ) 19... Kf5 20. g3 { Careful to avoid the perpetual after } ( 20. g4+ $2 Kxg4 21. Rg1+ Kxf3 22. Rg3+ ( 22. Rxf4+ { Bxc5-+ } ) 22... Ke2 $3 { if 22...Kxf2 White takes f4 with check and has a perpetual. } ) 20... Nh3 $15 { Careful not to blunder mate with } ( 20... Ng6 $2 $146 21. g4# { In any case, White needs to find all of this and still can only maintain the balance if they find 21... Ng6 21.b4!? or 21.Rh4! Nxf2 22.Rf4! Kg6 23.Nh4+ Kf7 24.Rxf2 Bxc5 , and even still Black is ever so slightly better. } ) * 

