1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bc8d7,Bd8d5][%csl Re4]Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { [%cal Bd5c6][%csl Rc6]Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { [%cal Be6c6][%csl Rc6,Re1]Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Kxe2 { [%cal Bh1d1,Bd2d4,Rc8d7,Ra7a6]White intends on pushing d4 after centralizing their pieces. Because this is somewhat slow, the immediate ...Bd7 followed by ...a6 comes with no resistance. } 7... Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. Rd1 a6 9. Bxc6 { Retreating to d3 would leave White's piece coordination in a dismal state, therefore the bishop must be exchanged. } 9... Bxc6 10. d4 cxd4 11. Rxd4 ( 11. Nxd4 $146 { drops a pawn with . } ) 11... f6 $1 { [%cal Be7e5]} 12. Nd5 $5 e5 $1 { Once again, this idea proves to furnish Black the advantage! It really doesn't matter that White is ahead in development. Once ...e5 arrives, Black's central control will make it difficult for White to navigate the position. White's tactical aspirations don't even work here: } 13. Nc7+ $2 $146 Kf7 14. Nxa8 $146 exd4 15. Nb6 $146 Bc5 16. Nc4 $146 Ne7 $146 { Black is ahead on development and has an excellent position. } * 

