 [%cal Bf5c2][%csl Rc2]This stops White's Nxe5 ideas. } 14. d3 ( 14. Nxe5 $2 $146 Bxc2 { Black would like White to play d3, obstructing the bishops vision on the queenside. Then we can redirect our bishop to e6 and force an exchange on c4, doubling White's pawns and giving Black great chances in the center. } ) ( 14. Bf1 { and Black should probably repeat with } 14... Bg4 15. Be2 Bf5 { etc. } ) 14... Be6 { [%cal Be6c4][%csl Rc4]White has no choice but to allow the exchange. } 15. Bf3 ( 15. Nd2 $2 $146 { allows } 15... Bb4 { tying down all of White's forces. } ) ( 15. b3 { might be seen too, but this weakens the dark squares. } 15... Bb4 16. Bd2 Nd5 $146 17. Bxb4 Nxb4 $146 18. Bf3 Bxc4 19. bxc4 a5 20. Qe2 f6 { Black can castle queenside if need be and has the preferable structure. } ) 15... Bxc4 16. dxc4 Bb4 { [%csl Bc4,Ba4,Rb4][%cal Bb4e1,Bd2d3]This is a move worth remembering in these variations. With both the a and former d pawns advanced, the b4 square is a most auspicious location to position our bishop. } 17. Bd2 Bxd2 18. Qxd2 O-O $13 { [%cal Bf8e8,Ba8d8][%csl Rc4]Stockfish gives this as dead equal, but Black has the center and White is the one with an immediate weakness. Attending to our central majority demands a certain level of caution, so I prefer Black. } * 

