Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 { Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. O-O ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Re1 { [%cal Be1e6,Be2b5]Re1 is critical and is to be expected as the most popular continuation. } 8... Qb6 $1 9. Bc4 { [%cal Bd2d3,Ye7e6,Yf8e7,Yc8d7]White relocates their bishop to a more favorable square before committing to the center with d3. Black's treatment of the position largely remains unchanged. We will continue with ...e6 and ...Be7. } 9... e6 { The solid move. A risky alternative worth mentioning is } ( 9... Bf5 $2 { I'm not so sure the bishop belongs on the kingside, but it's worth considering. I think it would be better placed somewhere on the a8-h1 diagonal, so I typically like to maneuver it to c6 with ...Bd7-c6. Anyways, after ...Bf5 Black's idea is to block White's bishop off with ...e6 and then build pressure on f3 with ...Bg4. However, the problem is that White has } 10. Nxd4 $146 cxd4 11. Qf3 { and suddenly Black's position begins to look a bit uncomfortable. } 11... Bg4 12. Bb5+ { Black is forced to move the king. } 12... Kd8 13. Qd3 { White looks to be a bit better. } ) 10. d3 Be7 11. Bg5 ( 11. Bf4 { might also be encountered, fighting for control of e5. } 11... O-O 12. Be5 Nc6 $146 { Black will exchange on e5 if permitted and continue by playing on the queenside, eventually making use of the a1-h8 and h2-b8 diagonals. } ) 11... h6 { We should wait to see if White intends on taking the knight before deciding which way to castle. } 12. Bxf6 { If } ( 12. Bh4 { Black can continue to target the bishop } 12... Nf5 $146 13. Bg3 Nxg3 $146 14. hxg3 O-O { with a solid middlegame ahead. } ) 12... gxf6 { [%cal Rc8d7,Be8c8,Ba8d8,Ye8f8,Bb6b2][%csl Rb2][%cal Rh8g8,Rh6h5,Rh5h4,Rh4h3]Black now can lob Harry down the board and aim for complications along the semi-open g-file. Black may castle to the queenside, or the king might remain in the center depending on the demands of the forthcoming positions. } 13. Rb1 { Covering b2, but this is rather slow. Alternatively, White might try to immediately clarify the position with } ( 13. Nxd4 $146 cxd4 14. Ne2 $146 h5 $2 15. c3 dxc3 16. bxc3 h4 { White has eventual ideas of sacrificing on e6. Both sides need to be careful. These middlegames can get extremely sharp. } ) 13... h5 { [%cal Bh5h4,Bh4h3,Bh6h5]Black wastes no time attempting to establish that White's king is the more vulnerable monarch. } 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Ne4 Bd7 16. c3 O-O-O $17 { [%cal Rd7c6,Rc6g2][%csl Re4,Rg2][%cal Rf6f5,Bd8g8,Bc8b8,Bh5h4]Black's attacking prospects look promising. Meanwhile, even though we have castled queenside, White doesn't have a direct way of counterattacking without making concessions. A game might proceed with } 17. Qc1 $2 { hoping for counterplay along the c-file, but Black can simply step aside } 17... Kb8 18. Qf4+ e5 19. Qf3 Bg4 20. Qg3 Qc7 { disallowing any tricks with the pin. } 21. h3 f5 22. hxg4 hxg4 $2 { Black sacrifices the bishop for a monstrous pawn storm! } 23. Nd2 $2 $146 Bd6 { and White has permission to resign. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "Quickstarter: 4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 9.d3 / 10.Ne5"]
