1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 { Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. O-O ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Re1 { [%cal Be1e6,Be2b5]Re1 is critical and is to be expected as the most popular continuation. } 8... Qb6 $1 9. d3 { d3 is the simplest and perhaps the most natural move to continue with. I see this often in my blitz games. } 9... e6 10. Ne5 { [%csl Bf7,Bg7,Bh7,Be6,Re5,Yd4]Ne5 is a common idea in some openings which result in similar kingside pawn structures. Black has control of d4 here though, so White must maintain the knight's outpost by some other means than through the support of their d-pawn. } 10... Qc7 { Ne5 can often be met with ...Qc7 and ...Bd6. } 11. Bf1 { [%cal Be1e5][%csl Yd4,Yf6,Bh5,Bg4,Bf3,Be2,Re5][%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2]White retreats the bishop and protects the knight, intending the eventual g3 and Bg2 to control the lovely h1-a8 diagonal. Another way to defend the knight might be: } ( 11. Bf3 Bd6 12. Bf4 { Black can simply castle here, but } 12... h5 $2 { is more to my tastes. } 13. h3 $2 g5 { White needs to tread with caution. } 14. Bg3 g4 15. hxg4 hxg4 16. Bxg4 b6 17. Bf3 Bb7 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. a4 O-O-O { with another sharp middlegame ahead. } ) 11... Bd6 12. Bf4 { Also worth mentioning is } ( 12. f4 $2 { but in my view this idea doesn't quite pair so well with the Bf1 \+ g3 \+ Bg2 maneuver, which was the point of dropping the bishop back to f1. For instance: } 12... O-O 13. g3 $2 b6 14. Bg2 Bb7 { Leela thinks that White should just drop the knight back to f3 and that Black is better regardless. } ) 12... h5 $5 { [%cal Bh5h4][%csl Rg3][%cal Bh8h5,Bh5e5][%csl Re5][%cal Yg7g5,Gb7b6,Gc8b7]Black simply wants to annihilate White's kingside. If White plays g3 we have a hook. If White plays h3 we have a different hook. Defending is not going to be easy. } 13. h3 { The computer at first confusedly praises the bold Alternatively, After giving it some thought, the engine favors the curious looking } ( 13. g3 $2 { but after } 13... h4 14. Bg2 Kf8 { it is evident that its initial appraisal was mistaken. Black can bring the knight to h5 and has good chances playing against White's tenderized kingside. } ) ( 13. h4 $2 { gives Black a pleasant advantage: } 13... b6 14. a4 a6 15. g3 { Fortunately for us, this weakening move is best for White. It wouldn't be wise to allow our bishop to control so much of the board unopposed. } 15... Bb7 16. Bg2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 O-O { White's kingside is weak and they don't really have a way to improve their position. } ) ( 13. a4 { , which voluntarily walks right into } 13... Ng4 $146 { Only one move saves White here. } 14. Nd5 $3 $146 Qb8 15. Bg3 f5 16. c3 O-O $2 { Frankly, this entire sequence is a bit ridiculous. Few would be able to extract equality from the mess without assistance from a computer. } ) 13... b6 { [%cal Bc8b7]} 14. Bg3 { [%cal Bf2f4]One unlikely but notable idea is } ( 14. Nb1 $146 { and after } 14... Nd5 $146 15. Bh2 f6 16. c3 Bxe5 17. Bxe5 fxe5 18. cxd4 exd4 { Black has a slight edge. } ) 14... Bb7 15. f4 g5 $3 { [%cal Bc7g3][%csl Re5,Rg3][%cal Bf6d7]Black has a dangerous initiative. A game might continue with } 16. fxg5 Nd7 $146 17. Nxd7 $146 Bxg3 18. Nf6+ $146 Kf8 { Black is threatening ...Bxe1 Qxe1 ...Nxc2, so } 19. Rc1 Bf3 $2 $3 { White is getting slaughtered. See the tactics chapter (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to see how Black converts. } * 

