ons White has numerous opportunities to make losing blunders, which will all be covered shortly. An alternative worth considering which keeps the queens on the board, at least temporarily, is ...Qf5. } 7. Nxd5 ( 7. Qxf3 $2 { is a mistake on pain of } 7... Qxf3 8. gxf3 Rc8 { , where White's structure will suffer and Black's will not. } ) 7... Bxd1 8. Nc7+ $2 { This is actually a risky decision which will most probably furnish the advantage to Black. White might instead benefit from his lead in development after the simple } ( 8. Rxd1 { , however Black seems to be performing quite well in this line after } 8... Rc8 { , ...e6, ...a6 etc. } ) 8... Kd7 { [%cal Bd7c6,Bb5c6][%csl Rc6]We defend our knight and prepare for the endgame by centralizing the king. } 9. Nxa8 Bh5 { Our bishop will actually be well placed here on the edge of the board. White will inevitably attempt to open the center to get at our king with d4, but our bishop will make it difficult for the White rooks to occupy the central d-file. Please be aware that } ( 9... Bxc2 { is a losing mistake after } 10. d3 { where our bishop is trapped. } ) 10. d3 $4 e6 11. Bf4 Bd6 $19 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be7c6,Bh8a8]This is just lost for White, as the knight will fall and Black's minor pieces will dominate the board. } * 

