1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension rings high! Chaos and confusion abounds! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White almost assuredly will be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. exd5 $2 { The frequency with which this mistake is played even at the advanced level is absolutely astounding. I do not understand why anyone would elect to corrupt Black's pawn structure only to immediately repair it a single move later. Perhaps the pressures of being confronted by an unfamiliar opening take a psychological toll. Needless to say, Black almost always gets the better end of this exchange. } 5... cxd5 { Black has the bishops and a head start on the fight for the center. } 6. d4 { White immediately strikes in the center. They do have a small lead in development, so this makes some sense. } 6... cxd4 { Eliminating White's remaining central pawn. } 7. Qxd4 f6 $1 { [%cal Ge7e5]Aiming for the typical ...e5! } 8. Nc3 { White targets d5. } ( 8. c4 $2 { is another way White might try to challenge Black's center. After c4 Black has two ways to press for an advantage. } 8... Bb7 $2 { is the simplest way. Black invites White to capture on d5 and will play ...e5 after the dust has settled. } 9. cxd5 Qxd5 10. Qxd5 Bxd5 11. Nc3 $146 Bc6 12. O-O e5 $15 { Black has a quiet advantage. We have the bishop pair and superior central control. A simple, yet comfortable position. } ) 8... Bb7 9. O-O ( 9. Qa4+ { Don't fear the queen trade. White get's nothing out of simplifying the position. } 9... Qd7 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 11. Be3 e5 12. O-O-O Ke6 13. Nb5 $146 Kf7 $19 ) 9... e5 $1 10. Qa4+ $4 { The most common response. Black can now offer an invitation to simplify into the endgame. } ( 10. Re1 { would be more accurate, but the evaluation only budges if White is able to detect that they must subsequently sacrifice on e5. This idea is very easy to miss when playing speed chess, which is why nobody has found it as of yet. } 10... Ne7 $146 { Legitimizing the threat on White's queen. } 11. Nxe5 $146 fxe5 12. Rxe5 Kf7 { White has good play in the center, so it's time for our king to leave! } 13. Qf4+ Kg8 $19 { The king escapes to g8. White is lost. } ) 10... Qd7 $1 11. Qxd7+ { White has nothing better. } ( 11. Qb3 $2 { Keeping the queens on the board would be much too risky. } 11... d4 12. Ne2 $146 Bd6 13. Ng3 $146 Ne7 $146 14. Re1 Bd5 $19 { White is clearly lost here. } ) 11... Kxd7 12. Rd1 { A natural response. White goes after d5. } 12... Ke6 13. Nb5 Kf7 $19 { White's threats have all been defused. With the center and the bishops, Black has a decisive advantage. } * 

