1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension rings high! Chaos and confusion abounds! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White almost assuredly will be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. exd5 $2 { The frequency with which this mistake is played even at the advanced level is absolutely astounding. I do not understand why anyone would elect to corrupt Black's pawn structure only to immediately repair it a single move later. Perhaps the pressures of being confronted by an unfamiliar opening take a psychological toll. Needless to say, Black almost always gets the better end of this exchange. } 5... cxd5 { Black has the bishops and a head start on the fight for the center. } 6. O-O f6 $5 { If White neglects to immediately challenge our center, we can play for ...e5! ...f6 aligns strategically with what I've recommended in previous chapters. I think it best to preserve the continuity. If you would prefer a more conventional approach, ...Nf6 and ...e6 are perfectly legitimate alternatives. } 7. d4 { White anticipates ...e5. This merely delays our central advance. One alternative worth mentioning is } ( 7. Nh4 $2 $146 { This unlikely move should be familiar to us. Similar to this line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), we should be weary of Qh5+ and respond with } 7... g6 { We can play ...Nh6-f7 and ...Bg7 to support the eventual ...e5 push and have a comfortable advantage. } ) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 { Naturally, } ( 8. Qxd4 $2 { is not an option because of } 8... e5 9. Re1 Ne7 $146 10. Qd1 Be6 $19 { White has no compensation for allowing Black to dominate the center. } ) 8... e5 { Black seizes the center! } 9. Nb3 Bb7 { Consolidating our center. We need to be prepared for White to break out with f4. } 10. f4 $1 { This is only move we should be concerned about. Notice that because White has no center pawns left, it is not so easy for them to contest our center. It will get progressively more difficult to do so once Black's forces are properly situated. This is the primary reason why it's important for White to break with f4 immediately; the longer White waits, the worse their chances get. It might be worth discussing an example to illustrate the point. Though a natural improving move, } ( 10. Re1 $2 { won't cut it. } 10... Ne7 $146 11. Nc3 $146 Rc8 12. f4 Ng6 $146 13. fxe5 $2 fxe5 14. Qf3 Be7 15. Bd2 Bf6 $19 { Black's advantage is already decisive, which might be somewhat surprising given that White's moves in this sample line have all been fairly natural. } ) 10... Bd6 { [%cal Gb7h1,Gd6h2]Supporting e5. Our bishops are propitiously pointed toward White's kingside, so any exchanges in the center are likely to benefit us more than White. } 11. fxe5 { What else is there for White to do? It's not easy for White to develop the queenside in a favorable way because of Black's oppressive center. White doesn't have } ( 11. Nc3 $2 $146 { due to } 11... d4 { and other developing moves are slow and enable Black to quickly castle and consolidate the center without issue. } ) 11... Bxe5 { [%cal Be5h2,Be5b2][%csl Rc1]By my lights, this is the preferable way to recapture. Now White's bishop is cemented on c1. } 12. Re1 Ne7 13. N1d2 { [%cal Gd2f3]White's knight is headed to f3. Defense is in order. } 13... O-O 14. Nf3 Nf5 $15 { Setting a trap! White might detect our ruse and proceed instead with the sensible } 15. Nxe5 $2 $146 ( 15. Qd3 { While this does avoid the chaos, Black gets a favorable position after } 15... Qb6+ 16. Kh1 g6 { We have excellent play in the center and strong bishops. There's nothing to complain about here. } ) 15... fxe5 16. Rxe5 $2 { White might be relieved to finally have ruptured Black's center, but the fact is is that Black is already winning! } 16... Qb6+ 17. Kh1 d4 { Black unleashes the bishop. The threat now is ...Nh4. } 18. Bg5 Rae8 19. Rxe8 Rxe8 20. Qd2 h6 $19 { White is busted. ...Nh4 is in the cards again! } * 

