1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing blitz against experts and advanced players. After much analysis and experimentation I have been convinced that 5.e5 is actually rather risky for White. With the center closed, the position is primed for combat on the flanks. Next, Black will play ...Bg4 and ...e6, preparing to meet White's inevitable kingside castling with an aggressive and potentially fatal pawnstorm. } 5... Bg4 { Before we establish a central pawn chain with ...e6 it would be wise to administer this pin. } 6. d3 e6 { Keeping things fresh. Of course, one could plausibly attempt to transpose to the 6.h3 variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) by starting with } ( 6... h5 $2 { too. Probably the most natural continuation will lead directly to that line: } 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 { , etc. Move order differences don't make much of a difference here, so play whatever you're more comfortable with. On another note, 6.d3 allows for an immediate Nbd2. Generally, when we see this idea play out we should forget about our plan to exchange on f3 when hit with h3. In most cases we can still proceed with the standard ...h5 \+ ...g5 pawn storm though, but there are strange continuations which can steer the game in a more positional direction if White accurately plays against our ...g5 push. } ) 7. Nbd2 { [%cal Bd2f3][%csl Rf3][%cal Bh2h3]Preparing h3. White might benefit from recapturing on f3 with a knight in the event of an exchange. Needless to say, White's campaign to improve their pieces is not an effort that we would like to contribute to, and so the incoming h3 will not be met with an exchange. Let's look at a few alternatives in case White doesn't opt for Nbd2. Remember, If White might also try } ( 7. h3 { transposes to 5.e5 with 6.h3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) after } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 h5 $2 ) ( 7. O-O { 7...h4! , making room for the bishop to drop back. Now our knight has the f5 square and we can eventually play for ...g5-g4 as usual. 8.h3 } 7... h5 ( 7... Bh5 8. Re1 Nh6 $146 9. c4 Nf5 $146 10. Qa4 Qd7 11. b3 Be7 12. Ba3 g5 { Black can continue with ...Rg8 and ...g4. } ) 8. Nbd2 $146 { Black has } ) ( 7. Bf4 $2 { , but then Black has } 7... g5 { with tempo. } 8. Bg3 h5 { This is basically the setup we've been pursuing all along. White has just gifted it to Black by playing Bf4. } 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qb8 { Targeting b2 and e5. Black can follow up with ...Ne7-Nf5 and ...Bg7. White will struggle to defend e5. } ) 7... Be7 $5 { [%cal Bh7h5,Rh2h3,Rg4f5,Bg7g5,Bg5g4,Gd2b3,Ga7a5,Ye8d7,Yd8f8,Yf8g7,Be1g1,Bh1f1]Black waits for White to commit to castling before initiating the thematic kingside pawn storm, ...h5 and ...g5-g4. } 8. O-O { If White doesn't castle right away the game might take a more positional turn. For instance, after } ( 8. h3 Bf5 { White no longer needs the knight on d2, so } 9. Nb3 $146 { makes sense. White probably intends on targeting c5. After } 9... a5 10. a4 h5 11. Be3 $2 { Black has to cover c5 with } 11... Qb6 { , and with the queen removed from the d8 square ...g5 has been precluded. Black can continue with ...Bg6 followed by ...Nh6-Nf5 and ...O-O. Black rarely kingside castles in the 5.e5 variations, but it makes sense to do this in slower positions. } ) 8... h5 $1 { [%cal Bg7g5,Gd2b3,Ga7a5,Bg8h6]We should be glad to see White castle. Now we continue with the thematic ...h5 and ...g5. } 9. h3 Bf5 10. b3 g5 $15 { [%cal Bg5g4][%csl Rg4]...g5 is the best against almost all of White's available moves. Our immediate threat is ...g4! Here are a couple ways White might try to continue: } 11. Re1 ( 11. Nh2 $146 { is another possibility, to which we still play } 11... g4 12. hxg4 hxg4 13. Nxg4 $146 Kd7 { Centralizing the king, of course. } 14. Ne3 $146 Nh6 $146 15. Nf3 $146 Qg8 { And White has little hope of defending such a position. As stated before, Black has excellent attacking chances in this 5.e5 variation. } ) 11... g4 12. hxg4 Bxg4 13. c4 Nh6 $146 14. Nf1 $146 { At this point, it's not totally clear what White is supposed to do. } 14... Nf5 $146 15. Ne3 $146 Nxe3 $146 16. Bxe3 d4 17. Bf4 Rg8 { and Black will play ...h4 and ...Kd7 with a strong advantage. } * 

