1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing blitz against experts and advanced players. After much analysis and experimentation I have been convinced that 5.e5 is actually rather risky for White. With the center closed, the position is primed for combat on the flanks. Next, Black will play ...Bg4 and ...e6, preparing to meet White's inevitable kingside castling with an aggressive and potentially fatal pawnstorm. } 5... Bg4 { Before we establish a central pawn chain with ...e6 it would be wise to administer this pin. } 6. O-O { Castling is a sensible choice, but now the king has committed to one side of the board. } 6... e6 7. h3 { The most common move. Let's pause briefly to discuss the most natural alternative before exploring further: 7.d3 Firstly, } ( 7. d3 h5 { will most probably transpose to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), as the most likely encounter is the natural } 8. h3 { , after which we are immediately prompted to capture on f3 with } 8... Bxf3 { Consult the linked variation for more information. There are two more moves to mention in passing after 7... e6 7.d3 h5 , one of which being 8.Nbd2 —Any time we see this move, we typically should abandon our disposition to exchange the bishop on f3 after being prompted to do so by h3, for instance: 8...g5!? 9.h3 Bf5! We keep the bishop and play for the ...g4 push. If White instead delays h3 on move nine we can develop with ...Be7 and ...Nh6 with the same idea of an eventual ...Bf5 and ...g4 to come. Lastly, 8... h5 8.Re1 deserves a mention. I like Stockfish's recommendation here: 8...Nh6! Black develops the knight, but does so in a way which doesn't block the queen off. White's most popular move, 9.Nc3? just makes no sense at all. 9...g5! 10.h3 Bxf3 11.Qxf3 g4! 12.hxg4 hxg4 13.Qg3 Nf5! 14.Qxg4 Kd7!! Black easily secures a nearly decisive initiative. Instead, the more natural 9... Bxf3 9.h3 is stronger. Though the position is closer to equal, Black gets our typical sort of dynamic play after 9...Bxf3 10.Qxf3 Nf5! with our standard ...g5-g4 push arriving very quickly. As a reminder, memorizing all of this analysis is not necessary. I am going over these lines in the text to give you an idea of how striking the thematic overlap is between variations, even for lines not directly included in the drillables. } ) 7... h5 $1 { [%cal Bd8h4,Bh8h1][%csl Rh1][%cal Yh3g4,Yh5g4][%csl Rf3]h5 is both aggressive and sound! White would be wise not to take the bishop. } 8. hxg4 $4 hxg4 9. g3 { Returning the piece is White's only hope. } ( 9. Nh2 $2 $146 { immediately loses to } 9... Qh4 ) 9... gxf3 10. Qxf3 $2 { White will likely be tempted to make this mistake. He should instead focus on development with } ( 10. d3 { at which point Black will have good play after targeting e5 with } 10... Rh5 11. Re1 Qb8 { and either e5 or b2 will fall. Qf3 is arguably a blunder, as Black will now be able to resume his attack on White's king. } ) 10... Qg5 { [%cal Bd8g5,Bg5g6,Rg5e5][%csl Re5]Mobilizing towards the kingside. } 11. d4 Qg6 12. c3 Ne7 { [%cal Be7f5,Bf5g3][%csl Rg3][%cal Bh8h3][%csl Rd4][%cal Bf5d4]Bringing more pieces into the attack! We also want to pressure d4, and maybe we have ...Rh3!? at some point too. } 13. Be3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nf5 { [%cal Bf5d4,Bf5e3,Bf5g3,Yf8e7,Ye8d7,Rh8h3,Ra8h8]The knight is incredibly strong on f5. Victory is nearly on the horizon. } 15. Nc3 Be7 $19 { [%cal Be7h4,Bf5h4,Rh8h5,Rh5f5,Bf3f4]White doesn't really have any good moves. Our plan is to play 16.-- Nh4! } 16. Qf4 $2 { and } 16... Rh5 { with intentions to bring everything to the attack. } 17. Bc1 O-O-O 18. Ne2 $146 Rdh8 19. f3 { Unfortunately for White, it's far too late to run. 20...Nf5 21.Kf2 } 19... Rh2 { 22.Ke1 Nxg3 23.Qxg3 Bb4+ } 20. Bd2 { Qd3 White is getting overwhelmed and has permission to resign. } * 

