1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5][%csl Re5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O $6 e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nc3 Ne7 { While I would like to keep things simple, ...Bd6 does not work here. However, } ( 7... Bg4 { is a notable alternative if you want to try for similar positions to the 7.b3 variations. For instance: } 8. h3 Bh5 9. b3 Bd6 $2 { It's in the spirit of these sorts of positions to sacrifice our pawns! } 10. exd5 Ne7 $146 11. dxc6 O-O 12. Ne4 $146 f5 { White is probably a little better in these sorts of positions, but they look promising for Black anyway. Meanwhile, 7...Ne7 allows Black to immediately press for an advantage, as will be seen. } ) 8. h3 { [%cal Bc8g4][%csl Rg4]White restricts Black's bishop and waits for Black to commit to a plan. } 8... Ng6 { [%cal Bc8e6,Bf8d6,Be8g8,Bh8f8]h3 is a bit slow. Black can now just develop and castle without any issues. } 9. Ne2 Bd6 10. c4 Be6 11. b3 { White might instead try to clarify the situation in the center with } ( 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5 Bxd5 13. Nc3 $146 Bc6 14. Ne4 $146 Be7 { These lines are super sharp. For instance after } 15. Be3 c4 16. Rc1 f5 17. Nc5 $146 f4 { The position is already incredibly messy. } 18. Ne6 $2 $146 Qd7 19. Nxg7+ $146 Kf7 20. Nxe5+ $146 Nxe5 $146 21. Qh5+ Ng6 $146 22. Nf5 $146 fxe3 23. fxe3 Raf8 24. Rxc4 Bf6 { Black is winning here, but it looks extremely dangerous. You can always close down the center earlier with ...d4 after 10.c4 if these complications aren't agreeable to you. } ) 11... O-O 12. Ng3 Qd7 $17 { [%cal Bg6f4,Bh7h6,Ba7a5]Black has a moderate edge here, probably due to superior piece activity and central control. These middlegames tend to be somewhat of a positional maneuver-battle, but dynamic opportunities will arise once the position opens up, so stay alert. } * 

