1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 $5 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5][%csl Re5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bf8e7][%csl Ye5,Yd5]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. The following lines display my preferred rejoinders to White's efforts to target c5. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. b3 { [%cal Rc1a3,Ra3c5][%csl Rc5][%cal Yb1c3,Yc3a4,Ya4c5]White chooses to invest their efforts into targeting c5. } 7... Bd6 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bf6f5,Bg8f6,Yd8e7]Remaining flexible. Stockfish has some creative ideas of ...Bg4 paired with ...f5 and ...Nf6. Of course, ...Bd6 also allows us to defend c5 with ...Qe7 if we would like. } 8. Ba3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nc3 { Be aware that } ( 10. g4 $2 { would be a serious mistake in these positions. } 10... Bf7 11. Nh4 $146 h5 { White's position is troubling already. For instance, White might continue with } 12. Nf5 $2 $146 hxg4 13. Nxg7+ $146 Kd7 14. Qxg4+ Kc7 { Black is winning. White will not be able to defend the kingside after ...Nh6, ...Qg8, etc. } ) 10... f5 $5 { [%csl Bc6,Bc5,Bd5,Be5,Bf5][%cal Yg2g4][%csl Rg4]Now dynamic complications are unavoidable. } 11. exf5 Nf6 12. Na4 Qe7 { [%cal Be7c5][%csl Rc5]Most of the time Black should be happy to give White c5 for free, but with our ...f5 gambit already accepted this would be too much. } 13. Qe2 O-O $17 { [%cal Bh5e2][%csl Rf3][%cal Be8e1,Re5e4,Ba8e8,Ye7d7,Ye7c7,Ye7d8][%csl Ra3,Ra4]Black is a pawn down, but White's position is much worse. White's queenside pieces are doing nothing now that they've failed in their assault on c5. If they ever move away from their posts, once Black gets ...Rae8 in, Black can simply move the queen from the e-file and aim for the killer ...e4!. A game might continue with Given the potency of the upcoming ...e4 threat, White might elect to break our everlasting pin with } 14. Rae1 ( 14. g4 $2 { , which loses immediately to } 14... Nxg4 $146 15. hxg4 Bxg4 16. Qe3 { And Black plays } 16... e4 { anyways! } 17. dxe4 dxe4 18. Nd2 $146 Qh4 19. f4 Rxf5 { White is getting crushed. } ) 14... Rae8 15. Bb2 $2 { Now Black's queen is free to step out of the e-file. } 15... Qd8 { Now let's see what can be done if White tries to unpin their kingside knight. Of course, if the queen strays too far, the capture on f3 would be fatal. } 16. Qe3 $2 d4 { This key move initiates a brilliant attack. } 17. Qe2 g6 { Black will soon find full compensation for the surrender of his kingside pawns. } 18. fxg6 $2 Nd5 $146 { The threat now is ...Bxf3! and White will be forced to give up the queen, lest the dark steed find his way to f4. } 19. gxh7+ $2 Kh8 { White is finished. He has no recourse to any defense which will prevent the forthcoming attack with ...Bxf3, ...Nf4, etc. } * 

