1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. In consolidating the central light squares by occupying them with pawns, White justifies the decision to trade off the corresponding bishop. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. c4 e5 { If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. The following lines display my preferred rejoinders to White's efforts to target c5. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nc3 d4 { [%cal Bf6f5,Bf8d6,Bg8e7,Be7g6]With so much pressure on d5, temporarily closing the center would be expedient to our objective of launching a future kingside attack. The immediate ...d4 also tempts White to coordinate their forces to the queenside to target our weak c5 pawn, which is precisely how we want them to play. As we have previously observed, Black is easily able to generate an initiative on the kingside when White focuses on c5. It's worth mentioning that White could release the tension immediately after 6...e5 with 7... e5 7.cxd5?! , but this isn't accurate. Black can secure an advantage after 7...cxd5 8.exd5 Ne7! Recapturing with the queen allows Nc3 with tempo. Black will recapture on d5 and castle with a better position. } 8. Na4 Bd6 9. O-O { [%cal Bb2b3,Bc1a3][%csl Rc5][%cal Ya4c5,Ya3c5,Rd8a5,Ra5c5,Ra5e1][%csl Re1]If White hastily pursues c5 without castling they might end up losing a piece. For instance, } ( 9. b3 Ne7 $146 10. Ba3 O-O 11. Bxc5 $2 Bxc5 12. Nxc5 $146 Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 9... Ne7 { [%cal Bf6f5,Be7g6]Same plan as before. } 10. b3 { [%cal Bc1a3,Ra3c5,Ra4c5][%csl Rc5]} 10... Ng6 11. Ba3 O-O ( 11... Qe7 { is also acceptable, but less ambitious. } ) 12. Bxc5 f5 { Black has an incredible initiative. The immediate threat is 13.-- fxe4 14.dxe4 Bg4! where Black will ruin White's kingside pawns and firmly plant a knight on f4 with a crushing attack soon to come. } 13. Nd2 { Freeing the f-pawn. This is probably White's best try at a defense. For instance, } ( 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Qd2 $2 { White really does need the support of the f-pawn to close things down. } 14... Nf4 $146 { Black has a decisive initiative. } 15. g3 fxe4 16. dxe4 Bg4 { etc. } ) 13... Nf4 { [%cal Bd8g5]White is already on thin ice. } 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Ne4 Bxe4 16. dxe4 Rf6 $17 { [%cal Bg2g3,Bf4e6,Be6g5,Bg5f3]Black is simply much better. If White ever elects to kick our knight with g3 we can reroute and target the new kingside weaknesses. } * 

