1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 { [%cal Bh8g8,Bg8g2,Be7e5,Yc8g4,Bd8d5]For those more positionally minded, } ( 7... exf6 { is playable as well. I prefer ...gxf6 here because it enables Black to easily generate a kingside initiative. With the g-file semi-open, Black already has a target. } ) 8. O-O Rg8 9. d3 { [%cal Bd8d5,Bc8g4,Bc8h3]While White has a number of viable moves here, Black's development blueprint (...Bg4 or ...Bh3, ...Qd5, ..Rd8 or ...O-O-O, ...e5!? etc.) is pretty much uniformly applicable to each deviation. Being familiar with the basic ideas should be sufficient for adequate treatment of similar positions. } 9... Bg4 { [%cal Bd8d5]This is a particularly annoying move. Once the bishop lands on g4 it's not so easy for White to remove it. Next we can simply continue to build pressure on f3 and mobilize our forces toward the kingside. } ( 9... Bh3 $2 { is a possibility too, but after } 10. Ne1 $146 Qd5 11. f3 { White is solid. However, in circumstances where White is unable to avail themselves of this Ne1 maneuver ...Bh3 is stronger than ...Bg4. For instance, suppose White starts with 9... Rg8 9.Re1 instead of d3. Now, after 9...Bh3! White is just totally beleaguered. g3 is pretty much forced, either now or after 10.Nh4 Qd5! 11.g3 , where Black has a small advantage due to the state of White's light squares . } ) 10. Kh1 { Stepping the king off of the file. } 10... Qd5 { [%cal Bc5c4,Bd5h5,Bd5h1,Bh5d1][%csl Rf3,Rh1,Rd1]This is usually the best spot for the queen. Defending the light squares without the corresponding bishop will be a challenge for White. ...c4!? might be strong at some point too. } 11. h3 $6 Qh5 $1 { The bishop will not be repelled! } 12. Rg1 c4 $1 { This move not only improves our structural situation but also sets a trap. But let's suppose White manages to spot this elementary tactic and resolves not to fall for it: } 13. dxc4 $2 { immediately loses. } ( 13. Qe2 cxd3 { Now } 14. cxd3 { is forced. If the queen were to capture the previous tactic would work all the same. Black can continue with } 14... Rd8 { , the threat being ...Rd4, which would most likely end the game if permitted. White's best defense is } 15. Qe4 { , attacking c6, where Black should simplify the position. } 15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. gxf3 Rxg1+ 18. Kxg1 Rxd3 { Black has the advantage in the endgame. } ) 13... Rd8 14. Qe2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. gxf3 Rxg1+ 17. Kxg1 Rd1+ 18. Kg2 Bh6 { White loses significant material and consequently has permission to resign. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "Quickstarter: 4.Nc3 with 5.Bxc6+ and 7.Nxc5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: 4.Nc3 with 5.Bxc6+ and 7.Nxc5"]
[Black "Quickstarter"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Nxc5 $2 e5 { [%cal Bf8c5][%csl Rc5][%cal Be5e4][%csl Rf3]Boom! Black strikes in the center once again! 7.Nxc5?, the most common move, is already a remarkable strategic mistake by my lights. In these positions the c5 pawn is a long-term weakness which White would be wise to target later in the game once their development has been completed and their activity optimized. Instead, the immediate capture simply gifts to Black a potent initiative after the sharp ...e5!, attacking the knight on c5 and preparing to misplace the kingside knight next with ...e4!. } 8. Nb3 e4 $1 { Now White only has two acceptable moves. The awkward looking } 9. Ne5 { This enables White to survive, although that is not to say that it comes without risk. } ( 9. Ne5 $2 $146 { and the professional 9... e4 9.Qe2! As such, is quite easy for White to err in this position. For instance, the most popular move here: 9... e4 9.Nfd4?? just outright loses. I would recommend that the reader pay close attention to the upcoming continuations. These positions are exceptionally sharp and perhaps not as easy to navigate as appearance may suggest. } ) 9... Bd6 { Encouraging White to take c6. It should be clear by now that the miserly preservation of material is not on Black's agenda. } 10. Nxc6 $2 Qc7 11. Ncd4 { The only move to save the knight. } 11... O-O 12. d3 { White cannot castle due to the pressure on h2. } ( 12. h3 { prevents ...Bg4, but we can play } 12... Ba6 { Black has an incredible position. It's not easy for White to unravel this mess. For instance, if 13.cxd3 Rfe8+ 14.Be3 Bb4+ Kf1 is forced. If 15.Nd2?? , Black wins. 15...Rxe3+ 16.fxe3? Qg3+ Checkmate is on the horizon. } 13. d3 exd3 ) ( 12. Nb5 $2 $146 { leads to some incredible tactics. You can check them all out here: 1 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) \- 2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) \- 3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 12... Bg4 { Striking on the light squares! While our pawn is on e4 we should always be looking for opportunities to play ...Bg4. } 13. Qd2 { While this does block the bishop in, } ( 13. Ne2 $2 $146 { instead would lead to disaster. White has to remember that for the moment their king is stuck in the center. There's no time to waste moving pieces backwards. } 13... Rfe8 14. d4 $2 { White cannot allow the center to open. } 14... Nd5 $146 { So many tactical opportunities. Almost every line leads to absolute mayhem. } 15. c4 $2 e3 $3 { White is getting crushed here. After } 16. f3 Bf5 17. cxd5 $2 Bc2 { the queen is gone. } ) 13... Rfe8 { White is still unable to castle, yet the king urgently needs to evacuate the center! } 14. Kf1 Be5 $17 { [%cal Be4d3,Ba7a5,Ba8c8][%csl Ra1,Rc1,Rh1][%cal Yd4b5,Ba8d8][%csl Yd6,Yc7][%cal Bd6e5]...Be5 prevents White's fork and enables us to get some play for our rook on the d-file. Black is much better. White's development is in a dismal state, their knights are targets, their center is on the verge of collapse, and the king isn't even very safe on f1. Black on the other hand is remarkably active and has a nearly decisive initiative. A small price to pay for only three pawns. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 with 6.Ne2 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.exd5 with 6.Ne2 #1"]
[Black "1) The Mainline | 4.exd5 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { [%cal Bd8d5,Bc8d7,Bd7g4][%csl Re4]Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { [%cal Bd5c6][%csl Rc6]Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Ne2 { [%cal Ba7a6][%csl Rb5]White elects to keep the queens on the board. Nonetheless, Black has now been afforded enough time to dispense with the pesky queenside pin. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... a6 $1 { Thematic. White is now forced to surrender the bishop pair really for not much of anything. I would be happy to play Black already. } 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. O-O ( 8. d4 { instead can be met simply with } 8... e6 { which will resemble positions discussed later in this chapter. } ) 8... Nf6 9. d4 e6 { [%cal Bf8e7,Bb7b5,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bc8b7,Rb7g2,Rd6h2,Bf8d6]Black is doing excellent here, as is indicated by the 65%+ win rate given by the lichess database. We have the bishops, an semi-open center, strategic flexibility, no issues completing development, and future prospects of an attack down the diagonals. One game I played continued with: } 10. Ne5 { [%cal Bc6c7,Bf8d6,Bc7h2][%csl Re5]This knight maneuver is the move I encounter most. Unfortunately for White this is not such a good idea when the knight is on e2, as the e5 knight can quickly become bothersome to defend in the center. As will be shown later in the chapter, this idea can usually effectively be met with ...Qc7 followed by ...Bd6. } 10... Qc7 11. Bf4 { Covering the knight. } 11... Bd6 12. Bg3 O-O $15 { [%cal Bf6h5,Bf8d8,Bb7b6,Bc8b7]Black has a quiet advantage and can slowly build pressure on the center and the kingside. For reference, my game continued with } 13. Re1 b5 14. a4 Bb7 { Black's bishops are magnificent pieces. } 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Rxa8 17. c3 Ne4 $146 { White is already running into trouble. The clumsy knight on e2 has accomplished nothing. } 18. Nf3 $146 Nxg3 $146 19. Nxg3 $146 { Black is already significantly better. White eventually crumbled from the pressure of the bishops. } * 

