1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { [%cal Bd8d5,Bc8g4,Bc8d7][%csl Re4]Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Ne2 { White elects to keep the queens on the board. Nonetheless, Black has now been afforded enough time to dispense with the pesky queenside pin. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... a6 { Thematic. White is now forced to surrender the bishop pair really for not much of anything. I would be happy to play Black already. } 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. O-O ( 8. d4 { instead can be met simply with } 8... e6 { which will resemble positions discussed later in this chapter. } ) 8... Nf6 9. d4 e6 { Black is doing excellent here, as is indicated by the 65%+ win rate given by the lichess database. We have the bishops, an semi-open center, strategic flexibility, no issues completing development, and future prospects of an attack down the diagonals. } 10. c4 { The second most common move, but perhaps a bit incautious. White needs to be careful not to slip up and let the c-pawn hang. Fortunately, most people fall in to error. } 10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 ( 11. Nexd4 $2 $146 { This mistake is actually way more common than one might think. Over half the time White errs and recaptures with the knight. } 11... Qxc4 $17 { Black is up a clean pawn for nothing. } ) 11... b6 $5 { I like this tricky move! Black's idea here is twofold. First, we want to bring the bishop to b7 to create the battery along the long diagonal. Second, once the bishop is out of the way we have ...Rd8 ideas to evict White's queen from her central post. } ( 11... Bc5 { looks more natural, but after } 12. Qh4 O-O 13. Bg5 { White has some pressure. Ng3-h5 is coming if we drop the bishop back to e7, and ...Nd7 is a bit awkward. } ) 12. Ne5 { Probably the most natural move. } ( 12. Be3 { makes sense too. We can simply continue with our development. } 12... Bc5 13. Qf4 Bb7 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. Rfd1 O-O $10 { With chances for both sides. } ) 12... Qc7 { The usual response to Ne5 in most positions. } 13. Bf4 ( 13. Be3 { comes with some risk. White will be forced to find some only-moves. } 13... Bc5 14. Qf4 $7 { Forced. } 14... Bd6 15. Bd4 O-O { The threat is now ...Nd7, so Qe3 is forced. } 16. Qe3 $7 Rb8 17. Rfd1 Rd8 18. Nf4 $146 Ne8 $13 $146 { A subtle move, intending ...f6-e5. This middlegame is equal, but quite unclear. Black has the bishops, but is somewhat uncoordinated. } ) 13... Bb7 { Setting a trap! } 14. Rad1 ( 14. Ng6 $2 $146 { would be dangerous if not for } 14... Qc6 { and now White is lost! } 15. Nh4 $146 Rd8 16. Qe3 Be7 $19 { White's c-pawn is hanging and they have no time to defend it, as Black is also threatening ...g5! followed by ...Rg8 and ...Ng4. } ) 14... Bc5 15. Qd3 O-O $13 { [%cal Be5g6,Be5g4,Be5d7,Gc7c6,Gf8d8,Yb7g2]Any discovery can simply be met with ...Qc6. Otherwise, Black will respond next with ...Nh5 to eliminate the bishop and can eventually challenge White along the open file. We have a promising future on the long diagonals too. } * 

