1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bc8d7,Bd8d5][%csl Re4]Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { [%cal Bd5c6][%csl Rc6]Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { [%cal Be6c6][%csl Rc6,Re1]Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Rc5]Taking on d4 would just improve White's pieces, so Black should instead focus on development. If White accepts the gambit, Black's initiative will more than compensate for the pawn. In most continuations White will be forced to return it anyway. } 9. dxc5 e6 10. Be3 { This is the most common continuation. Naturally, White would like to hold on to the pawn. However, now we have a new target to harass. } 10... Nd5 { [%csl Re3,Rc5][%cal Bd5e3,Bd5b4,Bb4c2,Bc2e1,Bc2a1][%csl Rc2]The knight leaps ahead! White would be wise to simply return the pawn and enjoy equality while it lasts. Endeavoring to defend c5 will only make White's position more difficult. } 11. Bxc6 { Making Bd4 possible. Retreating his dark squared bishop instead allows the immediate ...Bxc5, and most other moves allow ..Nxe3 along with a subsequent capture on c5. } 11... Bxc6 12. Bd4 $6 f6 $1 { [%cal Be6e5][%csl Re5]The materialist will suffer for their greed! ...e5 is incoming and White's bishop simply has no good square to retreat to! This ...f6-e5 sequence is thematic. } 13. c4 { White anticipates the incoming ...e5 by introducing a threat of their own! Once the knight has been ejected from d5 the bishop can safely retreat to e3, presumably. } 13... Nb4 { [%cal Bb4c2][%csl Rd4,Re3,Re1,Ra1]} 14. O-O e5 15. Be3 { Insisting on defending c5 will do White no favors. White could finally stop trying to hold onto the c5 pawn with } ( 15. Bc3 Bxc5 { This might be the more sensible route. Black has good chances in these positions. We have excellent control of the center and active bishops. } ) 15... Nc2 16. Rad1 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bxc5 $17 { [%csl Re3]Black is already borderline winning. We might see a game continue with } 18. Kf2 Rc8 19. Nc3 $146 Bb4 { Black threatens ...Bxc3 followed by ...Be4, where White's c4 pawn would be untenable. However, White needs to be careful about Black invading on the second rank. } 20. Nd5 $2 $146 Bxd5 21. cxd5 Rc2+ { would be game over. If 20... Bb4 21.Rc1 Black can take over the open file. 21...Bxc3 22.Rxc3 Ke7! 23.Rd1 Rhd8 Black has a significant advantage here. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 with 6.Qe2 #2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.exd5 with 6.Qe2 #2"]
[Black "1) The Mainline | 4.exd5 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bc8d7,Bd8d5][%csl Re4]Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { [%cal Bd5c6][%csl Rc6]Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { [%cal Be6c6][%csl Rc6,Re1]Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Rc5]Taking on d4 would just improve White's pieces, so Black should instead focus on development. If White accepts the gambit, Black's initiative will more than compensate for the pawn. In most continuations White will be forced to return it anyway. } 9. dxc5 e6 10. Be3 { This is the most common continuation. Naturally, White would like to hold on to the pawn. However, now we have a new target to harass. } 10... Nd5 { [%csl Re3,Rc5][%cal Bd5e3,Bd5b4,Bb4c2][%csl Rc2]The knight leaps ahead! White would be wise to simply return the pawn and enjoy equality while it lasts. Endeavoring to defend c5 will only make White's position more difficult. } 11. Bxc6 { Making Bd4 possible. Retreating his dark squared bishop instead allows the immediate ...Bxc5, and most other moves allow ..Nxe3 along with a subsequent capture on c5. } 11... Bxc6 12. Bd4 $6 f6 { The materialist will suffer for their greed! ...e5 is incoming, and White's bishop simply has no good square to retreat to! This ...f6-e5 sequence is thematic. } 13. c4 { White anticipates the incoming ...e5 by introducing a threat of their own! Once the knight has been ejected from d5 the bishop can safely retreat to e3, presumably. } 13... Nb4 14. Kd2 { White prevents the fork by activating the king. } 14... Na6 $17 { [%cal Ba6c5][%csl Rc5][%cal Bh7h5,Be6e5,Ba7a5,Ye8f7]And now White must return the pawn on c5. Black is better in this endgame because of his bishop pair and excellent central control. Our pawns restrict White's pieces and their king is unfortunately placed on an open file. } * 

