ontinuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { [%cal Be6c6][%csl Rc6,Re1]Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Rc5]Taking on d4 would just improve White's pieces, so Black should instead focus on development. If White accepts the gambit, Black's initiative will more than compensate for the pawn. In most continuations White will be forced to return it anyway. } 9. dxc5 e6 10. Be3 { This is the most common continuation. Naturally, White would like to hold on to the pawn. However, now we have a new target to harass. } 10... Nd5 { [%csl Re3,Rc5][%cal Bd5e3,Bd5b4,Bb4c2][%csl Rc2]The knight leaps ahead! White would be wise to simply return the pawn and enjoy equality while it lasts. Endeavoring to defend c5 will only make White's position more difficult. } 11. Bxc6 { Making Bd4 possible. Retreating his dark squared bishop instead allows the immediate ...Bxc5, and most other moves allow ..Nxe3 along with a subsequent capture on c5. } 11... Bxc6 12. Bd4 $6 f6 $1 { The materialist will suffer for their greed! ...e5 is incoming and White's bishop simply has no good square to retreat to! This ...f6-e5 sequence is thematic. } 13. a3 { A clever idea. White prepares c4 by preventing ...Nb4 and might also try for b4 at some point. } 13... e5 14. c4 Nc7 15. Be3 a5 { [%cal Bc7e6,Ba5a4][%csl Rc5]We must prevent b4, otherwise Black will be down a pawn for nothing. Our immediate plan is to continue to target c5. } 16. O-O a4 { Again preventing b4, which castling almost made possible! } ( 16... Ne6 $2 $146 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 { With White's rooks connected, capturing on b4 won't work. We need to be able to meet the potential b4 push with ...axb3. } ) 17. Rad1 Ne6 { [%cal Be6c5]c5 is doomed! } 18. Nc3 Bxc5 { [%cal Be8f7,Bh8d8,Bd8d4,Bd4c4][%csl Rc4][%cal Ye3c5,Ye6c5]Taking on c5 with the knight is fine too, but Black is a bit behind on development and should prepare to contest White's rook for control over the open d-file. White's c4 pawn is a weakness and installing a rook on d4 under the right conditions might prompt an exchange, giving Black a passed pawn. Moreover, our current central structure is primarily dark, so exchanging dark-squared bishops would favor Black. } 19. Bxc5 Nxc5 $17 { [%csl Rb3,Rc2,Rd3][%cal Be8f7,Bh8e8,Ba8c8,Ba8d8]Black is a bit better in this endgame. White's queenside is full of holes, and we still dominate the center. } * 

