ommon continuation. Naturally, White would like to hold on to the pawn. However, now we have a new target to harass. } 10... Nd5 { [%csl Re3,Rc5][%cal Bd5e3,Bd5b4,Bb4c2][%csl Rc2]The knight leaps ahead! White would be wise to simply return the pawn and enjoy equality while it lasts. Endeavoring to defend c5 will only make White's position more difficult. } 11. Bxc6 { Making Bd4 possible. Retreating his dark squared bishop instead allows the immediate ...Bxc5, and most other moves allow ..Nxe3 along with a subsequent capture on c5. } 11... Bxc6 12. Bd4 $6 f6 $1 { The materialist will suffer for their greed! ...e5 is incoming and White's bishop simply has no good square to retreat to! This ...f6-e5 sequence is thematic. } 13. O-O-O $5 e5 $1 14. Rhe1 { White has nothing better than to sacrifice the bishop! If White retreats the bishop Black will simply capture it and then eliminate c5, acquiring a decisive advantage. Note also that moving the rook here is a very computer-ish move, meaning you can be confident that most of the time Black will emerge with a sizable advantage immediately after 13...e5. It's still good to come prepared though. If } ( 14. c4 $2 { Black can respond with } 14... Nb4 $146 15. a3 ( 15. Be3 { Nxc5! A similar idea appears in an earlier variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Here White is similarly much worse. } ) 15... Na6 $146 { and will take c5. } ) 14... exd4 { The more ambitious move. White actually has compensation for the piece if they can find a sequence of only-moves. This we will discuss shortly, but first it's worth mentioning that } ( 14... O-O-O { is a simple, yet effective alternative for those who wish to avoid the complicated mess which follows ...exd4. } 15. c4 { is White's only move, where after } 15... Nb4 $146 16. a3 Na6 $146 17. Bc3 Bxc5 { Black enjoys a small advantage. } ) 15. Nexd4+ $7 Kf7 16. Nxc6 $7 { Once again, the only move. If White tries something like } ( 16. c4 $2 { instead Black has time to consolidate. } 16... Ne7 $146 17. Nxc6 $146 Nxc6 $146 18. Rd7+ Be7 $19 { White has seventh-rank activity, but it's worth much less than the piece they lost. } ) 16... bxc6 17. c4 $7 { White needs to get a rook to the seventh rank to secure any compensation for the sacrifice. } 17... Nf4 18. Rd7+ $7 Kg6 $5 { ...Kg8 works too, but clogs up the back rank. We'll need to connect our rooks quickly in the event that White attempts to mobilize a queenside pawn storm. } 19. Rd4 $1 { Nearly forced. If instead } ( 19. Re4 $2 { Black wins with } 19... Kf5 $3 { hitting the rook with tempo } 20. Rdd4 g5 { and is in time to deal with all of White's threats. } ) ( 19. b4 $2 { can be met with } 19... a5 20. a3 axb4 21. axb4 { and here } 21... Nxg2 $2 $146 { actually works. These lines are all somewhat complex, but being a piece up Black has at least a practical advantage in each case. } ) 19... Kf5 20. g3 { Careful to avoid the perpetual after } ( 20. g4+ $2 Kxg4 21. Rg1+ Kxf3 22. Rg3+ ( 22. Rxf4+ { Bxc5-+ } ) 22... Ke2 $3 { if 22...Kxf2 White takes f4 with check and has a perpetual. } ) 20... Nh3 $15 { Careful not to blunder mate with } ( 20... Ng6 $2 $146 21. g4# { In any case, White needs to find all of this and still can only maintain the balance if they find 21... Ng6 21.b4!? or 21.Rh4! Nxf2 22.Rf4! Kg6 23.Nh4+ Kf7 24.Rxf2 Bxc5 , and even still Black is ever so slightly better. } ) * 

