ontinuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { [%cal Be6c6][%csl Rc6,Re1]Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Rc5]Taking on d4 would just improve White's pieces, so Black should instead focus on development. If White accepts the gambit, Black's initiative will more than compensate for the pawn. In most continuations White will be forced to return it anyway. } 9. dxc5 e6 10. Be3 { This is the most common continuation. Naturally, White would like to hold on to the pawn. However, now we have a new target to harass. } 10... Nd5 { [%cal Bd5e3][%csl Re3][%cal Bd5b4]The knight leaps ahead! White would be wise to simply return the pawn and enjoy equality while it lasts. Endeavoring to defend c5 will only make White's position more difficult. } 11. Ned4 { This move is sensible enough. White aims to get the knight back into the game. } 11... Rc8 { Overprotecting c6. We would like to keep our queenside structure intact in the event of some trades. } 12. Nxc6 ( 12. Bxc6 { will likely transpose after a sequence of exchanges on c6. } ) 12... Bxc6 13. Bxc6+ Rxc6 { Boom. Nothing to worry about anymore. If White saves the bishop with Bd4 or Bd2 Black will simply recapture c5 with full equality. } 14. Bd4 Bxc5 15. O-O-O { If } ( 15. Bxg7 $2 { Black has a potentially deadly attack! } 15... Rg8 16. Be5 Bxf2+ $2 17. Kxf2 Rxc2+ 18. Kf1 $2 Ne3+ $146 19. Ke1 Rgxg2 $19 { Black is winning! If instead, 18... Rxc2+ 18.Ke1! Rgxg2 White has only one move to save the game. 19.Bd4! Black still has some remarkable pressure though. 19...e5! 20.Nxe5 Rge2+ 21.Kf1 Re4 with a slight edge to Black. } ) 15... Ke7 { [%cal Bh8d8,Bh8c8][%csl Ge7]Keeping the king active for the upcoming endgame. Black will continue by centralizing his remaining piece. } 16. Rhe1 Rd8 $10 { [%cal Bh7h5,Bg7g6,Bb7b5,Ba7a6]With equal chances for both sides. } * 

