ontinuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { [%cal Be6c6][%csl Rc6,Re1]Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Rc5]Taking on d4 would just improve White's pieces, so Black should instead focus on development. If White accepts the gambit, Black's initiative will more than compensate for the pawn. In most continuations White will be forced to return it anyway. } 9. dxc5 e6 10. Bxc6 { [%cal Bb2b4][%csl Rc5]With Bxc6 White actually manages to hang onto the pawn. For now. Black will have sufficient dynamic compensation through piece activity. } 10... Bxc6 11. b4 a5 { Black must challenge the queenside before White can consolidate. } 12. c3 axb4 13. cxb4 Nd5 { [%cal Bd5b4][%csl Rb4]} 14. Bd2 g6 { [%cal Bf8g7,Bh8a1]The bishop belongs on g7. } 15. O-O Bg7 $13 { [%cal Ya8a4][%csl Rb4,Ra1,Ra2][%cal Be8g8,Bh8a8,Yf8a8,Bd5c7,Yc6f3,Yg7a1,Ge8e7]Black has targets everywhere. While we are down a pawn, our bishops dominate the open lines unopposed. Black has full compensation, but it's still messy. } * 

