1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension rings high! Chaos and confusion abounds! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White almost assuredly will be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Qe2 { The simple solution is to initiate the endgame. This is fine for White, but not ambitious. White won't be able to do anything substantive with their lead in development and Black can actually play for dynamics in many continuations. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 { With ...Bd7 White will be unable to sabotage our structure. The evaluation is already equal. While this looks a little dry, Black has some crafty resources which might enable us to push for an advantage from here. } 8. c3 { White slowly prepares d4. You will not see this move often. } 8... a6 { I like this move best. c3 is slow, so Black has time to start asking White questions about the placement of their bishop. } 9. Ba4 { The most popular continuation, by far. } ( 9. Bd3 { Retreating to d3 would be inaccurate, but is the second most popular move. } 9... e5 { Black can punish White's setup by taking space in the center. The idea is to play ...f5 followed by ...e4. } 10. Ng3 $146 g6 { Ng3 doesn't stop the impending ...f5, but merely delays it! } 11. O-O f5 12. Nxe5 $2 $146 { White could try this sneaky idea, but it actually works out in Black's favor. } 12... Nxe5 $146 13. Re1 Bd6 14. f4 O-O-O { The rook is coming to e8. } 15. fxe5 Re8 $15 { Black will restore material balance next with ...Bxe5 and has an advantage due to having superior activity and better control of the center. Instead, after 12... f5 12.Bc2 White dodges the fork. 12...e4!? The most aggressive approach. ...Bd6 is a more solid option. 13.Ne1 c4 We would love to clamp down on the light squares and constrict White's position as much as we can. White has to break out on the queenside to try to maintain the balance. 14.b3! b5 15.a4 Na5 16.axb5! Nxb3! 17.Rxa6 Rd8! White now must give up the bishop pair to avoid being significantly worse. 18.Bxb3 cxb3 19.c4 Bg7∓ This position is extremely sharp. Black has ...Bc8 and ...b2 ideas. White's pieces aren't well coordinated and their queenside pawns might not be easy to defend. Black should be better. Also, after 16... Re8 16.bxc4?! bxc4⩱ White's position looks rather uncomfortable. } ) ( 9. Bc4 { is nothing to be concerned about either. Black can get a fine position with very typical play. } 9... b5 10. Bb3 Nf6 $146 11. d4 e6 $10 { is roughly equal. Black can continue with ...Be7, ...O-O, and play for eventual queenside expansion with ...c4, ...b4, ...Na5, etc. } ) ( 9. Bxc6 $2 { Of course, the exchange is nothing to worry about. } 9... Bxc6 { Notice that White doesn't have Ne5 due to g2 being loose. } 10. d4 e6 11. Be3 c4 $15 { Keeping things closed so that we can catch up on development. Black is slightly better. } ) 9... Nf6 { Staying flexible. } 10. Bc2 { White improves the bishop. } ( 10. O-O { and 10.d4 result in more typical positions. } 10... e6 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nexd4 $146 Nxd4 $146 13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 $146 14. Nxd4 $146 Bc5 $13 { Black is scoring very well in this line, from what I can see. } ) ( 10. d4 e6 11. Bg5 h6 { We'll gladly take the bishop pair if White allows it. But if they did not intend to trade by coming to g5, why place the bishop there? There's no pin. } 12. Be3 { If White takes the knight on f6 instead, Black can castle to the queenside and organize an assault down the g-file. } 12... Nd5 $15 $146 { The typical response when White brings the bishop to e3. Black is slightly better. } ) 10... e5 { With White's bishop gone from the a4-e8 diagonal, Black is free to play ...e5, stopping White from playing d4. Now c3 looks a little bit silly. On another note, I find that whenever we can play ...e5 in these middlegames we give more play to our light-squared bishop, which is always nice. } 11. Ng3 ( 11. d4 $2 { The quality of White's position takes a nose-dive if they dare challenge our center. } 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 e4 13. Ne5 $146 { White's best move. } 13... Bb4+ 14. Bd2 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nxe5 $146 16. dxe5 Ng4 $15 $146 { Black has excellent play here. e5 will fall and Black will castle, bringing the rook to the d-file. The unfortunate position of White's king affords Black the advantage. One might also consider 13... e4 13.Ng5 after 12...e4. This would be a good move, if not for 13...Nb4! 14.Bb1 Nd3+ 15.Bxd3 exd3 16.Ng3 Nd5⩱ Black has a comfortable advantage. The knight is coming to b4, then to c2. Black can also play ...h5-h4 and ...Rh5 to harass White's knights. ...Be7 and ...Rc8 are also coming. Instead, 14... Bb4+ 14.Bb3? targeting f7 would be a serious mistake. 14...Nd3+! 15.Kf1 Bb4!! Black can just totally ignore White's threats on f7. Rapid development is key! 16.Nxf7?? Rf8 17.Ng5 Ng4-+ Black has an incredible initiative. This is winning. Instead of 16.Bb3, 16... Nxe5 16.a3 is the best White can do. 16...Nxc1 17.Nxc1 Bd2 18.Nxf7 Rf8 19.Ne5 Ng4 Once again, going after f2. 20.Nxg4 Bxg4∓ Black has the bishops and more activity. You can already smell the distant resignation in the air. } ) ( 11. O-O { is also possible. } 11... O-O-O { ∞ You could also play ...Bg4 and force White to suffer a worse structure by taking on f3 if you care little for the bishop pair. In either case, Black has a fine game. Memorization of all this is not necessary to play this line effectively. I just thought some might appreciate the analysis! } ) 11... Bg4 $15 { [%cal Gg7g6,Gh7h5,Gf6d5,Ge8c8,Ga8d8,Bg4f3,Bg2f3][%csl Rf3]The computer's idea here is to take on f3, where our opponent's kingside will suffer from structural vicissitudes akin to those which White initially attempted to inflict upon Black's queenside with 3.Bb5! Once White's structure has been damaged we can fight to get a grip on the f4 square with ...Nd5 so that White will struggle to resolve their positional foibles. We can proceed further by castling to the queenside and expanding on the kingside with ...g6 and ...h5 to ensure that White's h-pawn won't cause any issues. Black has a slight advantage. } * 

