 will need to play this sooner or later. Their knight is not getting back into the game via c4. } 15... Nxe4 { I like exchanging here, as it is the sharper continuation. ...Be7 is perfectly fine as well for those more interested in approaching the position in a solid and principled way. } 16. Bxe4 Be6 $1 { [%cal Bf7f5][%csl Re4][%cal Bf8d6]The point with ...Be6 is that now we prepare f5, where White cannot respond with Bd5. A subtle, yet powerful idea. Our other plan is to simply develop the remaining bishop and castle. } 17. f4 { Lashing out makes sense. Black is somewhat underdeveloped, after all. We might also encounter } ( 17. Qh5 { in an attempt to delay our castling. Black can simple proceed with natural moves and eventually aim for ...f5. } 17... Bd6 18. Bd2 h6 $2 19. Rae1 O-O { The computer recommends White play g4 here to prevent Black's ...f5 advance, lest they suffer a worse position. Black has great play in these lines and in my estimation has the easier game. } ) 17... f5 { Forcing the bishop back! } 18. Bf3 Bd6 { [%cal Bc7h2][%csl Rh2,Rf4]Suddenly Black is the one exerting great pressures on White's position! } 19. fxe5 Bxe5 20. g3 $1 O-O $13 { [%cal Bb8c8,Bc8c2][%csl Rc2][%cal Bh7h6,Gf5f4,Bg7g5][%csl Rh2,Rg3][%cal Bb8e8]This is roughly equal, but I prefer Black. We've got a space advantage and chances at playing against White's c-pawn. Maybe we'll eventually try to break down the remnants of White's kingside too. } * 

