1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { [%cal Bf1b5,Bb5e2]This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 $1 { [%cal Bd2d4][%csl Rd4][%cal Bc6d4]Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. Nxd4 { White releases the central tension, probably wanting to preserve their bishop pair. } ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... cxd4 8. Nb5 { [%cal Bb5c7][%csl Re6,Re8,Ra8]White continues to make threats while avoiding danger. No one should play } ( 8. Nb1 $146 { , but it is a possibility. Black has a number of viable replies, but I particularly like } 8... d3 9. cxd3 Nh6 $146 10. Nc3 $146 Nf5 $146 { Where our knight will soon rest unopposed on d4, tormenting White's light squares. Black can then play ...g6 and ...Bg7 to add to our strong control of the center and has promising chances. } ) 8... Qd7 { The black monarch is forced to move yet again. Though unprincipled, this isn't problematic in this context. White has already moved their bishop twice, and once ...a6 arrives White will need to waste even more time navigating their knight to a desirable location. Therefore, both Black and White have wasted each other's time. } 9. O-O a6 10. Na3 Nf6 { [%cal Bd7c7,Bc8e6]The most flexible way to proceed. We don't want to yet commit to ...e6, as in some positions ...e5 would be a boon. } 11. Nc4 { [%cal Bc4b6]} ( 11. Bf3 g5 $2 { transposes to this line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), where we cover the 9.Na3 move order. } ) 11... Qc7 12. a4 { Preventing ...b5. Now that this has been precluded, Black should focus on the center. } 12... e5 { [%cal Bc8e6,Bc8f5][%csl Rc4,Rc2]Targeting the knight with } ( 12... Be6 { is also fine, but gaining central space and supporting our d4 pawn seems more propitious to me. We'll proceed with either ...Be6 or ...Bf5, depending on how White responds. } ) 13. Re1 { [%cal Be1e8]This is not a move we should ignore. White now threatens a would-be decisive sacrifice: } ( 13. Re1 { \-- 14.Nxe5! Qxe5? 15.Bb5+ , winning the queen. } ) 13... Bf5 { [%cal Bf5c2][%csl Rc2]This stops White's Nxe5 ideas. } 14. d3 ( 14. Nxe5 $2 $146 Bxc2 { Black would like White to play d3, obstructing the bishop's vision on the queenside. Then we can redirect our bishop to e6 and force an exchange on c4, doubling White's pawns and giving Black great chances in the center. } ) ( 14. Bf1 { and Black should probably repeat with } 14... Bg4 15. Be2 Bf5 { etc. } ) 14... Be6 { [%cal Be6c4][%csl Rc4]White has no choice but to allow the exchange. } 15. Bf3 ( 15. Nd2 $2 $146 { allows } 15... Bb4 { tying down all of White's forces. } ) ( 15. b3 { might be seen too, but this weakens the dark squares. } 15... Bb4 16. Bd2 Nd5 $146 17. Bxb4 Nxb4 $146 18. Bf3 Bxc4 19. bxc4 a5 20. Qe2 f6 { Black can castle queenside if need be and has the preferable structure. } ) 15... Bxc4 16. dxc4 Bb4 { [%csl Bc4,Ba4,Rb4][%cal Bb4e1,Bd2d3]This is a move worth remembering in these variations. With both the a and former d pawns advanced, the b4 square is a most auspicious location to position our bishop. } 17. Bd2 Bxd2 18. Qxd2 O-O $13 { [%cal Ba8d8,Bf8e8][%csl Rc4]Stockfish gives this as dead equal, but Black has the center and White is the one with an immediate weakness. Attending to our central majority demands a certain level of caution, so I prefer Black. } * 

