 } ( 13. Re1 { \-- 14.Nxe5! Qxe5? 15.Bb5+ , winning the queen. } ) 13... Bf5 { This stops White's Nxe5 ideas. } 14. Bf1 { [%cal Be1e5,Bc4e5][%csl Re5]White renews their threats on e5. This forces our hand. } ( 14. Nxe5 $2 $146 Bxc2 { Black would like White to play d3, obstructing the bishop's vision on the queenside. Then we can redirect our bishop to e6 and force an exchange on c4, doubling White's pawns and giving Black great chances in the center. } ) 14... Bg4 $1 { [%cal Bg4f5,Bf5g4,Bf1e2,Be2f1]Now White must either return the bishop to e2 or weaken their kingside with the f3 advance. If White brings the bishop back to e2, pursuing a repetition with 15...Bf5 is the most accurate way to proceed. If you need to avoid the draw, feel free to try } 15. f3 { With this, we can sacrifice e5 without worry of playing at a disadvantage. } ( 15. Be2 Be6 $2 { instead of 15...Bf5, however be aware that White has } 16. Nxe5 $146 O-O-O 17. Nf3 $146 { and seemingly escapes cleanly up a pawn. Of course, even though the computer favors White, Black might have the easier position. } 17... h5 18. d3 Ng4 $146 19. h3 Bd6 { Black's kingside pressure could easily grow into a decisive checkmating attack. Meanwhile it's not clear what White's plan is supposed to be. Their pieces are comparatively inactive and they lack the space to coordinate. Granted, navigating this position is no menial task for either side. } ) 15... Be6 { [%cal Be1e8][%csl Re6,Rf2]Blocking the e-file. White has weakened his kingside and so now sacrificing e5 is perfectly sound. } 16. Nxe5 Bd6 17. f4 ( 17. Qe2 $2 d3 18. cxd3 Bc5+ { Would be awful for White. Their bishops are both imprisoned and their central structure is a positional catastrophe. } ) 17... O-O-O $5 { [%cal Bh7h5,Bg7g5,Bd6h2,Bc7h2][%csl Rh2,Yg1,Yf1,Ye1,Yd1,Yc1,Ya1]You can instead castle kingside if you prefer calmer positions, but I infer from the state of White's army that a coordinated kingside pawn storm would be an exceptional challenge to endure. } 18. d3 g5 19. Qf3 h5 $15 { We've arrived at another extremely sharp middlegame. It is not easy to navigate these positions, so let's examine a couple of continuations: Instead, } 20. fxg5 $2 { immediately loses the game to } ( 20. Nc4 $146 Bxf4 21. g3 Bd5 { It's quite easy to fail to hold everything together here. For instance, } 22. Bxf4 gxf4 23. Qxf4 $2 Qxf4 24. gxf4 Rhg8+ 25. Kf2 Ng4+ $146 { White won't be able to hold on. } ) 20... Ng4 $146 21. Nc4 $146 Bxh2+ 22. Kh1 Bd5 { White is getting crushed. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 7.Nxd4 #7"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 7.Nxd4 #7"]
[Black "1) The Mainline | 4.exd5 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { [%cal Bf1b5,Bb5e2]This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 $1 { [%cal Bd2d4][%csl Rd4][%cal Bc6d4]Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. Nxd4 { White releases the central tension, probably wanting to preserve their bishop pair. } ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... cxd4 8. Nb5 { [%cal Bb5c7][%csl Re6,Re8,Ra8]White continues to make threats while avoiding danger. No one should play } ( 8. Nb1 $146 { , but it is a possibility. Black has a number of viable replies, but I particularly like } 8... d3 9. cxd3 Nh6 $146 10. Nc3 $146 Nf5 $146 { Where our knight will soon rest unopposed on d4, tormenting White's light squares. Black can then play ...g6 and ...Bg7 to add to our strong control of the center and has promising chances. } ) 8... Qd7 { [%cal Bc2c3,Rd4d3]The black monarch is forced to move yet again. Though unprincipled, this isn't problematic in this context. White has already moved their bishop twice, and once ...a6 arrives White will need to waste even more time navigating their knight to a desirable location. Therefore, both Black and White have wasted each other's time. } 9. O-O a6 10. Na3 Nf6 { [%cal Bd7c7,Bc8e6]The most flexible way to proceed. We don't want to yet commit to ...e6, as in some positions ...e5 would be a boon. } 11. Nc4 ( 11. Bf3 g5 $2 { transposes to this line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), where we cover the 9.Na3 move order. } ) 11... Qc7 12. a4 { Preventing ...b5. Now that this has been precluded, Black should focus on the center. } 12... e5 { Targeting the knight with } ( 12... Be6 { is also fine, but gaining central space and supporting our d4 pawn seems more propitious to me. We'll proceed with either ...Be6 or ...Bf5, depending on how White responds. } ) 13. d3 { White could delay Re1, anticipating ...Bb4 ideas. } 13... Be6 { Similar to our previous analysis, the knight on c4 becomes a target. ...Bf5 wouldn't make much sense here because White has already played d3. Keep in mind that the point of ...Bf5 in the 13.Re1 lines (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) is to induce d3 so that we can drop the bishop back to e6 to exchange on c4. With d3 already on the board, Black can just play ...Be6 right away. } 14. Bg5 Be7 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8]Black should get the king out of the center sooner rather than later. } 15. Bf3 O-O 16. Re1 Bxc4 { [%cal Be7b4,Bf6d7][%csl Ye5]Now that White has committed to Re1, Black finally eliminates the pesky knight. With the pressure on e5 relieved, Black can continue with ...Bb4 to hit the rook and then follow up with ...Nd7 to support e5 and potentially break out with the f-pawn. } 17. dxc4 Bb4 $13 { [%cal Yf6d7,Ba8e8,Ya1c1,Yc2c3,Bh7h6,Gf7f5,Yd7c5][%csl Rb7]This middlegame is imbalanced, but equal. White has the bishop pair but a weak queenside structure. Black has the center but is slightly less active. One of White's ideas in this position is to break with c3 at the right moment to open the b-file so that b7 can be targeted. Black can proceed by bringing the knight back to d7 and centralizing the remaining rook. A game might continue with: } 18. Re2 ( 18. Rc1 h6 19. Bh4 Rae8 20. c3 dxc3 21. bxc3 Ba5 $2 { Black leaves the c5 outpost vacant for the knight. } 22. Rb1 { Nc5! 23.Qc2 } 22... Qd7 { This would be slightly better for Black. } ) 18... Nd7 $146 * 

