nding variation from the PGN) to see Black appropriately deal with 14.c3. } ( 14. c4 { is another interesting queenside break. The sharpest continuation is probably } 14... e5 $2 15. Re1 Bxa3 16. bxa3 O-O 17. Rxe5 bxc4 18. dxc4 Qc7 19. Bf4 Qxc4 { with unclear complications. White is a little more active, but Black has a passed pawn and a better structure. Lots of imbalance. Lots to play for. } ) 14... e6 { [%cal Rc3d4,Rf8a3][%csl Ra3]Holding the tension. Now White's best according to the engine is } 15. Nc2 { The human move. } 15... dxc3 16. bxc3 Be7 $15 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8,Yf8d8,Ya8c8][%csl Rd3,Rc3]A simple, yet promising plan for Black here is to simply castle and start targeting White's exposed central pawns. I recommend here ...Be7 instead of ...Bd6 because the bishop doesn't block the d-file on e7, but the latter move has some venom to it as well. The point being that after } ( 16... Bd6 { White has no time to be passive, as after something slow like } 17. Re1 $2 { Black lines up both on h2 and c3 with } 17... Qc7 { and ends up with a big advantage. In any case, White needs to be very careful in these lines. Their central pawns are weaknesses and it is not so easy to figure out how to consolidate them. I like Black's chances. } ) * 

