d ...h5 is to support the ...g5-g4 push. The ideal square for White's bishop is f3; we're trying to make it difficult for White to harmonize their pieces. } 14. Re1 { White brings the rook to the file. A few alternatives worth mentioning. White could try Finally, } ( 14. d3 { , which prevents ...g5. Black can simply redirect the focus back to the center } 14... Rd8 15. Re1 Bd5 16. Bd2 b6 $10 { Black has equality in this murky middlegame. } ) ( 14. Bf3 { would run right into } 14... g5 15. g3 g4 16. Bg2 Bd5 { It's not clear that White gets much out of weakening the light squares like this. } ) ( 14. f4 $2 { is an interesting alternative, again with the idea to stop ...g5. The funny thing is that Black can just continue with } 14... g5 $2 { anyways! } 15. fxg5 $2 Ng4 $146 16. Bxg4 hxg4 17. g3 d3 { Black has excellent play in this line. } ) 14... Bd5 { [%cal Be1e6][%csl Re6]Improving the bishop. If we play something else White can sacrifice on e6 in a number of lines, which would be uncomfortable. } 15. Bf3 { White challenges our control of the diagonal. } 15... Rd8 $13 { [%cal Be7e6,Yf6g4,Bf6d5,Bd8d5,Yh8h6,Gg7g5,Gh2h3,Yc7f4,Yc1b2]Black has a fine, yet unclear middlegame ahead. We have a space advantage and excellent central and kingside play. We might consider continuing with ...e6 to support the bishop on d5. Other ideas involve ...Rh6 and/or ...Ng4 to start probing White's kingside. In some positions we might lunge forth with ...g5 too. Black seems to be the one calling the shots in this position. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 7.Nxd4 Alt #2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 7.Nxd4 Alt #2"]
[Black "1) The Mainline | 4.exd5 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight, Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { [%cal Bf1b5,Bb5e2]This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 $1 { [%cal Bd2d4][%csl Rd4][%cal Bc6d4]Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. Nxd4 { White releases the central tension, probably wanting to preserve their bishop pair. } ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... cxd4 8. Nb5 { [%cal Bb5c7][%csl Re6,Re8,Ra8]White continues to make threats while avoiding danger. No one should play } ( 8. Nb1 $146 { , but it is a possibility. Black has a number of viable replies, but I particularly like } 8... d3 9. cxd3 Nh6 $146 10. Nc3 $146 Nf5 $146 { Where our knight will soon rest unopposed on d4, tormenting White's light squares. Black can then play ...g6 and ...Bg7 to add to our strong control of the center and has promising chances. } ) 8... Qd7 { The black monarch is forced to move yet again. Though unprincipled, this isn't problematic in this context. White has already moved their bishop twice, and once ...a6 arrives White will need to waste even more time navigating their knight to a desirable location. Therefore, both Black and White have wasted each other's time. } 9. O-O a6 10. Na3 Nf6 { [%cal Bd7c7,Bc8e6]The most flexible way to proceed. We don't want to yet commit to ...e6, as in some positions ...e5 would be a boon. } 11. Nc4 Qc7 12. a4 { Preventing ...b5. Now that this has been precluded, Black should focus on the center. } 12... Be6 { Since } ( 12... e5 { can lead to an early repetition after } 13. Re1 Bf5 14. Bf1 Bg4 15. Be2 Bf5 16. Bf1 { etc., I will offer ...Be6 here as an alternative for those interested avoiding a draw. } ) 13. d3 { White closes off the bishop from the queenside and supports the knight with the d pawn. } 13... g6 { [%cal Bf8g7]We won't be able to advance the e-pawn as long as the bishop is positioned on e6, so we can prepare to develop our dark squared bishop to g7 instead of the typical e7 square. } 14. Re1 Bg7 15. Bf3 { White improves their bishop. } 15... Bd5 $1 { [%cal Be1e6][%csl Re6]Challenging White's bishop. Once again, we should avoid giving White the opportunity to sacrifice on e6. } 16. Bg5 { We needn't worry about potential exchanges on d5. } ( 16. Bxd5 Nxd5 $146 17. Qf3 Rd8 { We should be glad to see this exchange, as White has traded off one of their best pieces and improved the positioning of our knight. Now it rests comfortably on d5, exerting pressures on the key central dark squares in White's territory. } ) 16... Rd8 $13 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8,Yd1e2,Yd5f3,Ga4a5]Simply supporting the bishop on d5. Black has a fine middlegame to look forward to. If White proceeds with If instead White opts for } 17. Qe2 { , now would be the time to capture f3 } ( 17. a5 { Black can simply castle and play for ...e5 } 17... O-O 18. Nb6 $146 Rfe8 19. Nxd5 $146 { If Bxf6 instead Black should respond with ...Bxf3. } 19... Nxd5 $146 20. Qd2 f6 21. Bh6 e5 $10 { Both sides have good play in these lines. } ) 17... Bxf3 { , as White will have wasted time moving the queen to e2 only to move her once again to recapture the bishop. } 18. Qxf3 Nd5 $146 { Black will castle and has great pawn play. We might try for ...b5 if White's rook leaves a1 and play for an eventual ...e5. } * 

