{ With an unclear, but fun position. Black has intentions to play ...h5 followed by ...Rh6! next to activate the rook. } ) 10... Nf6 { Inviting White to transpose with Nc4. } 11. Bf3 { [%cal Be7e5,Rf1e1]Suddenly, } 11... g5 $5 { «I'm always looking for the move that makes my opponent uncomfortable, even if it's not the best move. - Vasily Ivanchuk» In my campaign to unearth chaotic and confusing complications, I stumbled upon this exciting idea. If such is not to your tastes } ( 11... e5 { isn't so attractive. After } 12. Nc4 $146 Qc7 { Black would be playing a position similar to those found earlier in the chapter, but where White has an additional tempo because a4 hasn't been played. Moreover, it's easier for them to target our center because the bishop is already on f3, leaving the e-file open for the rook. Therefore, Black must adopt an approach unique to this specific move order. } ) ( 11... e6 { is a less interesting, though solid way to continue. It's worth noting that things can get sharp either way, for instance: } 12. Nc4 $146 Bc5 13. b4 $2 Ba7 14. a4 O-O 15. b5 Qc7 16. bxa6 Nd5 $146 { So one is not necessarily choosing a boring continuation with 11...e6. } ) 12. g3 { [%cal Bf3g2]This is White's only move to avoid being worse. It looks a little bit strange because it weakens the light squares around White's king and gives Black an eventual hook, but the idea is to make room for the bishop to retreat if Black ever tries ...g4. } ( 12. Nc4 $2 $146 { would be inaccurate due to } 12... Qc7 13. d3 g4 14. Be2 b5 15. Nd2 $146 h5 { where Black has an enormous space advantage and prospects on both sides of the board. } ) 12... Rb8 { [%cal Bb7b5]Moving off the diagonal, enabling ...b5, and possibly even foreshadowing a trade of light squared bishops at some point. } 13. Nc4 b5 { We should play this immediately so as to avoid Nb6-Nxc8. If you don't mind the exchange } ( 13... Bg7 { is playable too. } 14. Nb6 $146 Qc7 15. Nxc8 $146 Rxc8 { etc. This very well may be the simpler route. } ) 14. Ne5 ( 14. Na5 $146 { is also a possibility. Black can handle the Bc6 threat with } 14... Rb6 { and proceed with typical moves. } 15. d3 g4 16. Bg2 Bg7 17. Bd2 Nd5 $146 18. Re1 h5 { These lines are double-edged. Careful treatment of the queenside is probably necessary to maintain the balance. } ) 14... Qd6 15. Re1 { The possible } ( 15. Bc6+ { shouldn't bother us too much. } 15... Nd7 $146 { Simplifies matters. Now ...Qxe5 is threatened. Simplification is inevitable. } 16. Nxd7 $146 Bxd7 17. Bg2 d3 { Black's position begins to look for choice. } ) 15... Nd7 16. Nxd7 { Instead if } ( 16. Qe2 { Black can get a fine endgame with } 16... Nxe5 $146 17. Qxe5 Qxe5 18. Rxe5 h6 $10 ) 16... Bxd7 17. d3 { [%cal Rd4d3][%csl Rd3]If White doesn't play d3 here, Black will. } 17... h6 18. Bd2 Bg7 19. Qe2 Bf6 $13 { [%cal Bd7e6,Ye8g8,Bh8f8,Yg8g7,Bf8c8][%csl Ge6,Ge7,Gf7,Gf6]Black has ideas to play ...Be6, creating an impenetrable central bulwark, and to fight on both sides of the board. A game could continue with } 20. Be4 Rc8 21. Rac1 Kf8 22. a3 Be6 { Somehow this ...g5 line has resulted in an unclear positional middlegame. } * 

