e pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 8. d3 { [%cal Bf1e1][%csl Re6][%cal Rd2d3]This is slow and not in spirit of the position. Our queen is a target, after all. } 8... Nxe2+ { Exchanging on e2 previously was riskier because White was able to play d4 in one move. d3 is slow and consequently affords Black the time to exchange and complete development without much to worry about. } 9. Nxe2 { Be aware that } ( 9. Qxe2 $2 { affords Black a favorable endgame after } 9... Qxe2 10. Nxe2 $146 Bg4 { There's no viable way to stop Black from doubling White's pawns. Black has a slight advantage here. } ) 9... b6 $13 { [%cal Ye6d6,Ye6c6,Bc8b7,Be7e6,Bf8e7]Black has easy development, the bishops, and the open diagonals to form an attack with. One possible continuation could be: } 10. d4 $2 Bb7 11. Nf4 $146 { Taking on c5 instead allows Black to ruin White's kingside structure, giving Black good attacking chances. } 11... Qd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Nd3 $146 Qd5 { With White's bishop gone, orienting our pieces to the light squares is a formidable strategy indeed. Next comes typical development. } 14. Re1 e6 15. Bf4 Be7 16. Qe2 O-O { Black's control of the light squares is admirable. The bishop pair is a valuable asset to have in these sorts of positions, so Black has a comfortable advantage. } * 

