h ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Bd3 { Clearing the e-file. } 8... Qb6 { [%cal Bf1e1]A common idea, as will be soon observed. } 9. Nxd4 { We should always anticipate the potential exchange on d4. It's almost never a bad move. } 9... cxd4 10. Ne4 { The best move. Something like } ( 10. Ne2 $146 { is a bit slow, blocks off the e-file, and allows us to gain central space with } 10... e5 ) 10... Nxe4 11. Bxe4 e6 { [%cal Bc8d7,Bd7c6,Rc6e4][%csl Re4][%cal Bf8d6]We will develop with ...Bd7-Bc6 to exchange off White's light squared bishop and also ...Bd6 to clear the way for our king. We might castle either way. } 12. d3 Bd7 13. c3 dxc3 14. bxc3 Bd6 15. Be3 { Or if } ( 15. Qg4 { we can surge forth with } 15... f5 { and will castle queenside after } 16. Qxg7 O-O-O 17. Bf3 Rhg8 18. Qh6 Rg6 19. Qh4 Bc6 $10 { and the game is rich with dynamic potential. } ) 15... Qc7 $13 { [%cal Bc7h2][%csl Rh2][%cal Bd7c6][%csl Re4][%cal Ye8g8,Yh8f8]Pressuring h2. Black will continue with ...Bc6 and ...O-O and has a roughly equal position. } * 

