 investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Nxd4 { The dynamic shifts a bit if White chooses to exchange on d4 after castling. More options are available to both sides, but Black should not feel threatened. } 8... cxd4 9. Nb5 { [%cal Bb5c7][%csl Re6,Re8,Ra8]In this variation } ( 9. Bb5+ { is a possibility, but is rather innocuous. } 9... Bd7 ) ( 9. Re1 Qd6 { and Black has no complaints. } ) 9... Qd7 { We've seen this idea before in the 7.Nxd4 variations. } 10. c3 $5 { Other moves most likely will end up transposing to the variations found after 7.Nxd4. This move makes all the difference now that White has castled and is precisely why 7.Nxd4 and 8.Nxd4 warrant their own distinct set of variations. Looking back to 7... Nd4 7.Nxd4 cxd4 8.Nb5 Qd7 9.c3?! is much riskier. After 9...d3! 10.Bxd3 Qxd3 11.Nc7+ Kd8 White's king is extremely precarious. One slip up and it's game over, so White would be wise to exchange queens after 12.Nxa8 Bd7 13.Qe2 Qxe2+ 14.Kxe2 Kc8 but unfortunately for White this endgame is still much worse. Black will have two minor pieces for the rook. Castling before exchanging on d4 inoculates White from this much worse endgame and subjects Black to an exceptionally challenging middlegame if we come unprepared. The forthcoming positions are some of the sharpest in the chapter, so pay close attention. } 10... d3 $1 { [%cal Bb5d4,Bc3d4][%csl Rd4]The only move. White was threatening Nxd4. } 11. Bxd3 Qxd3 12. Nc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8 Bd7 { [%cal Bd7b5][%csl Bc3,Bb2,Bd2,Rc1,Ra1][%cal Bd8c8,Bc8b8,Bb8a8][%csl Ra8]Black vacates the path for the king to make his way to the bank. It's time to cash in. Our other chief idea involves maintaining control over the light squares on the central queenside, preventing White's development for as long as possible. } 14. Qb3 { White could try a number of other moves here, but generally if White doesn't develop their queen we can simply pursue the cornered steed with ...Kc8, etc. For instance, Alternatively, } ( 14. Re1 { White attempts to discontinue our queen's central blockade. } 14... Kc8 15. Re3 Qd6 16. d4 Kb8 { 17.c5 Qc7 White's queenside activity might appear dangerous, but isn't coordinated enough to do much. Our advantage should be apparent once development has been completed. } 17. c4 Kxa8 ) ( 14. c4 $2 { is an interesting attempt, where again Black simply pursues the knight } 14... Kc8 15. Qb3 { White has developed their queen, therefore we should insist on maintaining our bind on the center. } 15... Bf5 16. Qa4 { is an interesting attempt. } 16... Kb8 17. Nc7 $2 $146 Kxc7 18. Qxa7 e6 { Black should simply develop as usual and is better due to being up an exchange. White needs to be careful about getting too aggressive. } 19. a4 $2 Bd6 20. a5 $2 Ng4 $146 { None of White's pieces are available to defend his king. White is lost. } ) 14... Bb5 { [%csl Rb7][%cal Bd7b5,Bb5f1][%csl Rf1]Simultaneously attacking and defending. } 15. Re1 e6 16. c4 { [%csl Re1]White doesn't have much of a choice here. Their rook is tied down to the first rank. Their queenside is immobilized. Their queen has no appealing moves. } ( 16. a4 { is the next best move, but doesn't accomplish much. } 16... Bc6 17. Re3 Qf5 { Black will play ...Be6 and attack White's king. This is lost for White. 16.c4 is the only viable way to loosen our queen's grip on the center. } ) 16... Qxc4 17. Qxc4 $6 { Simplifying the position doesn't make things any easier for White. } 17... Bxc4 18. d3 { [%cal Bc1e3,Be3a7,Rc1f4,Ra8c7]White exerts great efforts to rescue the stranded steed. } 18... Bd5 19. Bf4 Kd7 { [%cal Bf8d6]} 20. Nc7 Bc6 $19 { [%cal Bf6h5][%csl Rb5,Rd5]The knight will not escape. Black is winning. } * 

