but generally if White doesn't develop their queen we can simply pursue the cornered steed with ...Kc8, etc. For instance, Alternatively, } ( 14. Re1 { White attempts to discontinue our queen's central blockade. } 14... Kc8 15. Re3 Qd6 16. d4 Kb8 { 17.c5 Qc7 White's queenside activity might appear dangerous, but isn't coordinated enough to do much. Our advantage should be apparent once development has been completed. } 17. c4 Kxa8 ) ( 14. c4 $2 { is an interesting attempt, where again Black simply pursues the knight } 14... Kc8 15. Qb3 { White has developed their queen, therefore we should insist on maintaining our bind on the center. } 15... Bf5 16. Qa4 { is an interesting attempt. } 16... Kb8 17. Nc7 $2 $146 Kxc7 18. Qxa7 e6 { Black should simply develop as usual and is better due to being up an exchange. White needs to be careful about getting too aggressive. } 19. a4 $2 Bd6 20. a5 $2 Ng4 $146 { None of White's pieces are available to defend his king. White is lost. } ) 14... Bb5 { [%cal Bb5f1][%csl Rf1,Rb7]Simultaneously attacking and defending. } 15. Re1 e6 16. c4 { White doesn't have much of a choice here. Their rook is tied down to the first rank. Their queenside is immobilized. Their queen has no appealing moves. } ( 16. a4 { is the next best move, but doesn't accomplish much. } 16... Bc6 17. Re3 Qf5 { Black will play ...Be6 and attack White's king. This is lost for White. 16.c4 is the only viable way to loosen our queen's grip on the center. } ) 16... Qxc4 17. Qe3 { With our king in the center, White may surmise that keeping queens on the board offers the best chances. If } ( 17. d3 { Black should trade queens and keep the pace. } 17... Qxb3 18. axb3 Bb4 19. Re5 Ba6 20. Ra4 Bd6 { Black will have a winning advantage if White fails to find Rea5, with the idea to eventually sacrifice on a6. These lines are all rather high-level. } ) 17... Bc6 { We deliberately tempt White to take a7. It looks so alluring to try save the knight, close the distance between their queen and our king, and to secure a pawn all in one move! Who could possibly decline such an opportunity? } 18. Qxa7 { Taking a7 looks greedy, but Black actually has a forced win if White tries something else. For instance, White might try } ( 18. Qe5 $2 Bb4 $3 { this subtle move secures the win! The idea is that it prepares ...Qg4, where White won't have a repetition. } 19. a3 Qg4 20. f3 Bxf3 21. Qc7+ Ke8 22. Qc8+ Ke7 { Notice that White doesn't have Qc5+ here due to the bishop on Bb4! If Black mistakenly starts with 18. Qe5 18...Qg4? White will be able to take a draw precisely because the c5 square is unprotected. 19.f3 Bxf3 20.Qc7+ Ke8 21.Qc8+ Ke7 22.Qc5+ etc. Finally, 19... Bb4 19.Qg3 doesn't stop Black from playing 19...Qg4! Black will still be winning after the queen trade. 20.Qxg4 Nxg4 The cornered steed is doomed and White's state of development is abysmal. } ) ( 18. Qg3 $2 { instead of Qe5, but this won't change the evaluation. } 18... Qg4 $3 { White will be forced to eventually trade queens into a similar lost position to the one discussed prior. } 19. Qc7+ Ke8 20. Qc8+ Ke7 21. Qc7+ Nd7 $146 { The queen must return to g3 to stop mate. } ) 18... Bc5 $1 { [%cal Bc6g2,Bc5g1,Bc4f1][%csl Rg1,Ye1,Yc1,Ya1,Ra7][%cal Bc5a7]Black's pieces are beautifully placed. It seems incredibly difficult to defend White's king from the forthcoming assault. } 19. Qb8+ { A tempting mistake. Qa4+ was the only move! } 19... Ke7 20. Qc7+ Nd7 $19 { [%cal Bh8a8,Bc6g2,Bc5f2]Black's development is simply overwhelming. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 8.Nxd4 / 10.c3 #4"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 8.Nxd4 / 10.c3 #4"]
[Black "1) The Mainline | 4.exd5 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 { Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. O-O ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Nxd4 { The dynamic slightly shifts if White chooses to exchange on d4 after castling. } 8... cxd4 9. Nb5 { [%cal Bb5c7][%csl Re6,Re8,Ra8]In this variation } ( 9. Bb5+ { is a possibility, but is rather innocuous. } 9... Bd7 ) ( 9. Re1 Qd6 { and Black has no complaints. } ) 9... Qd7 { We've seen this idea before in the 7.Nxd4 variations. } 10. c3 { Other moves most likely will end up transposing to the variations found after 7.Nxd4. This move makes all the difference now that White has castled and is precisely why 7.Nxd4 and 8.Nxd4 warrant their own distinct set of variations. Looking back to 7... Nd4 7.Nxd4 cxd4 8.Nb5 Qd7 9.c3?! is much riskier. After 9...d3! 10.Bxd3 Qxd3 11.Nc7+ Kd8 White's king is extremely precarious. One slip up and it's game over, so White would be wise to exchange queens after 12.Nxa8 Bd7 13.Qe2 Qxe2+ 14.Kxe2 Kc8 but unfortunately for White this endgame is still much worse. Black will have two minor pieces for the rook. Castling before exchanging on d4 inoculates White from this much worse endgame and subjects Black to an exceptionally challenging middlegame if we come unprepared. The forthcoming positions are some of the sharpest in the chapter, so pay close attention. } 10... d3 { The only move. White was threatening Nxd4. } 11. Bxd3 Qxd3 12. Nc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8 Bd7 { [%cal Bd8c8,Bc8b8,Bb8a8,Bd7b5][%csl Rd2,Rc3,Rb2,Yc1,Ya1]Black vacates the path for the king to make his way to the bank. It's time to cash in. Our other chief idea involves maintaining control over the light squares on the central queenside, preventing White's development for as long as possible. } 