to try save the knight, close the distance between their queen and our king, and to secure a pawn all in one move! Who could possibly decline such an opportunity? } 18. Qxa7 { Taking a7 looks greedy, but Black actually has a forced win if White tries something else. For instance, White might try } ( 18. Qe5 $2 Bb4 $3 { this subtle move secures the win! The idea is that it prepares ...Qg4, where White won't have a repetition. } 19. a3 Qg4 20. f3 Bxf3 21. Qc7+ Ke8 22. Qc8+ Ke7 { Notice that White doesn't have Qc5+ here due to the bishop on Bb4! If Black mistakenly starts with 18. Qe5 18...Qg4? White will be able to take a draw precisely because the c5 square is unprotected. 19.f3 Bxf3 20.Qc7+ Ke8 21.Qc8+ Ke7 22.Qc5+ etc. Finally, 19... Bb4 19.Qg3 doesn't stop Black from playing 19...Qg4! Black will still be winning after the queen trade. 20.Qxg4 Nxg4 The cornered steed is doomed and White's state of development is abysmal. } ) ( 18. Qg3 $2 { instead of Qe5, but this won't change the evaluation. } 18... Qg4 $3 { White will be forced to eventually trade queens into a similar lost position to the one discussed prior. } 19. Qc7+ Ke8 20. Qc8+ Ke7 21. Qc7+ Nd7 $146 { The queen must return to g3 to stop mate. } ) 18... Bc5 { Black's pieces are beautifully placed. It seems incredibly difficult to defend White's king from the forthcoming assault. } 19. Qa5+ Ke8 { Not } ( 19... Ke7 $2 { because of } 20. d4 Bb4 21. Qc7+ { where White's knight manages to escape in the end. } ) 20. Nc7+ { White should not try to save the knight. d4 is the only move. See 20.d4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to learn more about this continuation. } 20... Kd7 { [%cal Bc4d4,Bc5b6,Bb6c7,Bb6a5][%csl Ra5,Rc7][%cal Bb6f2][%csl Rf2]Please avoid } ( 20... Ke7 $2 21. d3 { and now if we try } 21... Qg4 $2 22. Qxc5+ { White captures with tempo on our king. After 20...Kd7 Black has all sorts of winning threats. For instance ...Qd4 followed by ...Bb6. } ) 21. d3 { White really has nothing here. }