possible. } 14. Qb3 { White could try a number of other moves here, but generally if White doesn't develop their queen we can simply pursue the cornered steed with ...Kc8, etc. For instance, Alternatively, } ( 14. Re1 { White attempts to discontinue our queen's central blockade. } 14... Kc8 15. Re3 Qd6 16. d4 Kb8 { 17.c5 Qc7 White's queenside activity might appear dangerous, but isn't coordinated enough to do much. Our advantage should be apparent once development has been completed. } 17. c4 Kxa8 ) ( 14. c4 $2 { is an interesting attempt, where again Black simply pursues the knight } 14... Kc8 15. Qb3 { White has developed their queen, therefore we should insist on maintaining our bind on the center. } 15... Bf5 16. Qa4 { is an interesting attempt. } 16... Kb8 17. Nc7 $2 $146 Kxc7 18. Qxa7 e6 { Black should simply develop as usual and is better due to being up an exchange. White needs to be careful about getting too aggressive. } 19. a4 $2 Bd6 20. a5 $2 Ng4 $146 { None of White's pieces are available to defend his king. White is lost. } ) 14... Bb5 { [%cal Bb5f1][%csl Rf1,Rb7]Simultaneously attacking and defending. } 15. Re1 e6 16. a4 $2 { This move is not a good use of time. White seriously underestimates our attacking potential. } 16... Bc6 { [%cal Bc6g2,Bf8d6,Bd6h2,Rf6g4,Rd3f5]We redirect our bishop to target White's bare kingside, which his scattered queenside pieces cannot meaningfully supply a defense to. White is embracing an exceptionally dangerous attack if they opt for this 16.a4 line. } 17. Re3 Qf5 18. d4 Bd6 { [%cal Bd6h2,Bf6g4]Black threatens the brutal 19.-- ...Bxh2+ 20.Kxh2 Ng4+ } 19. h3 ( 19. Kh1 Qxf2 $19 ) 19... Qg6 { [%cal Bg6g2,Bc6g2][%csl Rg2][%cal Bf5g6,Bg6f5]Inducing further weaknesses. Once the kingside is sufficiently tender, we go in for the kill. On another note: As a general rule, if it's unclear how to proceed Black can always rely on the simple ...Kd7 followed by ...Rxa8. } 20. g3 { If } ( 20. f3 { Black invades with } 20... Qg3 21. Kf1 Qh2 { and the impending ...Bg3 will end the game. } ) 20... Qf5 $19 { [%cal Bf5h3]Black has slowly and methodically razed White's kingside. } 21. g4 { is the only move to delay the resignation. After } 21... Qf4 22. Kf1 Qh2 { White won't be surviving for long. This is the sort of attack we can expect if White misses 16.c4. It is imperative that they get their queenside pieces into the game. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 8.Nxd4 / 9.Bb5+"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 8.Nxd4 / 9.Bb5+"]
[Black "1) The Mainline | 4.exd5 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 { Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. O-O ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Nxd4 { The dynamic slightly shifts if White chooses to exchange on d4 after castling. } 8... cxd4 9. Bb5+ { This too is possible following the exchange on d4. Players from the black side seem to not know what to do from here, so it might be worth remembering this position. } 9... Bd7 10. Re1 Qd6 $1 { [%cal Bd6d7][%csl Rb5,Rc3]Keeping contact with the bishop. Now we force White's hand, as the bishop and knight are both under attack. } 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Ne4 Nxe4 { Simplifying the game. If we're in the mood for something wild, } ( 12... O-O-O $2 { is a move too. Just putting that on your radar. Feel free to experiment to see what works for you. } ) 13. Rxe4 e6 14. d3 Be7 { There are already a number of moves which are 0.0 here, so it's quite equal already. I like ...Be7 because we prepare ...O-O and want to eventually play ...Rc8. ...Bc5 would block the file. } 15. Qg4 { [%cal Rg4g7,Rg4d4][%csl Rd4,Rg7]White attacks d4 and g7. This is probably the most testing line, as Black will have a very slight advantage if White plays anything else. } 15... Bf6 $1 { [%csl Rg7,Rd4]The critical response. The bishop ties together our kingside. } 16. Bg5 { White aims to trade off the bishop. We will use this opportunity to simplify the position and get castled. } 16... Bxg5 17. Qxg5 O-O $10 { [%cal Ba8c8,Bf8d8]White has a little more activity, but Black is solid. We have a target along the c-file and can proceed by centralizing our rooks. White may try to attack our kingside, but it's hard to accomplish anything substantive when the position is so balanced. } * 

