. 9....e6 is much simpler and resembles middlegames we've already acquainted ourselves with. } ) 10. a5 { Sending the queen back home. } 10... Qd8 11. b3 { [%cal Be2b5,Be2d3,Bd3c4,Yc1b2,Yb2a3]White intends on developing the queenside, but also remains flexible. } ( 11. d3 { would lock the light squared bishop into the kingside and temporarily prevent it from relocating to a useful square. } ) 11... Be7 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8]} 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Bd3 { [%cal Bb2g7,Bd3h7]Keeping the tension and improving piece placement. } 13... Nxb3 $5 { [%csl Rd3,Yb3,Bc2,Bh7][%cal Yd4b3]Introducing complications, as usual. } ( 13... Bd7 { is probably the safer move if we want a more typical middlegame, with ...Bc6, ...Rc8, and maybe an eventual ...e5 incoming if conditions permit. } ) 14. Bxh7+ Nxh7 15. cxb3 ( 15. Ne5 $146 { Be8 16.Re3! with the idea to swing the rook over to h3. With ...f6 we stop Ne5 and prepare ...e5. We can stop here, as the game is already rather complex and White can continue in a number of ways. Black's ideas are as follows: Play ...e5 sooner than later to blunt White's bishop. Pair this with ...Rf7 or ...Re8, giving our knight a route to get back in the game. ...Rf7 is probably a little better in most contexts, as in some positions we will want to swing the rook over to the semi-open e-file. With the rook on the 7th rank we might play consider a possible ...g6 in some positions to swing the rook over to the g & h-files too. As for the queenside, ...b6 followed by ...Bb7 is a noteworthy idea. Black's position is a bit clunky to be fair, but White's queenside in disorganized and their center pawn is a target. It's an unclear position with chances for both sides. } ) 15... f6 $13 { [%cal Ge6e5,Gf8e8,Gf8f7,Bh7f8,Yb7b6,Yc8b7,Gf7d7][%csl Re5]} ( 15... Bd7 { was my original preference, but it seems that White can get an initiative with } ) * 

