Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 { Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. O-O ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Re1 { Re1 is critical and is to be expected as the most popular continuation. } 8... Qb6 9. a4 { The persistent harassment of our queen is how White should proceed. However, a4 is quite uncommon so let's examine a few other ideas White might be attracted to following 8...Qb6. Two other key moves, 9.d3 and 9.Bc4, will be explored later in this chapter. } ( 9. Nxd4 $146 { has nuances worth exploring. For instance, after } 9... cxd4 10. Na4 $146 Qd6 11. Bf3 { Black has a number of compelling ideas, including ...g5!?, but } 11... h5 { looks particularly alluring. Black can produce an attack after } 12. d3 Ng4 $146 13. h3 Qh2+ 14. Kf1 Ne5 $146 { Black is playing for ...g5! For instance, } 15. Nc5 $146 g5 16. Bxg5 Rg8 { . White is holding things together for now, but I would much rather be on the attacking side of this. } ) 9... e6 { The engine at first finds } ( 9... a6 { to be favorable, but White has } 10. a5 Qc7 { and then } 11. Ra4 { The critical move. } 11... Bd7 { Black is already in big trouble. } 12. Nxd4 $146 Bxa4 13. Ne6 $3 $146 { An incredible positional sacrifice! } 13... fxe6 14. Nxa4 $146 Qxa5 15. b3 e5 { Our weaknesses make prime targets for White's bishops and untangling the kingside is no menial task. A computer might be able to hold this, but this is not the sort of position we should be going for. Instead, 11. Ra4 11...e5!? might offer Black better chances, but if White finds the correct continuation they will be better. 12.Nxe5 Bd6 13.Nf3! O-O 14.Nxd4! Bxh2+ 15.Kh1 cxd4 16.Rxd4 Bd6 17.d3 Be6 18.Bf3 This certainly isn't lost, but White's advantage isn't trivial either. 9....e6 is much simpler and resembles middlegames we've already acquainted ourselves with. } ) 10. a5 { Sending the queen back home. } 10... Qd8 11. b3 { White intends on developing the queenside, but also remains flexible. } ( 11. d3 { would lock the light squared bishop into the kingside and temporarily prevent it from relocating to a useful square. } ) 11... Be7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Nxd4 { We should be prepared for this exchange at any moment. White probably won't want to hold the tension indefinitely. } 13... cxd4 14. Nb5 e5 { Covering d4. Naturally, Black would like to proceed by evicting the knight from its b4 post with ...a6 and expanding in the center further with ...e4. } 15. a6 { White anticipates our intentions to play ...a6 by doing so themselves. } 15... Qd7 { [%cal Be2f3][%csl Rb5]This move might look a little strange, but it dissuades White from opting for the otherwise attractive Bf3. Now if White wants to avail themselves of this resource, they will need to voluntarily withdraw their knight from Black's territory. } 16. Na3 Bc5 { [%cal Bf8e8,Be8e1][%csl Rd4,Re5]Black improves the bishop and enables our e-pawn to enlist the support of our rook. } 17. Nc4 Re8 18. axb7 { [%cal Bb7b5][%csl Rc4]Black has ...b5 as an active possibility, so White doesn't have time to play something passive. } 18... Bxb7 19. Bf1 e4 $13 { [%cal Yd2d3,Yc5b4,Ye4e3]I like Black's position. White's pieces are lacking in mobility due to our oppressive center and our pieces are mostly active. The d3 break can be met with ...Bb4 and ...e3. } * 

