. Instead, 9....e6 is much simpler and resembles middlegames we've already acquainted ourselves with. } ) 10. Nxd4 { We should be prepared for this exchange at any moment. White probably won't want to hold the tension indefinitely. } 10... cxd4 11. Ne4 Bd7 { Preventing tactical shenanigans. If White chooses to exchange knights on move ten, our king becomes vulnerable along the a4-e8 diagonal. Protection is necessary at this juncture. } 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. a5 Qc7 14. a6 b6 { Closing down the queenside. } ( 14... bxa6 { allows White to activate their rook. } ) 15. Bf3 { [%cal Bf3a8][%csl Ra8,Rb7,Rc6]White hopes to exploit the weak light squares on our queenside. } 15... Rd8 16. c3 { Or if } ( 16. d3 { Black's play is natural enough. } 16... Bd6 17. h3 Rc8 { Black can apparently even sacrifice the exchange with } 18. Bb7 Rg8 $2 19. Bxc8 Qxc8 20. Re4 e5 { Black is dong fine here and White probably won't be able to hold onto the extra material for long. Many of these lines are incredibly unclear. } ) 16... Bd6 17. h3 { Or, if White gives up on h2 with } ( 17. cxd4 { Black has } 17... Bxh2+ 18. Kh1 Qf4 { with a bizarre sort of computer-ish equality on the horizon. } 19. Re4 Qh6 20. Bh5 Bf4 21. d3 Bxc1 22. Rxc1 Ke7 $10 ) 17... Bh2+ { Forcing White's king into the corner. The extra tempo it takes for the king to return to the center when the position has been simplified to the endgame might make a difference later. } 18. Kh1 Be5 $13 { Black simply consolidates the center and holds the tension. The game might proceed with } 19. Qe2 Bc6 20. Bxc6+ Qxc6 21. Qe4 { Leela thinks White should reduce the position to an endgame. Otherwise it's not clear how White is supposed to coordinate their inactive queenside pieces without losing material. } 21... Qxe4 22. Rxe4 Ke7 { with an equal but imbalanced endgame. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 9.Bc4 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.exd5 with 6.Be2 / 9.Bc4 #1"]
[Black "1) The Mainline | 4.exd5 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. Nc3 { White develops with tempo. This is the obvious and most popular response to ...Qxd5. Time is everything here. Remember, the primary function of Bb5 was to attempt to injure Black's structure by exchanging on c6. However, with the recent exchange on d5 Black's queen has managed to centralize to a location wherefrom she can defend the knight. As long as Black's queen remains in contact with the c6 square, White will be unable to inflict a brutal blow to Black's queenside structure by capturing the knight. Therefore, while the queen defends the knight Black would love to play ...a6 to force White to either commit to the exchange or break the pin. In one moderately popular continuation, namely } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 $146 { , Black has time for } 6... a6 { and will be equal. This line illustrates the importance of time. Black gains time with the slow Ne2, which accomplishes little apart from breaking the check. A similar motif applies to White's other responses. Observe that after ...Qe6+ White can either block with the queen, the knight, or the bishop. If the queen blocks 6... Qe6+ 6.Qe2 Black can exchange queens 6...Qxe2+ 7.Nxe2 Bd7! and the bishop arrives on d7 just in time to prevent White from proceeding with their intended plan. Finally, if the bishop retreats 6... Qe6+ 6.Be2 Black has successfully circumvented White's ploy to destroy the queenside structure. Each position comes with its own nuances, which will all be analyzed in turn, but in each of them White's positional machinations have been foiled! Thus marks the theme of the position: Prevent White from damaging the queenside structure. } ) 5... Qe6+ { Make a mental note of this position. } 6. Be2 { This is the most accurate continuation. Stockfish thinks that if White is allowed to castle and play d4 Black is doomed. Black must play with precision if he is to emerge with an acceptable position. } ( 6. Be2 { is the critical response, which is not immediately obvious given that White has already moved their bishop. At the time of writing Be2 is played 13% of the time. } ) 6... Nd4 { Black thematically clogs up the center before White has the opportunity to blast it open with d4. Be aware that under most conditions Black's knight should remain seated on d4, intrusively disturbing White's territory for as long as it can. Do not be tempted to exchange it either on f3 or e2 until the kingside is developed and the king castled. Development is more important at the present time. There are few conditions under which the early exchange would be justified, one notable scenario being: } 7. O-O ( 7. O-O Nf6 $146 8. d3 $2 { With White investing time into advancing the pawn to d3, Black gains time. Now if White eventually intends on opening up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Re1 { [%cal Be1e6,Be2b5]Re1 is critical and is to be expected as the most popular continuation. } 8... Qb6 $1 9. Bc4 { [%cal Bd2d3,Ye7e6,Yf8e7,Yc8d7]White relocates their bishop to a more favorable square before committing to the center with d3. Black's treatment of the position largely remains unchanged. We will continue with ...e6 and ...Be7. } 9... e6 { The solid move. A risky alternative worth mentioning is } ( 9... Bf5 $2 { I'm not so sure the bishop belongs on the kingside, but it's worth considering. I think it would be better placed somewhere on the a8-h1 diagonal, so I typically like to maneuver it to c6 with ...Bd7-c6. Anyways, after ...Bf5 Black's idea is to block White's bishop off with ...e6 and then build pressure on f3 with ...Bg4. However, the problem is that White has } 10. Nxd4 $146 cxd4 11. Qf3 { and suddenly Black's position begins to look a bit uncomfortable. } 11... Bg4 12. Bb5+ { Black is forced to move the king. } 12... Kd8 13. Qd3 { White looks to be a bit better. } ) 10. d3 Be7 11. Bg5 ( 11. Bf4 { might also be encountered, fighting for control of e5. } 11... O-O 12. Be5 Nc6 $146 { Black will exchange on e5 if permitted and continue by playing on the queenside, eventually making use of the a1-h8 and h2-b8 diagonals. } ) 11... h6 { We should wait to see if White intends on taking the knight before deciding which way to castle. } 12. Bxf6 { If } ( 12. Bh4 { Black can continue to target the bishop } 12... Nf5 $146 13. Bg3 Nxg3 $146 14. hxg3 O-O { with a somewhat imbalanced middlegame ahead. } ) 12... gxf6 { [%cal Rc8d7,Be8c8,Ba8d8,Ye8f8,Bb6b2][%csl Rb2][%cal Rh8g8,Rh6h5,Rh5h4,Rh4h3]Black now can lob Harry down the board and aim for complications along the semi-open g-file. Black may castle to the queenside, or the king might remain in the center depending on the demands of the forthcoming positions. } 13. Rb1 { Covering b2, but this is rather slow. Alternatively, White might try to immediately clarify the position with } ( 13. Nxd4 $146 cxd4 14. Ne2 $146 h5 $2 15. c3 dxc3 16. bxc3 h4 { White has eventual ideas of sacrificing on e6. Both sides need to be careful. These middlegames can get extremely sharp. } ) 13... h5 { [%cal Bh5h4,Bh4h3,Bh6h5]Black wastes no time attempting to establish that White's king is the more vulnerable monarch. } 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Ne4 Bd7 16. c3 O-O-O $17 { [%cal Bh5h4,Rf6f5,Rd7c6,Bc8b8,Bh8g8,Bd8g8,Rc6g2][%csl Yg2]Black's attacking prospects look promising. Meanwhile, even though we have castled queenside, White doesn't have a direct way of counterattacking without making concessions. A game might proceed with } 17. Qc1 $2 { hoping for counterplay along the c-file, but Black can simply step aside } 17... Kb8 18. Qf4+ e5 19. Qf3 Bg4 20. Qg3 Qc7 { disallowing any tricks with the pin. } 21. h3 f5 22. hxg4 hxg4 $2 { Black sacrifices the bishop for a monstrous pawn storm! } 23. Nd2 $2 $146 Bd6 { and White has permission to resign. } * 

