ng up the center with d4 they will have used a total of two moves to complete the task. After } 8... Nxe2+ $146 9. Nxe2 $146 b6 { Black has excellent prospects. Contrastively, if Black were to exchange prior to d3 7\. O-O 7...Nxe2+ 8.Nxe2 b6 9.d4! White's lead in development is much more intimidating. } ) 7... Nf6 { While it is playable here, I would advise against } ( 7... Nxe2+ $146 { There's no need to exchange our most active piece without being prompted to do so. This would just make the position more difficult for Black, as White will be able to quickly open up the center and capitalize on their lead in development. To reiterate, one of the few conditions under which it is advisable to take the bishop this early is when White responds to 6...Nd4 with 7.d3, where White's inability to play d4 in one move forces them to lose time. See the following variation for more information: 4.6.Be2 with 8.d3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) However, if you are so inclined as to take the bishop do be aware that after } 8. Nxe2 $146 { the most accurate way to proceed is } 8... Qa6 { , freeing the e-pawn and light-squared bishop. a6 is the appropriate square for the queen because from a6 she can safely snipe at White's central light squares. In this position most people respond with } 9. Re1 { and now the bishop flies in. } 9... Bg4 { The queen's position on a6 suddenly makes sense. If White moves the knight on e2 Black can respond with ...Qc6 to increase the pressure on f3 and has an equal game. White's best ploy to try for an advantage is } 10. Ne5 $146 { upon which an exchange is prompted. } 10... Bxe2 11. Rxe2 f6 12. Nf3 $146 e6 { In the resulting position White has a quiet advantage which is slight, but noticeable. The computer has a slight preference for this continuation over 7...Nf6, but it doesn't look like Black is playing for much here. At least with ...Nf6 we keep more pieces on the board and drag White into a bizarre and complicated middlegame in which error is almost a certainty. Take note of the fact that 8... Nxe2+ 8.Qxe2 Qxe2 9.Nxe2 Bg4! gives Black a slight advantage, as there is no way for White to prevent us from corrupting their structure with ...Bxf3. There are numerous opportunities for White to slip up after 7...Nxe2+, so this line might be worth experimenting with if 7...Nf6 isn't producing the results you want. } ) 8. Re1 { [%cal Be1e6,Be2b5]Re1 is critical and is to be expected as the most popular continuation. } 8... Qb6 $1 9. d3 { d3 is the simplest and perhaps the most natural move to continue with. I see this often in my blitz games. } 9... e6 10. Ne5 { [%csl Be6,Bf7,Bg7,Bh7,Re5,Gd4]Ne5 is a common idea in some openings which result in similar kingside pawn structures. Black has control of d4 here though, so White must maintain the knight's outpost by some other means than through the support of their d-pawn. } 10... Qc7 { [%cal Bf8d6,Bc7h2][%csl Re5,Rd6]Ne5 can often be met with ...Qc7 and ...Bd6. } 11. Bh5 { [%cal Be1e5][%csl Re5][%cal Bh5f7][%csl Rf7][%cal Be5f7,Be2h5]White defends the knight by initiating a counterattack. This is White's strongest attempt. Another way to defend the knight might be: } ( 11. Bf3 Bd6 12. Bf4 { Black can simply castle here, but } 12... h5 $2 { is more to my taste. } 13. h3 $2 g5 { White needs to tread with caution. } 14. Bg3 g4 15. hxg4 hxg4 16. Bxg4 b6 17. Bf3 Bb7 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. a4 O-O-O { with another sharp middlegame ahead. } ) 11... Nxh5 12. Qxh5 g6 13. Qh4 { [%cal Bh4e7][%csl Re7,Rf6,Rg5,Rh6]Lingering on the dark squares where Black is weak. } 13... Bg7 14. Ng4 Nf5 $1 15. Bf4 { One might also consider Alternatively, } ( 15. Nf6+ $2 $146 Kf8 16. Ncd5 $146 Nxh4 $146 { Such positions are rich with tactical opportunities! Black has the better end of the tactics in this case. } 17. Nxc7 $146 Bxf6 18. Bh6+ Kg8 $2 19. Nxa8 $146 Nf5 $146 20. Bf4 Kg7 21. Nc7 $146 g5 22. Be5 Bd7 { Black prevents the knight from escaping and is consequently moderately better. } ) ( 15. Qg5 { is also worth consideration, and after } 15... h6 16. Qf4 Qd8 17. Ne3 $146 Nd4 $146 18. Ne4 $146 O-O 19. c3 e5 { Black has a slight edge, but the position is exceedingly sharp. } ) 15... Qc6 16. Qh3 f6 $1 { [%cal Be6e5,Bh7h5]With the bishop on f4, now is a prime opportunity to initiate our thematic ...f6-e5 sequence. ...h5 is also a formidable idea in some positions. } 17. Ne4 O-O $13 { [%cal Be6e5,Bh7h5][%csl Rg4,Rf4]Black would love to evict the knight with ...h5 and lay claim to the center with ...e5, if allowed. Therefore, White should proceed with } 18. Nh6+ $146 Kh8 { but } 19. g4 $2 { is perhaps too ambitious } 19... Nd4 $146 20. Bd6 Bd7 $3 { Black sacrifices the exchange! If White takes, they will be much worse: } 21. Bxc5 e5 22. Bxf8 $2 Rxf8 { now White's knight on h6 is trapped and will be lost after some tactics involving ...Ne6-g5. } * 

