 If White plays h3 we have a different hook. Defending is not going to be easy. } 13. h3 { The computer at first confusedly praises the bold Alternatively, After giving it some thought, the engine favors the curious looking } ( 13. g3 $2 { but after } 13... h4 14. Bg2 Kf8 { it is evident that its initial appraisal was mistaken. Black can bring the knight to h5 and has good chances playing against White's tenderized kingside. } ) ( 13. h4 $2 { gives Black a pleasant advantage: } 13... b6 14. a4 a6 15. g3 { Fortunately for us, this weakening move is best for White. It wouldn't be wise to allow our bishop to control so much of the board unopposed. } 15... Bb7 16. Bg2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 O-O { White's kingside is weak and they don't really have a way to improve their position. } ) ( 13. a4 { , which voluntarily walks right into } 13... Ng4 $146 { Only one move saves White here. } 14. Nd5 $3 $146 Qb8 15. Bg3 f5 16. c3 O-O $2 { Frankly, this entire sequence is a bit ridiculous. Few would be able to extract equality from the mess without assistance from a computer. } ) 13... b6 { [%cal Bc8b7]} 14. Bg3 { [%cal Bf2f4]One unlikely but notable idea is } ( 14. Nb1 $146 { and after } 14... Nd5 $146 15. Bh2 f6 16. c3 Bxe5 17. Bxe5 fxe5 18. cxd4 exd4 { Black has a slight edge. } ) 14... Bb7 15. f4 g5 $3 { [%cal Bf6d7,Bc7h2][%csl Re5]Black has a dangerous initiative. A game might continue with } 16. fxg5 Nd7 $146 17. Nxd7 $146 Bxg3 18. Nf6+ $146 Kf8 { Black is threatening ...Bxe1 Qxe1 ...Nxc2, so } 19. Rc1 Bf3 $2 $3 { White is getting slaughtered. See the tactics chapter (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to see how Black converts. } * 

