1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { [%cal Bd8d5,Bc8d7,Bd7g4][%csl Re4]Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { [%cal Ba7a6][%csl Rb5]I received some comments noting that I haven't addressed rare non-critical deviations in this position. To touch up on a theme discussed earlier, if it were Black's turn in this position ...a6 would be the move to play. Since the queen now covers c6 we should start asking White questions about the placement of their bishop. Naturally then, slow moves such as } 5. Qe2 $5 { White's idea here is to meet ...a6 with Nc3, where Black won't be able to check White's king with ...Qe6 anymore. In this case, ...Bg4 is the appropriate response. } ( 5. d3 { can swiftly be met with } 5... a6 { Even considering that } 6. Bc4 { arrives with tempo on our queen, after } 6... Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 $146 { Black has equality at least. Stockfish even gives Black a slight edge there. White has lost as much time as Black has because they have moved their bishop twice. If instead White tries 6... a6 6.Ba4 Black can preempt Nc3 with 6...Qd6 and proceed with typical moves. 7.Nbd2 b5! 8.Bb3 Nf6 9.a4 Bb7= Black has no issues here. Of course, exchanging on c6 affords Black an easy game as well: 6... a6 6.Bxc6+ Qxc6= A similar tale can be told for 5... Qxd5 5.c3 a6! White should give up the bishop here and be satisfied with an equal game. 6.Bxc6+ Qxc6 7.d4! Other moves afford Black the time to play ...Bg4. 7...cxd4 8.cxd4 Taking with the pawn is essential here. Nxd4 drops g2 and Qxd4 allows Black to strike with the typical ...f6-e5. 8...Nf6= White is the one fighting for equality in these lines. They have an IQP but insufficient activity to play for an attack. If we see the bishop retreat on move six: 6... a6 6.Ba4 White could get into serious trouble. 6...Qe4+!? The king is forced to move. 7.Kf1 Bf5 This doesn't look pleasant for White. Black is about to clamp down on the light squares. 8.d4! is their only hope to avoid being significantly worse. Finally, 6... a6 6.Be2 doesn't do White any favors either. 6...e5! Black confiscates the center! Now White won't be able to break out with d4, which was presumably one of the key points behind c3. These sidelines don't offer White what they're probably looking for. On another note, the questionable looking 5... Qxd5 5.c4!? is strangely much more popular than the prior deviations. This isn't a particularly worrisome move. White gets a positionally worse version of the 6.Qe2 variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) after 6...Qe6+ 7.Qe2 Qxe2+ 8.Kxe2 Bd7! White has eternally weakened the d4 square by playing c4. The premature advance has produced nothing beneficial for them. As it pertains to 5... Qxd5 5.h3!? a number of moves are viable, but the simplest to me seems to be 5...Bd7 , overprotecting c6. This is the natural square for the bishop now that the g4 square is protected. 6.O-O Nf6 7.Nc3 Qd6! No need to do anything fancy with the queen. 8.Re1 e6= This is a standard equal position with chances for both sides. Perhaps a sharper approach to h3 would be 5. d3 5...Qe6+ 6.Be2 Qg6!? These lines look to be much more unclear. The good thing is that Black is flexible and has a number of options to choose from after h3. Finally, there's one last deviation I would like to discuss. } ) 5... Bg4 $1 { Black intends to meet Nc3 with ...Qd7, but doesn't want to lock the bishop out. Additionally, now ...Rc8 becomes a possibility. This has actually transposed to a position you'll learn about later in chapter eleven (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Generally, when following the exchange on d5 we cannot meet the incoming Nc3 with a check via ...Qe6, then the bishop comes out to g4. This theme also applies in the 5.O-O variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 6. Nc3 Qd7 7. h3 Bxf3 { We must eliminate the knight here, otherwise once White breaks the pin Ne5 will arrive with deadly force. } 8. Qxf3 Rc8 $1 { [%cal Bg8f6,Be7e6,Ba7a6,Yb7b5,Yc6d4,Yb5a4,Ya4b3]Black once again saves the queenside structure from destruction and secures a typical sort of middlegame. White does have the bishops and is a little more active, granted, but there's nothing particularly detestable about Black's position. Often it's best for White to trade off the light-squared bishop in these lines anyway because ...a6-b5 (if we suppose the bishop retreats via a4-b3) followed by ...Nd4 can become quite strong for Black. } * 

