In the following complications White has numerous opportunities to make losing blunders, which will all be covered shortly. An alternative worth considering which keeps the queens on the board, at least temporarily, is ...Qf5. } 7. Nxd5 ( 7. Qxf3 $2 { is a mistake on pain of } 7... Qxf3 8. gxf3 Rc8 { , where White's structure will suffer and Black's will not. } ) 7... Bxd1 8. Nc7+ $6 { This is actually a risky decision which will most probably furnish the advantage to Black. White might instead benefit from his lead in development after the simple } ( 8. Rxd1 { , however Black seems to be performing quite well in this line after } 8... Rc8 { , ...e6, ...a6 etc. } ) 8... Kd7 { [%cal Bd7c6,Bb5c6][%csl Rc6]We defend our knight and prepare for the endgame by centralizing the king. } 9. Nxa8 Bh5 { [%csl Rd1]Our bishop will actually be well placed here on the edge of the board. White will inevitably attempt to open the center to get at our king with d4, but our bishop will make it difficult for the White rooks to occupy the central d-file. Please be aware that } ( 9... Bxc2 { is a losing mistake after } 10. d3 { where our bishop is trapped. } ) 10. d4 { [%cal Bc1f4][%csl Rc7][%cal Ba8c7,Bf4c7]Stockfish likes } ( 10. a4 $2 { best but after } 10... Kc8 { the knight is doomed without much resistance. Most players I expect will exert some effort to rescue the stranded knight. } ) 10... cxd4 11. Bf4 { [%csl Rc7]} 11... e6 { [%csl Rc7]It looks like the knight might escape now that it has been permitted safe travel to c7, but this will simply be met with ...a6. White at best gets a couple of pawns for the piece. } 12. Nc7 a6 { [%cal Ba7a6,Be7e6][%csl Rd5,Rb5,Rc7]And now the knight has no squares! } 13. Ba4 { The materialistic } ( 13. Nxa6 $2 $146 { is no better. } 13... bxa6 14. Bxa6 e5 15. Bg3 Bc5 { and Black's pieces will come to life and dominate the position. } ) 13... Nf6 { Patience is key. If } ( 13... Bd6 $2 { White's knight slips away. } 14. Bxd6 Kxd6 15. Ne8+ $146 { This would not be acceptable. } ) 14. Rfe1 { White doesn't have a clear way to get out of this mess. Almost every move is evaluated as around -2.0 or less. } ( 14. f3 { Is the other candidate move, blocking off the bishop. However, Black has the natural } 14... Bd6 { and will acquire a decisive material advantage. } ) 14... Bc5 { No need to rush with ...Bd6. White really isn't able to accomplish much at the current time, so Black has time to slowly improve the position. ...Bc5 is a patient improving move which supports d4 and enables us to activate our rook with ...Rd8 or ...Rc8. This allows us to squeeze the position for all it's worth before cashing out on the material. If we play the immediate } ( 14... Bd6 $2 { White might climb out of this mess with } 15. Bxd6 Kxd6 16. Bxc6 Kxc6 17. Nxe6 $146 fxe6 18. Rxe6+ Kd5 19. Rae1 Bg6 { Black has a moderate edge, but White has chances of coming back. In any case, in these sorts of positions piece activity is everything. It's important that we bring our pieces to the best squares while we have the time. } ) 15. a3 { The queenside is the only place where counterplay is possible. a3 might look bad, but other moves accomplish just as little. For instance } ( 15. c3 d3 16. Rad1 Bxd1 { Leela judges that White's best is to sacrifice the exchange, which is still lost. } 17. Rxd1 Nh5 $146 18. Rxd3+ $2 Kc8 { White is out of defensive resources. } ) 15... Rc8 { The immediate threat is ...Rxc7. Our active minor pieces will prove to be too much to defend against if White allows this exchange. } 16. b4 Bd6 17. Bxc6+ { Instead, if } ( 17. Bxd6 Kxd6 18. b5 Rxc7 { Black can give up the knight! Our pieces are far too active for that to be a point of concern at this point in the game. } 19. bxc6 b5 20. Bb3 Rxc6 { Black is winning. Our immediate threat is ...Rc3 and ...d3. Of course, we also have ...Nd5 /...a5 /...Bg6 ideas too. White's position is on the verge of collapse. } ) 17... Kxc6 18. Nxe6 { Nxe6 is White's best attempt at resistance. } 18... fxe6 19. Rxe6 Rd8 20. Rae1 Bg4 $19 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Bd8d6,Be6d6,Bf4d6,Yc6d6,Yd6d5,Yd5c4,Rf6e4,Re4c3][%csl Rc3]With our active king and minor pieces, there is no doubt that White will not survive this endgame. } * 

