1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. O-O { Castling is White's second most popular response. Evidently a sensible move. White intends on capitalizing on the eventual Nc3 after the king is safely castled, thereby circumventing the complications which ensue in the } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ { variations. Nonetheless, hopefully to White's consternation, the resulting positions prove to be just as dynamic and sharp as those found in the aforementioned lines. } ) 5... Bg4 { We immediately apply pressure to White's kingside. Note that after 5.O-O we should avoid ...a6 for the time being. With the incoming Nc3, Black needs to address both the targetable queen and the development concern. } 6. Nc3 Bxf3 { This seems to be the move which offers the best chances for Black. In the following complications White has numerous opportunities to make losing blunders, which will all be covered shortly. An alternative worth considering which keeps the queens on the board, at least temporarily, is ...Qf5. } 7. Nxd5 ( 7. Qxf3 $2 { is a mistake on pain of } 7... Qxf3 8. gxf3 Rc8 { , where White's structure will suffer and Black's will not. } ) 7... Bxd1 8. Nc7+ $6 { This is actually a risky decision which will most probably furnish the advantage to Black. White might instead benefit from his lead in development after the simple } ( 8. Rxd1 { , however Black seems to be performing quite well in this line after } 8... Rc8 { , ...e6, ...a6 etc. } ) 8... Kd7 { [%cal Bd7c6,Bb5c6][%csl Rc6]We defend our knight and prepare for the endgame by centralizing the king. } 9. Nxa8 Bh5 { Our bishop will actually be well placed here on the edge of the board. White will inevitably attempt to open the center to get at our king with d4, but our bishop will make it difficult for the White rooks to occupy the central d-file. Please be aware that } ( 9... Bxc2 { is a losing mistake after } 10. d3 { where our bishop is trapped. } ) 10. d4 { [%cal Bc1f4][%csl Rc7][%cal Ba8c7,Bf4c7]Stockfish likes } ( 10. a4 $2 { best but after } 10... Kc8 { the knight is doomed without much resistance. Most players I expect will exert some effort to rescue the stranded knight. } ) 10... cxd4 11. Bf4 { [%csl Rc7]} 11... e6 { [%csl Rc7]It looks like the knight might escape now that it has been permitted safe travel to c7, but this will simply be met with ...a6. White at best gets a couple of pawns for the piece. } 12. Nc7 a6 { [%cal Ba7a6,Be7e6][%csl Rb5]And now the knight has no squares! } 13. Bxc6+ { [%cal Bc7e8]This line can get a little tricky. Be very attentive of the fact that once our king is drawn away from c7, White's knight can access e8. } 13... Kxc6 $7 { White is lost, but a careful treatment of the position is necessary to convert. For instance, be careful of: } 14. c3 $1 { White must act now, lest Black land ...Nf6 and ...Bd6 —in that order. } 14... d3 $1 { Do not allow White to open the file. } 15. b4 $5 { Aggressive desperation. } ( 15. Ne8 $146 { would be too eager. } 15... Kd7 { Simply forcing the knight back to c7. } 16. Nc7 $146 { All paths lead to Rome here. } 16... Be2 17. Rfe1 Nf6 $146 { ...Bd6 comes next. The game is over. } ) 15... Bd6 $1 { [%cal Bd6c7,Bd6f4]Even though this allows Ne8+ after the exchange, White's knight will not escape! Most crucially, this forces the issue. } 16. Bxd6 Kxd6 17. Ne8+ Kd7 { [%cal Re8c7,Re8d6]I like this move. Disallowing the knight to return to the queenside. ...Ke7 is still winning, but the lines can get rather complicated as the knight can return to c7 and White has some b4 ideas which might quickly furnish them with a passed pawn. } 18. Nxg7 Be2 $1 { A necessary move. } 19. Rfc1 Nf6 $19 { [%cal Bh8g8]Calm, yet purposeful development. White's knight is trapped and is scheduled for the chopping block! Black will soon scoop up the pony with ...Rg8-xg7. Apart from our powerful minor pieces, our passed pawn is also an extremely strong asset. } * 

