1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. O-O { Castling is White's second most popular response. Evidently a sensible move. White intends on capitalizing on the eventual Nc3 after the king is safely castled, thereby circumventing the complications which ensue in the } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ { variations. Nonetheless, hopefully to White's consternation, the resulting positions prove to be just as dynamic and sharp as those found in the aforementioned lines. } ) 5... Bg4 { We immediately apply pressure to White's kingside. Note that after 5.O-O we should avoid ...a6 for the time being. With the incoming Nc3, Black needs to address both the targetable queen and the development concern. } 6. Nc3 Bxf3 { This seems to be the move which offers the best chances for Black. In the following complications White has numerous opportunities to make losing blunders, which will all be covered shortly. An alternative worth considering which keeps the queens on the board, at least temporarily, is ...Qf5. } 7. Nxd5 ( 7. Qxf3 $2 { is a mistake on pain of } 7... Qxf3 8. gxf3 Rc8 { , where White's structure will suffer and Black's will not. } ) 7... Bxd1 8. Nc7+ $6 { This is actually a risky decision which will most probably furnish the advantage to Black. White might instead benefit from his lead in development after the simple } ( 8. Rxd1 { , however Black seems to be performing quite well in this line after } 8... Rc8 { , ...e6, ...a6 etc. } ) 8... Kd7 { [%cal Bd7c6,Bb5c6][%csl Rc6]We defend our knight and prepare for the endgame by centralizing the king. } 9. Nxa8 Bh5 { Our bishop will actually be well placed here on the edge of the board. White will inevitably attempt to open the center to get at our king with d4, but our bishop will make it difficult for the White rooks to occupy the central d-file. Please be aware that } ( 9... Bxc2 { is a losing mistake after } 10. d3 { where our bishop is trapped. } ) 10. d4 { [%cal Bc1f4][%csl Rc7][%cal Ba8c7,Bf4c7]Stockfish likes } ( 10. a4 $2 { best but after } 10... Kc8 { the knight is doomed without much resistance. Most players I expect will exert some effort to rescue the stranded knight. } ) 10... cxd4 11. Bf4 { [%csl Rc7]} 11... e6 { It looks like the knight might escape now that it has been permitted safe travel to c7, but this will simply be met with ...a6. White at best gets a couple of pawns for the piece. } 12. f3 { This response is becoming more frequent, so we must address it. White detects that the knight won't be escaping after Nc7, so they block the bishop off and aim for play on the central files. } 12... Nf6 13. Rad1 { The human move. } ( 13. Rfd1 { the computer slightly prefers, but after } 13... Kc8 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Nc7 $146 ( 15. Rac1 Be7 { Black is winning all the same. } ) 15... Bg6 ) 13... Kc8 { Securing the king. Now our c6 knight is unpinned, and so ...e5 ideas become relevant again. White's best is to exchange on c6 and try to extract the knight. } 14. Bxc6 { Of course, if } ( 14. Nc7 $2 $146 { Black can force the issue with } 14... e5 { , where conversion becomes simpler. } ) 14... bxc6 15. Nc7 { Black is still winning, but precision is necessary. } 15... Bg6 $3 { [%cal Gf6d7,Yf6h5][%csl Gh5,Gd7]A precise intermediary move. The idea behind this move is quite deep, actually, as it accurately prepares ...Nd7 and ...e5. We hit c2, which is a threat White must address immediately, directly or indirectly. On another note, we also vacate the h5 square, a square which our knight might jump to instead of d7 in some lines. If we start with And if we slip up with } ( 15... Nd7 $2 $146 { White has } 16. Rfe1 { and now Black cannot play } 16... e5 $2 { as after some exchanges the bishop hangs on h5. } ) ( 15... Kb7 $2 { White escapes certain doom with } 16. b4 $10 ) 16. Rf2 { It doesn't matter how White defends c2, we proceed with ...Nd7. Do be cautious if White sacrifices c2. For instance, There is one last move worth discussing. } ( 16. b4 $2 { White threatens Rxd4, which now cannot be met with ...Bc5. I would be wary of opening queenside lines up with ...Bxb4, though this certainly keeps Black's advantage. The better move in my estimation is: } 16... Nh5 $146 { Ensure that you're staying tactically alert, otherwise White can slip away. } 17. Be5 f6 18. g4 fxe5 19. gxh5 Bxc2 { A precise finisher. Now our pawns should suffice to win the ending. } 20. Rd2 { One last opportunity to slip up. } 20... Bxb4 21. Rxc2 Kxc7 $19 ) ( 16. Be5 $2 { is another interesting move. White's idea is to capture d4 with the rook and then meet ...Bc5 with Na6, which would secure them an equal game. Hence, we would be wise to resist capturing c2 for now. } 16... Kb7 { is the simplest solution, disallowing the eventual Na6. Now Black can proceed with the standard ...Nd7 and ...e5. } 17. b4 Nd7 $146 18. Bg3 e5 19. Ne8 $146 f6 $19 { This is game over. } ) ( 16. c3 { This move is tricky, as now White's knight has a safe square to retreat to on the queenside after Na6. Black is still winning, but like in many lines precision is necessary. } 16... d3 17. Na6 $146 Kb7 { The best move, forcing the knight to b4. This takes away the a6 square from the knight in the future as well, which is key. } 18. Nb4 $146 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 Rd8 { Black's threat is a5!, trapping the knight once again. It may look like White might be able to reply with Nc2, but ...Nd5 would then hit White's bishop and close off the file, so the threat is actually lethal. } 20. a4 { Making a square for the knight. } 20... a5 21. Na2 $146 Nd5 $146 { Black's pieces suddenly swarm White. This is all about tactics. } 22. Bd2 Ne3 $146 23. Bxe3 Bxe3 24. Rfe1 Bh6 $19 { White is nearly paralyzed and has permission to resign. } ) 16... Nd7 $1 { [%cal Be6e5]With ...e5 incoming. } 17. Na6 { White manages to save the knight, but their plight is hardly over. Now they must suffer from positional turmoil instead of a material disadvantage! } 17... e5 $1 18. Bd2 ( 18. Bg3 $2 Kb7 $19 { and the knight dies. } ) 18... Kb7 { Every move forces White's hand! } 19. Nb4 c5 { Keeping the initiative alive! } 20. Nd3 c4 $1 21. Ne1 { The knight will not survive if it returns to b4. } ( 21. Nc1 $2 $146 Bxc2 22. Re1 Bc5 $19 { with a crushing advantage. } ) ( 21. Nb4 $2 $146 a5 22. Nd5 $146 Kc6 $19 ) 21... Kc6 $19 { White's piece-configuration is a practical nightmare to unravel. Their pieces are all jumbled up in an uncoordinated mess! It's not simply that they are uncoordinated though; White's pieces have little hope of finding harmony with the pressures exerted by Black's center and bishops. Black has ...f6 and ...Bc5 ideas, and will eventually enlist the support of the king to further the campaign of our oppressive central pawn mass. } * 

