1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. O-O Bg4 6. Nc3 Bxf3 7. Nxd5 Bxd1 8. Nc7+ Kd7 9. Nxa8 Bh5 10. d4 cxd4 11. Bf4 f6 $5 { This idea is also worth considering; aiming for a quick ...e5. Perhaps not as precise as ...e6, but maybe even more practical. This move is in theme with much of what I've been recommending in the course, so I thought I might mention it. Let's take a look at a few lines. } 12. Bb8 ( 12. Bxc6+ { Eliminating the defender of a7. } 12... Kxc6 13. Bb8 e5 14. Bxa7 { White can try to extract the knight from the corner, but will ultimately fail to secure the extra material. } 14... Nh6 $146 15. a4 b6 { Precise. Black gives the b7 square to the king. } 16. Nxb6 $146 Kb7 $19 ) 12... Kc8 $7 13. Bc7 e5 $5 { Inaccurate according to the engine, but given that our opponents are human the practical difference here will probably be negligible, as White only has one move to avoid losing immediately. } ( 13... e6 { I'm not really sure why Stockfish prefers this to ...e5 right away. After } 14. Rfe1 { Black will be playing } 14... e5 { anyway, and apparently this is significantly better than playing ...e5 in one move. } 15. c3 Nge7 $146 16. Rac1 Nd5 $146 17. cxd4 Bb4 { I guess the reason is that this move now comes with tempo four moves later? } 18. Rf1 Kd7 $19 { Now the rook can access the corner. Looks like this one move gives Black enough time to secure the win easier. } ) 14. c3 $7 { From a bird's eye view, this move clearly is best. However, records show that people are not playing this. On the other hand, what else is White supposed to do? Black is going to play ...Nge7-d5 if White plays passively, which would end the game on the spot if allowed. } ( 14. f4 $2 { One game proceeded with this move. White is lost now. } 14... e4 15. Bxc6 { Following the game. } 15... bxc6 16. Ba5 Bd6 17. h3 Ne7 $146 18. g4 Bf7 19. Rad1 c5 $19 { With a crushing position. White soon resigned. } ) 14... Nge7 15. Rac1 $7 { Only move once again. It is certainly not obvious as to why. } ( 15. Rfc1 $2 { loses to } 15... dxc3 16. Rxc3 Nd5 $19 $146 ) 15... Nf5 $1 { With the idea of ...Kd7 and ...Bd6. This next sequence is ridiculously computer-ish. } 16. Bd3 $7 g6 $1 17. Bxf5+ gxf5 18. cxd4 $7 Kd7 $1 19. dxe5 $7 { So many forced moves! } 19... fxe5 20. Bxe5 Nxe5 21. Rc7+ $7 ( 21. Nc7 $2 $146 { If White slips up, suddenly Black has an attack! } 21... Be2 22. Rfe1 Nf3+ $3 $146 { Boom. White has permission to resign. } 23. gxf3 Rg8+ 24. Kh1 Bxf3# ) 21... Kd6 22. Rxb7 Be2 23. Rb1 Nf3+ 24. Kh1 Be7 $15 { With perfect play Black ends up slightly better, though the position is extremely unclear. White will have two formidable passed pawns on the queenside. Black will have active minor pieces, the bishop pair, and eventual checkmating threats. It's not easy to evaluate these positions, but Black looks to have the practical edge. In any case, 13. Bc7 13...e6 will almost definitely guarantee Black a winning position with precise play. There are interesting features of both lines. As we might observe, this 11...f6 idea seems to be quite promising. In case 11...e6 doesn't end up working as you might like, consider trying this one out. } * 

