ications White has numerous opportunities to make losing blunders, which will all be covered shortly. An alternative worth considering which keeps the queens on the board, at least temporarily, is ...Qf5. } 7. Nxd5 ( 7. Qxf3 $2 { is a mistake on pain of } 7... Qxf3 8. gxf3 Rc8 { , where White's structure will suffer and Black's will not. } ) 7... Bxd1 8. Nc7+ $2 { This is actually a risky decision which will most probably furnish the advantage to Black. White might instead benefit from his lead in development after the simple } ( 8. Rxd1 { , however Black seems to be performing quite well in this line after } 8... Rc8 { , ...e6, ...a6 etc. } ) 8... Kd7 { [%cal Bd7c6,Bb5c6][%csl Rc6]We defend our knight and prepare for the endgame by centralizing the king. } 9. Nxa8 Bh5 { Our bishop will actually be well placed here on the edge of the board. White will inevitably attempt to open the center to get at our king with d4, but our bishop will make it difficult for the White rooks to occupy the central d-file. Please be aware that } ( 9... Bxc2 { is a losing mistake after } 10. d3 { where our bishop is trapped. } ) 10. a4 { The most resilient attempt, though one rarely seen. White forgoes the central break and pursues complications on the flank! } 10... Kc8 $1 { If White intends on lunging forth with their a-pawn we really cannot forego immediate pursuit of the trapped steed. There's no time to develop the kingside yet. } 11. Bxc6 { Capitalizing on the opportunity to damage our structure. } 11... bxc6 12. a5 Nf6 { [%cal Be7e5,Bf8d6]The cornered steed is going nowhere. Black has time to develop the kingside and will dispatch the knight in due time. Notice that White could try getting counterplay by opening up the a-file with } 13. d3 ( 13. Nb6+ $146 axb6 14. axb6 { at any time, but once our bishop comes to d6 Black will unlock the rook from the corner and will be able to cover all loose ends. } 14... e5 15. Ra7 Bd6 { White simply doesn't have the activity to make use of the passed b-pawn. } ) 13... e5 14. f4 Bd6 $15 { Black will be up an exchange soon and is a bit better. Once the tension in the center has been resolved we can step the king up off the back rank and eliminate the knight. } * 

