ications White has numerous opportunities to make losing blunders, which will all be covered shortly. An alternative worth considering which keeps the queens on the board, at least temporarily, is ...Qf5. } 7. Nxd5 ( 7. Qxf3 $2 { is a mistake on pain of } 7... Qxf3 8. gxf3 Rc8 { , where White's structure will suffer and Black's will not. } ) 7... Bxd1 8. Rxd1 $1 { Both the simpler and safer choice. } 8... Rc8 { [%cal Ba7a6,Be7e6][%csl Rd5,Rb5]We prevent White from doubling our pawns and fragmenting our structure. Next we repel White's minor pieces with ...e6 and ...a6. } 9. d4 e6 10. Ne3 cxd4 11. Rxd4 { Be aware that the tricky } ( 11. Nc4 $2 $146 { is easily addressed by } 11... a6 12. Nb6 $146 Rb8 { and Black is doing perfectly fine after } 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Nc4 $146 c5 15. c3 Rd8 { Black is a pawn up, but White's development compensates for the material deficiency. The position is equal. } ) 11... a6 12. Bxc6+ Rxc6 $10 { [%cal Bf8c5,Bg8f6,Bg8e7][%csl Rc2]We are slightly behind in development but have the time and flexibility to coordinate our pieces as we see fit. Both sides have chances and the better player will probably secure the victory from here. } * 

