1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common response. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. O-O { Castling is White's second most popular response. Evidently a sensible move. White intends on capitalizing on the eventual Nc3 after the king is safely castled, thereby circumventing the complications which ensue in the } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ { variations. Nonetheless, hopefully to White's consternation, the resulting positions prove to be just as dynamic and sharp as those found in the aforementioned lines. } ) 5... Bg4 { We immediately apply pressure to White's kingside. Note that after 5.O-O we should avoid ...a6 for the time being. With the incoming Nc3, Black needs to address both the targetable queen and the development concern. } 6. Nc3 Bxf3 { This seems to be the move which offers the best chances for Black. In the following complications White has numerous opportunities to make losing blunders, which will all be covered shortly. An alternative worth considering which keeps the queens on the board, at least temporarily, is ...Qf5. } 7. Qxf3 $2 { Seen in a shocking 25%+ of games. } 7... Qxf3 8. gxf3 Rc8 { Black is in time to prevent White from damaging the structure. Positionally speaking Black is better, but still, White has the bishops. There's still a fight to be had. We should be safe to already stop here, but I'll offer a basic blueprint regarding how I like to play these positions. } 9. d3 a6 { Immediately asking questions. Of course, we would be glad to see White to trade with Otherwise, White needs to be careful. } 10. Ba4 { Maintaining the pin is the way to go. } ( 10. Bxc6+ Rxc6 { as our rook has been activated and White is deprived of the bishop pair. } ) ( 10. Bc4 $2 { would be a sizable error, as with the pin broken our knight has license to strike with } 10... Nd4 $146 { where White will lose material for no compensation. } ) 10... e6 11. Be3 { [%cal Bc3e4,Be4c5,Be3c5][%csl Rc5]The most common attempt. White's idea is to go after our c5 pawn. Other moves, such as the natural-looking } ( 11. Bf4 $2 { don't adequately attend to Black's potential ...Nd4 ideas: } 11... b5 12. Bb3 Nd4 $146 13. Kg2 Ne7 $146 { with ...Nf5 incoming. } ) 11... f5 $1 { [%cal Be8f7,Bg8f6]I like this move. We disallow Ne4 and hence stop White's attack on c5. We needn't worry about the e6 weakness, as White's forces are too scattered and disorganized to break through. Moreover, White's pieces can hardly move in a way which is productive. If you don't find this idea compelling, another way to play is to break White's pin with ...b5 and follow up with ...Nd4, hitting f3 and White's bishop. I prefer ...f5, as White is able to achieve much less. } 12. Rfe1 { [%cal Be1e8][%csl Re8]The human move, lining up with our king. } 12... Nf6 13. Kg2 { Notice how White doesn't have a clear plan or really any moves which are appealing to human sensibility. } 13... Kf7 $15 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Yf8d6,Bh8e8,Bh8d8,Rb7b5,Gh7h6,Yf8g7,Bf6d5,Ra4b3,Rc6a5]Black has all the chances here. White's pieces are fortunately restricted by Black's pawns and we can easily gain even more space with ...b5, ...g5, ...h5, etc. If we're worried about White mounting pressure on e6 with Bb3, we can simply respond with ...Na5 and either capture the bishop at our leisure or even play something like ...Rc6 and ...c4. Our other ideas involve ...Bd6 paired with ...Rhe8, playing for an eventual ...e5. Or even something like ...Rg8 & ...g5 would fare well. There's lots of play here. } * 

