dvantage. } 6... e6 7. Nc3 ( 7. h3 { White could try hitting our bishop, and because White's bishop is on e2 I recommend that we avoid the trade on f3. Apart from not wanting to contribute to White's effort to improve their pieces, there's simply no demand for us to exchange here, unlike in many other variations where ...Bxf3 is a must. } 7... Bh5 8. Nc3 $146 Qd7 9. d3 Nf6 $146 10. Bf4 Bd6 $15 { Black has nothing to worry about in these lines. } ) 7... Qd7 { I like ...Qd7 slightly more than ...Qd8. We might want to leave open the possibility of queenside castling. } 8. d3 Nf6 9. Bg5 $5 { The most popular continuation, but not the best. People are also playing } ( 9. Bf4 { , to which we should respond by challenging White's strong bishop. } 9... Bd6 { An exchange is in order. } 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. h3 Bh5 $15 { Black is slightly better. White's light-squared bishop is trash and we have more central space. } ) 9... h6 { White is welcome to take on f6, but this would be a sizable mistake! White's dark-squared bishop is their good bishop, so they should be hesitant to trade off so quickly. On the other hand, it's not totally clear why people are placing the bishop on g5 if not to exchange. There is no pin. } 10. Bf4 ( 10. Bxf6 $2 { Opening up lines on the kingside only helps Black. } 10... gxf6 11. Ne4 $146 Be7 12. h3 h5 { White's position is already extremely unpleasant. Black would love to queenside castle and bring the other rook to the party. } 13. hxg4 $2 hxg4 14. Nh2 $146 f5 { White might be up a piece, but their position is crumbling. Black's plan is to get castled, target the dark squares with ...Bd6, and start shoving the pawns down the board. We can also stack the rooks on the h-file. White's survival prospects look grim. } 15. Ng3 $146 O-O-O 16. Re1 Bd6 17. Nhf1 $146 f4 18. Ne4 $146 f5 $19 { Vacating the path for the queen to reach h7. Black is winning. } ) 10... Bd6 { As stated in a prior sub-variation, Black should challenge White's strong bishop if it makes its way to f4. } 11. Bxd6 ( 11. Be3 { I haven't mentioned this move in yet, but White could have tried this earlier. The idea here is probably to support the d4 push. } 11... O-O-O $2 { Now d4 loses! } 12. d4 $2 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 cxd4 14. Bxc6 Qxc6 15. Bxd4 Bc5 16. Ne2 $146 e5 $19 { White either loses the queen or the bishop! } ) 11... Qxd6 12. h3 Bh5 13. Re1 O-O $15 { White's lack of space makes it a little awkward for them to maneuver their pieces. Black has a small advantage. } * 

