s horrendous. } ) 9... Qxf3 10. gxf3 O-O-O $1 { I like this move, as it raises certain difficulties to White. What shall they play? They cannot advance the d-pawn. Moreover, we threaten to plant the rook on the d3 square, immobilizing White's center and hitting f3. } 11. Bxc6 { The only serious attempt. Not even } ( 11. Ng5 $2 $146 { will do. } 11... Ne5 $3 $146 { A brilliant idea, preventing White from corrupting the queenside structure and simultaneously covering f7. The point is that } 12. f4 $2 { will be met with } 12... h6 13. fxe5 hxg5 { where White is simply lost. Their position is full of holes and Black's rooks are monsters. } ) 11... bxc6 $15 { [%cal Bd8d3,Bd8d2,Gg8h6,Gh6f5,Gf5d4]I think it is not so easy for a human to play from White's side here. If White wishes to support the d-pawn's advance with Instead, the computer finds this nice idea to temporarily sacrifice a pawn in exchange for rapid development with } 12. Rd1 { Black can simply plant the rook on d3. } ( 12. d3 Rxd3 13. Be3 Nf6 $10 $146 { where an unclear equality emerges on the horizon, but Black needn't initially take the pawn. It's a weakness which is going nowhere, after all. Hence, 12. d3 12...Nh6! is to be preferred, keeping the pace with White's development. 12.Be3 Nf5! With a slight advantage to Black. Even though White can snatch the pawn on c5, we have a dominant grip on d4 and are easily able to pursue the untenable f3 with ...Nh4. Black has the edge. } ) 12... Rd3 { White must now waste time in order to evict the rook. } 13. Kf1 Nh6 $146 14. Ke2 Rd7 15. d3 Nf5 $146 { Suddenly Black has a dominant grip on the d4 square. This is rather unpleasant for White. } * 

