1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { [%cal Bd5c6][%csl Rc6][%cal Ba7a6]Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. O-O { [%cal Bb1c3,Bd2d4][%csl Rd5,Rc6]Castling is White's second most popular response. Evidently a sensible move. White intends on capitalizing on the eventual Nc3 after the king is safely castled, thereby circumventing the complications which ensue in the } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ { variations. Nonetheless, hopefully to White's consternation, the resulting positions prove to be just as dynamic and sharp as those found in the aforementioned lines. } ) 5... Bg4 { [%csl Rf3,Rg1][%cal Bd5f3,Bg4d1][%csl Rc6]We immediately apply pressure to White's kingside. Note that after 5.O-O we should avoid ...a6 for the time being. With the incoming Nc3, Black needs to address both the targetable queen and the development concern. } 6. Nc3 { [%csl Rd5,Bf3,Rc6]} 6... Qf5 { [%cal Bf5f3][%csl Rf3][%cal Bg4d1,Yh7h5][%csl Rh5,Rc6]I'm offering ...Qf5 as a murky alternative to my primary recommendation of ...Bxf3. Black keeps the queens on the board and abandons contact with the knight on c6. One drawback to take note of is that often Black's best option is to just liquidate the queens through a series of exchanges on f3 anyway, so we may not even be preserving our queen's life for long. However, the positions are sharp and interesting enough to be worth considering on their own, so I'll supply a few variations so as to familiarize the reader with the basic ideas, where you can subsequently decide for yourself which option accords more with your tastes. Note that } ( 6... Qf5 7. h3 $2 { would be a positional blunder. We will exchange on f3 to destroy White's structure and our rook arrives just in time to prevent White from delivering a similar treatment to our own. } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qxf3 9. gxf3 Rc8 { Black has excellent long-term chances. For some reason this h3 move has struck the fancy of some moderately high rated lichess players, so I thought I might mention it in case one happens to encounter it. } ) 7. Bxc6+ { White elects to damage our queenside structure, as expected. } 7... bxc6 8. d3 Nf6 { Flexible development. We are waiting for the opportune moment to exchange on f3. } 9. Be3 { [%csl Rc5]My opponents seem to like this move. To me it appears rather benign, as we intended on playing ...e6 anyway. Otherwise } ( 9. Re1 { can be met with } 9... Rd8 { , where we remain flexible as to whether we want to play for ...e6 or ...g6 and will probably also exchange on f3 soon. } ) 9... e6 { [%cal Bg4f3,Bg2f3,Rd1f3,Rf5f3][%csl Yf3][%cal Bf8e7,Ge8g8,Gh8e8]} 10. h3 { This move should be expected sooner or later. As a general rule, meeting an early h3 with ...h5 in this sort of position is a playable idea. However, if White delays h3 for a while and instead prioritizes central expansion and development first, then ...h5 becomes much riskier and we should instead elect to exchange on f3 right away. } 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qxf3 12. gxf3 Nd5 { [%cal Bd5e3]Pressuring the bishop. White will probably attempt to target the c5 pawn soon. 13.Ng5 Bd6! Black sets a trap! 14.Nxe6?? loses the knight. 14...Ke7 15.Ng5 h6-+ } 13. Na4 { White elects to target c5 in such a way as to avoid possible complications in the center. } ( 13. Ne4 $146 { would invite Black to charge ahead with } 13... f5 { Remember, White cannot take c5 with the knight due to ...Nxe3, so instead the knight will probably relocate to g5. } ) 13... Rd8 { [%cal Bd5f4,Yd8d5,Yd5g5,Bf4h3,Yg5g2]A subtle, but potent move. Black invites White to capture c5, whereupon the Black pieces will direct themselves with great rapidity toward the damaged structure of White's kingside. } 14. Bxc5 { Remember that capturing on c5 with the wrong piece when our knight is on d5 is lost for White. } ( 14. Nxc5 $2 $146 Nxe3 $146 { where White will emerge down a piece. } ) 14... Bxc5 15. Nxc5 Nf4 16. Kh2 Rd5 { [%csl Rc5][%cal Bd5h5,Bh5h3,Bh6h3,Bg6g2]This is the point. Though White can defend with accurate play, Black's position is already quite compelling. I offer the following continuation as a possible way a game might proceed. } 17. Ne4 Rh5 18. Kg3 e5 19. h4 ( 19. Rh1 $2 { Is a fatal blunder. So easy it is for White to slip up here. } 19... f5 20. Nc5 $146 Rg5+ { White is unable to avoid the mate. } ) 19... O-O { [%cal Bf7f5,Bh5h6,Bh6g6]Black has ...f5 and ...Rh6-g6+ and many other ideas in the cards. } 20. Rae1 f5 21. Nd6 Rh6 { [%csl Rd6]This is preferable to Instead, after } ( 21... Rf6 { , as after } 22. Rxe5 { our knight hangs loose and White is afforded sufficient counterplay. } ) ( 21... Rh6 22. Rxe5 { Black has the intermezzo } 22... Nh5+ $146 { and will pick up White's knight on the next move. } ) 22. Nc4 Rg6+ 23. Kh2 Rg2+ 24. Kh1 Rf6 $17 { [%csl Bf4,Rh4][%cal Yc4e3,Yg2g6,Yg6h6,Rf4g6,Rg6h4,Yh6h4]This does look quite miserable for White. They may prevent checkmate after Ne3, but Black can maneuver the rook with ...Rgg6-h6 and target White's h-pawn. Black has excellent practical chances from here. } * 

