1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. O-O { Castling is White's second most popular response. Evidently a sensible move. White intends on capitalizing on the eventual Nc3 after the king is safely castled, thereby circumventing the complications which ensue in the } ( 5. Nc3 $146 Qe6+ { variations. Nonetheless, hopefully to White's consternation, the resulting positions prove to be just as dynamic and sharp as those found in the aforementioned lines. } ) 5... Bg4 { We immediately apply pressure to White's kingside. Note that after 5.O-O we should avoid ...a6 for the time being. With the incoming Nc3, Black needs to address both the targetable queen and the development concern. } 6. Nc3 Qf5 { I'm offering ...Qf5 as a murky alternative to my primary recommendation of ...Bxf3. Black keeps the queens on the board and abandons contact with the knight on c6. One drawback to take note of is that often Black's best option is to just liquidate the queens through a series of exchanges on f3 anyway, so we may not even be preserving our queen's life for long. However, the positions are sharp and interesting enough to be worth considering on their own, so I'll supply a few variations so as to familiarize the reader with the basic ideas, where you can subsequently decide for yourself which option accords more with your tastes. Note that } ( 6... Qf5 7. h3 $2 { would be a positional blunder. We will exchange on f3 to destroy White's structure and our rook arrives just in time to prevent White from delivering a similar treatment to our own. } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qxf3 9. gxf3 Rc8 { Black has excellent long-term chances. For some reason this h3 move has struck the fancy of some moderately high rated lichess players, so I thought I might mention it in case one happens to encounter it. } ) 7. Be2 { White retreats the bishop to anticipate the possibility of an exchange on f3. Be2 is a move I like to see in this position. Now Black will not suffer from a ruinous queenside pawn structure. We have another imbalanced middlegame ahead. } 7... O-O-O $5 { [%cal Bd8d1,Bh7h5,Be7e6]} 8. h3 h5 { The only acceptable move! } 9. hxg4 { White can also delay the capture with } ( 9. d3 { and after } 9... e6 10. hxg4 hxg4 { White now has a new square for the knight with } 11. Ng5 $146 Nf6 $146 { . The resulting position is extremely complicated and sharp. Black has ideas to play ...c4, develop the dark squared bishop, and has good long term attacking chances on the kingside. White might be tempted by } 12. Nxf7 $2 $146 { but after } 12... Qh5 13. Nxh8 $146 Bd6 14. f4 Rxh8 { White can resign in good conscience. } ) 9... hxg4 10. Nh2 e6 11. Bxg4 Qg6 12. Re1 ( 12. d3 $2 { allows } 12... Bd6 { , where after } 13. f4 Nf6 $146 14. Bf3 Qg3 15. Ng4 $146 Nxg4 $146 16. Bxg4 Be7 { Black's idea is to clear the file in order to play ...c4, disallowing d5 in response. Once the pawn has vacated the c5 square our bishop can occupy the diagonal and induce resignation. Black has excellent winning chances. } ) 12... Nf6 { [%cal Bf8d6][%csl Rh2,Rg4]Black now threatens ...Bd6. } 13. Bf3 Qh6 $13 { White is forced to return the piece and must defend an uncomfortable position. } * 

