1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. d4 { This is arguably a contender for the best move in the position, yet one I have yet to encounter in my hundreds of games playing this opening. The obviousness of 5.Nc3 compels so many players to move without due consideration, which is emblematic of a disposition we should be glad to see in our opponents. } 5... Bg4 { I will be offering } ( 5... cxd4 { as a riskier alternative, which is particularly meritorious in a blitz setting, though it can lead to positions that some would be unhappy with. ...Bg4 seems to be the more temperate choice of the two and is actually more ambitious in certain respects. Both moves are worth acquainting oneself with, in my opinion. } ) 6. Bxc6+ { [%cal Bd5c6,Rd4d5]Aiming for central expansion. } 6... Qxc6 7. d5 Qa6 { [%cal Ba6f1][%csl Re2,Rf1]This move must be particularly annoying to confront. After ...Qa6 White's king will remain in the center unless they elect to trade queens. Black has plans to queenside castle and open up the center, so White won't be comfortable leaving their king in the center for long. } 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. h3 { White has to play h3 and Qe2 at some point soon. Let's suppose they instead proceed in some other way: It's worth noting that h3 must be included before Qe2. If White tries } ( 9. Bf4 $2 Nf6 $146 10. Qd2 e6 { White's d-pawn will fall and their king is still uncastled. This is a disaster for White. } ) ( 9. Qe2 { first, Black is at least slightly better after } 9... Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 e6 11. dxe6 Bxe6 { . } ) 9... Bh5 10. Qe2 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2 Nf6 12. Rd1 e6 { The best that Black can do here is to simplify the position further. } 13. dxe6 Rxd1 14. Nxd1 fxe6 $10 { [%cal Bh5e8,Be8c6,Bh8d8,Bf8e7]This is roughly equal. Black has the bishop pair but also a weak e-pawn. Moreover, mobilization will be a little easier for us as White has more pieces still on the back rank. } * 

