1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. d4 { This is arguably a contender for the best move in the position, yet one I have yet to encounter in my hundreds of games playing this opening. The obviousness of 5.Nc3 compels so many players to move without due consideration, which is emblematic of a disposition we should be glad to see in our opponents. } 5... Bg4 { I will be offering } ( 5... cxd4 { as a riskier alternative, which is particularly meritorious in a blitz setting, though it can lead to positions that some would be unhappy with. ...Bg4 seems to be the more temperate choice of the two and is actually more ambitious in certain respects. Both moves are worth acquainting oneself with, in my opinion. } ) 6. Nc3 Bxf3 { This resembles the response we give to 6.Nc3 in the 5.O-O Variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). There's one key difference in how the resulting positions should be treated which will be discussed shortly. } 7. Nxd5 Bxd1 8. Nc7+ Kd8 { [%cal Bc6d4][%csl Rd4][%cal Bb5e8][%csl Gd8]In the aforementioned variations, after Nc7+ Black responds with ...Kd7 to stay in contact with the knight. The key difference here is that here White has already advanced their pawn to d4. Therefore, Black needs to step out of the pin to avoid d5: } ( 8... Kd7 $2 9. Nxa8 $146 Bxc2 10. d5 ) 9. Nxa8 Nxd4 10. Kxd1 { One alternative that Stockfish spots is } ( 10. Be3 $2 { after which Black should just drop the bishop back and go to kill the knight. } 10... Bh5 11. Ba4 Kc8 $10 { These continuations are roughly equal. } ) 10... Nxb5 11. a4 ( 11. Be3 { might complicate matters. } 11... Nf6 $146 12. a4 Nd4 $146 { Black will still end up with two minor pieces for the rook. } 13. a5 Kc8 14. c3 Ne6 $146 15. a6 bxa6 16. Rxa6 Kb7 { The knight falls. If 12... Nf6 12.Bxc5?! White would just be help Black secure the exchange even quicker. 12...e5! 13.Be3 Kd7 Black can play ...Nd4 and ...Bd6, where the knight in the corner will swiftly meet its end. } ) 11... Nd6 12. Be3 Kc8 13. Bxc5 Kb8 14. Re1 Nf6 $10 { [%cal Bb8a8,Ba7a6]Careful. After Although we will have two minor pieces for the rook, White has sufficient compensation if they find the right plan, which is as follows: } ( 14... Kxa8 $2 15. Bxd6 { Black is lost. } ) ( 14... Nf6 $146 15. Ra3 { White needs to exploit our lack of kingside development. } 15... Kxa8 16. Bxd6 exd6 17. Rf3 a6 18. g4 h6 19. h4 Ka7 20. g5 hxg5 21. hxg5 Nd7 $146 22. Re8 { Our kingside looks immobilized. The only way to unwind it is with } 22... Ne5 $146 23. Rf4 f6 { and after some exchanges the position is drawn. } ) * 

