1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. d4 { This is arguably a contender for the best move in the position, yet one I have yet to encounter in my hundreds of games playing this opening. The obviousness of 5.Nc3 compels so many players to move without due consideration, which is emblematic of a disposition we should be glad to see in our opponents. } 5... Bg4 { I will be offering } ( 5... cxd4 { as a riskier alternative, which is particularly meritorious in a blitz setting, though it can lead to positions that some would be unhappy with. ...Bg4 seems to be the more temperate choice of the two and is actually more ambitious in certain respects. Both moves are worth acquainting oneself with, in my opinion. } ) 6. Nc3 Bxf3 { This resembles the response we give to 6.Nc3 in the 5.O-O Variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). There's one key difference in how the resulting positions should be treated which will be discussed shortly. } 7. gxf3 Qxd4 8. Bxc6+ { If } ( 8. Be3 { instead, Black has } 8... Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Rc8 { where White is ahead on development, but Black has compensation. We would do best to just return the pawn and catch up, playing the long game against White's weak kingside structure. } 10. Bxc5 a6 11. Be2 e6 $10 ) 8... bxc6 9. Qe2 { The most accurate continuation. } ( 9. Bd2 { is much less ambitious. } 9... Qe5+ { Keeping queens on the board is not the way to go for White. } 10. Be3 $2 Rd8 11. Qe2 e6 12. Qa6 Qc7 13. Ne4 $146 Ne7 $146 14. Nxc5 $146 Nf5 $146 { Black is slightly better. } ) 9... Qd7 { [%cal Bc1e3,Ba1d1,Bd7b7,Bd7h3]The queen often becomes a target if she remains in the center. From d7 the queen could reposition to the queenside or the kingside once a rook comes to d1. } 10. Be3 { Targeting c5. If White instead tries } ( 10. Bd2 { , foreshadowing O-O-O, Black should prepare ...Bg7 with } 10... g6 { Black would benefit from remaining flexible about developing the knight. If White's king goes to the queenside we shouldn't block the bishop from its sniper post on g7. } ) 10... Nf6 { Prioritizing development. White can have the pawn if they want. } 11. Bxc5 e6 12. Bxf8 { Or if White refuses to initiate the exchange } ( 12. Qe5 { , Black will. } 12... Bxc5 13. Qxc5 O-O-O { with unclear complications. } ) 12... Kxf8 $13 { [%cal Bh7h5,Yh8h6,Yh6g6]Black's king is safe on f8. We can get our rook into the game by pushing Harry with ...h5 and then sliding the rook up and over with ...Rh6-g6. This is roughly equal, but White has a long term structural problems on the kingside. } * 

