e 5.O-O Variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). There's one key difference in how the resulting positions should be treated which will be discussed shortly. } 7. gxf3 Qxd4 8. Qe2 { If } ( 8. Be3 { instead, Black has } 8... Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Rc8 { where White is ahead on development, but Black has good compensation. We would do best to just return the pawn, improve our pieces, and play the long game against White's weak kingside structure. } ) 8... Qd6 { Preventing White from fragmenting our structure. } 9. Ne4 Qc7 10. Bd2 { [%cal Re1c1,Bb1d1,Bh1e1,Be1e8,Bd1d8,Ra1d1]White will castle to the queenside and coordinate their forces along the open central files. This is the critical continuation of the 5...Bg4 variation. With accurate play White will be slightly better, but the position will be messy. } 10... a6 11. Bxc6+ Qxc6 12. O-O-O Nf6 13. Bc3 { [%cal Bc3f6,Bf6e4][%csl Re4]The accurate way to proceed. If White tries something like } ( 13. Rhe1 { Black has enough time to finish developing the kingside } 13... g6 14. Bc3 $2 Bh6+ 15. Kb1 O-O 16. h4 Rad8 { and is actually slightly better. } ) 13... Nxe4 { I would prefer it if we didn't have to contribute to the remediation of White's dismal kingside structure, but it seems as if there isn't any desirable alternative. For instance } ( 13... Nd5 $2 $146 14. Be5 b5 15. f4 { This is annoying. Now } 15... e6 { can be met with } 16. f5 O-O-O 17. Ng5 $146 { White has a substantial inititave. } ) 14. fxe4 b5 { Hoping for queenside counterplay. } 15. Rhg1 Rg8 16. f4 b4 $14 { [%cal Bg7g6,Bf8g7,Ba8d8]Due to the awkward position of our king and our unfortunate lack of piece coordination, White has an advantage. The game might continue with } 17. Be5 g6 18. f5 Rd8 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 20. Rd1+ Ke8 21. Kb1 c4 22. Bf4 gxf5 23. exf5 Rg2 { Both kings are in danger and each player should accordingly proceed with caution. The first to make a mistake will probably lose the game. } * 

