1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. d4 { This is arguably a contender for the best move in the position, yet one I have yet to encounter in my hundreds of games playing this opening. The obviousness of 5.Nc3 compels so many players to move without due consideration, which is emblematic of a disposition we should be glad to see in our opponents. } 5... Bg4 { I will be offering } ( 5... cxd4 { as a riskier alternative, which is particularly meritorious in a blitz setting, though it can lead to positions that some would be unhappy with. ...Bg4 seems to be the more temperate choice of the two and is actually more ambitious in certain respects. Both moves are worth acquainting oneself with, in my opinion. } ) 6. c4 Qe4+ 7. Be3 { White should be careful not to misstep with } ( 7. Qe2 $2 Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 cxd4 { where Black would be up a clean pawn. } ) 7... cxd4 8. Qxd4 Bxf3 { [%cal Bg2f3][%csl Rf3]An important intermezzo. Black mutilates White's kingside structure before venturing into the endgame. } 9. gxf3 Qxd4 10. Bxc6+ { If instead } ( 10. Bxd4 $2 { , Black can win a pawn with } 10... O-O-O 11. Be3 Nd4 $146 12. Ba4 Nxf3+ $146 { and is slightly better. } ) 10... bxc6 11. Bxd4 Nh6 $10 { [%cal Bh6f5,Rf7f6,Re7e5,Rg7g5]This endgame is roughly equal, though I find Black's position to be slightly easier to play. Our knight will naturally maneuver to f5. We'll then begin to expand on the kingside and play against White's weaknesses. } * 

