1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. exd5 { The most common move at all levels. White likely spots Nc3 from a short distance and presumptuously anticipates a sizable advantage from the lead in development. } 4... Qxd5 { Given that White responds to 3...d5 with exd5 60-75% of the time, this position is our bread and butter! } 5. d4 { This is arguably a contender for the best move in the position, yet one I have yet to encounter in my hundreds of games playing this opening. The obviousness of 5.Nc3 compels so many players to move without due consideration, which is emblematic of a disposition we should be glad to see in our opponents. } 5... cxd4 $5 { [%cal Bd5b5][%csl Rb5]This might be theoretically riskier than ...Bg4, however the database indicates that the only critical response to ...cxd4 is missed around 95% of the time, making it a particularly auspicious response for blitz. Blitz is probably the ideal time control to play 3...d5 in anyway, so this continuation is certainly worth considering. Be warned, however, that if White spots the correct idea they will be better. White may be tempted to take on c6 now that their bishop is being attacked. This mistake happens to be White's top choice, even among strong players! Bizarrely, a remarkable percentage of games continued with both the immediately losing } 6. Bxc6+ $2 { A common mistake which will furnish Black the advantage. } ( 6. Nxd4 $2 $146 { which hangs the g-pawn for nothing, and 6... cxd4 6.Qxd4?? which gives a piece to Black for free. } ) 6... Qxc6 { [%cal Bd1d4][%csl Rd4]Black is already better and will be close to winning if White chooses to immediately recapture the pawn. } 7. Qxd4 $2 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5]This is another mistake. Now we can thematically confiscate the center with the usual ...f6-e5 sequence and hit the queen with tempo, where our bishop pair and open position give us a considerable advantage. Of course, } ( 7. O-O { is the correct move, but still leaves White with problems after } 7... Bg4 8. Nxd4 $146 Bxd1 9. Nxc6 $146 Bxc2 10. Nd4 $146 Bxb1 11. Rxb1 a6 { where White will be down a pawn with minimal compensation. } ) ( 7. Nxd4 $2 $146 { outright loses. } 7... Qxg2 8. Qf3 ( 8. Nf3 $146 f6 { This may not look crushing, but the engine already weighs Black's advantage in at -3.0 } ) 8... Qxf3 ) 7... f6 $1 { [%csl Rg5,Re5][%cal Bf3g5,Bf3e5,Be7e5]Other moves are fine but ...f6 is both thematic and the best move! We prepare ...e5 and simultaneously restrict White's knight. } 8. Nc3 e5 $17 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7f5,Bf8c5,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bc5b4]Black will quickly develop and either castle or bring the king to the center if we trade queens. Here's a sample line: } 9. Qd5 Bd7 { The exchange of queens will improve our pieces. } 10. O-O Ne7 $146 11. Qxc6 Bxc6 12. Be3 Nf5 $146 { Black has the better end of this endgame. Our king is close to the center and our pieces can easily make their way to good squares, with the quasi-open queenside and center files giving excellent play for our rooks. } * 

