te may be tempted to take on c6 now that their bishop is being attacked. This mistake happens to be White's top choice, even among strong players! Bizarrely, a remarkable percentage of games continued with both the immediately losing } 6. Nc3 $1 { [%cal Bc3d5,Bc3b5][%csl Rd4]The only critical move. } ( 6. Nxd4 $2 $146 { which hangs the g-pawn for nothing, and 6... cxd4 6.Qxd4?? which gives a piece to Black for free. } ) 6... Qe6+ 7. Ne2 Bd7 { Tempting White to immediately recapture in the center. } 8. Bxc6 { Removing the defender of d4. } 8... Bxc6 9. Nxd4 { If } ( 9. Qxd4 { Black has a number of appealing options, including ...f6!?, but } 9... Nf6 $146 { followed by ...Rd8, ...g6, ...Bg7, etc. looks best. Black will emerge with a small advantage. } ) 9... Qd5 { This seems to be the most uncomfortable for White. So much so that the engine thinks White should play f3. } 10. f3 ( 10. Nxc6 $2 $146 { does not prevent our threat on g2 } 10... Qxg2 11. Rg1 Qxc6 { Black should readily anticipate such mistakes due to the frequency with which they occur. } ) ( 10. c4 { is another interesting idea, but falls afoul of potential danger along the d-file } 10... Qxc4 11. O-O Rd8 { ...e5 is threatened. These middlegames get complicated fairly quickly. } ) 10... Rd8 { [%cal Be7e5,Bd8d1]Black is threatening ...e5. } 11. Qd3 e6 $13 { [%cal Bg8f6]You can also play ...e5, but it might become a target in some positions. The evaluation is balanced, but I find Black's position to be preferable. Our development comes naturally and White might face difficulties castling if they intend on going to the kingside. A game might proceed with } 12. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 13. Qb3 Nf6 $146 14. Bd2 { White probably has the best chances castling to the queenside. } 14... Be7 15. O-O-O O-O 16. Kb1 Nd5 $146 { Black has a slight edge here. } * 

