te may be tempted to take on c6 now that their bishop is being attacked. This mistake happens to be White's top choice, even among strong players! Bizarrely, a remarkable percentage of games continued with both the immediately losing } 6. Nc3 $1 { [%cal Bc3d5,Bc3b5][%csl Rd4]The only critical move. } ( 6. Nxd4 $2 $146 { which hangs the g-pawn for nothing, and 6... cxd4 6.Qxd4?? which gives a piece to Black for free. } ) 6... Qe6+ 7. Ne2 Bd7 { Tempting White to immediately recapture in the center. } 8. O-O { Resisting the temptation to immediately restore material balance. From here, if White knows what they are doing they can forcibly secure themselves an advantage. Such is the risk involved in the 5...cxd4 variations. } 8... Nf6 9. Nexd4 Nxd4 { We have nothing better than to simplify the position. } 10. Nxd4 Qd6 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. c3 { Most people are playing c3 here, but } ( 12. Bg5 { is probably White's best shot at playing for a substantive advantage. } 12... e6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. c3 Rd8 15. Qf3 Bg7 $2 16. Rad1 O-O { Even still, these positions are unclear. } ) 12... e6 13. Re1 Be7 14. Bf4 Rd8 $13 { [%cal Bf6d5,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bd7a4]If White has an advantage here, it's hardly apparent. They are slightly more active, but Black should be fine with accurate play. In all likelihood the better player will be victorious. } * 

