te may be tempted to take on c6 now that their bishop is being attacked. This mistake happens to be White's top choice, even among strong players! Bizarrely, a remarkable percentage of games continued with both the immediately losing } 6. Nc3 $1 { [%cal Bc3d5,Bc3b5][%csl Rd4]The only critical move. } ( 6. Nxd4 $2 $146 { which hangs the g-pawn for nothing, and 6... cxd4 6.Qxd4?? which gives a piece to Black for free. } ) 6... Qe6+ 7. Ne2 Bd7 { Tempting White to immediately recapture in the center. } 8. O-O { [%cal Be2d4][%csl Rd4][%cal Bf1e1,Be1e6][%csl Re6]Since there aren't any resources Black can avail themselves of to preserve the material advantage, simply castling is the most accurate way to proceed. Now the knight is no longer pinned and Black's queen can be targeted along the e-file. From here, if White knows what they are doing they can forcibly secure themselves an advantage. Such is the risk involved in the 5...cxd4 variations. } 8... Nf6 { Black should just develop and get castled. } 9. Re1 Qd5 10. Bxc6 { If } ( 10. Nexd4 $146 { Black emerges with an acceptable position after } 10... Nxd4 $146 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Nxd4 $146 e6 13. Be3 Be7 14. c4 O-O $10 { These middlegames look quite unremarkable, but Black should be fine. } ) 10... Bxc6 11. Nexd4 { [%cal Bd1e2,Ba1d1,Bb2b3,Bc2c4,Bc1b2]With material balance restored, White can begin to centralize their pieces. } 11... e6 12. Qe2 { Preparing c4. } 12... Be7 13. c4 Qd7 14. Nxc6 Qxc6 15. Ne5 Qa6 { a6 is the most active square for Black's queen which doesn't compromise her safety. ...Qd6 and ...Qc7 allow Bf4, ...Qb6 allows a4-a5, ...Qc5 allows a3 \+ b4, and ...Qc8 is extremely passive. } 16. b3 Rd8 17. Bb2 O-O $14 { [%cal Bf6d7]White is better here, but not by much. White might like to continue with } 18. Ng4 $2 $146 { , where the least dangerous path forward for Black would be } 18... Nxg4 $146 19. Qxg4 g6 { How should White proceed? Allowing Black's rook to invade the second rank should always be a concern, and Black's queen still maintains pressure along the a-file, so maybe it's not such an easy decision. Let's suppose White continues with } 20. Qf4 f6 { Black's thematic sequence makes yet another appearance! } 21. h4 e5 22. Qe3 Bb4 23. Red1 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Qxa2 { Black has at least equal chances here. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "6.O-O with 7.b3 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.O-O with 7.b3 #1"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 $5 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5][%csl Re5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bf8e7][%csl Ye5,Yd5]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. The following lines display my preferred rejoinders to White's efforts to target c5. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. b3 { [%cal Rc1a3,Ra3c5][%csl Rc5][%cal Yb1c3,Yc3a4,Ya4c5]White chooses to invest their efforts into targeting c5. } 7... Bd6 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bf6f5,Bg8f6,Yd8e7]Remaining flexible. Stockfish has some creative ideas of ...Bg4 paired with ...f5 and ...Nf6. Of course, ...Bd6 also allows us to defend c5 with ...Qe7 if we would like. } 8. Ba3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nc3 { Be aware that } ( 10. g4 $2 { would be a serious mistake in these positions. } 10... Bf7 11. Nh4 $146 h5 { White's position is troubling already. For instance, White might continue with } 12. Nf5 $2 $146 hxg4 13. Nxg7+ $146 Kd7 14. Qxg4+ Kc7 { Black is winning. White will not be able to defend the kingside after ...Nh6, ...Qg8, etc. } ) 10... f5 $5 { [%csl Bc6,Bc5,Bd5,Be5,Bf5][%cal Yg2g4][%csl Rg4]Now dynamic complications are unavoidable. } 11. exf5 Nf6 { [%cal Bf6g4]Keeping control over g4, a critical square which used to be covered by our fallen f-pawn. } 12. Na4 { Targeting c5, as expected. Watch out for } ( 12. g4 $2 { , which may appear intimidating at a first glance. Remember, the point of 11...Nf6 was to prevent g4. Therefore, we respond with } 12... Nxg4 $146 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Kg2 O-O $19 { and Black is winning. f5 will fall and White's remaining kingside defenses will subsequently crumble. } ) 12... Qe7 { [%cal Be7c5][%csl Rc5]Most of the time Black should be happy to give White c5 for free, but with our ...f5 gambit already accepted this would be too much. } 13. Qe2 O-O $17 { [%cal Ba8e8,Be8e1,Re5e4][%csl Ra4,Ra3][%cal Rh5e2][%csl Rf3][%cal Ye7d7,Ye7c7,Ye7d8]Black is a pawn down, but White's position is much worse. White's queenside pieces are doing nothing now that they've failed in their assault on c5. If they ever move away from their posts, once Black gets ...Rae8 in, Black can simply move the queen from the e-file and aim for the killer ...e4!. A game might continue with Given the potency of the upcoming ...e4 threat, White might elect to break our everlasting pin with } 14. Rae1 ( 14. g4 $2 { , which loses immediately to } 14... Nxg4 $146 15. hxg4 Bxg4 16. Qe3 { And Black plays } 16... e4 { anyways! } 17. dxe4 dxe4 18. Nd2 $146 Qh4 19. f4 Rxf5 { White is getting crushed. } ) 14... Rae8 15. Bb2 $2 { Now Black's queen is free to step out of the e-file. } 15... Qd8 { Now let's see what can be done if White tries to unpin their kingside knight. Of course, if the queen strays too far, the capture on f3 would be fatal. } 16. Qe3 $2 d4 { This key move initiates a brilliant attack. } 17. Qe2 g6 { Black will soon have full compensation for the surrender of his kingside pawns. } 18. fxg6 $2 Nd5 $146 { The threat now is ...Bxf3! and White will be forced to give up the queen, lest the dark steed find his way to f4. } 19. gxh7+ $2 Kh8 { White is finished. He has no recourse to any defense which will prevent the forthcoming attack with ...Bxf3, ...Nf4, etc. } * 

