1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5][%csl Re5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%csl Bf6,Be5,Bd5,Bc5,Bc6]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. The following lines display my preferred rejoinders to White's efforts to target c5. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. b3 { [%cal Rc1a3,Ra3c5][%csl Rc5][%cal Yc3a4,Yc3b1]White chooses to invest their efforts into targeting c5. } 7... Bd6 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bf6f5,Bg8f6,Yd8e7]Remaining flexible. Stockfish has some creative ideas of ...Bg4 paired with ...f5 and ...Nf6. Of course, ...Bd6 also allows us to defend c5 with ...Qe7 if we would like. } 8. Ba3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nc3 { Be aware that } ( 10. g4 $2 { would be a serious mistake in these positions. } 10... Bf7 11. Nh4 $146 h5 { White's position is troubling already. For instance, White might continue with } 12. Nf5 $2 $146 hxg4 13. Nxg7+ $146 Kd7 14. Qxg4+ Kc7 { Black is winning. White will not be able to defend the kingside after ...Nh6, ...Qg8, etc. } ) 10... f5 $5 { [%csl Bc6,Bc5,Be5,Bd5,Bf5,Re4][%cal Bh5d1][%csl Rf3]Now dynamic complications are unavoidable. } 11. exd5 Ne7 { [%cal Be7c6,Bc6d4,Bd4f3,Rd5c6][%csl Rc6]A quiet, yet wonderful move. With this pawn sacrifice White will serve as the primary benefactor in Black's campaign to relocate his knight to the d4 square. If we can manage to get the knight to d4, the pressure on f3 will be overwhelming. If White does not accept this sacrifice, Black will recapture on d5 and enjoy a dominant center and a pleasant space advantage. } 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. Nb5 { This is the only way for White to avoid being significantly worse. Other moves allow the unacceptable ...Nd4. } 13... O-O 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. c3 { The only way to stop ...Nd4. Although now d3 is a weakness. } 15... Rf6 { [%cal Ba3f8][%csl Rf8]Getting the rook off of the diagonal. We might sacrifice c5 in some positions but shouldn't allow Bxc5 to come with the threat of Bxf8. } 16. Qe2 e4 $17 { [%csl Rf3,Re2,Rh3,Rg2][%cal Bf6f3,Bh5e2,Bd6d7,Bd7h3,Bf6g6]With ...e4 Black will be down another pawn, but will have a deadly kingside attack in exchange. Once the f-file opens up we can take on f3, damaging White's defenses, and attack his weaknesses with ...Rg6, ...Qd7, ...Ne5, etc. The game might continue on with } 17. dxe4 fxe4 18. Qxe4 { at which point } 18... Bxf3 { is perfectly timed. } 19. gxf3 Qd7 { Black takes aim at the shattered kingside. } 20. Kh2 Re8 21. Qg4 Qd6+ 22. Qg3 Ne5 $146 { Now White is forced to surrender their queen. } 23. f4 Rg6 24. fxe5 Qc6 25. Qxg6 hxg6 { Black is better. White's pieces aren't well coordinated and there are numerous weaknesses Black can start targeting. If 18... fxe4 18.Qc4+! Black should be careful not to give White the time to capture c5. 18...Bf7! 19.Qxe4 Bd5! 20.Qe3 Bxf3 The bishop has swung around and finally lands on f3, as initially intended. Stockfish thinks that White shouldn't even bother taking back on f3! 21.gxf3?? Qd7!! Black is winning, but even still conversion requires some tactical finesse. 22.f4 Re8 23.Qf3 Ne5!! This is the killer. White is finished, as they are too weak on the g and h-files. } * 

