and has an enjoyable position. My prediction is that most won't find h4 palatable as it gifts Black the g4 outpost. Additionally, after h4 it seems as though White will never be able to repel the accursed pin on the knight we've so ardently sustained since move eight. Either way, Black secures a favorable position. } ) 14... Ng5 { [%cal Bg5f3,Bh5d1][%csl Rf3]} 15. c7 Qe7 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Qe2 Bxf3 { A notable alternative is } ( 17... e4 $2 { and after } 18. dxe4 Bxf3 19. gxf3 fxe4 { Black will be invading the kingside shortly. There is merit to both 17...Bxf3 and 17...e4, but the former is a little trickier in my opinion. } ) 18. Qxe5 $7 { This is forced. After } ( 18. gxf3 $2 Nxh3+ $146 19. Kf1 Nf4 $146 { White will soon lose their queen. } 20. Qxe5 Qh6 { White must sacrifice on f4 to stop mate. } ) 18... Qh6 19. Qh2 { White evidently cannot recapture on f3 due to the fork, which is why the forced 18.Qxe5 might look unappealing at first glance. The bizarre looking 19.Qh2 is Leela's favorite move, but White realistically might try something else, such as } ( 19. Re3 $2 { which loses to } 19... Qg6 20. Kh2 Bxg2 ) 19... Bb7 20. Bxc5 Rf6 21. Re7 Rg6 22. Kf1 Ne6 $13 { [%cal Be6c5,Bg6g2,Bb7g2][%csl Rg2,Rc5]Black threatens both ...Bxg2+ and ...Nxc5. These positions are extremely difficult to navigate for both sides. I can't possibly explain all the nuances of the position here, so I would recommend further analysis for those interested. However, as it pertains to our immediate threats, there are numerous ways White can survive. For instance, } 23. c8=Q+ $10 Rxc8 24. Rxb7 Nxc5 $146 25. Rb8 Rc6 26. Rxc8+ Rxc8 { Black has a piece for three pawns. This position is equal if White is able to find 27.Qe5!, yet is still rather unclear. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "6.O-O with 7.b3 #5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.O-O with 7.b3 #5"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5][%csl Re5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bf8e7][%csl Ye5,Yd5]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. The following lines display my preferred rejoinders to White's efforts to target c5. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. b3 { [%cal Rc1a3,Ra3c5][%csl Rc5][%cal Yb1c3,Yc3a4,Ya4c5]White chooses to invest their efforts into targeting c5. } 7... Bd6 { [%cal Bc8g4,Bf6f5]Remaining flexible. Stockfish has some creative ideas of ...Bg4 paired with ...f5 and ...Nf6. Of course, ...Bd6 also allows us to defend c5 with ...Qe7 if we would like. } 8. Nc3 Ne7 { [%cal Bc3d5]An early Nc3 forces Black to defend the center. ...Ne7 is similarly our response if White tries Nc3 on move six. } 9. Ba3 O-O { [%cal Be7g6,Bf6f5,Bg6f4]Targeting c5 with this move order changes things slightly, though the underlying theme remains: Sacrifice material to initiate a violent campaign on the kingside! } 10. Na4 { [%csl Rc5][%cal Ba3c5,Bb4c5,Ba4c5]White continues to target c5. } 10... Ng6 { We should not concern ourselves with White's inconsequential queenside trifles. The game will be decided on the kingside. } 11. Bxc5 ( 11. Nxc5 $2 $146 { loses to } 11... Qa5 ) 11... f5 { [%cal Bb2b3,Bb1c3,Bc3a4,Ba4c5,Bc1a3,Ba3c5,Rf6f5]White has used six of their eleven moves to capture a worthless pawn. Meanwhile, Black is cooking up something sinister on the kingside. } 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. exd5 ( 13. exf5 $2 { doesn't work out so well for White. } 13... Rxf5 14. Nc3 $146 Rh5 { Black's kingside initiative is deadly. For instance: } 15. Ne2 $146 Bg4 16. Ng3 $146 Nh4 $146 17. Nxh5 $2 $146 Nxf3+ $146 { This is game over. } ) 13... cxd5 $17 { [%cal Bd5d4,Bc8b7,Yg6f4,Bb7g2,Yd6h6,Yf8f6]White is a pawn up, but Black is clearly the favorite here. We can continue with ...d4 and ...Bb7, bring our knight to the wonderful f4 square, and hopefully coordinate the eventual execution of the white monarch. } * 

