1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5][%csl Re5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nc3 Ne7 { While I would like to keep things simple, ...Bd6 does not work here. However, } ( 7... Bg4 { is a notable alternative if you want to try for similar positions to the 7.b3 variations. For instance: } 8. h3 Bh5 9. b3 Bd6 $2 { It's in the spirit of these sorts of positions to sacrifice our pawns! } 10. exd5 Ne7 $146 11. dxc6 O-O 12. Ne4 $146 f5 { White is probably a little better in these sorts of positions, but they look promising for Black anyway. Meanwhile, 7...Ne7 allows Black to immediately press for an advantage, as will be seen. } ) 8. exd5 { [%cal Bf1e1,Be1e8][%csl Re8][%cal Be4d5]The only reason I can think as to why someone might play this is to open up the e-file, but will White really be sufficiently compensated for the remediation of Black's damaged structure and the surrender of the center? } 8... cxd5 9. Nh4 { White has to find this move. If they play anything else they will be significantly worse. For instance: } ( 9. Re1 $2 Ng6 $146 { White might try to open up the center somehow, so } 10. d4 $2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 $146 Kf7 { Once again, ...Kf7 proves itself to be a valuable resource! Black is much better here. } ) 9... Be6 { [%cal Be6f7,Bc8e6,Yf3h4,Yf2f4]This is often a good idea when White intends to open up the kingside with the Nh4 \+ f4 maneuver. } 10. f4 Nc6 11. Qh5+ { This is the more energetic way to continue. Instead, } ( 11. fxe5 { leads to typical complications after } 11... Nxe5 $146 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Nf3 $146 O-O { Black is always comfortable in these sorts of positions. } ) 11... Bf7 12. Qg4 Qd7 { [%csl Rg4,Rd7][%cal Be8c8,Ba8d8]Black aims to castle queenside. White has the option to trade queens, but this exchange would clearly favor Black. With an active king, the bishop pair, and a dominant center, Black's position would make counterplay difficult for White. } 13. Qg3 exf4 14. Bxf4 O-O-O { [%cal Bg7g5,Bh7h5]Most of White's pieces are on the kingside, so this is perfectly sensible. Castling also enables us to initiate a pawnstorm with ...g5 and ...h5. White has no choice but to withdraw their bishop from the prime diagonal. } 15. Bd2 g5 16. Nf5 h5 17. h4 { White also might try } ( 17. h3 { but either way Black has a hook. } 17... h4 18. Qf2 Be6 19. Rae1 Rg8 20. Kh1 g4 { This looks scary, but White can hold on with accurate play. } ) 17... Be6 $13 { [%cal Bg3f2,Bh8g8,Yc6e5,Ye5g4,Gc6d4,Rg5h4,Rf5h4,Rf8d6][%csl Rf5][%cal Bd8e8]I like Black's chances here. Black will soon open up the g-file with ...gxh4 and can coordinate an attack on the soon-to-be semi-open g-file and diagonals. This looks fun to play from the Black side. } * 

