gold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nc3 { [%cal Be4d5,Bf1e1,Be1e8][%csl Re8]} 7... Ne7 { While I would like to keep things simple, ...Bd6 does not work here. However, } ( 7... Bg4 { is a notable alternative if you want to try for similar positions to the 7.b3 variations. For instance: } 8. h3 Bh5 9. b3 Bd6 $2 { It's in the spirit of these sorts of positions to sacrifice our pawns! } 10. exd5 Ne7 $146 11. dxc6 O-O 12. Ne4 $146 f5 { White is probably a little better in these sorts of positions, but they look promising for Black anyway. Meanwhile, 7...Ne7 allows Black to immediately press for an advantage, as will be seen. } ) 8. exd5 { The only reason I can think as to why someone might play this is to open up the e-file, but will White really be sufficiently compensated for the remediation of Black's damaged structure and the surrender of the center? } 8... cxd5 9. Re1 $2 { A natural looking mistake. As mentioned previously, } ( 9. Nh4 $146 { is White's only move to keep the pace. } ) 9... Ng6 10. d4 $5 { If White doesn't immediately open lines Black will just castle and steamroll White in the center. } 10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 ( 11. Nxd4 $146 { can be met with } 11... Kf7 12. Nb3 $146 Bb7 { where Black is in excellent shape. White doesn't have the resources to attack Black's king. } ) 11... Be6 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Be5d4]Legitimizing the threat on White's queen. } 12. Qa4+ Qd7 { The endgame favors Black considerably. We have open lines to the queenside, a massive center, and the bishop pair. The cherry on top is that White has nothing better than to take. } 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. Rd1 Kc6 $1 { [%csl Rc1,Ra1][%cal Ba7a5,Bf8d6,Bh8d8,Bf8e7]Black prepares for the endgame by activating the king! Black has complete control over the center, a sizable space advantage, the bishop pair, and an active king. Additionally, White's development prospects seem grim. Where are the queenside pieces going to go? If White tries for a queenside pawnstorm, chances are that Black will end up with a passed pawn. } * 

