probably a little better in these sorts of positions, but they look promising for Black anyway. Meanwhile, 7...Ne7 allows Black to immediately press for an advantage, as will be seen. } ) 8. h3 { [%cal Bc8g4][%csl Rg4]White restricts Black's bishop and waits for Black to commit to a plan. } 8... Ng6 { [%cal Bc8e6,Bf8d6,Be8g8,Bh8f8]h3 is a bit slow. Black can now just develop and castle without any issues. } 9. Ne2 { [%cal Bc2c4]White aims for c4. It's not clear what else White should be trying to do. } 9... Bd6 { [%cal Bf8e7,Bf8d6]Since the knight stepped away from c3 Black can now place the bishop on d6 without dropping the d-pawn. } 10. c4 Be6 11. b3 { White might instead try to clarify the situation in the center with } ( 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5 Bxd5 13. Nc3 $146 Bc6 14. Ne4 $146 Be7 { These lines are super sharp. For instance after } 15. Be3 c4 16. Rc1 f5 17. Nc5 $146 f4 { The position about to get seriously messy. } 18. Ne6 $2 $146 Qd7 19. Nxg7+ $146 Kf7 20. Nxe5+ $146 Nxe5 $146 21. Qh5+ Ng6 $146 22. Nf5 $146 fxe3 23. fxe3 Raf8 24. Rxc4 Bf6 { Black is winning here, but it looks extremely dangerous. You can always close down the center earlier with ...d4 after 10.c4 if these complications aren't agreeable to you. } ) 11... O-O 12. Ng3 Qd7 $17 { [%cal Bg6f4,Bh7h6,Ba7a5]Black has a moderate edge here, probably due to superior piece activity and central control. These middlegames tend to be moderately positional, but dynamic opportunities will arise once the position opens up, so stay alert. } * 

