gold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nc3 Ne7 { While I would like to keep things simple, ...Bd6 does not work here. However, } ( 7... Bg4 { is a notable alternative if you want to try for similar positions to the 7.b3 variations. For instance: } 8. h3 Bh5 9. b3 Bd6 $2 { It's in the spirit of these sorts of positions to sacrifice our pawns! } 10. exd5 Ne7 $146 11. dxc6 O-O 12. Ne4 $146 f5 { White is probably a little better in these sorts of positions, but they look promising for Black anyway. Meanwhile, 7...Ne7 allows Black to immediately press for an advantage, as will be seen. } ) 8. Nh4 d4 { Playing Nh4 without first taking on d5 allows Black to close down the center before White can get f4 in. } 9. Na4 ( 9. Ne2 $2 $146 { Blocks White's queen in and therefore allows } 9... g5 10. Nf3 $146 h5 { where Black can relocate the knight to f4 and enjoy a substantial space advantage. } ) 9... h5 $1 { White can have c5 if they want. ...g5 is incoming! } 10. Nxc5 { The other two options for White are ~Sacrificing a piece with } ( 10. f4 $2 exf4 11. Rxf4 g5 12. Rxf6 gxh4 { It's not easy to evaluate these sort of positions. White probably has compensation or a forced draw somewhere in the mess, but it will probably be tricky to figure out in real time. ~The other move is } ) ( 10. Nf3 $146 { , which just allows Black to quickly catch up in development. } 10... Ng6 $146 11. b3 Be6 { etc. White would be unwise to pursue c5 with } 12. Ba3 $2 { as now Black has the f4 square. } 12... Nf4 $146 { Black can brew up a decisive attack very quickly if White is not careful, for instance: } 13. Bxc5 Bxc5 14. Nxc5 $146 Bg4 { White is in danger. } 15. h3 Rh6 { with the idea of ...Qc8 and sacrificing on h3, and if White succumbs to the pressure and captures the bishop } 16. hxg4 $2 { Black wins with } 16... hxg4 17. Nh2 $146 f5 18. g3 Kf7 $3 { A brilliant move, clearing the way for Black's pieces to access h8. There's plenty of attacking potential in these positions if White errs and opts for natural ideas. } ) 10... g5 11. Nf3 Ng6 { Black gains time if White greedily accepts the pawn. } 12. Nb3 Bg4 13. h3 Qd7 { Black threatens 14.-- Bxh3! 15.gxh3 Qxh3 where ...g4 followed by ...Nh4 would crush White. This could continue with: } 14. Kh2 { Defending h3. } 14... Be6 { [%cal Bg5g4]Black makes room for ...g4. } 15. c3 g4 $17 { [%cal Bf8d6,Bc6c5,Bh8g8,Bg4h3][%csl Rh3]White is on the defense. The game could continue with } 16. Ng1 $146 Bd6 17. Ne2 $146 gxh3 18. g3 c5 19. f4 Bg4 20. f5 Ne7 $146 { Black is slowly grinding out the win. Black can continue with a well-timed ...h4 and eventually sacrifice on f5 to open the diagonals to White's king. For instance: } 21. Qc2 $2 a5 22. a4 h4 23. gxh4 c4 $3 { This is the only winning move here. These positions are extremely sharp and are certainly worth investigating further. } 24. dxc4 Nxf5 $146 25. exf5 d3 26. Qxd3 e4+ { White loses the queen. } * 

