gold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nc3 Ne7 { While I would like to keep things simple, ...Bd6 does not work here. However, } ( 7... Bg4 { is a notable alternative if you want to try for similar positions to the 7.b3 variations. For instance: } 8. h3 Bh5 9. b3 Bd6 $2 { It's in the spirit of these sorts of positions to sacrifice our pawns! } 10. exd5 Ne7 $146 11. dxc6 O-O 12. Ne4 $146 f5 { White is probably a little better in these sorts of positions, but they look promising for Black anyway. Meanwhile, 7...Ne7 allows Black to immediately press for an advantage, as will be seen. } ) 8. b3 { White commits to the aforementioned b3 \+ Ba3 \+ Na4 plan to target c5. } 8... Ng6 9. Ba3 Nf4 $1 { [%cal Bc1f4]Taking advantage of the fact that White's bishop no longer covers f4. } 10. g3 { After ...Nf4 White looks to be out of good moves. g3 certainly isn't great, but Black's knight will be a great annoyance if left on f4. It would be worth explaining why other moves don't work out so well too, so below I've offered some analysis. Firstly, } ( 10. Ne2 $2 $146 { would be extremely risky. } 10... dxe4 11. Nxf4 $146 exf3 12. Re1 Kf7 { Black's king sensibly steps off of the file, renewing the kingside threats. } 13. Nh5 $146 g6 14. Ng3 $146 fxg2 15. Kxg2 $2 h5 { This is horrendous for White. } ) 10... Ng6 { [%csl Rf3,Rg2,Rh3]Black's equestrian endeavors have generated multiple weaknesses. It doesn't matter that Black is behind on development. This is already better for Black. } 11. Nd2 { White must withdraw the knight immediately. If instead White continues their attack on c5 with } ( 11. Na4 $2 $146 { Black should capitalize on the opportunity to exploit the weakened light squares } 11... Bg4 { Black now threatens 12.-- dxe4! 13.dxe4 Qxd1 14.Rfxd1 Bxf3 } ) 11... Bh3 12. Re1 Be7 { [%cal Bd8d5][%csl Rd5]Careful not to drop a pawn on d5. } 13. Na4 O-O 14. Bxc5 f5 $1 { [%cal Rf5f4]We have arrived at a position similar to those found in the 7.b3 variations. To learn more about those variations, click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). This appears to be an improvement on those, as White's kingside has already been considerably weakened. Black will find the opportune moment to play ...f4 and generate an attack, as per usual. } * 

