1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 $5 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5][%csl Re5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. O-O e5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bc8e6,Be7g6,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bf8e7]If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nh4 Be6 { [%cal Rd1h5,Rf2f4,Bf3h4]White intends on punishing ...f6 by invading on the light squares and opening up the kingside. } 8. f4 { White also might prepare f4 by first exchanging on d5 } ( 8. exd5 cxd5 9. f4 { This might be a little more dangerous for Black. Apparently ...exf4!? is sound, but quickly begins to look uncomfortable for Black. The safe way to continue is with } 9... Nh6 $146 10. fxe5 fxe5 11. Nf3 $146 Nf7 $146 12. Qe2 Bd6 13. c4 O-O { This is equal, but I much prefer Black. Black has the center, the bishops, and superior development. Granted, White does have counterplay in the center. } ) 8... dxe4 ( 8... exf4 $2 { would lead to a version of the uncomfortable mess I was referring to earlier. } 9. exd5 cxd5 10. Qe2 Qd7 11. Re1 { White gets serious play on the open e-file. Black now has to sacrifice the exchange. } 11... Kf7 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Nxg6 $146 hxg6 14. Qxh8 { Black apparently is doing fine, but White seems to be the one attacking here. I would rather the roles be reversed! } ) 9. fxe5 { The only testing move. Liquidating into the endgame with } ( 9. dxe4 $2 { just lands White in a worse position after } 9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 exf4 11. Nf3 $146 g5 ) 9... Qd4+ 10. Kh1 O-O-O { Black's king needs to get out of the center. } 11. Rf4 $1 { [%cal Bf4d4,Be4d3][%csl Rd4][%cal Bh4f3]This is a tricky idea if White can spot it. White is undeterred by the potential ...g5 threat and foreshadows Nf3. } 11... Qxe5 { [%cal Bh4f3]} ( 11... g5 $2 { would be premature. } 12. Nf3 $146 Qd7 13. Rxe4 ) 12. Nc3 f5 13. Qe2 Nf6 14. Nf3 Qc7 $13 { [%cal Bd3e4,Bf5e4,Be6d5,Bf8d6,Bd6h2,Bd5g2,Bh8e8,Bc8b8]This position is extremely strange. White will probably be a little bit better if they can accurately defuse Black's attacking ideas. The game might continue with } 15. dxe4 fxe4 16. Ng5 $146 Re8 17. Nxe6 $146 Rxe6 18. Nxe4 $146 Bd6 19. Nxd6+ $146 Qxd6 20. Qa6+ $2 { This looks natural, but White should be cautious about backrank ideas. } 20... Kb8 21. Rf1 Re4 { Black is now threatening ...Ng4! White should liquidate into the roughly equal endgame with } 22. Qd3 Qxd3 23. cxd3 Re2 { Both sides have chances here. } * 

