1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 f6 6. O-O e5 { As we have discussed, White needs to be exceptionally careful in these lines. So far we have examined 7.b3, 7.Nc3, and 7.Nh4. These are White's only good moves, however we might plausibly encounter others during our games. } 7. Re1 $2 { A natural looking move, but hardly one we should worry about. In any case, if White doesn't pressure our center we can just proceed with the simple ...Bd6, ...Ne7, and ...O-O, with a typical position and excellent attacking prospects. } ( 7. Nbd2 $2 $146 { You'll see this move in some mainline Rossolimo positions. Fortunately, here it is quite bad for White. } 7... Bd6 $2 { This is fine, but ...Ne7 is slightly more accurate. In some positions White will push c4, initiate exchanges on d5, and then place a knight on e4, hitting the bishop. So the engine prefers to delay the development of the bishop for this reason. } ) ( 7. exd5 cxd5 { We've discussed the variant of this with 7.Nc3 first. Much of the same applies here and in all likelyhood there will be transpositions. } 8. Re1 $2 { A common error. } 8... Bd6 9. Nc3 $2 $146 { Following the most common continuation, White is nearly lost already. } 9... Ne7 $146 10. Nb5 $146 Bb8 11. c4 d4 $19 { With a decisive advantage. } ) ( 7. Be3 $2 Bd6 $17 { The bishop is not well-placed on e3, as now White will be unable to play the typical Nc3. In any case, this allows us to accelerate our development scheme. } ) ( 7. h3 $2 { Attempting to restrict the bishop, but White effectively enters our prep a tempo down. The bishop won't go to g4 in many lines anyways. } 7... Bd6 8. Nc3 $146 Ne7 $146 9. b3 O-O 10. Ba3 $17 { etc. We've seen this already in the trainables, but without h3. } ) 7... Bd6 8. Nc3 ( 8. exd5 { We should always be glad to see White undouble our pawns. } 8... cxd5 { White only has one move to keep the pace. } 9. c4 { Even still, Black has all the chances. } 9... d4 10. Nbd2 $146 Ne7 $146 11. Ne4 $146 Bb7 $17 { White must be dearly missing their light squared bishop. This looks quite dreadful for them. } ) 8... Ne7 { The evaluation is already nearly -1.0 if White doesn't spot b3. It's difficult to see what else is to be done. } 9. Bd2 $6 ( 9. b3 { Now we basically transpose to a better version of the lines we've covered in the trainables. White has wasted time with Re1 and is consequently much worse.. } 9... O-O 10. Na4 $2 $146 Ng6 $17 $146 { With ...f5 ideas incoming. } ) 9... O-O 10. Ne2 Bg4 11. Ng3 f5 $17 { With a significant advantage already. As you can see, we only need acquaint ourselves with the basic schematic outlined in the trainables to easily parry these 7th move mistakes. } * 

