1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. In consolidating the central light squares by occupying them with pawns, White justifies the decision to trade off the corresponding bishop. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { [%cal Bf7f6,Be7e5]«Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. c4 e5 { If White doesn't opt for e5, exd5, or Nh4 on move six, Black should always reply with ...e5. After ...e5 White can pursue a number of basic middlegame plans. Among these include the following: * Target Black's weak c5 pawn with Nc3-Na4, b3 \+ Ba3, etc. Generally, we should entirely disregard White's nugatory queenside endeavors and focus on the kingside. Black can often generate a deadly attack in these lines because White's pieces are focused on the wrong side of the board. * Challenge Black's center with c4, Nc3, etc. This typically will result in closed positions because the mounting pressure on d5 will prompt Black to respond by temporarily closing the center with ...d4. White might eventually combine this blueprint with the former. * Pursue kingside mischief with Nh4, f4, Qh5, etc. This is by far the least-pursued plan, but is probably the most dangerous. Differences in move order do introduce certain nuances, but most deviations on move six and seven will lead to transpositions. } 7. Nc3 d4 { [%cal Bf6f5,Bf8d6]With so much pressure on d5, temporarily closing the center would be expedient to our objective of launching a future kingside attack. The immediate ...d4 also tempts White to coordinate their forces to the queenside to target our weak c5 pawn, which is precisely how we want them to play. As we have previously observed, Black is easily able to generate an initiative on the kingside when White focuses on c5. It's worth mentioning that White could release the tension immediately after 6...e5 with 7... e5 7.cxd5?! , but this isn't accurate. Black can secure an advantage after 7...cxd5 8.exd5 Ne7! Recapturing with the queen allows Nc3 with tempo. Black will recapture on d5 and castle with a better position. } 8. Ne2 { [%cal Be2g3][%csl Rf5,Rh5]White reroutes to the kingside, possibly hoping for counterplay on the light squares. } 8... Bd6 9. Ng3 g6 $1 { [%cal Bg3f5,Bg3h5][%csl Rh5,Rf5]Restricting White's knight. Not only is it poorly positioned, but now White has wasted time moving it to a place where it has no future. } 10. O-O h5 { Black immediately attempts to punish White's curious kingside configuration. } 11. Nh4 ( 11. h4 $2 Nh6 $146 { The knight will soon come to f7, Black will castle, and enjoy a moderate edge for the upcoming positional middlegame. } ) 11... Kf7 { [%cal Bf7g6][%csl Rg6]} 12. Qe2 Bg4 13. f3 Bd7 $15 { [%cal Bd8c7,Ba8e8,Ba7a5,Ba5a4,Bg8e7,Bf7g7][%csl Rg3,Rh4]Black most certainly has the preferable position here. Knights are usually regarded to be the better of the two minor pieces in closed positions, but White's knights are abysmal. They are almost entirely immobilized. } * 

