imilar idea earlier in this chapter. In this case, after } 8... Be6 9. f4 $2 { doesn't quite work out so well for White. } 9... exf4 10. Nf5 $146 g5 11. Qh5+ Bf7 12. Qf3 h5 { Black has an incredible position. } ) ( 8. h3 $2 { allows Black to strike on the kingside. } 8... g5 9. Nbd2 $146 h5 10. Nh2 $146 Bd6 { Black can proceed with typical developing ideas, such as ...Ne7-Ng6, prevent b4 with ...a5, and eventually play for the ...g4 break. } ) 8... Ne7 { [%cal Bf2f4,Re5f4,Be7g6,Bg6f4][%csl Rf4]Precise. Black will follow the exchange on f4 with ...Ng6, hitting whatever piece eventually lands there. } 9. f4 exf4 10. Bxf4 Ng6 11. Qh5 ( 11. Bg3 { would end up wasting time. } 11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Nd2 $146 O-O { Black has a small advantage. We can eventually try for ...f5 to open up the center. } ) 11... Be7 { Instead, } ( 11... Bd6 $2 { allows } 12. e5 fxe5 13. Bg5 Qd7 { , which looks rather uncomfortable. I recommend avoiding this mistake. } ) 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Bg3 a5 $15 { [%cal Ba8a7,Ba7b7,Bc8e6,Yg6h8,Yh8f7,Bf7e5,Bf7g5,Ba5a4,Rf6f5]Black is slightly better. We have the bishops and the b-file. Black might also play for an eventual ...f5. } * 

