er play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. Nh4 g6 { We need to prevent Qh5+. With our e-pawn still on e7 we can't play ...Ne7, so ...g6 is a necessity. } 7. f4 $1 e5 { Staying consistent with the theme of the chapter. Black plays ...e5 whenever the conditions permit. } 8. Nc3 dxe4 $1 { Now is the time to capture e4. This might appear positionally dubious due to the stacked pawn island that the capture produces, but Black would be wise to do it anyway. White is already ahead in development. If we wait a few more moves to catch up, White will be the one initiating exchanges and opening up the position. For instance, } ( 8... Bg7 $2 9. O-O Ne7 $146 10. fxe5 fxe5 11. Bg5 { Black will struggle to keep up with White's initiative if we choose to play like this. One particularly appealing feature of 8. Nc3 8...dxe4! is that if White recaptures with the d-pawn 9.dxe4?! White's f4 pawn will be swiftly executed. 9...Qxd1+ 10.Nxd1 exf4! Black's pawn is immune to capture due to the potential ...g5 fork. } ) 9. Nxe4 f5 $1 { [%cal Bf5e4][%csl Re4,Rh4][%cal Bd8h4,Ye4g5]Forcing White's hand. } 10. Ng5 Ne7 { Black sacrifices e5 to catch up on development! These lines can get crazy extremely quickly. For instance, } 11. fxe5 ( 11. Nhf3 $2 $146 h6 12. Nh3 $146 e4 13. Ne5 $146 c4 { The point here is that after } 14. Nxc4 $146 { Black has } 14... Ba6 { with compensation. These positions look like fun. } ) 11... Bg7 12. Ngf3 { [%cal Bc1g5]The knight sensibly vacates the g5 square to make room for the bishop. This is White's best move. Situating the loose knights should be White's priority. If they get too eager to get the king out of the center Additionally, choosing the correct knight to reposition is critical. } ( 12. O-O $2 { they could quickly land themselves in a lost position. } 12... Qd4+ 13. Kh1 Qxh4 $19 ) ( 12. Nhf3 $2 $146 { gets White into trouble. } 12... h6 13. Nh3 $146 g5 { You know something has gone wrong when the computer thinks White's best move is to stop trying to save the piece and just sacrifice on g5! } ) 12... h6 { [%cal Bc1g5][%csl Rg5][%cal Yg6g5]Preventing Bg5 and preparing ...g5. Notice that the knight on h4 will be lost if White doesn't play g3. Interestingly, White could sacrifice and maybe be ok. } 13. g3 ( 13. Qe2 $2 g5 14. Nxg5 $146 hxg5 15. Bxg5 Qd5 16. Nf3 $146 Ng6 $146 { Black has superior long term prospects, but it's still an unclear position. } ) 13... g5 14. Ng2 Ng6 15. O-O Qe7 $13 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8][%csl Re5][%cal Ba8b8,Rc1e3,Rb2b3,Rc1b2,Rf5f4,Rc8g4,Rc8h3]Covering c5 and adding more pressure to e5. Black will castle right away and wait for White to reveal their hand. If we are unable to capture e5 right away then we should try to break out with a well-timed ...f4. Suppose a game continues with } 16. b3 O-O 17. Bb2 { White wants to hold on to e5. Now is the time to strike. } 17... f4 { Black is now able to swing the bishop over to g4 or h3 and stack up on the f-file. } 18. Qe2 Bg4 19. Qe4 Qe6 20. Rae1 Rf7 21. Nd2 $146 Raf8 { Black has excellent play on the f-file. Moreover, White's kingside is likely to open up soon, making it difficult both to defend the king and the e5 pawn. Both sides have chances. } * 

