1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 $1 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bf6e5][%csl Re5,Rf3]«'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. exf6 $2 exf6 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be8f7,Be7g6,Bh7h5]Black is already better. In these structures, specifically those involving ...g5!?, Black's backward e-pawn becomes a long-term positional deficiency. It forces the kingside bishop and knight to develop by some other means than through the e7 square and is fixed defending the f-pawn so long as the tension is held. Taking on f6 just enables Black to improve piece coordination and remedy the disharmonious features of his structure. White has the best chances when they hold the tension as long as possible. Our position looks somewhat ridiculous, but development comes easy and Black has significant control over the center and kingside. Our plan for the immediate future is to play ...Ne7-Ng6, to secure our king with ...Kf7, and then launch ...h5. } 8. O-O { [%cal Bh7h5,Bg5g4]Apparently this is White's best move here, curiously walking the king straight into a pawn storm. } 8... Ne7 9. Re1 Kf7 $1 { [%cal Be7g6,Rg5g4,Bh7h5][%csl Rf3]Black's king will be perfectly safe on f7. White's pieces have no reasonable way to get to the kingside right now due to our oppressive central and anomalous kingside pawns. This might be a different story if White still had their light squared bishop, but too bad for them. } 10. c4 { White challenges our center. If they can chip away at our pawn mass their pieces might be able to use the center as a conduit to get access to our king. } 10... Ng6 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bg6h4][%csl Rh4][%cal Yf3d2][%csl Rc1,Rb1]Black prepares ...g4, after which White's knight would be forced backwards, obstructing the development of their queenside pieces. } 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. d4 g4 $1 13. Nfd2 h5 $17 { [%cal Bh5h4,Bh4h3,Ba8b8,Bd8c7,Bc7h2][%csl Rf3,Rg2,Rh1][%cal Bh3g2,Yc8b7,Yc8e6,Gg6e5,Ge5f3]Black has an excellent position and clearly has the advantage. Our plan is simple: Run Harry to h3. From there we could capture g2 if White lets us, opening up the h-file. h2 could subsequently be targeted with ...Qc7. Of course, g3 would prevent such a ploy from coming about, but then White's kingside light squares would suffer. Our bishop might go to b7. Our knight could come to e5 once White's d-pawn has been dealt with. This position is so rich with appealing ideas! A game might continue with } 14. dxc5 h4 15. Nc3 $146 h3 16. Qb3 g3 $2 { This position is already crazy! Taking g3 loses. } 17. hxg3 $2 hxg2 18. Kxg2 Qd7 { If White tries } 19. Rh1 $2 Nf4+ $3 $146 { results in mate. Trying to liquidate into an endgame earlier with 17... g3 17.Qxd5+?? also immediately loses. 17...Qxd5 18.Nxd5 gxh2+ 19.Kxh2 hxg2+ 20.Kxg2 Bb7!-+ Going back, 17... g3 17.Nf3 would be White's best chance, but after 17...gxf2+ 18.Kxf2 Rh5! 19.Be3 hxg2 Black's advantage is still significant. } * 

