l we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. exf6 $2 exf6 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be8f7,Be7g6]Black is already better. In these structures, specifically those involving ...g5!?, Black's backward e-pawn becomes a long-term positional deficiency. It forces the kingside bishop and knight to develop by some other means than through the e7 square and is fixed defending the f-pawn so long as the tension is held. Taking on f6 just enables Black to improve piece coordination and remedy the disharmonious features of his structure. White has the best chances when they hold the tension as long as possible. Our position looks somewhat ridiculous, but development comes easy and Black has significant control over the center and kingside. Our plan for the immediate future is to play ...Ne7-Ng6, to secure our king with ...Kf7, and then launch ...h5. } 8. O-O { Apparently this is White's best move here, curiously walking the king straight into a pawn storm. } 8... Ne7 9. d4 { White needs to try to open up the position. } 9... g4 $1 { [%csl Rd4]Simply forcing the knight away and increasing the pressure on d4. } 10. Nfd2 { Nfd2 looks ugly, but there really aren't any other good squares for the knight. Nh4 probably will result in the h-file opening up and will be discussed in more depth shortly. If White instead finds } ( 10. Ne1 $2 $146 { more appealing, Black can take d4, walk the king up to f7 after White's queen recaptures, and then launch Harry down the board: } 10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 Kf7 12. Nc3 $146 h5 { These are all typical ideas for us. The queen is not particularly well placed on d4, as ...Nf5 could come at any moment. Then we have ...Bd6 \+ ...Qc7, ...Bd7, etc. These positions look rough for White. } ) 10... cxd4 11. Nb3 h5 { Harry is headed to h3 and there's not much White can do to stop him. } 12. Nxd4 { Once again, if the queen captures d4 Black has similar complications as those outlined earlier, e.g. } ( 12. Qxd4 Kf7 13. Nc3 $146 { There are all sorts of appealing moves here: ...Ng6, ...Nf5, ...Qb6, etc., all of which retain Black's advantage. } 13... h4 { is probably my favorite of the bunch. Going straight for the throat. It's hard to find a good move for White here. } ) 12... h4 13. Re1 Kf7 { Typically f7 is the ideal square for our king in the 7.exf6 variations. We should play this at some point even if not prompted by Re1. } 14. Nc3 h3 15. g3 $2 c5 $17 { [%cal Bd5d4,Be7g6,Be7f5,Yc8f5]Black has a crushing initiative. White's light squares are hopelessly weak and their central endeavors have been futile. Once their knight retreats we can advance further in the center with ...d4 and try to find a way to break through on the light squares. A game might continue with } 16. Nb3 $146 d4 17. Bf4 $2 Bf5 18. Ne4 $146 Ng6 $146 { White is already lost! ...Nxf4 and ...Qd5 are coming. There is no viable defense. } * 

