ible. Our position looks somewhat ridiculous, but development comes easy and Black has significant control over the center and kingside. Our plan for the immediate future is to play ...Ne7-Ng6, to secure our king with ...Kf7, and then launch ...h5. } 8. O-O { Apparently this is White's best move here, curiously walking the king straight into a pawn storm. } 8... Ne7 9. d4 { White needs to try to open up the position. } 9... g4 { Simply forcing the knight away and increasing the pressure on d4. } 10. Nh4 Ng6 { Black invites White to open the h-file. White may not like it, but they don't have anything better than to exchange on g6. However, White does have a crafty trick here which we should be aware of: } 11. Re1+ ( 11. g3 $2 { would be disastrous. } 11... Nxh4 $146 12. gxh4 Qc7 13. Nc3 $146 Bd6 { h2 is doomed. } ) ( 11. f3 $2 { Black should not yet capture the knight. } 11... Nxh4 $2 $146 12. Qe1+ { Suddenly White is back in the game. Instead, we should simply force the rook to e1 with 11. f3 11...Ba6! 12.Re1+ Kf7 , and now the threat on h4 has been renewed. However, if White now proceeds with 13.Nxg6?? suddenly Black is winning! 13...hxg6 14.fxg4 Qc7! 15.g3 Bd6 16.Qf3 Rae8 17.Bd2 cxd4! This is horrendous for White. Their queenside is still undeveloped and there isn't a simple way to remediate White's inactivity. Black's queen is going to b6 to open discoveries on White's king and to take apart White's immobile queenside. Going back, White's only chance of staying in the game is with 12. Qe1+ 13.Nf5! but even so, White will be struggling after 13...h5! 14.fxg4 hxg4 15.Qxg4 Bc8! 16.Qf3 cxd4! etc. } ) 11... Kf7 12. Nxg6 hxg6 { [%cal Bf8d6,Bd8c7,Bc7h2][%csl Rh2][%cal Yd8b6,Yf8c5,Yb6f2][%csl Rf2][%cal Yb6b2,Gc8f5]With the h-file open, Black's default plan is to target h2 with ...Qc7 and ...Bd6. f2 is also a weakness here, so if White insists on defending h2 with } 13. c4 ( 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bf4 { then we can redirect our focus to f2 instead. } 14... Qb6 { White can't defend everything. If } 15. Bg3 { then the b-pawn falls } 15... Qxb2 16. Nd2 $146 Qc3 17. Nb3 $146 Bb6 18. a4 a5 { White should consider trading queens here with Qd3, but even then Black's advantage would be nearly decisive. These positions look quite miserable for White. } ) 13... Bd6 $5 { [%cal Bg2g3,Rh8h5,Rd8h8][%csl Rh2][%cal Rd6h2]...Qd6 and ...Qc7 are also excellent here too, but I discovered a particularly nasty idea with ...Bd6. We will follow up with ...Rh5! after White naturally responds with g3 and then ...Qh8!!, where we would have a monstrous attack on the h-file. } 14. g3 Rh5 $19 { [%cal Bd8h8,Bh8h2][%csl Bh2]White's king is in serious danger. If White fails to find Nd2, a well timed ...Qh8 simply ends the game. For instance, } 15. Nc3 $2 $146 Qh8 16. h4 Rxh4 17. gxh4 Qxh4 $19 { However, 15... Rh5 15.Nd2 actually addresses the threat of ...Qh8 because White then would have Nf1!, so instead Black should just play in the center for now. 15...cxd4! 16.cxd5 Rxd5 17.Ne4 Be6 and this still looks extremely unpleasant for White. } * 

