ible. Our position looks somewhat ridiculous, but development comes easy and Black has significant control over the center and kingside. Our plan for the immediate future is to play ...Ne7-Ng6, to secure our king with ...Kf7, and then launch ...h5. } 8. O-O { Apparently this is White's best move here, curiously walking the king straight into a pawn storm. } 8... Ne7 9. c4 { The most accurate way to proceed. White should not waste any time with Re1. Black's king will be headed to f7 whether or not he is provoked to do so. } 9... Kf7 { It's better that we evacuate the king from what will quickly become an open center sooner rather than later. } 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. d4 { White slowly breaks away at our center, as they should. Opening up the position in this manner is their best shot at finding compensation for their previous mistakes. } 11... c4 $1 { [%cal Yc8f5][%csl Rd3,Rc2]White's central light squares are weaknesses. Black can proceed with ...Bf5 and might install the bishop on d3 if White allows it. } 12. b3 { Of course, if White does nothing to continue to challenge our central pawns, e.g. with something like } ( 12. Re1 { , Black can proceed with our typical kingside expansion. } 12... h5 { White can now try to sacrifice on g5, but to little success. Either way, Black's initiative grows with each move. } 13. Bxg5 $2 fxg5 14. Nxg5+ $146 Kg6 $2 { Somehow our king is safe on g6! Safe enough for the moment, anyway. } 15. h4 Nf5 $146 16. Qc2 Bh6 { White's illusion of compensation fades away with each move. } 17. Nf3 $146 Bf4 18. Nc3 $146 Kh6 { This looks like pure chaos, but Black is winning! } ) 12... Bf5 { [%cal Bf5b1][%csl Rd3,Rc2]Continuing the theme of targeting the weak light squares. } 13. Nc3 { Or, if } ( 13. Re1 { Black has } 13... Ng6 $146 14. bxc4 dxc4 { These positions are super complicated, as usual. Black has ...Bd3 & ...Bb4 ideas and should be a bit better so long as we accurately fight for the center and queenside. } ) 13... Rc8 $15 { Black has a great position here. We'll likely need to delay our plans to storm the kingside in order to deal with White's efforts to undermine our center, but this should play out in our favor if we can parry White's attempts at counterplay. Granted, this is easier said than done, but this sort of position probably approximates a best case scenario for White following the exf6? mistake. A game might continue with } 14. bxc4 Rxc4 15. Qb3 Nc6 $146 { The idea here is to hit the queen with ...Na5, then withdraw the rook so that our knight can occupy the c4 square. } 16. Be3 Qd7 $2 { Black stops Na4-c5 ideas! } 17. Rac1 Na5 $146 18. Qb2 Rc8 19. Ne2 $146 Nc4 $146 { Black is in excellent shape here. With the knight on c4 it will be hard for White to get progress on the queenside. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.d3 with 7.exf6 #5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.d3 with 7.exf6 #5"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. exf6 $2 exf6 { Black is already better. In these structures, specifically those involving ...g5!?, Black's backward e-pawn becomes a long-term positional deficiency. It forces the kingside bishop and knight to develop by some other means than through the e7 square and is fixed defending the f-pawn so long as the tension is held. Taking on f6 just enables Black to improve piece coordination and remedy the disharmonious features of his structure. White has the best chances when they hold the tension as long as possible. Our position looks somewhat ridiculous, but development comes easy and Black has significant control over the center and kingside. Our plan for the immediate future is to play ...Ne7-Ng6, to secure our king with ...Kf7, and then launch ...h5. } 8. Qe2+ { [%cal Bb1c3,Bc1d2,Be1c1,Ba1d1]White prepares queenside castling. } 8... Kf7 9. Nc3 { White could try castling to the kingside after Qe2 too, but then Black gets a similar initiative to our previous lines. Plus, the addition of Qe2 just makes no sense. Our king was headed to f7 eventually anyway and the queen will only be a target so long as it's on the open e-file. } ( 9. O-O $2 Ne7 $146 { White's best attempt to confuse Black might start with } 10. h4 $2 { , but after } 10... h6 { Black has no problems. White needs to be extremely cautious. For instance, after } 11. Nbd2 $146 Ng6 $146 12. h5 $2 Nf4 $146 { White's position is beginning to collapse. } 13. Qe1 Qd7 { h4 has considerably weakened White's kingside. Now we go in for the kill. } 14. Nh2 $146 Bd6 15. g3 $2 Qh3 16. gxf4 Rg8 { White has permission to resign. } ) 9... Bd6 { I think it's best to start with ...Bd6. If we opt for } ( 9... Rb8 $2 { first, White has some tricky sacrifices we will have to worry about accurately addressing. } 10. Bxg5 $2 fxg5 11. Ne5+ $146 Kg7 12. Nxc6 $146 { These lines are playable, but I think we would be prudent to avoid affording White the opportunity to choose this route. } ) 10. Bd2 Ne7 11. O-O-O h5 $17 { [%cal Be7g6,Be7f5,Ba8b8,Yc8f5,Bh8e8,Rh2h3,Rg2g4][%csl Rf5]Strangely enough, neither side really has immediate attacking opportunities at the moment. Naturally, Black has the advantage. We have a sizable space advantage, so it's much easier for us to coordinate and maneuver our pieces to more palatable squares. The key squares we will be fighting over are on the kingside. White probably will be displeased with the limited mobility of their pieces and will try to stack up on the open e-file, open up the kingside, or both. White should eventually try for the g4 break to target the weak f5 square. } * 

