comes easy and Black has significant control over the center and kingside. Our plan for the immediate future is to play ...Ne7-Ng6, to secure our king with ...Kf7, and then launch ...h5. } 8. h4 { White may try an early h4, which is a clever idea in a way. Black will probably have to play ...g4 sometime soon, partially closing down the kingside. Hence, with h4 White sidesteps a dynamic middlegame where White is forced to endure an aggressive kingside maelstrom. } 8... Qe7+ { I judge this to be positionally superior to the natural alternative 8...g4. The reasoning is simple. With ...Qe7+ White is faced with an uncomfortable choice. Either forfeit castling rights with } 9. Qe2 $6 ( 9. Kf1 g4 10. Ng1 $146 h5 11. Ne2 $146 Kf7 { where mobilizing both the king and queen side pieces would surely be a challenge, or instead elect to simplify the position with 9... Qe7+ 9.Qe2!? I suspect most people would opt for the latter, but it comes with an unfortunate twist which will be discussed shortly. } ) 9... Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 g4 { [%cal Bf3g1,Bg1e2][%csl Re2,Rf4,Bg5,Be5,Bd4][%cal Be2f4]Forcing the knight back. Due to the exchange of queens, White's king now obstructs the path his knight needs to access the f4 square, which has become a positional hole with the ...g4 push. If we had played ...g4 instead of ...Qe7+, the knight could retreat to g1 and with little effort make its way to the key f4 square, but now we've effectively forced White to waste their time creating a route for their knight to escape inactivity. Black already had a space advantage and superior control of the center/kingside, but with this extra tempo we will also be more active. This is why 8...Qe7+ is a subtle, yet remarkable improvement over 8...g4. } 11. Ne1 Ne7 $17 { [%cal Be8f7,Be7f5,Bh7h5,Bc8a6,Bc5c4,Ba6e2][%csl Re2,Rd3,Rc4][%cal Bf5d4,Yd4c2][%csl Rc2][%cal Yf8d6]Black is much better here. We have a space advantage and superior piece activity. Moreover, White's pieces are all restricted by Black's oppressive pawns. It will be difficult for them to find good squares. We can continue with the typical ...Kf7, ...Nf5-d4 to target c2, ...Bd6 to cover the f4 square, ...h5 to stabilize g4, etc. Another notable idea is to try ...Ba6 followed by ...c4!? to undermine the light squares and open up the position. } * 

