the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. O-O g4 { [%csl Rf3,Re5][%cal Bf6e5]We win e5 but should still be careful. White can find compensation if they find the right ideas. } 8. Nh4 { [%cal Bg2g3][%csl Rh4][%cal Yf8g7,Yg7f6,Bf6e5][%csl Re5]The only way to secure compensation is to condemn the knight to the rim. If the knight instead drops back with Strangely enough, the knight accomplishes much more on h4 than it might elsewhere. After } ( 8. Ne1 $146 { or 8... g4 8.Nfd2 Black will just take e5, quickly consolidate the center, and might just send Harry to White's king for a visit. 8...fxe5 9.c4 Qd6 10.Nc3 Nf6 11.Nb3 Bg7 Like many lines earlier in the chapter, we need not worry about defending c5. 12.Na4 h5! 13.Naxc5 h4! Black once again has secured a formidable kingside initiative. } ) ( 8. Nh4 $146 { Black will be unable to play ...h5-h4 with the knight fortuitously blockading the h-file. Of course, Nh4 comes with its own drawbacks. For instance, what will White do if Black manages to threaten the knight, say with ...Bg7-f6 after e5 has been captured? The knight has no squares. g3 will then be forced and the light squares around White's king will become tender. } ) 8... fxe5 { [%cal Bd8d6,Bf8g7,Bg7f6,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Yg8h6,Yh6f7,Yf7g5,Gg8f6,Gf6d7][%csl Re5,Rh3,Rg2,Rf3]Black once again has dominion over the center. The e5 pawn is a weakness, so we should develop in a way which consolidates the pawn. Our queen should almost always come to d6 in these positions. Adding another defender to e5 with ...Nf6-d7 is also typical. One noteworthy idea I alluded to earlier would be to induce g3 with ...Bg7-f6. With the light squares thus weakened, maneuvering the knight around with ...Nh6!-f7-g5 would be advantageous. It really all depends on how White decides to proceed. White needs to realize that the only way to get counterplay here is by breaking out with the f-pawn soon. } 9. f4 { [%csl Re5][%cal Bf4e5]Going right for e5. Instead, Similar themes apply to } ( 9. f3 { would be less pressing. Black can simply cover g4 with } 9... Nf6 $146 { and hold the tension. } 10. Qe1 Qc7 11. Nc3 $146 Bg7 $10 { These positions are roughly equal, but Black looks more comfortable. } ) ( 9. Qe2 { , where Black's development schema remains fixed. } 9... Qd6 10. Nc3 $146 Bg7 { etc. White will not progress until they break out by advancing their f-pawn. } ) 9... Bg7 10. Nc3 Qd6 { [%cal Yg8h6,Yh6f7,Be8g8,Bh8f8]} 11. Qe2 Nh6 { [%cal Bg7e5][%csl Re5]The knight should not obstruct the bishops sight of the center. We're still set on defending e5 but need to get castled soon, so ...Nh6 is the best move here. The knight will naturally be headed to f7 to support e5 even further. } 12. fxe5 { [%csl Rh6][%cal Bg7e5,Bf1f8][%csl Rf8]White intends on trying to keep Black's king in the center. } 12... Bxe5 { [%cal Bd6h2][%csl Rh2]Don't worry about } 13. g3 ( 13. Bxh6 $2 { While it looks like Black might be dropping a piece, after } 13... Bxh2+ 14. Kh1 Qxh6 { Black is winning! A similar sequence plays out if White tries Qe1 on move eleven instead of Qe2: 11... Qd6 11.Qe1 Nh6! 12.fxe5 Bxe5 13.Bxh6?! Bxh2+ 14.Kh1 Bg3! 15.Qe3 Bxh4 Black gets the piece back with interest. } ) 13... Nf7 { [%cal Bf3h4,Bg2g3,Rh6f7,Rf7g5][%csl Rf3,Rh3][%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8]Anytime we see this Nh4 \+ g3 sequence, having our knight exploit the new kingside weaknesses is the appropriate response. Plus, here this enables us to castle. 14.-- Bd4! } 14. Qf2 $4 { White best not dilly dally about with single-move threats! Every tempo matters in these chaotic positions. However, even if White tries something less dubious, such as } ( 14. Bf4 { , Black will be slightly better. } 14... Bxf4 15. Rxf4 Ng5 $146 { White's weaknesses are much more troublesome than Black's. } ) ( 14. Be3 { Bxe3 16.Qxe3 } 14... d4 { , so let's suppose White sidesteps this with 15... d4 15.Na4 Bd7! Black prepares ...Ng5. White has nothing better than to simplify the position to an endgame. 16.Nf5 Qf6 17.Nh6+ Nxh6 18.Qxf6 Rxf6 19.Rxf6 Bxf6 20.Bxh6 Bf5 Even still, Black should win this with moderate ease. } ) 14... O-O $17 { [%cal Bf7g5,Bg5h3,Bg5f3,Bf8f1][%csl Rf2][%cal Bc8d7,Bc8a6]White's kingside weaknesses make this position rather difficult for them. Black threatens to end the game with } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.d3 with 7.O-O #2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.d3 with 7.O-O #2"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. O-O g4 { [%csl Rf3]We win e5 but should still be careful. White can find compensation if they find the right ideas. } 8. Nfd2 $2 fxe5 { [%cal Bd8d6,Yf8g7,Gg8h6,Bh7h5,Bh5h4,Gg8f6]Black once again has dominion over the center. The e5 pawn is a weakness, so we should develop in a way which consolidates the pawn. Our queen and bishop will naturally come to d6 and g7, respectively. The knight could come to h6 or f6. Given that White's knight has withdrawn from the kingside, we also should consider sending Harry to visit White's king. Black is already in the drivers seat. } 9. Nb3 Bg7 { [%cal Bh7h5,Bh5h4,Bd8d6]As is typical, we don't need to worry about c5 here. Our attention should be directed towards the kingside, where White's defenses are scant. } 10. Nxc5 $6 { White could try a number of options instead of Nxc5, but so long as we are familiar with Black's typical ideas we should be equipped to meet them all. For instance, if } ( 10. c4 { standard complications arise after } 10... Qd6 11. Nc3 $146 Nf6 $146 12. Na4 $146 { White's queenside activity is so inconsequential that it can just be ignored! } 12... h5 13. Be3 $2 h4 14. Bxc5 Qc7 15. Re1 h3 { White's king is under extreme pressure. This is the sort of initiative Black usually scrounges up whenever the knight doesn't make it's way to h4 after 7...g4. } ) 10... Qd6 11. b4 { b4 weakens the dark squares, but White should at least try and make use of the c5 outpost. } ( 11. Nb3 $2 $146 { would accomplish nothing. } 11... h5 12. Nc3 $146 Nh6 $146 13. Qe2 h4 { Black's attack usually becomes quite formidable whenever White's pieces are all loitering on the queenside. } ) 11... e4 12. d4 { White locks down the dark squares. } 12... Nh6 { [%cal Bh6f5,Bh7h5,Bh5h4]} 13. c3 Nf5 $17 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8,Be7e5,Bh7h5,Ba7a5,Yf5h4,Yh4f3][%csl Rg1]Black is on the verge of defenestrating White. A number of attractive ideas stand out, for instance ...a5, ...h5, ...e5, ...O-O, etc. The knight on f5 might head to f3 in some positions too. There are all sorts of dynamic opportunities in this position. Taking g4 would be a mistake: } 14. Qxg4 $2 O-O 15. Qg5 Kh8 16. Bf4 e5 { White is in all sorts of danger. } 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe5+ Qxe5 19. Qd2 a5 { The rook will make it's way over to the kingside. White doesn't have a viable defense. } 20. b5 Ra7 21. bxc6 Rg7 22. g3 e3 23. fxe3 Rxg3+ { White is finished. } * 

