the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. Be3 { Targeting c5 and ignoring our immediate threat of ...g4. } 7... g4 8. Nh4 fxe5 { [%cal Bf8g7,Bd8c7,Yg8h6,Yh6f7,Yf7g5,Bg7f6][%csl Rh4][%cal Bg2g3,Ba8b8]Black once again has dominion over the center. The e5 pawn is a weakness, so we should develop in such a way as to consolidate the pawn. With the knight on h4, the thematic ideas here are similar to those of the analogous line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) starting with 7.O-O. As such, we can induce g3 with Bg7-f6! and then proceed to target the weakened light squares with the ...Nh6-f7-g5 maneuver. Also, because White will likely capture c5 our queen should land on c7 instead of d6. } 9. Bxc5 Bg7 10. O-O Bf6 $1 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Bg8h6,Bh6f7,Yg2g3,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bd8c7,Gf8g7,Gg7f6][%csl Gf6]A thematic bishop maneuver. We consolidate our center and hit the offside knight. Now g3 is forced. } 11. g3 Nh6 $15 { [%cal Bh6f7,Bf7g5,Ye8g8,Yh8f8,Yc8e6]Black has a slight edge here. We have superior control over the center and the light squares around White's king are weak. A game might continue with } 12. Qe2 Nf7 $146 13. Nd2 $146 O-O 14. Rae1 { White is preparing f4. } 14... Kh8 { The king steps aside. Black might play ...Rg8-g6 and stack up on the g-file. } 15. f4 $2 gxf3 16. Qxf3 Rg8 17. Nf5 $146 Be6 18. Kh1 Qd7 19. g4 Rg6 { Black has good chances here. The other rook is headed to g8 and we might break out with ...e4!? \+ ...Ne5 or ...h5 at some moment. } * 

