the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. Be3 { Targeting c5 and ignoring our immediate threat of ...g4. } 7... g4 8. Nfd2 Qc7 { [%cal Bc7e5,Be5e1,Be3c5][%csl Re5,Rc5]Playing ...Qc7 after the knight drops back to d2 makes sense. Now if White captures c5 with } 9. exf6 ( 9. Bxc5 { Black can take e5 with check and the b-pawn will fall. } 9... Qxe5+ 10. Qe2 Qxb2 11. Nb3 $146 Qe5 12. Qxe5 fxe5 { Black has effectively won an extra pawn here. Also by adding another attacker to e5 White might succumb to the pressure and release the tension by capturing f6, which would resolve the issue of our positionally dubious e7 pawn. } ) 9... exf6 { [%cal Bf8d6,Bh7h5,Ye8f7,Bh5h4,Yg8e7,Yc8f5]Capturing this way allows us cover c5. Also, ...d4 is now a threat which White cannot ignore. This position structurally resembles some of the positions we've encountered in the 7.exf6 variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Naturally, we can treat the position in a similar fashion by continuing with ...h5-h4, ...Kf7, ...Ne7, etc. The bishops can develop to d6 and f5 too. Black's development plan is fairly straightforward here. } 10. Nb3 { Addressing the d4 threat. } ( 10. c3 $2 { would be too slow. } 10... Kf7 11. Na3 $146 Bf5 { Now the knight will be effectively persuaded to occupy b3 anyways, rendering c3 a misuse of time. } 12. Nb3 $146 h5 13. Nxc5 $146 Re8 14. O-O Bd6 { Black's initiative is nearly decisive. The typical ...h4-h3 will arrive soon. } ) ( 10. Qe2 $2 { temporarily deals with the threat, but after the thematic } 10... Kf7 { White will still need to play } 11. Nb3 $146 { In these lines Qe2 isn't such a great idea. It accomplishes little and just gives Black a clear target. } 11... d4 12. Bd2 Bf5 { White is already in serious trouble. } 13. O-O Re8 14. Qd1 Bd6 { Black is already pressing for a win. This looks miserable to defend. } ) 10... h5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be7f5][%csl Rg4,Re3]White's bishop on e3 is a target. Black would like to harass the bishop by bringing the knight to f5, but to do so immediately would allow g4 to drop. Hence, Black prepares ..Ne7-f5 by advancing Harry to h5. } 11. Nxc5 { White cannot capture c5 with the bishop. } ( 11. Bxc5 $2 Bxc5 12. Nxc5 $146 Qa5+ { White would emerge down a piece. However, one clever idea which prepares Bxc6 is 11... h5 11.Qd2!? We should take note of the change in dynamic here and cover c5. 11...Qb6! 12.a4 a5 I doubt White would go for something like this, as now they can't even take c5 at all, but I thought it worth mentioning anyway. } ) 11... Ne7 { [%cal Be7f5][%csl Rc5,Re3]The knight is headed to f5. Both of White's developed minor pieces are targets here. } 12. O-O $6 { If White doesn't castle now, they will feel the pressure to do so soon. Let's suppose White anticipates ...Nf5 with } ( 12. Nb3 $146 Nf5 $146 13. Qd2 Nh4 $2 $146 { With g2 under attack White has no choice but to play Kf1 or O-O. Of course, Kf1 would condemn the rook to life in the corner, so } 14. O-O { looks to be the more sensible continuation. Still, after } 14... Bd6 { White is under pressure. It doesn't look like White will be able to save h2. } 15. Kh1 Kf7 16. c4 dxc4 17. dxc4 Bxh2 18. Nc3 $146 Bf5 19. Rad1 Rad8 { Black is better, but converting this will still be a challenge. } ) 12... Nf5 $19 { [%cal Bf5e3][%csl Re3][%cal Be8f7,Bf8d6,Bc7h2][%csl Rh2][%cal Rh5h4,Yc7h7,Yh8h2]Black's advantage is decisive here. White needs to worry about ...Nxe3 followed by ...Bxc5. They will also need to worry about the incoming ...Bd6 followed by ...h4!. White's position is truly on the brink of collapse. A game might continue with } 13. Nb3 $146 { White preserves their material. } 13... Bd6 14. g3 h4 { Now it all falls apart. } 15. Bf4 $2 Bxf4 16. gxf4 a5 { Black is intent on removing the knight on b3 so that ...Nd4! becomes possible! } 17. a4 Rb8 18. Nc3 $146 Kf7 19. Re1 Rxb3 20. cxb3 Nd4 $146 { White is getting crushed here. Black can convert by planting the knight on f3 and then evacuating the queenside light squares with ...d4 and ...c5 to make room for the bishop and queen to smash through. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.d3 with 7.Be3 #3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.d3 with 7.Be3 #3"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. Be3 { Targeting c5 and ignoring our immediate threat of ...g4. } 7... g4 8. Nfd2 Qc7 { Playing ...Qc7 after the knight drops back to d2 makes sense. Now if White captures c5 with } 9. O-O { [%cal Bc7e5]White prepares Bxc5 by getting the king off of the e-file. } ( 9. Bxc5 { Black can take e5 with check and the b-pawn will fall. } 9... Qxe5+ 10. Qe2 Qxb2 11. Nb3 $146 Qe5 12. Qxe5 fxe5 { Black has effectively won an extra pawn here. Also by adding another attacker to e5 White might succumb to the pressure and release the tension by capturing f6, which would resolve the issue of our positionally dubious e7 pawn. } ) 9... fxe5 { ...Qxe5 after White has castled could be played too, but the queen can become somewhat of a target on e5. Taking back with the f-pawn at this juncture is simplest. } 10. Bxc5 h5 $13 { [%cal Gf8g7,Gg7f6,Bg8h6,Bh6f5,Yc8f5,Ba8d8,Ba8b8,Rh5h4][%csl Rb2][%cal Yg8f6]We arrive at another unclear position. Naturally, all of our standard development themes are applicable here due to the structural similarities to the lines we've already examined. The bishop being on c5 rather than c1 changes the dynamic of the position some, for instance b2 is a weakness here and White isn't in control of the c1-h6 diagonal anymore, but it's probably a fair tradeoff all things considered. With the pawn exchanged, White has become more active and Black's control over d4 and b4 has been attenuated. Both sides have chances here. } * 

