1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { [%csl Re5,Rf3]«'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. Qe2 { [%cal Be2e8,Be5f6][%csl Re7,Re8]White holds the tension and defends e5. 7.Qe2 is one of two critical moves which must be addressed. White's current threat is 7...-- 8.exf6 Nxf6 followed by a capture on g5, where White would be winning. } 7... g4 { [%cal Bf6e5][%csl Rf3][%cal Bg8f6,Bd8d6][%csl Re5]} 8. Nh4 { Retreating the knight anywhere else is too passive and will allow Black to exchange on e5 and complete development without issue. The upside of this move for us is that often it's extremely difficult for White to get this piece back into the game. } 8... fxe5 9. Qxe5 Nf6 10. Bf4 $1 { [%cal Bd8d6][%csl Re5,Rd6]This is White's strongest reply. In fact, anything else enables Black to yank the evaluation back to equilibrium. The explanation as to why certainly is not very clear at a glance, so let's take a moment here to understand the nature of the position following the e5 exchange. After Qxe5, White's queen is safely stationed in the most active place she could possibly be. Her presence in Black's territory is more than irritating. Consequently, Black would benefit from evicting White's queen from her central post. ...Qe6 would accomplish precisely this. White's queen would then either exchange or withdraw, both possibilities which benefit Black. A visual guide might be conducive to illustrate the theme I'm suggesting here. Suppose White simply castles before Bf4: } ( 10. O-O Qd6 11. Bf4 Qxe5 12. Bxe5 Bh6 { Black has a lot to play for here. Some ideas might be: ...O-O, ...Nd7, and maybe an eventual ...e5 or ...c4. The position is very strange, but not particularly bad. Instead, if the queen withdraws with 11... Qd6 11.Qe2 Black is able to play in spirit of the lines we've previously examined. 11...Bg7 12.Nc3 O-O 13.Bg5 e5!? 14.Rae1 Nh5 Black gets decent play in these lines. Now, in light of the fact that ...Qd6 is Black's idea, the reason why 10... Nf6 10.Bf4! presses for an advantage is because after 10...Qd6 White has 11.Qe3! , hitting our queen with tempo. Black must once again must go for the queen trade, lest we risk being overwhelmed by White's lead in development. However, after 11...Qe6 12.Qxe6 Bxe6 12.O-O Bg7 Black's position is extremely awkward. Such awkwardness is only made possible by 10.Bf4!. } ) 10... Qd6 { Black attempts to remove White's queen from the center. } 11. Qxd6 $2 { [%csl Re7]Simplifying the position this way is a sizable strategic error. } 11... exd6 { [%csl Gc6,Gd6,Gd5,Gc5]Black has established an impenetrable pawn cube! } 12. Nc3 Be7 $15 { [%cal Bc8e6,Bf6h5][%csl Rf4,Rh4][%cal Yd5d4,Be8d8]Black's space advantage makes piece coordination easier for us. We can proceed with ...Nh5 and ...Be6. Meanwhile, it's not entirely clear how White is supposed to proceed. Their offside knight has no squares and their bishop is a target. } * 

