me. } 8... fxe5 9. Qxe5 Nf6 10. Bf4 $1 { This is White's strongest reply. In fact, anything else enables Black to yank the evaluation back to equilibrium. The explanation as to why certainly is not very clear at a glance, so let's take a moment here to understand the nature of the position following the e5 exchange. After Qxe5, White's queen is safely stationed in the most active place she could possibly be. Her presence in Black's territory is more than irritating. Consequently, Black would benefit from evicting White's queen from her central post. ...Qe6 would accomplish precisely this. White's queen would then either exchange or withdraw, both possibilities which benefit Black. A visual guide might be conducive to illustrate the theme I'm suggesting here. Suppose White simply castles before Bf4: } ( 10. O-O Qd6 11. Bf4 Qxe5 12. Bxe5 Bh6 { Black has a lot to play for here. Some ideas might be: ...O-O, ...Nd7, and maybe an eventual ...e5 or ...c4. The position is very strange, but not particularly bad. Instead, if the queen withdraws with 11... Qd6 11.Qe2 Black is able to play in spirit of the lines we've previously examined. 11...Bg7 12.Nc3 O-O 13.Bg5 e5!? 14.Rae1 Nh5 Black gets decent play in these lines. Now, in light of the fact that ...Qd6 is Black's idea, the reason why 10... Nf6 10.Bf4! presses for an advantage is because after 10...Qd6 White has 11.Qe3! , hitting our queen with tempo. Black must once again must go for the queen trade, lest we risk being overwhelmed by White's lead in development. However, after 11...Qe6 12.Qxe6 Bxe6 12.O-O Bg7 Black's position is extremely awkward. Such awkwardness is only made possible by 10.Bf4!. } ) 10... Qd6 { Black attempts to remove White's queen from the center. } 11. Qe3 Qe6 { We insist on simplifying the position. } 12. Qxe6 { White needs to take our queen to press for an initiative. Otherwise Black will just capture on e3 himself and should be able to mobilize quick enough. For instance after } ( 12. O-O $2 Qxe3 13. fxe3 c4 $2 14. dxc4 Ne4 $146 { Black is perfectly fine and might even be slightly better. } ) 12... Bxe6 13. O-O Bg7 { The typical square for the bishop. } 14. Re1 { White targets the awkward bishop on e6. Oddly enough, Black shouldn't move the bishop. d7 is where our knight is eventually headed and c8 would block the rooks. Moreover, retreating to the kingside just blunders Nf5. Black needs to bring the king up to defend. } ( 14. Nc3 $2 $146 { Black also should able to hold with accurate play. } 14... Nh5 $146 15. Bg5 Rg8 { These positions are probably easier to play from the white side. Such is the condition of the game after 6...g5!?. Black will be a little bit worse in the 7.Qe2 line if White finds the correct continuation. } ) 14... Kf7 15. Nc3 ( 15. Nd2 $146 { is worth examination too. In these positions Black has ideas to sacrifice a pawn with ...c4 to make room for the knight to access c5. Once the knight leaves f6 ...Bf6 becomes viable as well. For instance, } 15... a5 16. a4 Nd7 $146 17. Re2 c4 18. dxc4 Bf6 19. Bg3 Nc5 $146 20. Rae1 h5 { The knight on c5 protects the awkward bishop on e6. Black is a little bit worse here too, but should be able to hold with accurate play. } ) 15... d4 $1 { Capitalizing on the opportunity to create some space for our pieces. } 16. Na4 Nd7 $14 { [%cal Rg7f6,Bh7h5,Be6d5,Ba8g8][%csl Rh4]No doubt White is a little better here, but Black finally is able to get some play and looks to be defending successfully for now. With the center/queenside being semi-closed, our best chances involve coordinating our forces to optimal kingside squares to prepare for the opening up of the position. White will probably need to break out at some point with f3 or h3. } * 

