1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 f6 6. e5 g5 7. Qe2 { Time to look a little further into these lines. There are complications unexplored in the trainables which may fare well for Black. They may not; You can decide. At minimum, we might benefit from being made aware of their existence. } 7... g4 8. Nh4 $1 { The critical move. } 8... fxe5 9. Qxe5 Nf6 10. Bf4 { In this position we reccomend ...Qd6, however ...Bg7 is also a move. } 10... Bg7 $5 { This is certainly worth examination. The resulting positions are quite interesting. I may consider adding some alternative lines in the future. } 11. Qg5 $1 ( 11. O-O { Less ambitious, but perfectly natural. } 11... O-O { Black now threatens the would-be decisive ...Ne5! White should withdraw the queen. } 12. Qe3 d4 $2 { Perhaps a little positionally suspect, but Black will soon follow up with ...c4 to remedy the structural troubles. } 13. Qe2 e5 { A nice shot. } 14. Bxe5 $2 Re8 15. f4 gxf3 16. Nxf3 $146 Ng4 $19 $146 { White has permission to resign. } ) ( 11. Nd2 $146 O-O 12. Nf5 $146 Bxf5 13. Qxf5 Qd7 { This makes sense. } 14. Qxd7 Nxd7 $15 $146 { Black is playing for ...e5, as is typical. } ) 11... O-O { Black threatens the would-be decisive ...Ne4! } 12. Be5 $1 { The only critical move. } ( 12. Bg3 $2 Qb6 13. O-O Qxb2 14. Nd2 $146 Qxc2 $17 ) ( 12. O-O $2 Ne4 $3 $146 13. dxe4 h6 14. Qg6 Rf6 { Forcing the queen to the side. } 15. Qh5 Rxf4 16. Nd2 $146 Bd7 $17 { With threats of ...Be8. } ) 12... h6 13. Qe3 ( 13. Qg6 $2 { White needs to withdraw. The queen is not safe. } 13... e6 14. O-O Bd7 15. Nd2 $146 Be8 { The key idea. } 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Qxg4 Rb8 18. b3 Rb4 $15 { Black has excellent activity. } ) 13... Qb6 14. O-O ( 14. Nd2 $2 $146 d4 { Ugly, but Black has no better. } 15. Qe2 Qxb2 16. O-O Qxc2 17. Rfc1 Qb2 18. Rcb1 Qc2 { With a repetition. White could play on, but they have a draw if they want it. } 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Rc1 Qb2 21. Ng6 $146 Rf7 22. Nf4 $146 Qb8 23. Nh5 $146 Qe5 24. Nxf6+ $146 exf6 25. Ne4 $13 $146 { With an unclear game. } ) 14... c4 $1 15. Qe2 ( 15. Qxb6 $2 axb6 16. dxc4 dxc4 17. Nc3 $146 Nd5 $10 $146 { With an equal, though deeply imbalanced game. } ) 15... Nh5 $5 { An interesting idea. Attempting to eliminate White's strong bishop. } 16. Bxg7 cxd3 17. cxd3 $1 ( 17. Qxd3 $2 Ba6 18. Qd4 Nxg7 $146 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. Re1 Nf5 $146 21. Nxf5 $146 Rxf5 22. Rxe7 $2 Raf8 $17 { White is under some serious pressure. } ) 17... Nxg7 18. Ng6 ( 18. Nc3 $146 Bf5 19. Rac1 Rae8 20. Nxf5 $146 Rxf5 21. Qxg4 Qxb2 $13 { With an unclear game. } ) 18... Rf6 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Nxc8 Rxc8 21. Nc3 Rcf8 22. Qd2 $14 { White, being up a pawn and having a safer king, is better. Black has partial compensation due to having active and coordinated pieces, but White still is for choice. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.d3 with 7.Qe2 #3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.d3 with 7.Qe2 #3"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 $16 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { 5.d3 undoubtedly stands as the most testing challenge. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's positional deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! This sequence has made an appearance countless times in the mainline. We should know by now that, as a general rule for this specific opening, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { [%csl Re5,Rf3]«'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. Qe2 { [%cal Be2e8,Be5f6][%csl Re7,Re8]White holds the tension and defends e5. 7.Qe2 is one of two critical moves which must be addressed. White's current threat is 7...-- 8.exf6 Nxf6 followed by a capture on g5, where White would be winning. } 7... g4 { [%cal Bf6e5][%csl Rf3][%cal Bg8f6]} 8. Nfd2 $2 Bg7 $5 { The usual capture on e5 is fine too, but ...Bg7!? looks absolutely diabolical. White once again is invited to capture f6, a mistake which many will likely be tempted by. After } 9. e6 { [%cal Be2g4][%csl Rd7,Rf7,Rg4]This is one way to deal with the threat of ...fxe5. White locks down Black's center and dreams of taking g4. If White ignores our threat on e5 and instead pursues the c5 pawn with } ( 9. exf6 $2 Nxf6 $146 10. Nb3 $146 O-O { Black is in the drivers seat. We can continue with ...Qd6, ...e5, and ...Nh5-f4 with a strong initiative on the kingside. But then if taking f6 is not accurate, what should White do given that e5 is hanging? This is precisely why I opted for ...Bg7!? here. It's not particularly easy for White to find the right idea. } ) ( 9. Nb3 $146 fxe5 { , we will find ourselves in a position similar to the 7.O-O #1 variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) only with Qe2 on the board instead of O-O. There's plenty of thematic overlap between these lines, however in this specific position it seems that White's pressure on e5 makes it tricky to situate the remainder of our kingside pieces without dropping the pawn. Hence, Stockfish's response is to just sacrifice it: } 10. Nc3 $146 Nh6 $2 $146 11. Bxh6 Bxh6 12. Qxe5 O-O { Notice how our bishop conveniently stops White from queenside castling here. Next Black can simply chase White's queen away from the center and play for the eventual ...e5 push. } 13. O-O Bg7 14. Qe2 Qd6 15. Rae1 e5 { Black has the advantage once again. } ) 9... f5 $1 { [%cal Bh7h5,Bd8d6][%csl Re6]Covering g4. Black will next consolidate the kingside structure and target e6. } 10. h3 { Another line worthy of discussion is } ( 10. O-O $2 { Stockfish doesn't seem to fear Black's aggressive kingside activities. } 10... Qd6 11. Nb3 $146 a5 12. a4 c4 { Black finally is able to open up the position. ...a5 was an important inclusion, as after } 13. dxc4 dxc4 { threats of ...Ba6 loom in the air. White would be wise to avoid falling victim to this move. } 14. N3d2 $146 c3 $2 15. bxc3 Qxe6 16. Qxe6 Bxe6 17. Re1 Kf7 { Black is a bit better here. This bishops are extremely strong and White's forces are uncoordinated. } ) 10... h5 { [%cal Bh8h6,Bh6e6][%csl Re6]A multipurpose move. White needs to be careful. Any move other than hxg4 or Nb3 would be a blunder due to 11.-- Rh6! } 11. hxg4 fxg4 12. Nb3 $1 Qd6 $15 { [%cal Bd6e6]Black is a little bit better here. We can trade off the c5 pawn for the e6 pawn and eventually play for ...e5. I would guess that a game would continue from here with } 13. Nc3 $146 Qxe6 14. Qxe6 Bxe6 15. Nxc5 $146 Bf5 16. Bg5 Kf7 17. O-O-O e5 { Black has a great position here. The plan is to walk the king up the g6 and force White to make concessions. For instance, } 18. Ne2 $146 Kg6 19. Bd2 $2 h4 { Black is doing a great job of restricting White's pieces and has all the chances. } * 

