or control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. Qe2 { [%cal Be2e8,Be5f6][%csl Re7,Re8]White holds the tension and defends e5. 7.Qe2 is one of two critical moves which must be addressed. White's current threat is 7...-- 8.exf6 Nxf6 followed by a capture on g5, where White would be winning. Naturally, Black shall proceed with our standard plan: ...g4 followed by ...fxe5. } 7... g4 { [%cal Bf6e5][%csl Rf3][%cal Bg8f6]} 8. Nfd2 $2 Bg7 { The usual capture on e5 is fine too, but ...Bg7!? looks absolutely diabolical. White once again is invited to capture f6, a mistake which many will likely be tempted by. After } 9. h3 $1 { Counterattacking! White's best chance is to just forget about e5 altogether. If White ignores our threat on e5 by instead pursuing the c5 pawn with } ( 9. exf6 $2 Nxf6 $146 10. Nb3 $146 O-O { Black is in the drivers seat. We can continue with ...Qd6, ...e5, and ...Nh5-f4 with a strong initiative on the kingside. But then if taking f6 is not accurate, what should White do given that e5 is hanging? This is precisely why I opted for ...Bg7!? here. It's not particularly easy for White to find the right idea. } ) ( 9. Nb3 $146 fxe5 { , we will find ourselves in a position similar to the 7.O-O #1 variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) only with Qe2 on the board instead of O-O. There's plenty of thematic overlap between these lines, however in this specific position it seems that White's pressure on e5 makes it tricky to situate the remainder of our kingside pieces without dropping the pawn. Hence, Stockfish's response is to just sacrifice it: } 10. Nc3 $146 Nh6 $2 $146 11. Bxh6 Bxh6 12. Qxe5 O-O { Notice how our bishop conveniently stops White from queenside castling here. Next Black can simply chase White's queen away from the center and play for the eventual ...e5 push. } 13. O-O Bg7 14. Qe2 Qd6 15. Rae1 e5 { Black has the advantage once again. } ) 9... gxh3 { [%cal Bg2h3,Yh1g1,Bg1g7][%csl Rg7]There are a number of moves here which work, but ...gxh3 seems to offer the best balance between ambition and simplicity. If we instead try The other notable alternative is } ( 9... h5 $2 { White will be able to develop some formidable counterplay on the kingside. } 10. hxg4 Bxg4 11. f3 Bf5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Qg2 $2 h4 14. f4 { White just surges forth on the kingside with little regard for anything else. This doesn't look easy for us to navigate at all. } 14... fxe5 15. f5 Bf7 16. g5 { Danger abounds here. Black has to find } 16... Nf6 $146 { to preserve an advantage. Apparently we will have more than enough compensation for the piece. This line isn't forcing though. White can deviate at a number of key points. After ...gxh3 White has less options to choose from and Black's position is arguably just as good. } ) ( 9... Qd7 $2 { The resulting positions resemble those of the former line, just without the queens. } 10. hxg4 Qxg4 11. Qxg4 Bxg4 12. f3 Bf5 13. g4 { etc. } ) 10. gxh3 Nh6 $5 { [%cal Bh6f5][%csl Rd4][%cal Bf5g7,Bf5d4]With the g-file open, I would recommend that we consider prioritizing development. The knight will head to f5, where it covers important ground and cannot be easily repelled. Naturally, ...fxe5 is fine too, but by holding the tension we invite White once more to capture f6, a capture which typically benefits Black. Our bishop becomes extremely strong when the center opens up. Here's an example of the sort of thing one can expect from that: } 11. Rg1 { The immediate One notable alternative to Rg1 is } ( 11. exf6 Bxf6 { White's best option here is to just go for simplification. } 12. Nb3 $146 Nf5 $146 13. Qh5+ Kf8 14. Bh6+ Nxh6 $146 15. Qxh6+ Ke8 { Our king can go for a walk over to the central queenside. He'll be both safe and active there. } 16. Qh5+ Kd7 { As is typical, we don't really need to worry about saving our weak c-pawn. } 17. Nxc5+ $2 $146 Kd6 18. Na4 $146 Rb8 19. Nbc3 $146 Qg8 { Black has the advantage. } ) ( 11. Qh5+ $2 { would not be accurate. Once again, it is no trivial matter to accurately navigate these positions. } 11... Nf7 $146 12. Rg1 Kf8 13. Nf3 $146 Qd7 { Targeting h3. } 14. Rg3 Qf5 { White has nothing better than to trade the queens here. } 15. Qh4 $2 { allows } 15... Rb8 { followed by ...Rb4! However, even after 15... Qf5 15.Qxf5 Bxf5 Black's lead in development clearly establishes that the advantage is his. } ) ( 11. Nf3 $2 $146 { White redirects the focus back onto e5. Quite an ingenious idea, actually. Now Black is unable to take e5 for free. } 11... Nf5 $146 12. Bf4 Qa5+ $2 { The queen might land on b4 in some positions. For instance, } 13. Nbd2 $146 O-O 14. Rg1 Qb4 { This is already somewhat uncomfortable for White. Black hits b2 and the f4 bishop. } ) 11... Nf5 12. Qh5+ { Given the chance Black will castle, so White forces the king to f8 before Black can do so. 12...Qe8 14.Qxe8+ Kxe8 15.Bf4 Stockfish evaluates Black as slightly better after 15...fxe5!? 16.Bxe5 Bxe5 17.Nxe5 Nd4 18.Kd1 Bxh3 , but White has a serious grip on e5. It's an unclear position. } 12... Kf8 $13 { [%cal Bd8e8,Bh5e8][%csl Re8][%cal Bf5d4,Be5f6][%csl Bf6][%cal Bf6e5,Bc8h3][%csl Rh3]This position is extremely strange, but Black should be fine. Black will play ...Qe8 to induce the queen trade and can then try to target c2 and h3 with ...Nd4 if White allows it. White's strongest play is to just clamp down on e5. } 13. Nf3 $146 { This also happens to stop ...Nd4, unfortunately. } * 

