the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 $1 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4][%csl Re5,Rh3,Rf3]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Be3 { White targets c5 and tries to bait Black into the positionally dubious ...d4!?. I want to reiterate once more that a premature capture on f6 hands Black an advantage. } ( 8. exf6 $2 exf6 { Holding the tension on e5 is White's only way to play for an advantage in these positions. } ) 8... Qc7 { [%csl Rc5,Re5][%cal Be3c5,Bc7e5]The focus has always been on e5 in these lines. Let's preserve the continuity. } 9. Bxc5 g4 $1 10. hxg4 { Anything else drops e5. } 10... Bxg4 { [%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3][%cal Bc7e5][%csl Re5]Continuing to fight for e5. It's worth noting here that taking on f6 would be fine for White at this stage of the opening. It's not particularly good, but White wont be immediately worse. } 11. Nbd2 ( 11. exf6 exf6 12. Bxf8 Kxf8 13. Nc3 $146 Re8+ { We should almost always be glad to see exf6. Black is at least equal in these lines. The fact that White is up a pawn doesn't really matter. We have a strong pin on f3 and excellent piece activity. } ) 11... fxe5 12. Qe2 Bg7 13. O-O-O Nf6 $13 { [%cal Bf6d7,Yg7f6,Bh8g8,Be8c8,Ba8d8,Ya8b8,Yc7b6]We've seen this sort of position before in the 7.Be3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) variations, but without the inclusion of h3 and the subsequent exchange on g4. Black's space advantage and control of the center makes this position slightly more comfortable for us. Our plan is to continue with ...Nd7 to evict the bishop from c5 and to then plant our bishop on f6. From there we can either choose to play on the kingside with ...O-O-O and ...Rdg8, or pressure White's queenside with ...Rb8 and ...Qb6. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.d3 with 7.h3 / 8.Be3 #2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.d3 with 7.h3 / 8.Be3 #2"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4][%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3][%cal Bf8h6,Bg8h6]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. We've observed in other lines that when White plays h3 while a piece is on f3, ...h5 \+ ...g5-g4 become quite a strong idea. Click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to see an example of this. However, because White has not yet castled Black's relative attacking potential is greatly diminished. } 8. Be3 { White targets c5 and tries to bait Black into the positionally dubious ...d4!?. I want to reiterate once more that a premature capture on f6 hands Black an advantage. } ( 8. exf6 $2 exf6 { Holding the tension on e5 is White's only way to play for an advantage in these positions. } ) 8... Qc7 { [%csl Rc5,Re5]The focus has always been on e5 in these lines. Let's preserve the continuity. } 9. Bxc5 g4 10. hxg4 { Anything else drops e5. } 10... Bxg4 { Continuing to fight for e5. It's worth noting here that taking on f6 would be fine for White at this stage of the opening. It's not particularly good, but White wont be immediately worse. } 11. e6 ( 11. exf6 exf6 12. Bxf8 Kxf8 13. Nc3 $146 Re8+ { We should almost always be glad to see exf6. Black is at least equal in these lines. The fact that White is up a pawn doesn't really matter. We have a strong pin on f3 and excellent piece activity. } ) 11... Bxe6 12. Nh4 $1 { e6 releases the tension and forces Black to break the pin. Nh4 prevents Black from re-instituting the annoying pin. If White instead follows up with } ( 12. Nc3 $146 { Black will just install the bishop back on g4 } 12... Bg4 { and can play for ...e5, as is typical. } ) 12... Qe5+ 13. Kf1 { Or, if } ( 13. Qe2 { Black can just trade queens and develop the kingside. } 13... Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Kf7 15. Nd2 $146 Nh6 $146 { Our knight will come to f5 and our bishop to h6. This is roughly equal. } ) 13... Qxb2 { 14.Nb3 Bg4! } 14. Nd2 ( 14. f3 Bd7 { After the bishop drops back to d7 Black can play for ...e5. The pawn on f3 leaves the knight on the rim totally bereft of escape squares. } 15. Qd2 e5 16. Bxf8 { Rxf8 This game could easily go either way. } ) 14... Kf7 $10 { [%cal Be6g4,Rf2f3,Bg4d7,Be7e5,Bg8h6][%csl Rh4][%cal Bb2c3]Preventing Ng6. Black is doing fine here. One notable idea is to have our bishop return to g4 to induce f3. For instance: } * 

