the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4][%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3][%cal Bf8h6,Bg8h6]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Be3 { White targets c5 and tries to bait Black into the positionally dubious ...d4!?. I want to reiterate once more that a premature capture on f6 hands Black an advantage. } ( 8. exf6 $2 exf6 { Holding the tension on e5 is White's only way to play for an advantage in these positions. } ) 8... Qc7 { [%csl Rc5,Re5]The focus has always been on e5 in these lines. Let's preserve the continuity. } 9. Bxc5 g4 10. hxg4 { Anything else drops e5. } 10... Bxg4 { Continuing to fight for e5. } 11. exf6 exf6 { [%cal Ba8e8,Bf8c5][%csl Rc5][%cal Bc5f8][%csl Rf8]If White releases the tension by finally capturing f6, opening up the e-file is the way to go. Black can quickly mobilize the rook to e8 and will have excellent play in the center and kingside. } 12. Bxf8 { Or if } ( 12. d4 { Black should insist on the exchange and establish control over the open e-file. } 12... Bxc5 13. dxc5 Kf7 14. Nc3 $146 Re8+ { These positions can be treated similarly to the standard exf6 variations. } ) 12... Kxf8 13. Nc3 Re8+ 14. Kf1 { Breaking the pin at any point allows us to weaken White's kingside. } ( 14. Ne2 $146 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qe5 ) 14... Ne7 $13 { [%cal Be7g6,Yh5h4,Bf8f7,Bg6f4,Yh4h3,Yh3h2,Yg4f3][%csl Rf3][%cal Yg2f3]Black has a slight edge here. We can proceed with ...Kf7 and ...Ng6-f4. White will need to eventually break the pin by stepping the queen out of the way or blocking with the knight, after which we can force the doubling of White's pawns by exchanging on f3. After the g-pawn has been removed, Black should start marching Harry down the board. A game might continue with } 15. Qd2 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Kf7 17. Ne2 $146 Ng6 $146 18. Re1 h4 { Harry's march begins. } 19. Qb4 h3 20. Qg4 h2 21. Qg3 Qe5 22. d4 Qh5 $10 { White's pieces look paralyzed. Still, it's not clear how Black can progress. Our best shot is probably to use Harry as bait and go after White's queenside pawns at the right moment, but with accurate play this should be a draw. } * 

