the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Nc3 Bg7 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bg7e5]Black prepares ...g4 followed by ...fxe5. Starting with } ( 8... g4 $2 { transposes to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) after } 9. Nh4 $146 Kf7 10. Qe2 { We should avoid playing into this if possible. Black has to put up a serious fight to get a playable position in those lines. } ) 9. exf6 { White anticipates our threats by releasing the tension. } 9... exf6 { Recapturing with the pawn might look a little strange due to the bishop being on g7, but we need to protect g5. } 10. Qe2+ { [%cal Bc1d2,Be1c1,Ba1d1]White foreshadows O-O-O. This plan seems safer than the alternatives, which would require White to castle in the opposite direction. Given Black's extended kingside, however, I can't imagine anyone seriously considering castling kingside here. One example of such an alternative would be: } ( 10. d4 $2 c4 11. b3 cxb3 12. axb3 Ne7 $146 { The queenside is clearly not safe here. Castling is one of the top moves, but after } 13. O-O Ng6 $146 14. Qd3 Kf7 { ...g4 is incoming and the h-file is likely to open up. White should still be okay, but it certainly looks riskier. } ) 10... Kf7 11. Bd2 Ne7 12. O-O-O Ng6 $15 { [%cal Yg7f8,Yf8d6,Ra8b8,Rb8b7,Rb7e7,Re7e1,Bh8e8,Gc8e6,Gd5d4,Ge6a2][%csl Ra2]The upcoming early middlegame will be a positional battle, at least for a little while, and we have plenty of time to properly situate our pieces. Black's pawns do excellent work restricting the mobility of White's pieces. Our dark squared bishop is not doing much on g7, so we might benefit from maneuvering it to d6 with ...Bf8-d6. Black's other ideas involve ...Re8 to contest for the e-file, ...Rb8 to put some pressure on White's queenside, and maybe even ...Be6 and ...d4!? to try to open lines towards White's king. We have an interesting game ahead of us. } * 

