1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Nc3 Bg7 { Black prepares ...g4 followed by ...fxe5. Starting with } ( 8... g4 $2 { transposes to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) after } 9. Nh4 $146 Kf7 10. Qe2 { We should avoid playing into this if possible. Black has to put up a serious fight to get a playable position in those lines. } ) 9. Qe2 $1 g4 10. exf6 { White anticipates the threats on e5 by releasing the tension. We cannot recapture with the e-pawn due to White's pin, so we shall do so with our knight instead. } 10... Nxf6 11. Ne5 { Taking on g4 would allow Black to institute an annoying pin which would cause White more trouble than it's worth. The other two viable knight moves, } ( 11. hxg4 $2 Bxg4 { Now Black can play for ...e5! } 12. Bf4 Nd7 $146 13. O-O-O e5 { Typical insanity. We need not worry about pressures building up on the e-file, as after } 14. Rde1 { Black can simply castle } 14... O-O { and has a great position. } ) ( 11. Nh4 $146 { and 11... Nxf6 11.Ng5 , can both be met with 11...Rb8! This move might look a little bit arbitrary, but the idea is just to patiently get active while White decides what to do with their knight. It also pressures White's remaining bishop to stay where it is. This line is likely to continue with 12.Ne6 Bxe6 13.Qxe6 Qd7! and White's initiative is gone. By contrast, after 11... Nxf6 11.Nh4 Rb8! 12.Ng6 Rg8 the position is a little more complicated. Black is holding on just fine. If anything, White might have issues with the knight being so deep in Black's territory. For instance, if the game proceeds with 13.hxg4 Nxg4! 15.Rxh5 Qd6! 16.Nf4 Be5 17.g3?! Qf6! Black ends up with an initiative. } ) 11... Qd6 { [%cal Bf6d7][%csl Rc6]Defending the c6 pawn. If White's knight doesn't jump to g6 we might challenge it at the right moment with ...Nd7. We don't want to drop this pawn. } 12. Ng6 { White should invade the kingside immediately to misplace Black's rook. Notice that if } ( 12. Bf4 $2 { Black has } 12... Nd7 $146 13. Nxd7 $146 Qxf4 14. Nxc5 $146 gxh3 15. gxh3 O-O { and Black is much better. } ) 12... Rg8 13. Bf4 { White's only move to keep the pace. } 13... Qe6 { Simplification is best here. } 14. Qxe6 Bxe6 15. hxg4 Nxg4 $10 { [%cal Ge6f7,Bg7f6,Bg7d4,Ye6d7,Gc5c4,Rg8g6][%csl Rg6][%cal Gf7h5][%csl Rh5]Even though White has pressure on our weak h-pawn this should be roughly equal because of our potential in the center and strong bishop pair. White currently needs to deal with the threat of ...Bxc3+ followed by ...Rxg6, so they must withdraw the knight. Black should then move the e6 bishop out of the way of the pawn, reposition the dark squared bishop to f6 or d4, and might eventually play for ...c4 to open up the center. } * 

