 e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Nc3 Bg7 { Black prepares ...g4 followed by ...fxe5. Starting with } ( 8... g4 $2 { transposes to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) after } 9. Nh4 $146 Kf7 10. Qe2 { We should avoid playing into this if possible. Black has to put up a serious fight to get a playable position in those lines. } ) 9. Qe2 g4 10. Nh4 { [%cal Bh4g6]White holds the tension on both the central and kingside fronts and prepares to have the knight jump deep into Black's territory. Taking on g4 would allow Black to institute an annoying pin which would cause White more trouble than it's worth. I should also mention } ( 10. hxg4 $2 Bxg4 { The pressure on e5 is palpable. If White releases the tension with } 11. exf6 Nxf6 $146 { Black can play for ...e5! } 12. Bf4 Nd7 $146 13. O-O-O e5 { Typical insanity. We need not worry about White potentially breaking through on the e-file, as after } 14. Rde1 { Black can simply castle } 14... O-O { and has a great position. Of course, White need not take on f6. If they instead try 11... Bxg4 11.Bf4!? Black has the incredible 11...Qb8! , attacking b2 and e5! This looks like pure madness, but Black will take the lead if we find the right moves. 12.exf6!? Qxb2! 13.O-O Bxf6 14.Be5 Bxf3! 15.gxf3 Qb4 This is at least slightly better for Black. } ) ( 10. Nd2 $146 { here in passing. We've seen this sort of position a number of times already. There are a number of viable responses, but the classic } 10... fxe5 { lands us in familiar terrain. One idea that stands out to me is that after } 11. Nb3 $146 { Black can immediately strike in the center with } 11... c4 12. dxc4 Ba6 13. hxg4 Bxc4 14. Qd1 d4 $2 { Black aims to steamroll White in the center, paying no regard to White's kingside activities! } 15. Ne4 $146 Nf6 $146 16. Nxf6+ $146 exf6 $2 17. Rxh5 Kf7 { This is a fun example of the sort of chaos we might encounter in these lines. } ) 10... fxe5 { 10.Nh4 is the critical line of the 8.Nc3 variations. The upcoming sequence is pretty much all forced. } 11. Ng6 { [%cal Bd8d6][%csl Rg6]White should jump in immediately before Black can prevent it with ...Qd6. } 11... Rh7 12. Nxe5 Qd6 { [%csl Re5,Rd7,Rc6,Rc4,Rf3]The knight is actually trapped here. } 13. Bf4 $7 Nh6 $1 { [%cal Yh6f7,Yf7e5,Bg7e5]Our knight is headed to f7, where we can continue to build pressure on White's trapped central steed. } 14. O-O-O { In the event that White tries either } ( 14. g3 { or 14. g3 14.Bh2 Black should respond with 14...Nf5! , the idea being to counterattack White's queen after 15.Nxg4 Nd4! 16.Qd2 Qg6 Black has sufficient counterplay in these lines. } ) 14... Nf7 $1 15. Rde1 Bxe5 { Simplification. Black should be fine once the endgame arrives. } 16. Bxe5 Qxe5 17. Qxe5 Nxe5 18. Rxe5 gxh3 $1 { [%cal Be8d7,Bd7d6]Black will walk the king up to d6, but should ensure that the kingside tension has been resolved first. } 19. gxh3 Kd7 $10 { [%cal Bd7d6,Yc8d7,Yd7e6,Ba8f8,Bf8g8]Black will bring the king to d6 to ensure that c5 can't be captured by White's knight, activate the bishop with ...Bd7 or ...Be6, and then swing the rook on a8 over to the kingside. Both sides have chances in this endgame. } * 

