appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 $1 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4][%csl Re5]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. b3 g4 { 8.b3 is a bit slow and enables Black to immediately strike with the thematic ...g4! Most of our typical ideas are applicable here, but unlike other variations Black has much more flexibility. The engine already weighs in the position in at flat zeros. } 9. hxg4 Bxg4 10. Bb2 { White protects e5 by placing the bishop on the long diagonal. White has a number of other moves here, but Bb2 looks to be the most natural follow up to the b3 advance. The other way to cover e5, namely } ( 10. Qe2 $2 { , results in chaos if we immediately take e5. Black need not capture e5 though. One notable move which happens to be particularly effective whenever White plays b3 in these structures is } 10... Qa5+ { , the idea being to clear the way for the king to castle in the event that we see } 11. Bd2 Qc7 12. Bc3 O-O-O { Black has great play in these lines. With White's bishop off of the c1-h6 diagonal our bishop will be well placed on h6. If White instead Blocks with the knight 11... Qa5+ 11.Nbd2 our queen will invade the queenside. 11...Qc3! 12.Rb1 Qxc2 13.O-O Bh6 14.Re1 Rh7! Lots of interesting positions emerge from this line. } ) 10... Nh6 $5 { If we instead play } ( 10... fxe5 $2 { White can fight to establish control over the central dark squares. } 11. Bxe5 Nf6 $146 12. d4 $2 cxd4 13. Qxd4 { Black should be okay here anyway, but I dislike how active White is getting all of a sudden. ...Nh6!? looks a little bizarre, but the idea is to try to position the knight on f7 to increase the pressure on e5. Unless White responds here with Qe2 we will follow up with ...Nf7. Once again, Black always gets good play when White succumbs to the pressure and captures f6. For instance, let's suppose a game continues with 11... fxe5 11.Nbd2 Nf7! 12.exf6 exf6 13.Qe2+ Kd7! 14.O-O-O Bh6 15.Kb1 Re8 Black has some serious activity here. We control the e-file and have excellent bishops. Moreover, our king is totally safe on d7. } ) 11. Qe2 { [%cal Be5f6]White legitimizes the threat of exf6. Funnily enough, Black can still continue with } 11... fxe5 ( 11... Nf7 $2 $146 { , but only if we meet } 12. exf6 { with } 12... e5 { Honestly, I have no clue what is going on here. This position is pure madness. } 13. Bxe5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nxe5 $146 15. Qxe5+ Kf7 { Apparently this is equal, but to my eye this looks like the sort of position Black could easily slip up in. Hence, instead of ...Nf7!? I recommend that we simply take e5. } ) 12. Qxe5 { Or, if } ( 12. Bxe5 { Black can simply shift the rook over } 12... Rg8 { and should be fine. We can expect something like the following to ensue: } 13. Nbd2 $146 Nf7 $146 14. Bb2 Qa5 15. a3 O-O-O 16. O-O-O e5 { I like how much space Black has in these lines. White doesn't have the same ease of mobility that Black has. } ) 12... Nf7 $13 { [%cal Bh8h6,Bd8d6,Yf7d6,Yd6f5,Yf8h6,Bh6e6,Ge8c8,Ga8d8]Once the queen steps away Black will move the rook off of h8, step the queen up, and try to get castled. A game might continue with } 13. Qg3 Rh6 14. Nh4 $146 { White notices that our thematic pin has been broken. They likely intend to repel our bishop with f3 at some point soon. } 14... Qd6 15. Qxd6 exd6 16. f3 Bd7 17. Nd2 $146 O-O-O { Black has a pawn cube! It doesn't seem easy for White to break through here. Our central pawns make it difficult for their rooks to invade through the e-file, meanwhile Black can easily start targeting White's kingside pawns along the g and f-files. On another note, their knight is stuck on h4, similar to how we've seen in other lines. } * 

