the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 $1 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4][%csl Re5]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. b3 g4 { 8.b3 is a bit slow and enables Black to immediately strike with the thematic ...g4! Most of our typical ideas are applicable here, but unlike other variations Black has much more flexibility. The engine already weighs in the position in at flat zeros. } 9. Nh4 { White holds the tension and prepares to launch the knight into our kingside. } 9... Bg7 { It's important that we keep our dark squared bishop in these lines. If we instead take e5 with } ( 9... fxe5 $2 { White has } 10. Ng6 $146 Rh7 11. Nxf8 $146 Kxf8 12. Bb2 { and suddenly e5 is untenable. Our bishop is functionally necessary for the defense of our central dark squares. } ) 10. Ng6 { White leaps into g6, forcing us to adjust our rook. Responding otherwise, for instance with } ( 10. Bb2 { , allows Black to acquire typical complications with } 10... fxe5 11. Qe2 Qd6 { etc. These lines are slightly better for Black. } ) 10... Rh7 11. hxg4 { The most accurate move here. If White tries } ( 11. Bb2 { or } ) ( 11. Qe2 { Black will simply send the knight back to h4 with } 11... Kf7 12. Nh4 $146 { and capture e5 } 12... fxe5 { with an advantage. } ) 11... Bxg4 { [%cal Bh1h7][%csl Rh7]Here we must recapture g4 with the bishop, lest the rook on h7 fall. } 12. f3 { 13...Qxg6! 14.hxg6 Rxh1+ 15.Ke2 Rxd1 16.Kxd1 e4!! Unleashing the bishop! After 17.c3 exd3 Black has a decisive advantage. } 12... fxe5 $5 { [%cal Rg7a1][%csl Ra1][%cal Bf6e5,Be5e4,Yd8d6,Yd6g6,Yd6g3][%csl Rg6,Re1]Black sacrifices the bishop! Of course, 13.gxh5?? Black wins! } ( 12... Bf5 { is reasonable as well. We might see something like: } 13. Nh4 $146 e6 14. Nxf5 $146 exf5 { Black has great chances in a lot of these lines because White is so uncoordinated. Their position is full of weakness too. } ) 13. fxg4 Qd6 { [%cal Be5e4][%csl Rg6]Forcing the knight to retreat. If White attempts to sustain its post on g6 with } 14. Nh4 e4 $1 { [%cal Bg7a1][%csl Ra1][%cal Bd6g3,Bg3e1,Bg3h4][%csl Rh4,Re1]Unleashing both the bishop and the queen! } 15. Nf5 { This is the only move. If } ( 15. c3 $2 { Black crushes White with } 15... Qg3+ 16. Kf1 hxg4 { White can try to hold on } 17. Qe1 { , but with } 17... Qxd3+ 18. Qe2 Be5 19. Qxd3 exd3 { Black should have a win. Appropriately treating the pin on the h-file is key to conversion. If White proceeds with } 20. Kg1 { Black needs to keep the knight from escaping. } 20... Kf7 { White might try to make room for the knight with } 21. g3 { , but Black has } 21... Bxg3 22. Ng2 $146 Bf2+ { It's over. Stockfish evaluates this as something like -6.2 } ) 15... Qe5 $13 { This position is even sharper than the typical chaos we encounter in these lines! Of course, if you prefer those sorts of positions feel free to withdraw the bishop on move twelve instead of sacrificing it. As it pertains to how we are supposed to play on from here, White presumably has to address our attack on the rook on a1, so we might see them elect to continue with Another continuation worth mentioning is } 16. c3 ( 16. d4 $2 { , where Black will soon acquire a monstrous center. } 16... cxd4 17. Bb2 c5 18. Qe2 a6 { Disallowing the queen's invasion. } 19. Nd2 $146 Bh8 $2 { It's hard to see how White can progress here. If they queenside castle Black has tactics. } 20. O-O-O d3 $3 { If they try to rescue their stranded knight Black secures a decisive initiative. 19... a6 19.Qf2?? Nf6!! 20.Qg3 Qxg3 21.Nxg3 h4! 22.Nf5 Nxg4 23.Nxg7 Rxg7 24.Rxh4 Ne3!! Black can even just sacrifice more material! 25.Rh8+ Kf7 26.Rxa8 Rxg2! White is getting crushed. If they finally try to get their queenside pieces into the game 27.Na3? d3!! Black has forced checkmate. } ) 16... exd3+ { If White decides to block with the bishop or knight Black will play d4 and eventually get the piece back. Those positions are roughly 'equal' by Stockfish's lights. But if White instead tries to run the king } 17. Kf1 $2 { Black has tactics! } 17... hxg4 18. Rxh7 Qxf5+ 19. Kg1 Qxh7 $19 { This is clearly winning. Additionally, 12. f3 17.Kf2? would not be much better. Black secures an extremely strong initiative with 17...Nf6! 18.Qxd3 Nxg4+ 19.Kg1 O-O-O Black is winning here too, but these lines require more precision to convert than the former. 20.Ne3!? d4!! 21.Nxg4 hxg4! 22.Rxh7 dxc3! 23.Qa6+ Kb8 White's king is too exposed to survive this without returning a significant amount of material. } * 

