the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4,Re5]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Qe2 $1 { 8...-- 9.exf6! Nxf6 10.Bxg5+- , therefore we issue the ...g4 push immediately. The lines with 8.Qe2 are the most testing lines in all the 5...f6 6.e5! variations. Playing patiently and preserving the tension in the center is White's best chance at playing for an advantage. I want to emphasize once more that few people have had the strategic acumen to determine that e5 is the accurate reply to ...f6, and of those few none have found the critical responses after ...g5!?. These positions are untested waters. } 8... g4 { White was threatening } 9. hxg4 Bxg4 10. exf6 $2 Nxf6 { [%cal Bf6d7,Bf8g7,Ye7e5]Once again, prematurely exchanging on f6 forfeits White's claim to an advantage! Unlike in the 7.exf6 variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) White won't be immediately worse following the exchange, but now Black has much less to worry about. } 11. Bf4 Nd7 { [%cal Bf8g7,Ye7e5]Black will play for ...e5, as is typical. } 12. Nbd2 Bg7 $13 { [%cal Rd8b6,Re2e3,Be1g1,Bh1f1,Be7e5,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Ye8c8,Ya8d8][%csl Rb2]We have another complicated mess of a middlegame on our hands here. Black has a choice between castling either direction. Both are fine. Black is flexible. Our bishop exerts great pressures on White's queenside, so I doubt White will castle that direction. Still, their king should not remain in the center, so we will probably see them playing O-O at some point. They could do so right away In my eye, White might benefit from starting by break Black's pin. } 13. O-O { and surprisingly } ( 13. Qe3 { Now Black cannot strike in the center with ...e5. } 13... Qb6 { Black hits b2 and clears the way to castle to the queenside. } 14. Rb1 O-O-O 15. Ne5 $2 $146 { White insists that Black abstain from ...e5. } 15... Nxe5 $146 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Qxe5 Rh6 { Leaving the king on the e-file is not safe. Still, castling might not be much safer. } 18. O-O Rg8 { This game could still go either way, but Black's kingside pressure looks intimidating. } ) 13... e5 $2 { is a viable response. } 14. Bxe5 $2 Nxe5 $146 { If we want to play ...e5, we will have to proceed with precision. } 15. Qe3 Qe7 16. Rae1 Nxf3+ $146 17. gxf3 Qxe3 18. Rxe3+ Kd7 19. fxg4 Bh6 20. Re2 Rag8 $10 { This looks like a draw. Earlier, 16... Qe7 16.Nxe5? was a possibility, but is actually a mistake. 16...Bxe5 17.Rae1 Bf6! 18.Qxc5 Be6! 19.Qxc6+ Kf7 Black has an advantage here. The piece is stronger than the three pawns in the long term. Of course, 13...e5 is hardly forced. 13. O-O Black can simply castle instead. 13...O-O This looks safer and simpler. 14.Qe3 e5! 15.Bg5 Qb6 16.Rab1 Rae8 Black has no issues here. } * 

