 have found the critical responses after ...g5!?. These positions are untested waters. } 8... g4 { White was threatening } 9. hxg4 Bxg4 10. Bf4 $1 { The most accurate move. White holds the tension and supports e5. } ( 10. Nc3 $146 Bg7 { transposes to a harmless continuation mentioned in the clickable subvariations here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) ( 10. b3 $2 Qa5+ { transposes to a continuation mentioned in the clickable subvariations here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 10... Qb6 { Tickling b2. Of course, the main purpose of this move is to clear the way for ...O-O-O. In the future we should consider such moves as ...Nh6, ...Bg7, etc. } 11. Nbd2 { Holding the tension and continuing with development. If White has the patience to hold the tension this long they deserve a medal. If White wastes time defending b2 with } ( 11. c4 $2 { Black will get castled and start to push back on the kingside. } 11... O-O-O 12. Nc3 $146 dxc4 13. dxc4 Bh6 14. Bxh6 Nxh6 $146 { This should be fine for Black. } ) 11... Nh6 $16 { [%csl Gf4,Gf3,Ge5,Ge2]Sacrificing f6! Black should try to complicate the position once again. The future doesn't hold promising prospects for us if we don't start confusing White. The problem with our position is that White can just hold the tension on e5 for as long as it takes to coordinate their pieces into an ideal configuration. White's current setup makes it impossible for us to undermine e5, and so Black doesn't really have a way to break through. White is just better. } 12. exf6 $1 { White need not accept the sacrifice, but I suspect most wouldn't be able to resist. Instead, } ( 12. O-O-O Qb4 13. Bh2 O-O-O 14. Nb3 $146 Nf7 $146 { would simply preserve White's advantage, which would sit roughly around +0.3-0.5. A number of other moves fare a bit better for White too, but we need not explore them all here. White can just hold the central tension indefinitely, it seems. However, even though White's position is advantageous it certainly seems difficult to find a clear plan. } ) 12... O-O-O $1 13. fxe7 { Certainly not forced, but perhaps the most human. Other moves are at least slightly better for White too, such as O-O, Be5, and even b4!?. } 13... Bxe7 $13 { [%cal Bd8e8,Bh6f5,Be1g1,Bh1f1]Naturally, if you allow the engine to run long enough it will produce a number approaching zero as the evaluation. Nonetheless, we must admit that White is somewhat better here on practical grounds. They have superior piece harmony, a better structure, fewer weaknesses, and a safer king. However, the game is hardly over. Black has managed to open up lines by sacrificing a pawn. As such, addressing the position is not such a simple matter. Black would be wise to continue by fighting for control over the e-file. At first glance, it might appear as though Black is dropping a piece with Returning to move fourteen 14... Bxe7, Black's threat is ...Rde8. Therefore, White should evacuate the king from the center. In response to 14.O-O-O Black has 14...Bf6! 15.c3 Rde8 16.Qf1 Qa6! 17.Kb1 Bf5 and is successfully generating counterplay. c3 clearly weakens d3, so what happens instead if White blocks the b-file with the knight? 14... Bxe7 15.Nb3!? Rhe8 16.Qd2 Nf5 Suddenly Black has a remarkable threat. If White wastes time playing something passive 17.Kb1?? then 17...c4!! strikes with deadly force! White cannot move the knight due to mate. 18.dxc4 dxc4 19.Qc1 cxb3-+ Next, let's briefly examine a sample continuation with kingside castling. } 14. Bxh6 $2 ( 14. O-O { These lines are a little trickier to navigate. The key here, like in most positions, is centralization. } 14... Rde8 15. Qe5 Nf5 $146 { Black intends ...Bd6!, so the queen must run. } 16. Qc3 Nd4 $146 17. Nxd4 $146 cxd4 18. Qb3 Rhf8 { Black keeps the pace! } 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. Bh6 Rg8 { We're down a pawn here but should be fine anyways. The power of the bishops compensate for the material deficiency. Another interesting line is 15. Qe5 15.Rfe1!? , where White intends to sacrifice the queen! 15...Bd6 16.Qxe8+ Rxe8 17.Rxe8+ Kd7 18.Bxd6 Kxe8 19.Re1+ Kf7 20.Re7+ Kf6 21.Ne5 Qxb2 Both sides have winning chances in these lines. } ) 14... Rxh6 15. Qxe7 { , but Black conveniently has } 15... Re6+ { as a response. } * 

