1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4,Re5]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Qe2 $1 { 8...-- 9.exf6! Nxf6 10.Bxg5+- , therefore we issue the ...g4 push immediately. The lines with 8.Qe2 are the most testing lines in all the 5...f6 6.e5! variations. Playing patiently and preserving the tension in the center is White's best chance at playing for an advantage. I want to emphasize once more that few people have had the strategic acumen to determine that e5 is the accurate reply to ...f6, and of those few none have found the critical responses after ...g5!?. These positions are untested waters. } 8... g4 { White was threatening } 9. Nh4 { White holds the tension and relocates the knight. } 9... Kf7 $1 { [%cal Bh4g6]Black prevents the knight from invading and steps the king up off the e-file, enabling our e-pawn to recapture on f6 if White tries exf6. I would like to pause here for a moment to discuss an important maxim which applies to the variations in which White responds to g4 by relocating the knight to h4. Following 9.Nh4, the possibility of releasing the tension by capturing g4 with hxg4 persists, and in case we do encounter } ( 9... Kf7 10. hxg4 $2 { we need to understand that: Generally speaking, if we cannot administer a pin by recapturing on g4 with the bishop, we should not recapture with the bishop. In this instance (and most others), } 10... hxg4 { is the correct move. If we play Bxg4 then the bishop will simply be exiled back to the queenside upon the arrival of f3. Also, Harry is somewhat of a target on the semi-open h-file. There are some obvious exceptions to this rule, for instance if our rook were to hang following ...hxg4 then clearly ...Bxg4 would be necessary, but generally if the conditions permit, hxg4 is the way to go. } ) 10. Bf4 { White holds the tension on all fronts and sensibly develops. This strategic approach is the one White needs to adopt to play for an advantage. To reiterate, as in most variations, capturing on f6 is just not a good idea. } ( 10. exf6 $2 exf6 { Especially considering that White's king and queen are lined up on the open e-file, this is just asking for disaster. } 11. Nc3 $146 Rb8 { Black stops the bishop from developing. White's only safe haven for the king is the queenside, but they will not be able to castle if the bishop cannot leave c1. Moreover, if White leaves his queen on e2 we might swing the rook over to b7 and then to e7. One might argue that this position is already lost for White. 11... exf6 11.Bf4 stops ...Rb8, but Black will still be better after 11...Bh6! White has similar troubles to the former line. If they retreat the bishop with Bg3 Black will have complete control over the c1-h6 diagonal, making queenside castling infeasible, however if they exchange bishops 12.Bxh6 Nxh6 suddenly Black has threats of ...Re8! This is a catastrophe for White. 13.O-O is the best move, but castling into a pawnstorm looks unsustainable. A game could continue with 13...Rb8 14.b3 Qd6 15.Nd2 Re8 16.Qd1 Bd7 Black has a healthy advantage here. } ) 10... Bh6 $1 { Black challenges White's dark squared defender of e5. Notice that if White retreats } 11. Bxh6 ( 11. Bg3 $2 { Black gains valuable time! } 11... Qb6 { b2 is a target and will be captured momentarily if White fails to address the threat. } 12. b3 Bg5 { This should be slightly better for Black. Therefore, White should exchange on h6. } ) 11... Nxh6 12. Nd2 Qc7 $13 { [%cal Bh6f5,Bc7e5][%csl Re5][%cal Bg4h3][%csl Rh3]Targeting e5 once again. Both sides are under some pressure here, but to White's credit this looks more difficult to play as Black. Suppose White decides that they've held the central tension long enough and proceeds with White could also try } 13. exf6 $2 ( 13. f4 $2 Rb8 14. O-O-O Nf5 $146 15. Nxf5 $146 Bxf5 16. Rde1 Qb6 { The engine comes up with some mind-boggling ideas here. For instance, after } 17. b3 $2 { Stockfish gives the incredible } 17... Kg6 $2 { as the best move. Absolute madness. } ) 13... exf6 { and then evacuates the king from the center. } 14. O-O-O Re8 15. Qf1 gxh3 16. gxh3 Nf5 $146 { This position is difficult to evaluate. On the one hand, Stockfish says this is dead equal. On the other hand, do we really trust ourselves to play like Stockfish? Probably not. Black should continue by fighting to control the open files. } * 

