similar troubles to the former line. If they retreat the bishop with Bg3 Black will have complete control over the c1-h6 diagonal, making queenside castling infeasible, however if they exchange bishops 12.Bxh6 Nxh6 suddenly Black has threats of ...Re8! This is a catastrophe for White. 13.O-O is the best move, but castling into a pawnstorm looks unsustainable. A game could continue with 13...Rb8 14.b3 Qd6 15.Nd2 Re8 16.Qd1 Bd7 Black has a healthy advantage here. } ) 10... Bh6 { Offering to trade makes sense. White will have weakened the dark squares on the queenside if they accept, rendering it a less desirable location to sequester their king. We can expect something like this to come about from the exchange on h6: } 11. Bb2 ( 11. Bxh6 Nxh6 $146 12. Nd2 $146 Qa5 13. O-O Nf5 $146 14. Nxf5 $146 Bxf5 15. Rae1 Rae8 { Black has sufficient counterplay here. On the other hand, if White proceeds with Bb2 as initially intended Black will have control over the c1-h6 diagonal. } ) 11... Bg5 $5 { [%csl Rg6,Rf5,Rf3,Rg2]Asking White some questions. } 12. hxg4 { [%cal Bh1h4]White defends the knight by opening up the h-file. } ( 12. g3 { also prevents the knight from dying in vain. The simplest way to continue is with } 12... Qa5+ $2 13. Nd2 $146 Qxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 gxh3 { Black has good play here. Some ideas that come to mind are ...c4, ...Nh6, ...Bg4, etc. If White tries to avoid the endgame with 13... Qa5+ 13.Bc3!? Black just drops the queen back. 13...Qc7! Now we can play ...d4 at the right moment with tempo. White's e5 pawn is back on the menu. 14.hxg4 hxg4 15.Nd2 d4! Now is the time to strike. White won't have time for Nc4. 16.Bb2 Bxd2+ 17.Kxd2 Qxe5 18.Qxe5 fxe5= This is equal. Black will have to surrender c5 after Ba3. We have a straightforward plan of maneuvering the bishop to d5 with ...Be6-d5, swinging the rook up to h5 to defend the e5 pawn, ...Nf6, and then bringing our other rook over to g8 to contribute to the fight for the kingside. } ) 12... hxg4 { As stated earlier, recapturing g4 with the bishop } ( 12... Bxg4 $2 { when White has played Nh4 runs into } 13. f3 ) 13. g3 $7 Nh6 { [%cal Bh6f5,Bf5h4]Our knight is headed to f5. Black will exert exceptional pressure on the knight on h4 in a moment. } 14. Nd2 { Capitalizing on the opportunity to get the knight out of danger would be a sizable error. } ( 14. Ng2 $2 $146 Nf5 $146 15. Rxh8 Qxh8 { White should have spent the time getting castled! } 16. Nd2 $146 Qh1+ 17. Qf1 Qxf1+ 18. Nxf1 $146 Nd4 $146 19. Nfe3 $146 fxe5 { White is lost! Keeping the rooks on the board won't change the evaluation. 15... Nf5 15.Rg1 Nd4! 16.Bxd4 cxd4 17.Nd2 Qa5! White doesn't have any appealing moves. This looks miserable. } ) 14... Nf5 15. O-O-O Nxh4 16. gxh4 Bf4 $1 { [%cal Bc8f5,Bc5c4,Yd8a5,Ya5c5,Ba8g8,Rd8c7,Rf4e5]Blockading White's f-pawn and pressuring e5. If we capture h4 instead After A more sensible response would be } ( 16... Bxh4 $2 { White can start marching forward. } 17. f3 g3 18. Rde1 Bf5 19. f4 { It would not be to Black's benefit to allow this. } ) ( 16... Bf4 { White would suffer if they try the same plan. } 17. f3 $2 g3 18. Rde1 Bf5 { White doesn't have f4 and cannot easily repel the bishop. Black's kingside is solid. White can easily fall off the board in this position by being careless. } 19. e6+ $2 Ke8 20. Reg1 Qa5 21. Rg2 c4 $3 { White is already lost! } 22. dxc4 Qxa2 23. Rhg1 Rb8 { ...Rxb3 is coming! Apart from giving up the house, there's nothing White can do to prevent it. White has permission to resign. } ) 17. Kb1 { , after which Black can continue to pressure e5. } 17... Qc7 { All paths lead to Rome here. } 18. Rde1 Bxe5 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Qxe5 fxe5 21. Rxe5 Bd7 $10 * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.d3 with 7.h3 / 8.Qe2 / 9.Nfd2 #1 "]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.d3 with 7.h3 / 8.Qe2 / 9.Nfd2 #1 "]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. d3 { The best move. White justifies the decision to trade off the light squared bishop by consolidating the light squares. With d3 White aims for a positional game, hoping that Black's structural deficiencies will contribute to the eventual collapse of his position and consequent obliteration of his king. Certainly a formidable scheme; Black no doubt would struggle to endure this war of attrition. Therefore, Black must cast the game into dynamic chaos! I would recommend that White strap in, because Ferguson's Cannon is about to be reloaded. } 5... f6 { «Never play f6. - Ben Finegold» Black now threatens to confiscate the center with ...e5! A similar thematic sequence appears numerous times in the 4.exd5 mainlines, so we should be familiar and comfortable with this idea by now. Generally speaking, when White is deprived of their light-squared bishop Black has much more breathing room when it comes to weakening the light squares. Hence, ...f6 is not necessarily as repugnant a move as appearance might make it out to be. In any case, ...f6 certainly enables the position to evolve into the sort of dynamic chaos I am in pursuit of, even if it might be risky. } 6. e5 { This is the critical test. With e5 White obstructs Black's grand vision to occupy the center. } 6... g5 $5 { «'It is not enough to be a good player. You must be prepared to make moves that appear ridiculous to the uninitiated.' - Mikhail Tal» If we cannot yet strike in the center, we shall start with the flank! I imagine such a move will come as a shock to many, however once we recover from our stupefaction and are reminded of the strategic blueprint which has guided us through the opening up until this point, the motivation behind ...g5!? should become apparent. With 5...f6, Black prepared to commandeer the rest of the immediate center, ...e5 being the intended follow-up. Evidently, White's previous move has rendered ...e5 an impossibility, but Black should not therefore be deterred from fighting for control over the e5 square. Until the central tension has been clarified, Black's kingside pieces will be effectively stuck where they are. ...e6 would not be an acceptable resolution to the development concern. Our light squared bishop would unfortunately acquire French citizenship and we would find ourselves stuck in the same sort of positional nightmare which we had initially intended on avoiding by playing 3...d5 in the first place. The only viable means of proceeding is to argue that White has overextended by playing e5. To deliver this argument persuasively, we must do all we can to contend for control of the e5 square by making threats and continuously building pressure. Since we now understand that the point of focus in the position is the e5 square, the function of ...g5!? should be clear: Black intends to remove the defender of e5, planning to strike next with ...g4. White can attempt to resist, but ...g4 will come sooner or later. Thus marks the theme of the position: Black's efforts should be directed towards undermining White's pawn, while White should endeavor to sustain its position. Needless to say, the upcoming positions are without a doubt the most difficult to navigate in the entire course. Unfortunately, I have yet to form an opinion about the practical merits of this line. None of my opponents have been strong enough to discern that e5 is the critical move on move six, even though I have dozens of practice games in the Bxc6+ variations. At the time of writing, every single one of my opponents have simply allowed me to confiscate the center with ...e5 on move six, granting Black total central dominance and future kingside attacking chances. Out of personal curiosity I interviewed a number of masters to see how they would approach this position from the White side. Most of them had no clue how to evaluate the position and offered moves which immediately surrendered the advantage to Black. I'm very curious to learn about how this will perform following the publication of this course. } 7. h3 h5 { [%cal Bg5g4,Bc8g4][%csl Rg4,Re5]With h3 White forces Black to commit to further kingside expansion in order to proceed with ...g4. } 8. Qe2 { 8...-- 9.exf6! Nxf6 10.Bxg5+- , therefore we issue the ...g4 push immediately. The lines with 8.Qe2 are the most testing lines in all the 5...f6 6.e5! variations. Playing patiently and preserving the tension in the center is White's best chance at playing for an advantage. I want to emphasize once more that few people have had the strategic acumen to determine that e5 is the accurate reply to ...f6, and of those few none have found the critical responses after ...g5!?. These positions are untested waters. } 8... g4 { White was threatening } 9. Nfd2 $2 Qc7 { Black should be glad to see White passively retreating the knight. Now we can proceed by targeting e5. I prefer ...Qc7 here over ...Bg7 because the typical Another mistake to take note of here is } 10. hxg4 { The only decent move. } ( 10. exf6 $2 { comes with a special twist. } 10... Kf7 { Getting the king out of the way. Black would like to take f6 with the pawn! Of course, White will not allow it. } 11. fxe7 Nxe7 $146 12. Nc3 $146 Bg7 { Black's rook is coming to e8. White's king is not safe in the center, but where to go? } 13. O-O Ng6 $146 14. Nb3 $146 Re8 { I don't foresee White surviving. Black's initiative in these lines are just as potent as in the 7.exf6? variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) ( 10. e6 $2 { , threatening our g-pawn. } 10... gxh3 11. Rxh3 { White has some activity here, but it's nothing remarkable. } 11... Qe5 12. Re3 Qh2 { Black has eyes on g2. Trying to save the pawn will only bring White more trouble. } 13. g3 $2 Qh3 { e6 is Black's new target. White will suffer after ...Nh6-f5-d4. } ) ( 10. exf6 { and 10... Qc7 10.e6 are serious mistakes, as previously stated. 10... Qc7 10.Nb3 allows 10...gxh3 11.gxh3 c4! 12.dxc4 Qxe5 , and after 10... Qc7 10.Nc3 Black gets a similar advantage with 10...gxh3 11.gxh3 Qxe5 } ) 10... Bxg4 11. f3 Bc8 $5 { We could play } ( 11... Bf5 $2 { , but that would run into } 12. g4 { These lines are playable, but not particularly pleasant. 11. f3 11...Be6 is okay, but the bishop is a little awkward on e6. 11. f3 If 11...Bd7?! Black gets hit with 12.e6! ...Bc8 looks like the best of the bunch to me. } ) 12. Nb3 c4 $5 { [%cal Rb3c5]If we're going to give up the c-pawn, we might as well discombobulate White's center! This looks a little cleaner than } ( 12... Qxe5 13. Qxe5 fxe5 14. Nxc5 $146 e6 15. Nb3 $146 Ne7 $146 { , but you can choose for yourself. Playing this way is perfectly fine too. } ) 13. dxc4 Qxe5 $15 { Black has a slight edge. We have excellent potential in the center and the bishops in an open position. A game might continue with } 14. Qxe5 fxe5 15. cxd5 $2 cxd5 { White has gotten rid of their doubled pawns, but now Black's center is extremely strong. White will struggle to break out. Under most conditions c4 or f4 will result in Black securing a passed pawn. } 16. Nc3 $146 Nf6 $146 17. Kf2 Kf7 18. Bg5 Be6 19. Rae1 Bg7 { Black enjoys a comfortable advantage here. } * 

