ve found the critical responses after ...g5!?. These positions are untested waters. } 8... g4 { White was threatening } 9. Nfd2 Qc7 { Black should be glad to see White passively retreating the knight. Now we can proceed by targeting e5. I prefer ...Qc7 here over ...Bg7 because the typical Another mistake to take note of here is } 10. hxg4 { The only decent move. } ( 10. exf6 $2 { comes with a special twist. } 10... Kf7 { Getting the king out of the way. Black would like to take f6 with the pawn! Of course, White will not allow it. } 11. fxe7 Nxe7 $146 12. Nc3 $146 Bg7 { Black's rook is coming to e8. White's king is not safe in the center, but where to go? } 13. O-O Ng6 $146 14. Nb3 $146 Re8 { I don't foresee White surviving. Black's initiative in these lines are just as potent as in the 7.exf6? variations (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) ( 10. e6 $2 { , threatening our g-pawn. } 10... gxh3 11. Rxh3 { White has some activity here, but it's nothing remarkable. } 11... Qe5 12. Re3 Qh2 { Black has eyes on g2. Trying to save the pawn will only bring White more trouble. } 13. g3 $2 Qh3 { e6 is Black's new target. White will suffer after ...Nh6-f5-d4. } ) ( 10. exf6 { and 10... Qc7 10.e6 are serious mistakes, as previously stated. 10... Qc7 10.Nb3 allows 10...gxh3 11.gxh3 c4! 12.dxc4 Qxe5 , and after 10... Qc7 10.Nc3 Black gets a similar advantage with 10...gxh3 11.gxh3 Qxe5 } ) 10... Bxg4 11. f3 Bc8 { We could play } ( 11... Bf5 $2 { , but that would run into } 12. g4 { These lines are playable, but not particularly pleasant. 11. f3 11...Be6 is okay, but the bishop is a little awkward on e6. 11. f3 If 11...Bd7?! Black gets hit with 12.e6! ...Bc8 looks like the best of the bunch to me. } ) 12. exf6 $2 Kf7 $1 { The same theme applies here as mentioned before. Black would like to recapture f6 with the pawn, but cannot do so as long as it's pinned! } 13. fxe7 Nxe7 $17 { [%cal Be7f5,Bf8g7][%csl Rd2,Rc1,Rb1,Ra1]It might look hazardous to have our king out in the open, true, but the fact is that Black is actually just much better here. White is simply too passive to punish ...Kf7! In fact, Black is winning if White doesn't have the strategic acumen to discern that On another note, it might be worth considering the case in which White doesn't find f4 on move fourteen. Let's suppose White instead continues with something else. } 14. f4 { is the best move. White not only threatens Harry's life, but also might bring the knight back to f3 to start targeting our king. Black can just ignore White's threats on h5 and develop. } ( 14. Nc3 $2 $146 Bg7 { Black's plan is simply to exploit White's kingside and central weaknesses with ...Nf5 and ...Re8. } 15. Nf1 $146 Nf5 $146 { Defending the dark squares is a hopeless endeavor! } 16. Qf2 Bd4 17. Be3 Re8 18. Nd1 $146 Bf6 { ...d4 is unstoppable. White is finished. } ) 14... Bg7 { White has no time to waste. } 15. Rxh5 $2 { is lost. } 15... Bd7 16. Nc3 $146 Nf5 $146 { Black's lead in development is overwhelming. Instead, White's best chance is with 15... Bg7 15.Nf3! Bg4 16.Ne5+! Bxe5 17.Qxe5 Qd7 White once again is in a tough spot. ...Rae8 is the threat, which would end the game on the spot. That is, unless White finds 18.f5! The point is that after 18...Nxf5 White's queen has a means of remaining on the kingside if Black meets 19.O-O! with ...Rae8. So instead of that, Black should just focus on the kingside directly. 19...h4! 20.Qf4 Rag8 21.Kh2! Rg6 This is technically better for Black, but you'd probably need to be an engine to convert the advantage into anything substantive. What an incredible defense from White. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "6th-Move Alternatives (Instead of ...g5) - Analysis"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6th-Move Alternatives (Instead of ...g5) - Analysis"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 f6 6. e5 { It might be worth examining some alternatives to 6...g5, as it is certainly not forced and some might find the more pressing lines rather uncomfortable. Its practicality too has yet been put to the test, as there are few games if any which have followed the analysis I have conducted in this line. } 6... Bg4 { Perhaps one of the more interesting moves. The pressure on e5 is palpable. From here, more than 35% of people are taking on f6, which is a mistake. } ( 6... Qc7 $2 { Probably the least pressing attempt at targeting e5. } 7. Qe2 { The natural response. } 7... Bg4 $2 { The most played move. I see the vision, but it has one small flaw. } 8. Nbd2 $146 { Anything else and Black has compensation. Unfortunately for Black, this is already nearly lost. } 8... Nh6 $146 9. h3 Bc8 $16 { And the attempt to undermine e5 has failed. } ) ( 6... e6 $16 { This I find to be the worse out of all the alternatives. Our position is unreasonably cramped and our pieces don't have an easy way to get in the game. Moreover, our light squared bishop is particularly detestable, positionally speaking. } 7. O-O { In these lines I think it's easier for White to intuit that e5 is the critical square to maintain. It's much more difficult to know what to do after ...g5 because of the foreign character of the position and the constant kingside and central pressures exerted by the ...g4 and ...fxe5 threats. } 7... Qc7 8. Re1 Ne7 $146 9. c4 Ng6 $146 10. Nc3 $146 Be7 11. exf6 gxf6 $16 { Even if we find the right ideas, the position is not so easy to play. } ) 7. exf6 $2 ( 7. Bf4 $2 { White's second pick. I think this line gets us closer to the madness involved in the 6...g5 lines. } 7... g5 8. Bg3 $2 f5 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 $146 e6 11. c3 Ne7 $146 12. Qa4 h6 $17 { Black is just better. Our pawn bastion renders this a positional nightmare for White, as their pieces don't have the mobility to do anything substantive. Moreover, Black has the b-file and can also play against White's e5 pawn if they're not careful. } ) ( 7. h3 { Probably the most natural move. This is one of the better responses. } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 fxe5 9. Qh5+ { The critical line. We will see something like this variation in the next chapter, though White is better here because both the d and h-pawns have already advanced. } 9... g6 10. Qxe5 Nf6 $146 11. O-O Qd6 12. Bf4 Qxe5 13. Bxe5 Bh6 $14 { White is definitely better, but all is not lost. Black can play ...Kf7 or ...O-O and ...Re8, eventually hoping to push ...e5. } ) ( 7. Nbd2 $146 { No doubt the best move. The best Black can do here is to go into a positionally worse middlegame. } 7... e6 { Ugly, but better than the alternatives. } 8. h3 Bh5 9. Qe2 f5 { Keeping things interesting. Black now might lunge forth with ...g5 at the right moment if White castles. } 10. Nb3 $146 { White should avoid castling in the short-term to press for the edge. } 10... Nh6 $146 { This is the best we have. } 11. Bxh6 gxh6 12. Qe3 a5 13. O-O Rg8 14. Kh2 Kf7 $14 { White has a pleasant edge and ease of mobility. } ) 7... exf6 $15 { Black already has a great position, with the bishop pair and the f-pawn fortuitously restricting White's knight. } 8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1+ Ne7 10. h3 Bh5 { It's already not easy for White to figure out a plan. Black's advantage can easily grow from here. } 11. Nbd2 $1 { This clumsy looking move is the only one which holds on. The idea is to reroute to the kingside, as seen in Italian middlegames. } ( 11. Nc3 $2 $146 { This, for instance, is already lost! } 11... O-O { A sample line: } 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Bd2 Nf5 $146 14. Qd1 Rxe1+ 15. Bxe1 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nd4 $146 17. Qd1 Qe7 18. Bd2 Re8 $19 ) 11... O-O 12. Nf1 Qc7 13. Ng3 Bf7 $15 { I think Black has decent chances here, with the bishop pair and the unique pawn configuration which restricts White's knights. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "A 5th-Move Alternative (The Endgame) - Analysis"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A 5th-Move Alternative (The Endgame) - Analysis"]
[Black "4) Dynamic Chaos | 4.Bxc6+ with 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 dxe4 { This is a simple alternative for those who don't care for the chaos of involved in the ...f6 middlegames. This endgame is slightly worse for Black due to the structure, but Black has some interesting ideas anyway. } 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Nf6 { Black apparently is scoring 54% in this line. I guess White's king on the open file is a little awkward and it will be cumbersome to connect the rooks once Black plays ...Ba6. } 8. Nc3 ( 8. Re1 $2 { Probably one of the more interesting continuations comes after this move. } 8... Ng4 $146 { Black goes straight for f2. White cannot protect it with the rook or king because of ...Ba6. } 9. Ke2 $2 Ba6+ 10. Kd2 Rd8+ { Precise. } 11. Kc3 Nxf2 $19 $146 ) ( 8. e5 $2 { This is not a great move. Black's knight now can access d5. } 8... Nd5 $146 9. c4 $2 { This is what people are playing, but it is suboptimal. } 9... Nb4 $146 10. a3 Nd3 $146 { White simply rolled down the red carpet for the knight to enter the position. } 11. Ke2 Nxc1+ $146 12. Rxc1 g5 $17 { The rook is coming to g8, the bishop to g7, etc. Black is doing great. } ) ( 8. Nbd2 $2 $146 { An interesting way of protecting e5. On the one hand, the knight is probably better placed on d2 than c3, on the other the bishop is closed off for now. } 8... g5 $2 { Closing off the bishop enables Black to strike with this classic push! } 9. Nxg5 $2 $146 Rg8 10. Ngf3 $146 Rxg2 $15 { with excellent play. The bishops are an superb asset in this sort of position. } ) 8... Ba6 $1 { A key idea, cutting through the open light-squared diagonal. Now White's king has been deprived of the e2 square. } 9. Be3 { Naturally, pursuing c5. } ( 9. Bg5 { A favorite of intermediate players. We don't mind allowing further corruption of our structure, as opening up the files will give us excellent play for our rooks. } 9... h6 10. Bxf6 $2 exf6 11. Kc1 O-O-O 12. Rd1 Bd6 $17 { An excellent position. } ) 9... e6 10. Ne5 $6 { The most common move, going after c6. Perhaps this is too ambitious though. Black can just sacrifice the pawn! } ( 10. h3 { The next most frequent move. White plays the waiting game. } 10... Nd7 $146 { With the idea of an eventual ...f6-e5. } 11. Kc1 f6 12. b3 c4 13. Kb2 e5 $14 { White is a bit better. } ) ( 10. Kc1 { White wishes to make use of the open file, however now Black can jump in! } 10... Ng4 $146 { This looks a bit unpleasant. } 11. Re1 Nxe3 $146 12. Rxe3 g5 $15 { Getting active. White cannot capture due to ...Rg8. This already looks somewhat fine for Black. } ) ( 10. e5 $2 { This gives Black the d5 square. } 10... Nd5 $146 11. Re1 O-O-O $10 { Black can either take on c3 or e3 next and has an equal game. } ) 10... Bd6 $1 { Really, the only acceptable move. } 11. Nxc6 Ng4 $1 { The point. Suddenly Black is getting a ton of play. We have ...Kd7 ideas coming next when White deals with the threat on the bishop. } 12. Kd2 Kd7 13. Na5 c4 $1 { The knight is officially out of the game. Black is threatening to end the game with ...Bb4. } 14. Rad1 ( 14. Na4 $2 $146 { An interesting idea. Hoping for queenside counterplay. } 14... Rhc8 { Renewing ...Bb4 ideas. ...Bb5 becomes a possibility too. } 15. c3 $7 Bb5 16. b3 $7 Bxa4 17. bxa4 Bc5 $15 { Black has plenty of compensation for the pawn. } ) ( 14. b3 $2 { Too eager. } 14... Bb4 15. Nxc4 $146 Ke7 $19 { White will lose a piece. } ) 14... Kc7 { Simply stepping aside. Now a3 is forced. } 15. a3 Rhd8 $1 16. Ke2 Nxe3 17. Kxe3 g5 $15 { Black is down a pawn, but has active pieces and potential to generate an attack against White's exposed king. The bishops can become dangerous when the queenside situation has been resolved and the board opens up. } * 

