1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 $1 Qc7 $5 { After 5...f6 6.e5 g5!? the dubiousness of this opening becomes more apparent. Hence, I thought it fitting to offer some analysis on an alternative 5th move. The quantity of trainable variations for this chapter is already arguably inordinate, so I have elected to omit more for the time being. If demand is high I will be happy to add some alternative trainables, but for now a reference file should suffice for those curious about alternative ways to play. 5...Qc7 is a legitimate alternative to 5...f6 which is played in a similar spirit: Black wants a quick ...e5. Here we will explore some of White's most common continuations and how they should be parried. } 6. e5 { The most common, though hardly the most critical. } ( 6. O-O { The most principled response. Keeping the queenside flexible. } 6... e5 $2 { The ambitious way to play. Nobody likes those slightly worse positional middlegames with the patient ...e6 anyways! } 7. Re1 f6 { Black is back in business with the typical shenanigans we see in the trainables in this chapter! } 8. Nc3 $146 Ne7 $146 9. b3 d4 $2 { Tempting White to go after c5. } 10. Na4 $146 Ng6 $146 11. Ba3 Nf4 $146 12. Bxc5 Bg4 $17 { With complications very similar to a variation we've learned about already. } ) ( 6. exd5 $2 { No idea why this move is being played. } 6... cxd5 7. O-O f6 $2 8. Re1 e5 { Boom. Black gets the typical massive center for free. } 9. c4 d4 10. b4 Ne7 $146 11. bxc5 Nc6 $146 { With a transposition to a position found earlier. } ) ( 6. Nc3 $146 { Pressuring d5 immediately. Unfortunately, Black should probably abandon the plan to play ...e5. This is probably the cleanest 'refutation' to our idea, as now Black has to defend d5 and consequently is forced into the sort of dry positional middlegames which just aren't great for Black. } 6... e6 { Every move is now roughly +0.5 for White. A clean advantage with no complications. Or is it.... } 7. O-O Ne7 $146 8. b3 Ng6 $146 9. Ba3 { However, if White goes for c5 \--a plan which is supported by the computer --Black can try to transform the position into those chaotic middlegames we know and love! } 9... Be7 10. Na4 $146 O-O 11. Bxc5 e5 { ...f5 and ...Nf4 might be coming! } 12. c4 $2 { As seen in one game. } 12... d4 { Releasing the pressure. } 13. Qd2 Bxc5 14. Nxc5 $146 a5 $17 ) ( 6. Qe2 { This is always an annoying move. Now if Black plays ...e5 White will capture on d5. White is usually able to stop all of Black's attempts at pursuing dynamic shenanigans early in the game with a quick Qe2. Somehow Black is still scoring quite well already though, with over 50% of games resulting in a victory. } 6... Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 $14 { White is better, etc. We've seen this sort of position frequently already. } ) 6... Bg4 { The typical response to White's ...e5 push when we have not yet advanced with ...f6. } 7. Bf4 $6 { Following the most common continuation here. White has already gone awry. } ( 7. Nbd2 $146 e6 8. h3 Bh5 { We never trade on f3 when White can recapture with a knight. } 9. O-O Ne7 $146 10. Re1 Bg6 11. Nf1 $146 Nf5 $13 $146 { With an unclear, though certainly playable middlegame to come. } ) ( 7. Qe2 $2 { Neglecting to attend to Black's threats. } 7... Bxf3 8. gxf3 { Otherwise e5 falls. } 8... e6 9. f4 Ne7 $17 $146 { Black is just positionally much better. } ) 7... g5 $3 { Thematic. } 8. Bg3 ( 8. Bxg5 $2 { Getting greedy will do White no favors. } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qxe5+ 10. Qe3 Qxb2 $19 { With a decisive advantage. } ) ( 8. Be3 { The computer's choice. A move which probably makes little sense to human sensibility. } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qxe5 10. Nd2 $146 h5 $15 { Black is up a clean pawn. } ) 8... e6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. h3 Bf5 $17 { Black already has a fantastic position. ...h5-h4/...g4 paired with ...Nh6 are typical ideas in these positions with the closed center, as will be seen later in the course. } * 

