1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. e5 { [%cal Bc8g4,Be7e6,Bh7h5]It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing blitz against experts and advanced players. After much analysis and experimentation I have been convinced that 5.e5 is actually rather risky for White. With the center closed, the position is primed for combat on the flanks. Next, Black will play ...Bg4 and ...e6, preparing to meet White's inevitable kingside castling with an aggressive and potentially fatal pawnstorm. } 5... Bg4 { [%cal Be7e6,Bg4d1][%csl Rf3]Before we establish a central pawn chain with ...e6 it would be wise to administer this pin. } 6. h3 { In all likelihood our opponent will have little tolerance for our pin. We should expect h3 more often than not. } 6... Bxf3 { I dislike } ( 6... Bh5 { due to } 7. g4 Bg6 8. e6 $2 { While the resulting positions are perfectly playable, I personally find such complications unattractive compared to what follows from ...Bxf3. } ) 7. Qxf3 e6 { [%csl Bf7,Be6,Bd5][%cal Bh7h5][%csl Bg4]Black's position doesn't look too bad! We have a sizable center, easy development, and no bad bishop to be locked away behind a chain of pawns. } 8. d3 h5 $10 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be7f5,Bf5d4,Bf8e7,Bd8c7,Rc1g5,Rd8b8][%csl Rb2][%cal Gg7g6,Gg6g5,Ye8d7]Black also has ...h5 if White plays 8.O-O instead of 8.d3. Black would love to plant the knight on f5 and eventually go for the ...g5-g4 push. Generally in the 5.e5 variations Black rarely needs to kingside castle. Our center is so impenetrable that our king might be best left in the center, perhaps eventually even landing on d7 in some positions, leaving the kingside available as an avenue for assault. Here is an illustrative continuation which shows the dynamic potential of the position: } 9. O-O Ne7 $146 10. Re1 Nf5 $146 11. Nc3 $2 $146 g5 { Where the incoming g4 would result in a devastating attack. For instance: } 12. a3 $2 g4 13. hxg4 Nd4 $146 14. Qd1 hxg4 { White's resignation will arrive momentarily. White might try defending with 12... g5 13.Ne2 to which Black should respond with 13...Nh4! After White moves the queen, Black can continuously build pressure on the kingside and wait for the right moment to break out with ...g4. 14.Qg3 Be7 15.Bd2 Rg8! This position looks quite promising for us. } * 

