resh. Of course, one could plausibly attempt to transpose to the 6.h3 variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) by starting with } ( 6... h5 $2 { too. Probably the most natural continuation will lead directly to that line: } 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 { , etc. Move order differences don't make much of a difference here, so play whatever you're more comfortable with. On another note, 6.d3 allows for an immediate Nbd2. Generally, when we see this idea play out we should forget about our plan to exchange on f3 when hit with h3. In most cases we can still proceed with the standard ...h5 \+ ...g5 pawn storm though, but there are strange continuations which can steer the game in a more positional direction if White accurately plays against our ...g5 push. } ) 7. Nbd2 { [%cal Bd2f3][%csl Rf3][%cal Bh2h3]Preparing h3. White might benefit from recapturing on f3 with a knight in the event of an exchange. Needless to say, White's campaign to improve their pieces is not an effort that we would like to contribute to, and so the incoming h3 will not be met with an exchange. Let's look at a few alternatives in case White doesn't opt for Nbd2. Remember, If White might also try } ( 7. h3 { transposes to 5.e5 with 6.h3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) after } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 h5 $2 ) ( 7. O-O { 7...h4! , making room for the bishop to drop back. Now our knight has the f5 square and we can eventually play for ...g5-g4 as usual. 8.h3 } 7... h5 ( 7... Bh5 8. Re1 Nh6 $146 9. c4 Nf5 $146 10. Qa4 Qd7 11. b3 Be7 12. Ba3 g5 { Black can continue with ...Rg8 and ...g4. } ) 8. Nbd2 $146 { Black has } ) ( 7. Bf4 $2 { , but then Black has } 7... g5 { with tempo. } 8. Bg3 h5 { This is basically the setup we've been pursuing all along. White has just gifted it to Black by playing Bf4. } 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qb8 { Targeting b2 and e5. Black can follow up with ...Ne7-Nf5 and ...Bg7. White will struggle to defend e5. } ) 7... Be7 $5 { [%cal Bh7h5,Rh2h3,Rg4f5,Bg7g5,Bg5g4,Gd2b3,Ga