%csl Yf7,Ye6,Yd5,Be5,Bd4,Bc3,Yc5]After c3 we find ourselves in a strange structure that will probably start to resemble the Advanced French soon, but where White doesn't have the glorious light-squared bishop, where our light squared bishop has escaped the reputed inactivity of the infamously bad French bishop, and where Black has two c-pawns. If White plays d4, which presumably was the point of c3, Black can simply take on d4 and eventually follow up with ...c5. Black will typically end up with a passed d-pawn once the central situation has been clarified. } 6... h5 $5 { [%cal Be7e6,Bg8e7,Be7f5][%csl Rd4]After 6...h5!? Black has a remarkable win percentage. Nearly 70% according to the lichess database. If White meets ...h5 with h3 we would find ourselves in positions similar to those mentioned earlier in the chapter, e.g. } 7. d4 ( 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 9. O-O g5 $2 { with excellent attacking prospects on the kingside. In the meantime, we need not rush the position. Our plan is fairly straightforward: Play ...e6 followed by ...Ne7/Nh6 and ...Nf5, securing control over d4 and maintaining central dominance. } ) 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 e6 $15 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be7f5,Bf5d4][%csl Rd4][%cal Bd8b6,Bb6d4][%csl Rf3][%cal Ba8c8,Bb6b2][%csl Rb2][%cal Bg4f3,Bc6c5]Black has flexibility here. While on the one hand we could target the weak d4 by proceeding with typical French ideas, e.g. ...Qb6, ...Ne7-Nf5, ...c5, etc. we could also pursue a more aggressive path by opting for the more familiar kingside pawnstorm once White has castled. Both are promising options. } * 

