ible choice, but now the king has committed to one side of the board. } 6... e6 7. h3 { The most common move. Let's pause briefly to discuss the most natural alternative before exploring further: 7.d3 Firstly, } ( 7. d3 h5 { will most probably transpose to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), as the most likely encounter is the natural } 8. h3 { , after which we are immediately prompted to capture on f3 with } 8... Bxf3 { Consult the linked variation for more information. There are two more moves to mention in passing after 7... e6 7.d3 h5 , one of which being 8.Nbd2 —Any time we see this move, we typically should abandon our disposition to exchange the bishop on f3 after being prompted to do so by h3, for instance: 8...g5!? 9.h3 Bf5! We keep the bishop and play for the ...g4 push. If White instead delays h3 on move nine we can develop with ...Be7 and ...Nh6 with the same idea of an eventual ...Bf5 and ...g4 to come. Lastly, 8... h5 8.Re1 deserves a mention. I like Stockfish's recommendation here: 8...Nh6! Black develops the knight, but does so in a way which doesn't block the queen off. White's most popular move, 9.Nc3? just makes no sense at all. 9...g5! 10.h3 Bxf3 11.Qxf3 g4! 12.hxg4 hxg4 13.Qg3 Nf5! 14.Qxg4 Kd7!! Black easily secures a nearly decisive initiative. Instead, the more natural 9... Bxf3 9.h3 is stronger. Though the position is closer to equal, Black gets our typical sort of dynamic play after 9...Bxf3 10.Qxf3 Nf5! with our standard ...g5-g4 push arriving very quickly. As a reminder, memorizing all of this analysis is not necessary. I am going over these lines in the text to give you an idea of how striking the thematic overlap is between variations, even for lines not directly included in the drillables. } ) 7... h5 $1 { [%cal Bd8h4,Bh8h1][%csl Rh1][%cal Yh3g4,Yh5g4][%csl Rf3]h5 is both aggressive and sound! White would be wise not to take the bishop. } 8. hxg4 $4 hxg4 9. g3 { Returning the piece is White's only hope. } ( 9.