1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing blitz against experts and advanced players. After much analysis and experimentation I have been convinced that 5.e5 is actually rather risky for White. With the center closed, the position is primed for combat on the flanks. Next, Black will play ...Bg4 and ...e6, preparing to meet White's inevitable kingside castling with an aggressive and potentially fatal pawnstorm. } 5... Bg4 { [%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3][%cal Be7e6,Bg8e7,Be7f5]Before we close our pawn chain with ...e6, it would be wise to administer this pin. Bf5 is an alternative to be aware of, but I think the positions become more interesting after Bg4. } 6. O-O { Castling is a sensible choice, but now the king has committed to one side of the board. } 6... e6 7. h3 { The most common move. Let's pause briefly to discuss the most natural alternative 7.d3 before exploring further. Firstly, after } ( 7. d3 h5 { will most probably transpose to the forthcoming line, as the most likely encounter is the natural } 8. h3 { There are two more moves to mention in passing after 7... e6 7.d3 h5 , one of which being 8.Nbd2 —Any time we see this move, we typically should abandon our disposition to exchange the bishop on f3 after being prompted to do so by h3, for instance: 8...g5!? 9.h3 Bf5! We keep the bishop and play for the ...g4 push. If White instead delays h3 on move nine we can develop with ...Be7 and ...Nh6 with the same idea of an eventual ...Bf5 and ...g4 to come. Lastly, 8... h5 8.Re1 deserves a mention. I like Stockfish's recommendation here: 8...Nh6! Black develops the knight, but does so in a way which doesn't block the queen off. White's most popular move, 9.Nc3? just makes no sense at all. 9...g5! 10.h3 Bxf3 11.Qxf3 g4! 12.hxg4 hxg4 13.Qg3 Nf5! 14.Qxg4 Kd7!! Black easily secures a nearly decisive initiative. Instead, the more natural 8. h3 9.h3 is stronger. Though the position is closer to equal, Black gets our typical sort of dynamic play after 9...Bxf3 10.Qxf3 Nf5! with our standard ...g5-g4 push arriving very quickly. As a reminder, memorizing all of this analysis is not necessary. I am going over these lines in the text to give you an idea of how striking the thematic overlap is between variations, even for lines not directly included in the drillables. } ) 7... h5 $1 { h5 is both aggressive and sound! White would be wise not to take the bishop. } 8. d3 { White frees the bishop, ignoring our hanging bishop. This is the most testing reply against 7.h5. 8...-- 9.hxg4 hxg4 10.Nh2 } 8... Bxf3 { We must exchange on f3. After the cunning 8.d3 White is actually threatening to take the bishop for nothing. } ( 8... Qh4 9. Bf4 ) 9. Qxf3 Ne7 { [%cal Bg7g5,Be7f5,Ba7a5,Be7g6]We will proceed in similar fashion to our previous lines. Our knight comes to f5 or g6 and we will play ...g5! Black has great play in these lines. } 10. Nd2 { A friendly reminder that if White finds } ( 10. Bg5 $2 { to be an appealing move, Black has the thematic } 10... Qb8 { where White will face difficulty defending both e5 and b2. } ) 10... g5 $1 { [%cal Bc1g5][%csl Rd2]If White temporarily blocks his bishop, we can use this opportunity to get ...g5 in! } 11. Nb3 Ng6 $13 { [%cal Bf8e7,Bg5g4,Bh5h4,Bg6e5][%csl Re5][%cal Be8d7,Bd8b6,Ba8g8,Ba7a5]...Nf5 is a strong option too. I like ...Ng6 because we are pressuring e5 and we support h4 in the event that we want to place a rook there. If White neglects to attend to the pressure on e5 with something like To illustrate Black's ideas some more, White could try } 12. Bd2 $2 { we immediately strike with } ( 12. Re1 Be7 13. Bd2 { and we again issue the thematic } 13... g4 14. hxg4 hxg4 15. Qxg4 { With White's queen is no longer eyeing f7 we can step away with } 15... Kd7 { and begin to attack! Black is threatening to immediately end the game with ...Rh4 followed by ...Qh8. White once again is on the defense. } ) 12... g4 13. hxg4 hxg4 14. Qxg4 Nxe5 $146 { and Black has a moderate advantage and excellent attacking prospects down the open files. } * 

