ible choice, but now the king has committed to one side of the board. } 6... e6 7. h3 { The most common move. Let's pause briefly to discuss the most natural alternative before exploring further: 7.d3 Firstly, } ( 7. d3 h5 { will most probably transpose to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), as the most likely encounter is the natural } 8. h3 { , after which we are immediately prompted to capture on f3 with } 8... Bxf3 { Consult the linked variation for more information. There are two more moves to mention in passing after 7... e6 7.d3 h5 , one of which being 8.Nbd2 —Any time we see this move, we typically should abandon our disposition to exchange the bishop on f3 after being prompted to do so by h3, for instance: 8...g5!? 9.h3 Bf5! We keep the bishop and play for the ...g4 push. If White instead delays h3 on move nine we can develop with ...Be7 and ...Nh6 with the same idea of an eventual ...Bf5 and ...g4 to come. Lastly, 8... h5 8.Re1 deserves a mention. I like Stockfish's recommendation here: 8...Nh6! Black develops the knight, but does so in a way which doesn't block the queen off. White's most popular move, 9.Nc3? just makes no sense at all. 9...g5! 10.h3 Bxf3 11.Qxf3 g4! 12.hxg4 hxg4 13.Qg3 Nf5! 14.Qxg4 Kd7!! Black easily secures a nearly decisive initiative. Instead, the more natural 9... Bxf3 9.h3 is stronger. Though the position is closer to equal, Black gets our typical sort of dynamic play after 9...Bxf3 10.Qxf3 Nf5! with our standard ...g5-g4 push arriving very quickly. As a reminder, memorizing all of this analysis is not necessary. I am going over these lines in the text to give you an idea of how striking the thematic overlap is between variations, even for lines not directly included in the drillables. } ) 7... h5 { h5 is both aggressive and sound! White would be wise not to take the bishop. } 8. c3 { [%cal Bd2d4]White aims for a quick d4. } 8... Nh6 { [%cal Bh6f5,Bg7g5,Rd8h4]c3 gives us time to develop, so we bring our knight closer to our favorite f5 square. This should not be done through ...Ne7, as that would block our queen. While it's true that } ( 8... Ne7 $2 $146 9. hxg4 hxg4 10. Nh2 $146 Ng6 $146 11. Qxg4 { White ends up being better. } ) ( 8... Nh6 $146 { blocks the h-file, } 9. hxg4 $2 { would still be a blunder. } 9... hxg4 10. Nh2 $146 Qh4 11. d3 Nf5 $146 12. Bf4 { With the knight on f5, Black can break through White's defenses. } 12... g3 13. Bxg3 Nxg3 $146 14. fxg3 Qxh2+ 15. Kf2 { Black is winning. We can follow up with ...Be7 and ...Rh3!. g3 is doomed. } ) 9. d4 Bxf3 { Now that White has moved his d-pawn and his bishop is free to develop, we must exchange on f3. } 10. Qxf3 Nf5 { [%cal Bf5d4,Bc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 11. Qd3 { d4 is being threatened and White must choose how to defend it. If White instead errs with } ( 11. Be3 $2 { we have } 11... Qb6 12. dxc5 Qxb2 13. Nd2 $146 Qxc3 { and Black is winning. } ) ( 11. Rd1 { is a possible choice for White, and Black can get an advantage after } 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Qb6 13. Qd3 c5 { And if White tries } 14. Be3 $2 cxd4 15. Bxd4 Nxd4 $146 16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. Rxd4 Bc5 { Black ends up with a strategically winning endgame. } ) 11... g5 $15 { [%cal Bg5g4,Ba7a5]We charge forward as usual! ...g4 is a thematic threat which should not be ignored. Here is a possible continuation: } 12. Nd2 $146 g4 13. Rd1 c4 14. Qe2 Qh4 { White better be a good defender. } * 

