, ...Be6 does not work. Instead, because White has not advanced their d-pawn, Black has } 6... Nh6 $146 7. d3 Nf7 $146 { , a maneuver favored by the great Philippe Du Chattel! As is typical, White might try } 8. f4 { , but with ...Nf7 on the board, surging forth in the center with } 8... e5 { becomes viable. These atypical positions are unclear, but Black is doing fine. } ) ( 6. d3 e5 7. O-O { transposes to the line discussed here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 6... cxd5 7. d4 { White makes his claim on the center! This will be to the advantage of Black, but we should nonetheless proceed with care. } 7... cxd4 8. Qxd4 ( 8. Nxd4 $146 { allows } 8... e5 { , where Black ends up with an uncontested center. The bishops will soon begin to terrorize White from the queenside. Qxd4 is therefore White's only choice. } ) 8... e6 { [%cal Be6d5][%csl Rd5][%cal Bf8d6,Bg8e7]As much as I would like to play ...e5, defending d5 is essential here. If you don't mind going into an endgame here, } ( 8... Bb7 { is worth considering too. } 9. Qa4+ Qd7 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 { Black has good chances here. } ) 9. O-O { White might instead opt to castle to the queenside with } ( 9. Bf4 Ne7 $146 10. O-O-O $2 { and control the central files with an incoming Rhe1. In this case, Stockfish favors manually castling with } 10... Kf7 { with plans for Ng6 andQb6. White doesn't have a clear way of breaking through and Black will have excellent play on the queenside with a moderate advantage. } ) 9... Bd6 $17 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be8g8,Bh8f8,Be7g6][%csl Yd6,Yc8]Black will play ...Ne7 and castle, with a formidable center and the bishop pair. } * 

