ore dangerous renditions of this idea in other similar positions (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). In this case, ...Be6 does not work. Instead, because White has not advanced their d-pawn, Black has } 6... Nh6 $146 7. d3 Nf7 $146 { , a maneuver favored by the great Philippe Du Chattel! As is typical, White might try } 8. f4 { , but with ...Nf7 on the board, surging forth in the center with } 8... e5 { becomes viable. These atypical positions are unclear, but Black is doing fine. } ) 6... dxe4 ( 6... cxd4 { should be avoided. } 7. Nxd4 $146 dxe4 { allows White to play } 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qc5 { . It would be preferable to avoid this if possible, which can be done by playing dxe4 first. } ) 7. Nxe4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 { Or if } ( 8. Nxd4 $146 { will arrive at a similar endgame after } 8... e5 9. Nb3 $146 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 $10 ) ( 8. O-O { Black should prompt White to capture d4 to get to similar positions. } 8... Qd5 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Nxd4 $146 e5 11. Nb3 $146 Bf5 { etc. } ) 8... Qxd4 9. Nxd4 e5 { [%csl Yf8,Yc8][%cal Ba7a5,Bh7h5]With this we remove the knight from the center and free our bishops. Note that c6 is not hanging. } 10. Nb3 ( 10. Nxc6 $2 $146 { loses a piece to } 10... Bb7 { . } ) 10... Bf5 $13 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bg7g5,Bh7h5,Ba7a5,Be7f5]This endgame could go either way. } * 

