k. Instead, because White has not advanced their d-pawn, Black has } 6... Nh6 $146 7. d3 Nf7 $146 { , a maneuver favored by the great Philippe Du Chattel! As is typical, White might try } 8. f4 { , but with ...Nf7 on the board, surging forth in the center with } 8... e5 { becomes viable. These atypical positions are unclear, but Black is doing fine. } ) 6... Qc7 { If White overextends in this way, they will face difficulty resisting the capitulation of their center. Next we will continue to build pressure on the loose e5 with ...Bg5. This will be played almost without exception. } 7. O-O { d3 instead will not change our reply. } 7... Bg4 { [%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3,Re5]Pinning the knight destabilizes the center makes the position moderately difficult for White. } 8. h3 Bxf3 { We shouldn't exchange unless provoked by h3. Instead, if White intends on continuing development with 8... Bg4 8.d3 we support our center with 8...e6 and will soon capture on e5 or play ...f5 if White defends with Bf4. } 9. Qxf3 Qxe5 $15 { [%cal Be7e6,Bf8d6,Bg8e7]Black is up a pawn but behind on development. The following is one of many possible ways the game might continue. } 10. d3 Qc7 { [%cal Be7e5,Bf8d6,Bg8e7,Be8g8,Bh8f8]Going for a similar structure to what we've previously opted for looks sensible enough. Stockfish thinks } ( 10... e6 { is a bit better, but things get dicey after } 11. Bf4 Qf5 12. g4 Qg6 13. Rae1 { White has a number of pressing sacrificial opportunities in the center, some of which might involve forcing Black's king out into an exposed center. } ) 11. Bd2 e5 { [%cal Bf8d6,Bg8e7,Be7g6,Be8h8,Bh8f8,Re8f7]Now that we have successfully confiscated the center with ...e5, we can resume development and try to secure our king. In some positions Black will not have the time to safely castle. If White tries to open up the center our king can simply advance to f7 where he will safely remain until development has been completed. } 12. Rae1 { [%cal Be1e8,Bf3g3,Rf2f4]White aims to blast open the center. } 12... Bd6 13. Qg3 Kf7 ( 13... Ne7 $2 $146 { Allows our kingside to crumble. } 14. Qxg7 { Apparently Black is still doing ok after } 14... O-O-O 15. Qxf6 Kb7 { etc. There might be some merit to this line, but Black is just better after ...Kf7. } ) 14. f4 Re8 $15 { [%csl Rf4][%cal Be5f4,Bg7g6,Bh7h5,Yg8h6,Yh6f5,Gg8e7,Ge7g6]While White's initiative does look a bit intimidating, Black's defenses are rock solid. For instance: } 15. fxe5 $2 { would not help White break through. } 15... Bxe5 16. Qf3 Ne7 $146 { Black will play ...Rhf8 and finish manually castling. Black is also up a pawn if that counts for anything. } * 

