orse position. We already know what to do if White neglects to play e5. Here too this is the critical move, but suppose instead White opts for } ( 6. Nh4 $146 { , intending to possibly invade with Qh5+ or f4. We have discussed the more dangerous renditions of this idea in other similar positions (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). In this case, ...Be6 does not work. Instead, because White has not advanced their d-pawn, Black has } 6... Nh6 $146 7. d3 Nf7 $146 { As is typical, White might try } 8. f4 { , but with ...Nf7 on the board, surging forth in the center with the typical } 8... e5 { affords Black typical unclear complications with a slightly better position. } ) ( 6. Nc3 $146 { or really anything excepting the formerly mentioned 6.Nh4. } 6... e5 { is our move, as we should know by now. The position will evolve in a similar direction to those lines outlined in the previous chapter, e.g. } 7. d3 Ne7 $146 8. O-O Ng6 $146 9. b3 Be7 { etc. with an advantage to Black. Placing the queen on e2 doesn't make a lot of sense in those variations and the same theme applies here. } ) 6... Bg4 $1 { [%cal Bg4e2][%csl Rf3,Re5][%cal Bf6e5]While occupying the center with e5 prevents Black from doing so himself, now Black has a clear target. It's worth noting that Black could also try } ( 6... g5 $2 { to attempt to transpose to a continuation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) analyzed in the previous chapter. For instance, after } 7. h3 g4 8. hxg4 Bxg4 9. d3 h5 { the positions converge. However, the transposition is not forced and Black must be comfortable with sacrificing a pawn. 7... g5 7.exf6 Nxf6 8.Nxg5! Qd6 9.O-O Bg7= Black does have compensation. In any case, 6...Bg4 might be trickier than 6...g5, so I'll be offering it as my primary recommendation. Feel free to experiment to see what works for you. } ) 7. h3 { A natural response. One also might encounter the frequent mistake } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 fxe5 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qxe5 Nf6 { [%cal Bf8g7,Bd8d6,Be8g8,Bh8f8]Now that the excitement has died down, we will finish development with ...Bg7 and ...O-O, with sufficient play for our dubious choice of opening. } 11. O-O Bg7 12. Re1 O-O { Setting a trap. } 13. Qe6+ ( 13. Qxe7 $2 { is a losing move! We respond with } 13... Qb6 $3 { threatening ...Rae8. } 14. Qd6 { Doesn't thwart our pursuit of the king! } 14... Rae8 15. Rxe8 Rxe8 { This position is tactic city. } 16. Nc3 $2 $146 Re1+ 17. Kh2 Ng4+ $146 18. hxg4 Be5+ { and White has permission to resign. } ) 13... Rf7 14. Qxc6 { White should be cautious not to be too greedy. Wasting too much time enables Black to develop an attack on the vulnerable f2 square. } 14... Ne4 $15 { [%cal Be4f2,Bg7d4,Ba8c8,Bf7f2]Black has extreme kingside pressures. White best not be tempted by White should instead play } 15. Rf1 $2 { as } ( 15. Nc3 $146 { which is arguably the only surviving move. } 15... Bd4 16. Nxe4 $146 dxe4 17. Rf1 Qf8 18. Qe6 Kg7 { Rxf2 is a lethal threat. White can survive, but must play very precisely. Perhaps a bit too much to ask from a human under time pressure. } 19. Qxe4 { Only move. Stockfish thinks White can survive by sacrificing the queen for the bishop after } 19... Rxf2 20. Qxd4+ cxd4 21. Rxf2 Qc8 { where Black is slightly better. } ) 15... Rf6 { crushes White. ...Bd4! is also winning, but not as straightforward. } 16. Qb5 Nxf2 $146 17. Rxf2 Rxf2 18. Kxf2 Qd6 { White will die on the dark squares. } 19. d4 Rf8+ 20. Ke2 Qe6+ { And that's game. } * 

