1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Bxc6+ { In the Rossolimo it is customary to often exchange on c6, where the desecration of Black's pawn structure putatively affords White favorable long- term positional prospects. Many perceptive Rossolimo players will find that the esoteric inclusion of ...d5 changes little with respect to the positional prospects of this theme, and consequently proceed to play in spirit of a standard Rossolimo game. } 4... bxc6 5. O-O { A rare but possible choice for the determined gambiteer. } 5... dxe4 6. Ng5 { [%cal Bg5e4]Maybe this was the point of 5.O-O. Our structure is pulled apart and White can target and possibly recapture our overextended e-pawn. } 6... e5 $1 { [%cal Bf7f5,Bf8d6,Bg8f6][%csl Be5,Bf5]Defending e4 is far too laborious and complicated to be worth it. In most variations Black will be forced to give the pawn back in one way or another anyway, which is why I think it would be a strategic improvement to simply take the center. White has no better choice than to play into this. } 7. Nxe4 f5 { [%cal Bf7f5][%csl Rf4,Rd4,Re4,Rd5]Like in many other variations, the center is ours! } 8. Ng3 Nf6 9. d3 Bd6 { [%cal Bc5c4][%csl Rc4][%cal Be8g8,Bg8f8,Rb1d2,Rd2c4]We simply develop, supporting the center and preparing O-O. Black will have an ideal position if he is permitted to castle and play c4!. } 10. Nd2 { [%cal Bd2c4,Bc5c4][%csl Rc4]The accurate way to maneuver the knight. Nc3 would be a terrible move. The knight would be totally restricted by Black's oppressive pawns. } 10... O-O 11. Nc4 Bc7 $15 { [%cal Bd8d4,Bf6d5,Bc8e6,Rf5f4][%csl Rf4][%cal Ba8b8,Ba7a5]We should play this move at some point even if unprovoked by Nc4. Our queen would then have direct access to the center, should we like to bring her there. Black will finish development and aim for f4!. A sample continuation could be: } 12. Re1 f4 13. Nf1 $146 Qd4 { Threatening ...e4 and ...Bg4. Danger levels are high. } 14. Nfd2 $146 Bg4 15. Nf3 $146 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 e4 17. Qh3 { Instead if 17.Qd1??, ...Rae8 would be crushing for Black. } 17... h5 $2 { Black threatens to win with ...Ng4, and after the natural } 18. Qe6+ Rf7 19. Qxc6 Ng4 $146 { , the tempting } 20. Qxa8+ $2 Rf8 { is entirely lost for White. } * 

