1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Nxc5 $2 e5 { Boom! Black strikes in the center once again! 7.Nxc5?, the most common move, is already a remarkable strategic mistake by my lights. In these positions the c5 pawn is a long-term weakness which White would be wise to target later in the game once their development has been completed and their activity optimized. Instead, the immediate capture simply gifts to Black a potent initiative after the sharp ...e5!, attacking the knight on c5 and preparing to misplace the kingside knight next with ...e4!. } 8. d4 $5 exd4 { [%cal Bc5d3]Returning the pawn with d4 is an interesting idea. After Black takes on d4, White will liberate the knight from the perils involved in remaining in Black's territory and the position will quiet down. } 9. Nd3 ( 9. Nb3 $2 $146 { is not what White wants, as after } 9... Qe7+ 10. Qe2 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2 Ba6+ 12. Kd1 O-O-O { Black is in the drivers seat and has immediate threats of ...Ng4 or ...Ne5, where defending f2 is not easy with our sniper bishop posted on a6. } ) 9... Be7 10. O-O O-O $13 { [%cal Bc6c5,Ba8b8,Gd8c7,Ba7a5,Yc8b7,Ge7d6,Rb8h2,Rb7h1]This position is more than fine for Black. We have the bishops, a space advantage, and aren't even down material. We can proceed with ...c5, ...Rb8, and ideally ...Bb7 at some moment. The bishops will be glorious on the long diagonals. } * 

