 are exceptionally sharp and perhaps not as easy to navigate as appearance may suggest. } ) 9... c5 $1 { [%cal Bc6c5,Bc5c4]} 10. Ne2 { Of course, Same story with } ( 10. Nc6 $2 $146 Qd5 11. Nba5 $146 Bd7 { ends the game immediately. } ) ( 10. Nb5 $2 $146 c4 11. N3d4 $146 a6 12. Nc6 $146 Qb6 13. Nbd4 $146 Bb7 { White's dancing horses are done for. } ) 10... c4 $1 { Black continues to punish White for poor piece placement. We have done nothing but shove around White's knights for the last four moves! } 11. Nbd4 Bc5 { [%cal Bc2c3][%csl Rd3,Re2]Forcing White to compromise their central light squares. } 12. c3 { If the knight continues to dance } ( 12. Nb5 $2 $146 { , Black swiftly ends the game with } 12... Ng4 $146 13. O-O Qh4 14. h3 Nxf2 $19 $146 { Of course, 12. Nb5 12...Qb6 also crushes White, hitting f2 and the knight simultaneously. } ) 12... O-O $19 { [%cal Rf6g4,Yf6d7,Rg4e5,Re5d3][%csl Rd3][%cal Yd7e5,Yh2h3]With White's queen free to access the queenside, Black should castle right away to avoid any Qa4+ tricks. Now that the king has been secured, Black's plan is simple. Get the knight to e5 to exploit the horrendously weak light squares. Defending looks utterly hopeless. Of course, White might try to undermine Black's control of the light squares with White might anticipate ...Ng4 with } 13. b3 $2 { , but Black can simply proceed with the plan without paying much mind to White's futile attempts to extricate themselves from this positional bind. } ( 13. h3 { , but this doesn't stop the knight from getting to e5 } 13... Nd7 $146 14. O-O Ne5 $146 { The knight is headed to d3 next. White's position is horrendous. } ) 13... Ng4 $146 14. bxc4 $2 Qh4 15. Ng3 $146 { 16...Nf3+! Check out the tactics (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) chapter to see how Black can convert this. } 15... Ne5 $146 { 16.Qe1 , Black has the incredible } 16. O-O Bg4 { White is getting crushed. If White tries } * 

