1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Nxc5 $2 e5 { Boom! Black strikes in the center once again! 7.Nxc5?, the most common move, is already a remarkable strategic mistake by my lights. In these positions the c5 pawn is a long-term weakness which White would be wise to target later in the game once their development has been completed and their activity optimized. Instead, the immediate capture simply gifts to Black a potent initiative after the sharp ...e5!, attacking the knight on c5 and preparing to misplace the kingside knight next with ...e4!. } 8. Nb3 e4 { Now White only has two acceptable moves. The awkward looking } 9. Qe2 { A sensible idea. White develops the queen and temporary halts our attack. } ( 9. Ne5 $2 $146 { and the professional 9... e4 9.Qe2! As such, is quite easy for White to err in this position. For instance, the most popular move here: 9... e4 9.Nfd4?? just outright loses. I would recommend that the reader pay close attention to the upcoming continuations. These positions are exceptionally sharp and perhaps not as easy to navigate as appearance may suggest. } ) 9... Be7 10. Nfd4 $2 Qb6 { [%cal Be8g8]Nfd4 already almost amounts to a fatal blunder. Black threatens to trap the knight with ...O-O and ...c5! There are ways for White to save the piece, but not without handing over a significant initiative to Black. These possibilities will be analyzed shortly. } 11. Qc4 { [%cal Bc4c6]White detects their mistake and aims to simplify the position by inducing a queen trade. Such won't change the evaluation, ultimately. One tricky idea that Black might benefit from being aware of is that of: } ( 11. O-O $2 { White might allow the knight to get trapped! } 11... O-O 12. d3 c5 13. Nf3 $2 $146 { The point being that the bishop on e7 drops if Black takes f3. Fortunately, this doesn't quite work out in White's favor. } 13... exf3 14. Qxe7 Re8 15. Qxc5 fxg2 16. Rd1 Bg4 { White will be forced to give up the exchange. } ) 11... c5 12. Qb5+ { Both } ( 12. Nb5 $146 { and 12... c5 12.Ne2 accomplish nothing. 12...O-O 13.d4 exd3 14.Qxd3 Rd8 In both cases Black's development is simply overwhelming. } ) 12... Bd7 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Ne2 Nd5 { [%cal Bd5b4,Bb4c2][%csl Rc2]The knight is headed to b4, if allowed. } 15. a3 f5 $17 { [%csl Rh1,Rc1,Ra1][%cal Be8c8,Ba8d8,Yd7b5,Yd7e6,Ye7f6,Yh8e8]Black is just much better. We have the bishops, a significant space advantage, superior activity, and better control of the center. We can continue with queenside castling, repositioning our bishops to better squares, and centralizing our rooks. This looks promising for Black. } * 

