. These positions are exceptionally sharp and perhaps not as easy to navigate as appearance may suggest. } ) 9... Be7 10. Ng5 { [%cal Bg5e4]White targets e4. } 10... Qd5 { [%cal Bd5g5][%csl Rg5]Covering e4 and forcing White to decide what to do with the knight. } 11. d3 { [%cal Bc1g5]} 11... exd3 { Other moves can be met with ...O-O and ...h6. For example, 11... Qd5 11.d4 O-O 12.O-O h6 Interestingly, White can actually sacrifice the knight! 13.Nxe4!? Qxe4 14.Qxe4 Nxe4 15.Re1 f5 16.f3 Here Black has the convenient resource 16...Bh4! 17.g3 Nxg3 18.hxg3 Bxg3 Material balance has been restored, but Black is better anyway. We have the bishops in an open position, an h-pawn with no opposition, and an army which is easy to mobilize. } 12. Qxd3 Qxg2 13. Qf3 Bh3 $1 { Keeping the pace! Black now threatens ...Qxf3 followed by ...Bg2. } 14. Qxg2 Bxg2 15. Rg1 Bd5 $17 { [%cal Bh7h6,Bg7g5,Be8c8,Ra8d8,Rh8e8,Re8e1,Rd8d1]Black is a little bit better here. Our plan is to repel the knight, castle, and dominate the open central files. A game might continue with } 16. Be3 h6 17. Nh3 $146 g5 { Restricting the knight. } 18. f4 O-O-O 19. fxg5 { Black can ignore the kingside for now. The action is in the center! } 19... Bb4+ $2 20. c3 Rhe8 { Black has a pleasant initiative. White's only move to save the game is: } 21. O-O-O Rxe3 22. cxb4 Nh5 $146 23. Nf2 $146 Rf3 { This position has a lot of moving parts, but Black is clearly the one in the driver's seat. } * 

