. These positions are exceptionally sharp and perhaps not as easy to navigate as appearance may suggest. } ) 9... Be7 10. Ne5 Qd5 { [%cal Ba7a5,Bc8a6,Ba6f1,Be4f3,Be4d3][%csl Rb3,Re2][%cal Ba5a4]Ne5 is White's best move. Black should just keep up the pressure and continue forcing White to make decisions. Note that White's light squares are often where the weaknesses are in these lines. With the queen on d5 White needs to be careful about breaking in the center with the d-pawn. g2 might drop if the center opens up. It's worth mentioning that we should consider playing ...a5 \+ ...Ba6 at the right moment. The queen on e2 is a target and it's not a trivial matter for White to challenge Black's control of the light squares without the aid of the corresponding bishop. } 11. Nc4 O-O 12. Ne3 { Keep in mind that White should be careful about leaving the c4 square clogged up for too long. ...Bg4! would be extremely strong if White's queen doesn't have access to c4 and if the king steps away from e1. Suppose White castles instead of Ne3 here: } ( 12. O-O $2 Bg4 { The queen can't run to c4, so } 13. f3 { is forced. } 13... exf3 14. Qxe7 Rfe8 { This looks incredibly dangerous for White. } ) 12... Qd7 { [%cal Ba7a5,Bc8a6,Bd7d1]Blocking the bishop from accessing the kingside isn't problematic. ...a5 and ...Ba6 is what we were looking to play anyways. The queen on d7 is keeping her eye on the d-pawn for any central breaks. } 13. d4 { It probably would be wise for White to do this now. After } ( 13. O-O $2 a5 { the threat of both ...Ba6 and ...a4 look quite challenging to meet. White's queenside knight needs some space for mobility. } 14. d3 Ba6 15. Nc4 $146 exd3 $2 { White already is on thin ice. } 16. Qxd3 $2 { loses! } 16... Qe6 17. Nbd2 $146 Rad8 $19 ) 13... a5 { [%cal Ba5a4,Bd7d4][%csl Rd4][%cal Bc8a6]} 14. Qc4 { ...a4 followed by ...Qxd4 was our threat, so this makes sense. Instead, } ( 14. a4 $2 { would be way too slow. } 14... Ba6 15. c4 Nd5 $146 16. O-O f5 { White would be wise to avoid these complications. } ) 14... Rd8 $13 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Ba5a4,Bc8a6]Black has a great position here. We have pressure on d4, threats of ...a4 and ...Ba6 loom in the air, and White's king is still in the center. Here are a couple of possible continuations: White is probably best off simplifying the position by returning the pawn. } 15. a4 $2 { still doesn't quite work. } ( 15. Nc5 $146 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 Rxd4 17. Nb3 $146 Rd8 { Material balance has been restored. Black is marginally better due to slightly better activity and the bishops, however White's structure is a superior to ours. } ) 15... Bb4+ 16. Bd2 Ba6 17. Nc5 $146 { is the only way to stay in the game. } 17... Qa7 18. Qxa6 Bxd2+ 19. Kxd2 Qxc5 { Black clearly has the upper hand. If instead White tries 16... Bb4+ 16.c3?! the situation worsens rather than improves. 16...Ba6! 17.Nc5 Bxc5 18.Qxc5 Bd3! This looks rather unfortunate for White. } * 

