er extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Nxc5 $2 e5 { Boom! Black strikes in the center once again! 7.Nxc5?, the most common move, is already a remarkable strategic mistake by my lights. In these positions the c5 pawn is a long-term weakness which White would be wise to target later in the game once their development has been completed and their activity optimized. Instead, the immediate capture simply gifts to Black a potent initiative after the sharp ...e5!, attacking the knight on c5 and preparing to misplace the kingside knight next with ...e4!. } 8. Nb3 e4 { Now White only has two acceptable moves. The awkward looking } 9. Qe2 { A sensible idea. White develops the queen and temporary halts our attack. } ( 9. Ne5 $2 $146 { and the professional 9... e4 9.Qe2! As such, is quite easy for White to err in this position. For instance, the most popular move here: 9... e4 9.Nfd4?? just outright loses. I would recommend that the reader pay close attention to the upcoming continuations. These positions are exceptionally sharp and perhaps not as easy to navigate as appearance may suggest. } ) 9... Be7 10. Ne5 Qd5 { Ne5 is White's best move. Black should just keep up the pressure and continue forcing White to make decisions. Note that White's light squares are often where the weaknesses are in these lines. With the queen on d5 White needs to be careful about breaking in the center with the d-pawn. g2 might drop if the center opens up. It's worth mentioning that we should consider playing ...a5 \+ ...Ba6 at the right moment. The queen on e2 is a target and it's not a trivial matter to challenge Black's control of the light squares without the aid of the corresponding bishop. } 11. Qc4 c5 $1 { Once again, Black ends up with a space advantage and the bishops. Our pieces look easier to mobilize as well. Let's suppose White simplifies by exchanging queens here: If you would like to instead play something wild, apparently Black could also sacrifice the exchange with } ( 11... Qxe5 $2 12. Qxc6+ Nd7 $146 13. Qxa8 O-O 14. Qxa7 Qg5 { These positions look quite interesting! I initially considered this as my primary recommendation, but I realized that adequate coverage of all the relevant permutations might increase the size of this chapter by 50%. Though tempting, my commitment to keep this course relatively compact compelled me to offer the tame 11...c5 instead. In most lines Black will be forced to find a repetition in the mess anyway. } ) 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 $146 { With the knight on d5 White needs to worry about ...Nb4, but if they respond with } 13. a3 { , Black has } 13... Ba6 $2 { White will eventually need to open up the position with d3 or d4. Black has good long term prospects here due to the potential of the bishops. } * 

