1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 { [%cal Bh8g8,Bg8g2,Be7e5,Yc8g4,Bd8d5]For those more positionally minded, } ( 7... exf6 { is playable as well. I prefer ...gxf6 here because it enables Black to easily generate a kingside initiative. With the g-file semi-open, Black already has a target. } ) 8. O-O Rg8 9. d3 { [%cal Bd8d5,Bc8g4,Bc8h3,Ye7e5,Ba8d8]While White has a number of viable moves here, Black's development blueprint (...Bg4 or ...Bh3, ...Qd5, ..Rd8 or ...O-O-O, ...e5!? etc.) is pretty much uniformly applicable to each deviation. Being familiar with the basic ideas should be sufficient for adequate treatment of similar positions. } 9... Bg4 { [%cal Bd8d5]This is a particularly annoying move. Once the bishop lands on g4 it's not so easy for White to remove it. Next we can simply continue to build pressure on f3 and mobilize our forces toward the kingside. } ( 9... Bh3 $2 { is a possibility too, but after } 10. Ne1 $146 Qd5 11. f3 { White is solid. However, in circumstances where White is unable to avail themselves of this Ne1 maneuver ...Bh3 is stronger than ...Bg4. For instance, suppose White starts with 9... Rg8 9.Re1 instead of d3. Now, after 9...Bh3! White is just totally beleaguered. g3 is pretty much forced, either now or after 10.Nh4 Qd5! 11.g3 , where Black has at least a small advantage due to the state of White's light squares. } ) 10. Kh1 { Stepping the king off of the file. } 10... Qd5 { [%cal Bc5c4,Bd5h5,Bd5h1,Bh5d1][%csl Rf3,Rh1,Rd1]This is usually the best spot for the queen. Defending the light squares without the corresponding bishop will be a challenge for White. ...c4!? might be strong at some point too. } 11. h3 $6 Qh5 $1 { The bishop will not be repelled! } 12. Rg1 { The only serious attempt at a defense. White needs to be careful. } ( 12. Kh2 $2 { is arguably a losing mistake. } 12... O-O-O 13. Qe2 { White's best try would be to break the pin. } 13... e5 14. Qe3 Kb7 15. Ng1 $146 f5 16. Qe1 f4 { Black's advantage is decisive. } ) 12... c4 $1 { This move not only improves our structural situation but also sets a trap. But let's suppose White manages to spot this elementary tactic and resolves not to fall for it: } 13. dxc4 $2 { immediately loses. } ( 13. Qe2 cxd3 { Now } 14. cxd3 { is forced. If the queen were to capture the previous tactic would work all the same. Black can continue with } 14... Rd8 { , the threat being ...Rd4, which would most likely end the game if permitted. White's best defense is } 15. Qe4 { , attacking c6, where Black should simplify the position. } 15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. gxf3 Rxg1+ 18. Kxg1 Rxd3 { Black has the advantage in the endgame. } ) 13... Rd8 14. Qe2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. gxf3 Rxg1+ 17. Kxg1 Rd1+ 18. Kg2 Bh6 { White loses significant material and consequently has permission to resign. } * 

