g4. If you prefer to keep the queens on the board, } ( 9... e5 $2 { is a noteworthy alternative. } 10. Qe2 Be6 { ...c4 is coming. Even if White tries } 11. b3 { Black can still offer the pawn! } 11... c4 { This is a very interesting position. Black's activity will compensate for the pawn. } ) 10. dxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Bg4 { [%cal Bg4d1][%csl Bf3]The point. White is forced the move the king once again. } 12. Ke2 e5 13. h3 Bf5 $10 { [%cal Be8c8,Ba8d8,Bd8d1,Bg8g1,Bf8b4][%csl Gf5,Gf8,Gg8]We have the bishop pair in an open position. This is roughly equal. White is up a pawn, but won't be for long. If Moving the king onto the d-file to preserve the c2 pawn is strategically unwise and won't even allow White to retain the material. Finally, if } 14. Ne1 $146 { then h3 drops } ( 14. Kd1 $2 O-O-O+ 15. Bd2 Bc5 { At least one of the pawns will be captured. } ) ( 14. Kd2 $2 { won't serve to preserve the material advantage either. } 14... Bb4+ 15. c3 O-O-O+ { Now the king has to return to the e-file anyway. So much wasted time. } 16. Ke1 Be7 17. Be3 Be4 18. Ke2 Bd3+ { Now c4 falls. } ) ( 14. c3 $2 { Black has } 14... O-O-O { and ...Bd3+ is threatened. } ) 14... Bxh3 * 

