er extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Ng3 h5 { Naturally, I'm recommending that we pursue the most aggressive continuation. ...h5 is clearly suited for the task. Black will try to establish that the knight is misplaced on g3 and may even initiate a diabolical pawnstorm if White decides to castle. } 8. h4 Bg4 { [%cal Bf6d5]With h4 Harry's aggressive advance has been obstructed, however now Black has the g4 outpost. This pin won't be easy for White to undo. Black should consider ...Nd5 at some moment. One of the only ways White can attempt to break the pin without suffering the fragmentation of their kingside structure is to try for Qe2 and Qe3 /Qe4, followed by moving the knight. ...Nd5 would rule out Qe3 and Qe4 would allow ...Nb4. } 9. d3 e6 10. Bg5 { Like I was mentioning before, if White tries to break the pin first starting with } ( 10. Qe2 { , Black has } 10... Nd5 $146 11. Qe4 Nb4 $146 { This looks like it would be a little annoying to encounter. } ) 10... Qc7 { True, White can use the g5 outpost, but we have no issue simply stepping out of the pin to revitalize our ...Nd5 idea. Black shouldn't be worried about the potential exchange on f6 either. } 11. O-O ( 11. Bxf6 $2 gxf6 { Black has excellent play in these positions. We can play ...Rb8, ...f5, ...Bg7 or ...Bh6, etc. All of our pieces will be quite active, especially the dark-squared bishop. } ) 11... Nd5 12. Re1 Bd6 $10 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bf7f6,Be6e5,Ya8b8,Bb8e8,Ya8e8,Rg3e4,Re4d6]Black is fine here. All that's left to do is castle and finish centralizing. White most likely would continue with } 13. Ne4 $146 O-O 14. Nxd6 $146 Qxd6 15. Qe2 { This position is rich with interesting ideas. As mentioned before, } 15... Nb4 $2 $146 { is a decent idea in these positions. If White tries to kick the knight with } 16. a3 { Black has a key intermezzo: } 16... Bxf3 17. gxf3 Nd5 $146 { This looks equal, yet imbalanced. Also worth mentioning: Our signature 15. Qe2 15...f6!? \+ ...e5 sequence makes some sense, especially considering that we've traded our dark-squared bishop. 16.Bd2 e5 17.Qe4 Rae8 18.Nh2 White has managed to break the pin, but now Black has: 18...f5! 19.Qc4 f4 This position is a total mess. } * 

