er extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Ng3 h5 { Naturally, I'm recommending that we pursue the most aggressive continuation. ...h5 is clearly suited for the task. Black will try to establish that the knight is misplaced on g3 and may even initiate a diabolical pawnstorm if White decides to castle. } 8. h3 h4 { [%cal Bg7g5,Bg5g4][%csl Rg4]Stockfish judges h3 to be the best move, but now Black has a hook. In such structures I always look for an opportunity to play ...g5-g4. } 9. Ne2 ( 9. Nf1 $146 { is playable too and may be more sensible than 9.Ne2, the idea being to bring the knight to the c4 outpost. Generally, in these positions if White delays castling Black should play } 9... Nd5 $146 10. d3 { to allow } 10... f6 { Next we have ...e5 and ...Be6. While the engine sees equality on the horizon, these complications are extremely bizarre. I'm not entirely sure how to evaluate them. } ) 9... Nd5 { A useful waiting move. We would like to see White castle, at which point we surge forth with ...g5! } 10. O-O g5 $1 { This puts White in a tough spot. If White elects not to capture g5 they will need to worry about ...g4, however capturing g5 enables our rook to exert great pressures on White's kingside with ...Rg8. Pick your poison. } 11. Nxg5 Rg8 { [%cal Bg8g1,Bc8h3][%csl Rh3,Rg5]Pinning the knight down. h3 will fall if the knight retreats. } 12. d4 { Defending the knight. Another interesting attempt is Same story with } ( 12. f4 $2 { , but after } 12... f6 { the knight will have to retreat, leaving h3 up for grabs. } ) ( 12. d3 $2 f6 { Funnily enough, White can actually just sacrifice the g5 knight. } 13. Nc3 $146 Nxc3 $146 14. Qh5+ Kd7 15. bxc3 fxg5 16. Bxg5 Qe8 17. Qxh4 Qg6 { This position is a total mess. White has three pawns for the piece, but Black will probably be the one playing for a win here. Black's king will be safe on c7. } ) 12... e5 { [%cal Bg8g5,Bd8g5]Adding another attacker to g5. After d4 } ( 12... f6 $2 { doesn't work. } 13. c4 fxg5 { Taking g5 is the best move. Even so, after } 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. Nc3 $146 { White is just much better. If we try to save our knight either White gets a crushing attack or a decisive initiative: 13. c4 13...Nb6?? 14.Ng3!! Absolutely disgusting. The queen will be invading. 14...fxg5 15.Qh5+ Kd7 16.dxc5+- If 13. c4 13...Nb4?! 14.a3! Na6 15.Nc3! Bf5 16.Qh5+ Bg6 17.Qe2 fxg5 18.Qe6 Rg7 Black's position is crumbling. Our coordination is terrible and our defenses are extremely lacking. 19.Qxc6+ Kf7 20.dxc5! An exhaustive explanation of precisely how Black is lost here is probably not worth getting into. Just remember to avoid ...f6 after d4. } ) 13. dxe5 { This position is extremely messy. Another ridiculous computer continuation is } ( 13. f4 $2 exf4 14. Nxf7 $146 Qe7 $3 { Nobody has a clue what's happening here. } 15. Ne5 $146 cxd4 16. Nd3 $146 Ne3 $146 { This is total chaos. } ) 13... Rxg5 14. Bxg5 Qxg5 $17 { [%cal Bc8h3,Ba8d8]Black is a bit better here due to the pressure on the kingside. We also have two minor pieces for the rook. A game might continue with } 15. Qd3 { , covering h3. } 15... Bf5 16. Qb3 Be4 17. f3 Bxc2 { White is in trouble. If } ( 17... Ne3 $146 { Instead, 18... Ne3 17.Qb7 leads to more crazy complications. 17...Rd8 18.Qxc6+ Rd7 19.Nc3 Nf4!? White has put up a fight, but Black should have a significant lead here. } ) 18. Qxc2 $2 { the queen is lost after } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.Bxc6+ with 7.Ng3 #3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.Bxc6+ with 7.Ng3 #3"]
[Black "6) The Engine's Choice | 4.Nc3 with 5.Bxc6+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Ng3 h5 { Naturally, I'm recommending that we pursue the most aggressive continuation. ...h5 is clearly suited for the task. Black will try to establish that the knight is misplaced on g3 and may even initiate a diabolical pawnstorm if White decides to castle. } 8. h3 h4 { Stockfish judges h3 to be the best move, but now Black has a hook. In such structures I always look for an opportunity to play ...g5-g4. } 9. Ne2 ( 9. Nf1 $146 { is playable too and may be more sensible than 9.Ne2, the idea being to bring the knight to the c4 outpost. Generally, in these positions if White delays castling Black should play } 9... Nd5 $146 10. d3 { to allow } 10... f6 { Next we have ...e5 and ...Be6. While the engine sees equality on the horizon, these complications are extremely bizarre. I'm not entirely sure how to evaluate them. } ) 9... Nd5 { A useful waiting move. We would like to see White castle, at which point we surge forth with ...g5! } 10. O-O g5 { This puts White in a tough spot. If White elects not to capture g5 they will need to worry about ...g4, however capturing g5 enables our rook to exert great pressures on White's kingside with ...Rg8. Pick your poison. } 11. d4 { White rejects the pawn, thereby allowing ...g4. There are a few other notable ways to reject the pawn. One of which is Another interesting idea would be } ( 11. c4 $2 g4 { This doesn't look particularly compelling for White. } 12. cxd5 gxf3 13. Nf4 $146 Rg8 $2 14. Qxf3 Bh6 { With the semi-open g-file, Black once again has pressure on h3! } 15. Kh2 Qd6 16. d3 cxd5 { Black is in great shape here. } ) ( 11. Nh2 $2 $146 Rg8 12. Nc3 $146 { White is trying to prevent ...g4. If the g-file opens Black gets similar compensation to the Nxg5 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) line. Black should insist on the ...g4 push. } 12... Nf6 $146 13. Ng4 $146 Nxg4 $146 14. hxg4 Qd4 15. Qf3 Rg6 { Covering c6. } 16. Ne4 $146 f5 $2 { Black complicates matters! } 17. gxf5 g4 18. Qf4 Bh6 19. Qc7 Bxf5 { This looks promising for Black. } ) 11... g4 12. hxg4 h3 13. gxh3 { Or, if } ( 13. g3 { Black has } 13... Bxg4 14. Ne5 $146 h2+ 15. Kh1 Bh3 16. Re1 f6 { White is clearly worse here. Moreover, if White slips up } 17. Nxc6 $2 $146 { Black can induce resignation with: } 17... Ne3 $3 $146 18. Nf4 $146 Qd5+ 19. f3 Bg2+ 20. Nxg2 $146 Nxd1 $19 $146 ) 13... Rxh3 14. Kg2 { These positions are totally wild! } ( 14. Ng5 $2 $146 { is another noteworthy idea. } 14... Rh4 15. f3 $2 Qc7 16. Rf2 Ba6 { Black will queenside castle and continue the attack. So many interesting positions come out of this line. } ) 14... Bxg4 15. Ne5 Rh4 $15 { [%cal Be7e6,Bg4d1][%csl Re2][%cal Bd8f6,Bf8d6,Be8c8,Ba8d8,Bg4h3]Black has torn apart White's kingside and drawn the king away from the back rank. This doesn't look pleasant for White. Black's typical ideas to complete development involve moves such as ...e6, ...Qf6, ...Bd6, and ...O-O-O. My expectation is that White will try to simplify matters to secure the safety of their king. For instance, we might encounter something along the lines of: } 16. Rh1 e6 17. Rxh4 Qxh4 18. Qd3 Bf5 19. Qg3 Qe4+ 20. Qf3 { These lines are super sharp. Here Stockfish finds } 20... f6 { and if White tries } 21. Nxc6 $2 $146 { , apparently } 21... Bh3+ 22. Kg3 Qh7 { is winning. } * 

