1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. Qe2 { 7.d3 and 7.Qe2 are the two most challenging moves Black can encounter after 6...Nf6. Fortunately for us, at least according to the non-master lichess database, around 95% of the time Black faces other moves for games taking place in the rating range between 1600-2500. Above 2000 there are zero games with either move. Granted, there is hardly any data to work from here (mere dozens of games) so perhaps nothing substantive can be reasonably inferred. In any case, it is interesting information nonetheless. Qe2 probably is the better of the two moves. White develops a piece and now threatens Nxc5, where Black wouldn't have ...e5 as an viable response. Trying ...e6 to defend c5 would be too slow, therefore Black should eliminate the threat by exchanging the knights } 7... Nxe4 { Stopping Nxc5. } 8. Qxe4 Qd5 { Black offers the trade of queens. Ideally White will trade here and repair our abysmal structure, but we would be delusional to expect White to even be tempted by the trade. } 9. d3 { This is White's best move. If the queen moves away from the e-file Black gets some compensation: Suppose that the queen remains on the e-file: } ( 9. Qa4 Qe6+ { Now the king is forced to move. } 10. Kf1 g6 { Black has the bishops and White's king is misplaced. Both colors' deficiencies cancel each other out. } ) ( 9. Qe2 { Runs straight into } 9... Bg4 $10 { , and 9. Qe2 9.Qe3 allows 9...g5! Black has excellent play here. Hence, d3 is probably White's best chance to play for an advantage. } ) 9... Bf5 { Development with tempo. } 10. Qe2 Bg4 $1 { [%csl Rf3]Qe2 allows us to inflict upon White's structure deficiencies similar to that of our own. To make proper use of our time, we should not exchange on f3 until White has prompted us to do so with h3 or if until the pin is broken by the relocation of White's queen. } 11. h3 Bxf3 { [%cal Be7e6]When prompted by h3 we should damage White's structure. Other moves, such as 11... Bg4 11.b3 allow Black to conjure up some exciting counterplay. 11...h5! 12.Bb2 Rh6! } 12. Qxf3 Qxf3 13. gxf3 e6 $10 { [%csl Rc5,Rc6,Ra7,Re6,Rf7,Rg7,Rh7,Yh3,Yf3,Yf2,Yd3,Yc2,Yb2,Ya2][%cal Be8c8,Ba8d8]The resulting position is equally bad for both players, roughly speaking. White might have a slight edge due to the potential mobility of the bishop and because it is their turn, but this hardly amounts to anything substantive. The superior strategist will probably be the one to emerge victorious. } * 

