so leads to bizarre positions. For instance, } 14. c3 f6 15. Be3 Rg8 { Black's activity is admirable! } ) 13... cxd3 14. Rd1 f6 { [%cal Bh8g8]A key idea, enabling the queen to cover g8. } 15. cxd3 Rg8 $13 { [%cal Be7e5,Ba8d8,Bf5h3]Black has sufficient play here, however it must be said that there are numerous points at which White could reasonably deviate in the last few moves. Exhaustive coverage of these lines seems a little superfluous, especially given that Black's ideas generally remain fixed: Eventually play ...Rg8, expand in the center with ...e5, trade queens at an opportune moment, etc. The general theme is that White tends to be at least slightly better in these lines. } * 

