extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Bxc6+ { Before recapturing on e4 White inflicts a brutal blow to Black's structure. It is reasonable to expect this to happen sooner or later. Unfortunately, there's nothing Black can do to prevent this. } 5... bxc6 6. Nxe4 Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 6... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 7. d3 { 7.d3 and 7.Qe2 are the two most challenging moves Black can encounter after 6...Nf6. Fortunately for us, at least according to the non-master lichess database, around 95% of the time Black faces other moves for games taking place in the rating range between 1600-2500. Above 2000 there are zero games with either move. Granted, there is hardly any data to work from here (mere dozens of games) so perhaps nothing substantive can be reasonably inferred. In any case, it is interesting information nonetheless. } 7... c4 { [%cal Bc4d3][%csl Re4]Black immediately attempts to destabilize the knight. If we can induce an exchange on f6 Black will emerge with an acceptable position. } 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 { We will giving the position the same treatment as this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Our ideas are mostly the same, involving ...Rg8, ...Bg4, ...e5, ...O-O-O, etc. } 9. dxc4 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Rg8 11. Ne1 ( 11. Rg1 { would result 