te is more active and has the superior structure. Also our c6 pawn is a weakness. White's advantage is not decisive, but this is certainly not very comfortable. The following continuation is an example of how a game might proceed. } 12. Nd4 Bg7 13. Be3 { Of course, } ( 13. Nxc6 $146 { allows } 13... Bb7 $10 ) 13... Bb7 { [%cal Bc6c5]Threatening ...c5. } 14. Rac1 O-O { [%cal Bg7b2][%csl Rb2][%cal Bd4c6][%csl Rc6]Black exchanges the c-pawn for White's b-pawn. } 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Rxc6 Bxb2 17. Ra6 Rfd8 18. Rxd8+ { There are some tricks in these positions. For instance, if } ( 18. Rb1 Rac8 19. Rxa7 $2 Bc1 $3 { This is winning. } 20. g4 Rd1+ 21. Kg2 Bxe3 $19 ) 18... Rxd8 19. Kf1 { If instead } ( 19. f3 e5 { Black can apparently give up a7 and still hold. } 20. Rxa7 Bd4 21. Bxd4 exd4 { with ...e3, ...Rc8-Rc2 coming, etc. The rook can eat up the kingside pawns when White's king goes after our d-pawn. We can also get our rook behind White's a-pawn. Black should be fine. Once again, easier said than done. } ) 19... Bd4 { Similar story with } 20. Ke2 ( 20. Bxd4 Rxd4 21. Rxa7 Rxe4 $10 { This should be a draw with accurate play. Of course, that's easier said than done. } ) 20... Bxe3 21. Kxe3 Rd7 $14 { White's king is more active. Still, Black should be able to hold. } * 

