er extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Nxe4 { This chapter will be exploring those variations in which an early Bxc6+ is omitted. } 5... Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 5... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 6. Nxc5 $5 e5 $1 { [%cal Bf8c5,Be7e5,Rf3e5][%csl Re5]White accepts the gambit. With ...e5!, Black offers White another pawn! The more we sacrifice, the sharper the position gets. Of course, White may not be inclined to capture this second pawn given the current threat on the knight. Either way, Black has already complicated matters. Now a dynamic middlegame is ineluctable. } 7. Nxe5 $5 { [%cal Be5c6][%csl Rc6][%cal Bb5e8,Bc6a8][%csl Ra8,Re8]White accepts our second gambit, hoping that the tactics work out in their favor. While it's true that White will inevitably secure a material advantage, it is debatable whether this will sufficiently compensate for the remarkable initiative Black will receive in return. } 7... Bxc5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Qe2+ { An important intermezzo. Click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to find out what happens if White tries Bxa8 instead. } 10... Kf8 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 12. O-O h5 $1 { [%cal Bd7h3,Bh8h6,Rd7c6,Ra8g2]Expanding on the kingside. Our rook needs to get in the game somehow. Black sneakily threatens 13.-- Bh3!! 14.gxh3 Rh6 , with a crushing attack. An alternative worthy of consideration is } ( 12... Bc6 $2 { Black's bishops are magnificent pieces. White is forced to respond with } 13. d4 Bxd4 { 14.fxe3? h5! The rook is coming to h6, then g6. Black's attack regains some force. Even if White manages to defend, Black has the two minor pieces for the rook. } 14. Be3 Bxe3 { White must now recapture with the queen, after which Black has excellent play with ...Bxg2 and ...h5. Instead, if } ) 13. d3 ( 13. d4 $2 { might be slightly more resilient. Black has nothing better than to take and to cooperate in White's attempt at simplification. } 13... Bxd4 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. Qxe3 { Opportunities for aggression still remain, however. } 15... h4 16. h3 Rh6 { The pressure begins to mount. The engine thinks White's best attempt at a defense is to eternally weaken the light squares: } 17. Kh1 Rg6 18. f3 Qb8 { The resulting position is close to equal, but is anything but clear. } ) 13... Bc6 14. Be3 { The only move to prevent Black from taking on g2. White needs to free the f-pawn. } 14... Bd6 15. f3 Qb8 { [%cal Bb8h2][%csl Rh2]White has successfully blunted our battery, but in doing so has weakened the dark squares. With ...Qb8, Black induces further weaknesses on the dark squares. White's defenses are slowly coming apart. } 16. h3 ( 16. h4 { wouldn't be any better. Black still has } 16... Qxb2 { followed by ...Qe5, and of course 16... Qb8 16.g3?? runs into 16...h4! } ) 16... Qxb2 { [%cal Bb8b2,Bb2e5,Bd6h2][%csl Rh2][%cal Yf6d5,Yd5f4]Black reroutes the queen! White's kingside has been tenderized. Black aims to break through on the dark squares. } 17. Rab1 { White could also try } ( 17. Bxa7 { , stopping ...Qe5, but grabbing pawns looks a bit risky. Here Black has } 17... Nd5 $146 { , eyeing the dark squares once again. This also vacates the f6 square, so if White wants to follow up with } 18. Rab1 { the queen can reposition to the kingside. } 18... Qf6 { This line can actually lead to a funny double queen sacrifice: } 19. Qf2 Rh6 20. Qd4 Be5 21. Qxe5 Qxe5 22. Rfe1 Qg3 23. Rb8+ Qxb8 24. Bxb8 Nb4 $146 { Black is winning! } ) 17... Qe5 18. f4 Qf5 $17 { [%cal Be3h6][%csl Rf4][%cal Yh8h6,Gf8g8,Bf6d5,Yh6g6,Gg8h7,Yh8e8,Ye8e2]White has obstructed their bishop's view, allowing our rook to get in the game via h6, then g6. Another interesting way of getting the rook into the game is to enable ...Re8 by marching the king to h7. Either way, Black's position is superb. Our pieces are far more active and White's position is riddled with weaknesses. White's best attempt is probably } 19. c4 { , disallowing Black's knight from accessing the optimal d5 square. } 19... Kg8 { The king is going to h7 and the rook to the center. } 20. d4 Kh7 21. d5 Re8 { If White slips up with dxc6?? Black simply wins after Rxe3!! So instead, } 22. Qf3 Ba4 { The bishop aims for c2 where it has a clear pathway back to the center! White's position looks depressing. There will be no c5 without the d-pawn dropping, and beyond White's passed pawns White's position doesn't have much going for it. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "5.Nxe4 with 6.Nxc5 / 7.Nxe5 #2"]
