[Black "7) The Engine's Choice | 4.Nc3 with 5.Nxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Nxe4 { This chapter will be exploring those variations in which an early Bxc6+ is omitted. } 5... Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 5... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 6. Nxc5 e5 { White accepts the gambit. With ...e5!, Black offers White another pawn! The more we sacrifice, the sharper the position gets. Of course, White may not be inclined to capture this second pawn given the current threat on the knight. Either way, Black has already complicated matters. Now a dynamic middlegame is ineluctable. } 7. Nxe5 { White accepts our second gambit, hoping that the tactics work out in their favor. While it's true that White will inevitably secure a material advantage, it is debatable whether this will sufficiently compensate for the remarkable initiative Black will receive in return. } 7... Bxc5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Qe2+ { An important intermezzo. Click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to find out what happens if White tries Bxa8 instead. } 10... Kf8 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 12. O-O h5 { [%cal Bd7h3]Expanding on the kingside. Our rook needs to get in the game somehow. Black sneakily threatens 13.-- Bh3!! 14.gxh3 Rh6 , with a crushing attack. An alternative worthy of consideration is } ( 12... Bc6 $2 { Black's bishops are magnificent pieces. White is forced to respond with } 13. d4 Bxd4 { 14.fxe3? h5! The rook is coming to h6, then g6. Black's attack regains some force. Even if White manages to defend, Black has the two minor pieces for the rook. } 14. Be3 Bxe3 { White must now recapture with the queen, after which Black has excellent play with ...Bxg2 and ...h5. Instead, if } ) 13. d3 ( 13. d4 $2 { might be slightly more resilient. Black has nothing better than to take and to cooperate in White's attempt at simplification. } 13... Bxd4 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. Qxe3 { Opportunities for aggression still remain, however. } 15... h4 16. h3 Rh6 { The pressure begins to mount. The engine thinks White's best attempt at a defense is to eternally weaken the light squares: } 17. Kh1 Rg6 18. f3 Qb8 { The resulting position is close to equal, but is anything but clear. } ) 13... Bc6 14. Be3 { The only move to prevent Black from taking on g2. White needs to free the f-pawn. } 14... Bd6 15. f4 Rh6 { [%cal Bh6g6,Bg6g1]Capitalizing on the opportunity to mobilize the rook. } 16. f5 { [%cal Bf5g6][%csl Rg6]White must stop ...Rg6. } 16... Ng4 $1 { [%cal Bd6h2][%csl Rh2][%cal Ba8g2][%csl Rg2][%cal Bg4h2]Black sacrifices yet another exchange to continue the attack! } 17. Bxh6 { White does have some tricks if instead they try the weird-looking } ( 17. Bf4 $2 { Black needs to be precise. } 17... Qb8 18. Qd2 { Here only one move wins. } 18... g5 $3 { Black either removes the bishop from f4 or gets the g6 square for the rook! } 19. fxg6 Rxg6 20. Bxd6+ Qxd6 21. Qf4 Ne5 $146 { White has permission to resign. If } 22. Rf2 { Black ends the game with } 22... Rxg2+ $3 23. Rxg2 Nf3+ $146 { If instead 22... Ne5 23.g3 Rg4 24.Qe3 Qd5 White dies on the light squares. } ) 17... Bxh2+ 18. Kh1 gxh6 19. Rae1 Bg3 { [%cal Bg3h4,Ba8b8,Rb8h2][%csl Rh2]Black has the clever idea of playing ...Qb8 and ...Bh4. ...h4-h3 also looks quite appealing. White probably will have to give up a rook for the light-squared bishop to avoid succumbing to the attack. Still, the position is still quite sharp. We should be weary of White's queen potentially invading our scantily defended kingside corner. } 20. Qe7+ Kg8 21. Re2 h4 $19 { [%cal Bh4h3,Bh6h5]I don't see White surviving this. Even with perfect play White ends up being much worse. } 22. Qb4 { is the only defensive resource White has left. Black very straightforwardly shuts down all of White's counterplay with } 22... h5 { White might try to sneak in to the weak g5 with } 23. Qd2 { , but simply } 23... f6 { will do. } 24. Re6 h3 25. Rxc6 { Eliminating the bishop does little to ease the pressure on the long diagonal. } 25... Qxc6 26. Rf3 Qxf3 $3 27. gxf3 Nf2+ $146 { White is done for. And if instead White tries 23... h5 22.Qe7! with the same idea, Black wins with an incredible tactical sequence. 22...Bxg2+! 23.Rxg2 h3 24.Rf3!? A tricky attempt at obfuscation. Black must remain sharp. 24...hxg2+ 25.Kxg2 Now comes the key move. 25...Be5! Covering the dark squares and vacating the h2 square for the knight. Black can soon follow up with ...Nh2 to pick up the rook. } * 

