][%csl Re2,Rg4][%cal Bd7g4]Now the point of Black's shuffling around becomes apparent. Black has a discovery on the queen and White is unable to save her! } 16. Bxd7 $7 { Maybe White's best attempt at survival. } ( 16. Qxe8+ $2 { insufficiently attends to Black's checkmating pressures. } 16... Bxe8 17. d4 { is the only move to stop mate. Black will simply renew the checkmate threat with } 17... Qxg4 { and after } 18. Be3 Bb5+ 19. Kg1 Bc6 { White can resign in good conscience. } ) ( 16. d4 $2 { just barely keeps White afloat. } 16... Rxe2 17. Bxe2 Bxd4 18. Be3 Bxe3 19. fxe3 Qf6+ 20. Ke1 Bc6 21. Rf1 Qxb2 22. Rd1 Qc3+ 23. Kf2 { White's is alive, true. But the weak king affords Black an easier game. } ) 16... Rxe2 17. Kxe2 Qe7+ 18. Kd1 Qxd7 19. f3 Qd4 { [%cal Bd4f2]We're going to take advantage of White's terrible piece coordination by tearing apart their kingside. } 20. Re1 ( 20. c3 Qf2 { results in an unclear position after } 21. b4 Bd6 22. Bb2 Qxg2 23. Kc2 h5 { , where both sides have chances. } ) 20... h5 { Eliminating potential back rank mating ideas and getting a head start on the upcoming pawn race. } 21. c3 Qf2 $17 { [%cal Bf2g2][%csl Rf3,Rg2,Rh2][%cal Bh5h4,Bh4h3,Bh3h2]Black will eliminate White's kingside pawns and try to promote Harry while White gets coordinated. This is better for Black, but we still need to be cautious. White's central pawns can become a formidable threat if we're not careful. } * 

