er extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Nxe4 { This chapter will be exploring those variations in which an early Bxc6+ is omitted. } 5... Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 5... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 6. Nxc5 e5 { White accepts the gambit. With ...e5!, Black offers White another pawn! The more we sacrifice, the sharper the position gets. Of course, White may not be inclined to capture this second pawn given the current threat on the knight. Either way, Black has already complicated matters. Now a dynamic middlegame is ineluctable. } 7. Nxe5 { White accepts our second gambit, hoping that the tactics work out in their favor. While it's true that White will inevitably secure a material advantage, it is debatable whether this will sufficiently compensate for the remarkable initiative Black will receive in return. } 7... Bxc5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Bxa8 O-O { Black gambits material once again! Sure, taking on a8 is fine, but why not instead draw White deeper into dynamic waters? Indeed, who could sensibly resist Black's friendly invitation to withdraw the bishop to safety? Who would dismiss the opportunity to be the equivalent of five pawns up after just eleven moves? Five pawns worth! The real question, you might ask, is how can Black feasibly afford to surrender so much material this early on? The answer to said inquiry becomes evident once we take notice of the state of White's development. No piece has left its starting square apart from that of the bishop; the piece which must move once again if it is to be kept alive! Neck-deep in the sea of dynamic chaos, White almost assuredly will not survive the deluge of torrential waves which will follow from the decision to preserve the bishop, but then again, even if the bishop is abandoned it may already be too late to quell the incoming maelstrom! } 11. Bf3 { White wagers that Black is bluffing. If White can defend for a little while they should be winning, right? } 11... Re8+ { Black must strike now, lest the white patriarch flee from the open center. } 12. Kf1 $7 { The only move. } 12... Ng4 { «'Sacrifices are not losses; they are investments.' - Garry Kasparov» Black insists that White take even more material! The difference between our former gambits and ...Ng4 is that this time White is compelled to accept. One simpler alternative worth mentioning is } ( 12... Qb6 { , where White cannot stop the incoming ...Bxf2 followed by ...Re1+, forcing White to give up the queen for the rook and bishop. Black is doing fine there, and even is slightly better, but the attack on White's king has largely subsided. I prefer to go for the throat. } ) 13. Bxg4 Qf6 { Forcing White's queen off the back rank. } 14. Qf3 { Notice that } ( 14. d4 $2 { loses. } 14... Bb5+ { If } 15. Be2 Rxe2 { funnily enough, White will end up the one being down significant material. } 16. Qxe2 Bxd4 17. f3 Qh4 18. g3 Qh3+ 19. Ke1 Bxe2 20. Kxe2 Qg2+ ) ( 14. Bf3 $2 { also loses. } 14... Qd4 { White loses the queen, at minimum. } ) 14... Qe7 { White must now decide between Qe2 or g3. } 15. g3 Bxg4 { [%cal Bf3g4][%csl Rf2]Drawing the queen away from the f2 square. } 16. Qxg4 Qe1+ 17. Kg2 Qxf2+ 18. Kh3 Re2 { [%cal Bf2g2,Be2e4,Be4h4,Bg2h1,Bc5e7]We threaten 19.-- ...Qg2+ , where checkmate would be unavoidable: } 19. d3 { White must cover the e4 square. } ( 19. Kh4 Be7+ 20. Qg5 Re4+ 21. Kh5 { Qh3+ 23.Qh4 } 21... Re5 { White must play d3 in order to survive. } ) ( 19. d4 $2 Qg2+ 20. Kh4 Be7+ 21. Bg5 Bxg5+ 22. Kxg5 f6+ 23. Kh4 Re4 { is the killer. This is why d3 is forced. } 24. Rag1 Rxg4+ 25. Kxg4 Qe4+ 26. Kh3 g5 { If 22... Bxg5+ 25.Qxg5 , the best White can do is transpose to the previous line after 25...f6! 26.Qg4 Re4 27.Rag1 Rxg4+ 28.Kxg4 Qe4+ 29.Kh3 g5! Either way, White must sacrifice a rook in order to prevent the impending ...g4+ followed by ...Qg6 and mate on g5. 24... Re4 24.Rae1!? is a tricky move worth mentioning. Black only has one winning move. 24...g5+!! If we take on g4 first, ...g5 will not come with tempo. Hence, it is necessary to start with this. 25.Kh5 Rxg4 26.Kxg4 Once again, only one move wins. 26...Kf7! The king needs to advance without being susceptible to checks. Next ...h5+ arrives with decisive force. } ) 19... Qg2+ 20. Kh4 Re6 { Black once again threatens mate: 21.-- ...Be7+ } 21. Bg5 $7 ( 21. Bg5 Rh6+ 22. Qh5 Rxh5+ 23. Kxh5 Qh3+ 24. Bh4 Qf5+ 25. Bg5 Qxg5+ { therefore, Bg5 is forced. } ) 21... h6 22. Bd8 $7 { [%cal Bg5d8]Forced. If the bishop moves off the d8-h4 diagonal Black has ...Be7+. } 22... Rd6 { [%cal Bd6d4,Bd6d8][%csl Rg4,Rd8][%cal Bd4h4]Now White must prevent ...Rd4 with c3, after which the bishop drops. } 23. c3 $7 Rxd8 { Black has removed the key dark-squared defender and once again threatens ...Be7+. } 24. Qe4 { This is the only move that holds. If 24\. Qe4 25.Qe4 is the other move to watch out for. Similarly, Black must find a series of only-moves to preserve the advantage. 25...g5+ 26.Kg4 h5+! 27.Kxg5 Both Kxh5 and Kf5 result in forced mate. 27...Qh3! 28.Kf4 Rd6! Black threatens to win the queen with ...Bh6+, where the king will be forced to walk into a pin on the e-file. The clever 29.Qe5 prevents the immediate ...Bh6+, but the queen falls all the same after 29...Qg2!! 30.Qxh5 Rf6+ 31.Kg5 Qd5+ 32.Kg4 Qf3+ 33.Kh4 Rh6 } ( 24. Rae1 $2 { Black is winning, but has to find } 24... Bf8 { These lines are incredibly sharp. They are the sort of positions White can easily bounce back from if Black even slightly errs, so it may be worth examining a couple of continuations to illustrate how Black can convert. First, if } 25. Qf5 { Black must spot a series of only-moves to maintain the advantage. } 25... Rd6 26. Qf1 g5+ 27. Kg4 Qc6 { The idea here is ...Qd7+. } 28. Kh3 h5 29. Qf5 g4+ 30. Kh4 { Now all Black needs to do is find an opening on the dark squares. White must surrender the queen to keep the game going. } 30... Rd5 31. Qf4 Bh6 { The queen is dead. 27... g5+ So, White might try 27.Kh5 instead. Black similarly drops the queen back with 27...Qc6 and will look for an opportunity to trap the king. 28.d4 Rd5! 29.Re3 f5! Now the king cannot easily escape. White can survive the attack with 30.Qe2 Kf7! 31.Re6 Qxe6 32.Qxe6+ Kxe6 , but this only delays their resignation. } ) 24... Be7+ { [%cal Bd8d5,Bd5d3,Bg7g5,Re4e7][%csl Re7]We need to draw the queen out of the center. } 25. Qxe7 g5+ 26. Kg4 Rd5 $13 { [%cal Bh6h5,Bg2h3,Yd5d3,Yh2h3]...h5+ followed by ...Qh3# is the threat. After } 27. h3 ( 27. h4 $2 { complicates matters slightly; Black will be the one to end up performing the repetition. Black needs to find both } 27... h5+ 28. Kxh5 gxh4+ 29. Kxh4 { , and } 29... Qf3 30. Kh3 Rh5+ 31. Qh4 Rxh4+ 32. Kxh4 f5 33. Kh3 Qg4+ { etc. If both players have survived this long, a draw is mutually deserved. } ) 27... Rxd3 { White should force repetition with Qe8+ & Qe5+ to avoid getting mated. } * 

