ck is winning. Or, 15... Ng4 15.g3?! results in similar complications. 15...h6 16.h3 Nxf2! 17.Rxf2 hxg5 18.Qf3 Qxd4 19.Rd1 Qb6 Black is winning here as well. } ) 15... Nh2 { [%cal Bd7h3][%csl Rh3,Rg2,Rf3,Rf1][%cal Bh2f3,Bh2f1]Black's steed leaps right onto the white king's front porch! White's kingside is on the verge of collapse. The light squares will be the target of our attack. } 16. Re1 Qg6 17. Qd2 { White has recourse to no other defense. Instead, And finally, } ( 17. f4 $2 { loses to } 17... Bxh3 18. gxh3 Bxf4 19. Kh1 Qxg5 { White's weak king affords Black a decisive advantage. 18... Bxh3 If instead 18.Kxh2 , Black has 18...Qxg5! 19.gxh3 Qxf4+ Now the key to converting is to draw the king out toward the center. 20.Kg2 Qg3+ 21.Kf1 Qxh3+ 22.Kg1 Bh2+ 23.Kf2 Bg3+ 24.Ke2 Re8+ The rook on e1 falls and the game ends. } ) ( 17. g3 $2 { weakens h3. } 17... Qf5 ) ( 17. Qc1 $2 { does nothing to prevent Black from breaking through on the light squares. } 17... Bxh3 18. gxh3 $2 Nf3+ $146 19. Kf1 Nxg5 $146 { This is also winning! Accurately defending these positions looks like quite the challenge. } ) 17... Bxh3 $15 { [%cal Bh2f3,Rg2h3][%csl Rg1,Rd2,Re1][%cal Yd2e3,Yh3d7,Yh2g4,Gf7f6,Gh7h6]White cannot take on h3. When White relocates the queen we can drop our bishop back to d7, evict White's bishop from our territory with ...h6 or possibly ...f6, and try to set up some checkmating threats with ...Ng4. Black has a great position here. } * 

