ortunately, ...e4 doesn't work out as well as it does in the lines where White has already captured on c6. } 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. d3 { As will be seen, } ( 9. O-O $2 { hands the game to Black. Click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to learn more about what happens if White castles without first playing d3 or d4. } ) 9... O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Re1 { If White goes for the pin with } ( 12. Bg5 $2 { they best be prepared to give up the bishop. } 12... h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 Nd5 $146 { Black prepares ...f5 and is slightly better. } ) 12... Nd7 $14 { [%cal Bf7f5,Bd6c7,Bd8f6,Ba8e8]Black's plan is to expand on the kingside with ...f5, centralize the remaining undeveloped pieces with ...Qf6 and ...Rae8, then eventually play for ...e4. White's strongest plan is probably to try to build pressure on e5, starting with } 13. Nbd2 $146 { , where the knight heads to c4. } 13... f5 14. Nc4 $146 Bc7 15. b3 Qf6 16. Bb2 Rae8 17. Qe2 { White's setup here is quite harmonious. If we are to emerge with sufficient counterplay we must play for ...e4. } 17... Qf7 18. Qe3 { Now that the pin on f3 has been successfully broken, Black must play } 18... e4 { immediately. } * 

