ortunately, ...e4 doesn't work out as well as it does in the lines where White has already captured on c6. } 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. d4 { As will be seen, } ( 9. O-O $2 { hands the game to Black. Click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to learn more about what happens if White castles without first playing d3 or d4. } ) 9... e4 { [%cal Bd6h2][%csl Rf3]d4 enables Black to advance in the center, unleashing the bishop and forcing the knight to abandon its kingside post. } 10. Ne5 O-O 11. Nxc6 { I suspect most would go for the pawn, but there are reasonable alternatives. For instance, A slightly trickier one is } ( 11. O-O Qc7 12. Bf4 Ng4 $146 { The exchange on e5 will simplify the position. } 13. h3 Nxe5 $146 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Qxe5 $10 { These middlegames are structurally imbalanced, but equal. } ) ( 11. Bg5 $2 { , intending Nxc6 to arrive with a little more force. } 11... Be6 12. Nxc6 $146 Qc7 13. Bxf6 Qxc6 { With the bishop on e6 White has less reason to try d5, so } 14. Be5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Rfd8 16. Qe2 a5 { Black is down two pawns but has superior activity. In all probability White won't be able to preserve the material for long. Both sides have chances in these positions. } ) 11... Qc7 12. d5 { A multipurpose move. White needs to anticipate ...Bg4 followed by ...e3, but also needs to save the knight. Suppose White saves the knight with With } ( 12. Nca5 $2 $146 Bg4 13. Qe2 e3 { This is already lost for White. } 14. fxe3 Bxh2 { The kingside is getting ripped to shreds and the primary constituents of White's development are loitering on the queenside. Here's (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) another example of what happens when White fails to adequately anticipate this ...Bg4 \+ ...e3 threat. } ) ( 12. d5 { , the d4 square has been vacated to make room for the queen. Therefore, } 12... Bg4 $2 { is now met with } 13. Qd4 e3 14. Bxe3 { and ultimately surrenders the game to White. } ) 12... Bd7 { [%cal Bf6d5,Bd7c6][%csl Rc6]Threatening ...Nxd5 followed by ...Bxc6. While Black is sustaining the battery along the b8-h2 diagonal White will be unable to castle, hence White will most likely invest their short-term future into resolving the bizarre situation on the central queenside. } 13. Nba5 { [%cal Bf6d5][%csl Rd5]Covering the knight, thereby preventing ...Nxd5. Another move worth consideration is } ( 13. Be3 $2 { , where } 13... a5 { would be strong, simply removing the possibility of Nba5 altogether. Now Black can take on c6 or d5 at some moment and try to take advantage of the fact that White still needs to spend some time figuring out how to safely evacuate the king from the center. For instance, } 14. a4 Rfc8 { no need to rush with the exchange just yet. If we exchange too early, our battery on the b8-h2 diagonal will be undone. Let's use the time instead to improve our pieces. Once the threat on h2 is defused, for instance with } 15. h3 { , then we should initiate the exchange. } 15... Nxd5 $146 16. Qxd5 ( 16. Qd2 f5 { Now it's unclear whether White should even castle at all! Black has a formidable pawn-mass headed toward the central kingside and our bishops are propitiously pointed straight towards the kingside corner. Castling queenside looks risky as well due to the positioning of Black's queen and rooks. This looks somewhat uncomfortable for White. } ) 16... Bxc6 ) 13... Ng4 { [%cal Bf7f5]Freeing the f-pawn. } 14. h3 { Instinctively, it makes sense to want to punish Black for the pointless looking ...Ng4 by sending the knight straight back to f6. I suspect most people would automatically respond with this. One alternative worth mentioning: } ( 14. Qd4 { White aims to get castled on the queenside, forcing Black to react to the threat on e4. } 14... Rae8 15. Bd2 { This position requires a high degree of precision of both players. Here Black must find the incredible } 15... e3 16. fxe3 Bg3+ $3 17. hxg3 Qxg3+ 18. Kd1 Nf2+ $146 19. Kc1 Nxh1 $146 { With a deeply unclear middlegame ahead. If instead, 16... e3 16.Bxe3?! Black has tactics. 16...Bxc6! 17.Nxc6 Bf4! } ) 14... Nxf2 $5 { [%cal Bf7f5,Bf5f4,Be4e3,Ba8e8]We will not be retreating. We force White's king out off the back rank and onto the lines of fire. } 15. Kxf2 f5 $13 { [%cal Bf5f3,Bf5f4,Be4e3,Ba8e8]Black's initiative is frightening. It's not at all clear how White is supposed to defend this. Suppose White opts to manually castle with } 16. Rf1 { , Black simply surges forth with } 16... f4 17. Kg1 $2 f3 { Black is already winning. The truth is that White doesn't have time to reposition the king, and even if they did the kingside is not the place to do it. 16... f5 16.Qd4! is White's best chance, preventing ...Bc5+ ideas. 16...f4! 17.Ke1 Rae8 18.Rf1 f3! 19.Be3 fxg2 20.Rxf8+ Rxf8 White is extremely close to falling off the board. 21.Ke2! is White's only chance to stay in the game. 21...Bxh3 Now the threat is ...Rf1 22.Nc4 is the only move! These positions are super sharp! I personally think they are easier to play from the Black side. } * 

