1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Nxe4 { This chapter will be exploring those variations in which an early Bxc6+ is omitted. } 5... Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 5... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 6. Nxc5 e5 { White accepts the gambit. With ...e5!, Black offers White another pawn! The more we sacrifice, the sharper the position gets. Of course, White may not be inclined to capture this second pawn given the current threat on the knight. Either way, Black has already complicated matters. Now a dynamic middlegame is ineluctable. } 7. Nb3 { White rejects our second gambit. Dropping back to b3 is the most common response to ...e5. The interesting } ( 7. Bxc6+ { would transpose to the lines analyzed in chapter six (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) ( 7. b4 $2 { would lead to obscure complications after } 7... Bxc5 8. bxc5 e4 9. Ne5 $146 Qd4 { Super sharp stuff, as always. } 10. Nxc6 $146 Qxa1 11. Ne5+ $146 Kf8 12. c3 { Here it's important to notice that White has some nasty threats beginning with Bc4, so Black must start with } 12... Be6 { and after } 13. O-O Qxa2 14. d4 exd3 15. Qxd3 Qd5 { Black is doing fine. We are up an exchange and White has some long-term weaknesses they need to figure out how to consolidate. } ) 7... Bd6 { Defending e5. Unfortunately, ...e4 doesn't work out as well as it does in the lines where White has already captured on c6. } 8. d3 { As will be seen, } ( 8. O-O $2 { hands the game to Black. Click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to learn more about what happens if White castles without first playing d3 or d4. } ) 8... O-O 9. Bg5 { Activating the bishop before Black can play ...h6 makes sense. Other sensible moves result in unremarkable middlegames. For instance, } ( 9. O-O Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Bg5 h6 { These positions play out fairly naturally. White is usually ever so slightly better. } ) 9... h6 10. Bh4 Nd4 { [%cal Yd4b5]Black hits the bishop. White has to capture the knight to maintain the balance. Retreating the bishop is no good. For instance, } 11. Nbxd4 { This is the correct knight to capture on d4 with. Otherwise White will need to spend additional time worrying about the bishop on b5 potentially getting trapped. } ( 11. Bc4 $2 g5 12. Bg3 b5 13. Nbxd4 $146 exd4 14. Bb3 Re8+ { now White is forced to move the king. Black is better. So taking on d4 is necessary, but with which piece? } ) ( 11. Nfxd4 $2 $146 exd4 12. Nd2 $146 { White needs to anticipate ...a6-b5, but now Black can take the wheel. } 12... g5 13. Bg3 a6 14. Bc4 b5 15. Bb3 Re8+ { Black takes the advantage. Notice that 12... exd4 12.Nxd4?? is not an option due to 13...Bb4+ 14.c3 Qxd4-+ } ) 11... exd4 { [%cal Bd8a5][%csl Rb5,Re1]The threat is now ...Qa5+. } 12. O-O g5 $1 { Breaking the pin. White could sacrifice on g5, but it ultimately doesn't work out for them. For instance, } 13. Bg3 ( 13. Nxg5 $2 $146 hxg5 14. Bxg5 Kg7 15. Qf3 Kg6 $2 16. h4 Bc7 { Black can establish a battery with ...Qd6 and hit the queen with ...Bg5. Black is better. } ) 13... Bg4 $1 { [%cal Ba8c8,Bc8c5,Bc5f5,Bf5f3][%csl Rf3]Establishing the classic pin. Black's idea is to get the rook to f5 via ...Rc8-c5-f5 and then to destroy White's structure with a subsequent capture on f3. } 14. h3 Bh5 $13 { [%cal Ba8c8,Bc8c5,Bc5f5,Bf5f3][%csl Rf3][%cal Bh5d1,Ya7a6,Yb7b5,Rg5g4]We should pursue the same plan of getting the rook to f5. ...a6, ...b5, and ...g4 are also some moves we should consider at the right moment. A game could continue from here with } 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Re1 Rac8 { It looks a bit ugly, but White should play g4. If they don't, Black can. } 17. Bc4 g4 $2 18. hxg4 Bxg4 { and Black has a slight edge. Instead, if 17... Rac8 17.g4! Black brings the rook in. 17...Rc5! 18.Bc4 b5! This line is incredibly sharp and unclear. Both sides have attacking chances, but Black's rooks look a little more mobile. if 19.b4?! Black should be fearless. 19...Rf5!! 20.gxf5?! Qf4! } * 

