er extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Nxe4 { This chapter will be exploring those variations in which an early Bxc6+ is omitted. } 5... Nf6 { Black needs to focus on development. } ( 5... e6 { would be far too slow! White is welcome to capture c5, but if they dare accept the gambit they best be equipped to endure the tactical slug-fest which is sure to follow! } ) 6. Nxc5 e5 $1 { White accepts the gambit. With ...e5!, Black offers White another pawn! The more we sacrifice, the sharper the position gets. Of course, White may not be inclined to capture this second pawn given the current threat on the knight. Either way, Black has already complicated matters. Now a dynamic middlegame is ineluctable. } 7. Nb3 { White rejects our second gambit. Dropping back to b3 is the most common response to ...e5. The interesting } ( 7. Bxc6+ { would transpose to the lines analyzed in chapter six (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) ( 7. b4 $2 { would lead to obscure complications after } 7... Bxc5 8. bxc5 e4 9. Ne5 $146 Qd4 { Super sharp stuff, as always. } 10. Nxc6 $146 Qxa1 11. Ne5+ $146 Kf8 12. c3 { Here it's important to notice that White has some nasty threats beginning with Bc4, so Black must start with } 12... Be6 { and after } 13. O-O Qxa2 14. d4 exd3 15. Qxd3 Qd5 { Black is doing fine. We are up an exchange and White has some long-term weaknesses they need to figure out how to consolidate. } ) 7... Bd6 { Defending e5. Unfortunately, ...e4 doesn't work out as well as it does in the lines where White has already captured on c6. } 8. d4 { As will be seen, } ( 8. O-O $2 { hands the game to Black. Click here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) to learn more about what happens if White castles without first playing d3 or d4. } ) 8... e4 { d4 enables Black to advance in the center, unleashing the bishop and forcing the knight to abandon its kingside post. } 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxc6 $5 ( 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxc6 $146 { Transposes to 7.Nb3 #2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 10... bxc6 11. Bxc6 $4 { A natural blunder. More accurate would be } ( 11. Bc4 h6 12. O-O Ng4 $146 { where Black gets typical kingside complications. } ) 11... Bg4 $1 12. Qd2 { I imagine White would prefer this to f3, but this might actually be more dangerous. If } ( 12. f3 $2 { instead, things get spicy. } 12... exf3 13. Bxf3 $2 Re8+ 14. Kf2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qc8 $3 { A brilliant idea! Black threatens both ...Ng4+ and ...Qxc2+. White cannot prevent both. } 16. Qd3 Ng4+ $146 17. Kf1 Nxh2+ $146 18. Rxh2 Bxh2 { This is game over, and of course 16... Qc8 16.c3?? Ng4+ ends with mate! 17.Kf1 Qc4+ etc. } ) 12... Rc8 $19 { [%cal Be4e3][%csl Rc6]Seeing that ...e3! is imminent, White is in serious trouble. Let's examine a few continuations. 13.fxe3?? Ne4! Now White must give up the queen. If instead 14.Qd4?? Qh4+ , mate is on the horizon. White might also attempt 13... Rc8 13.Bb5 e3! 14.Qd3 Nd5! Black has tons of winning threats: ...Nb4, ...Nf4, ...Bb4+, etc. White needs to get the king out of the center, however even after 15.O-O the chaos continues. 15...Qh4! 16.g3 Qh3 17.Qe4 Nf6! 18.Qg2 Qh5 This is crushing. White either loses their queen or remaining bishop. } 13. d5 { looks reasonable as a means of defending the bishop, but after } ( 13. g3 Bxg3 14. Kf1 { Qh3+ 17.Kg1 } 14... Bxf2 { But if White instead captures e3 with the queen: 14... Bxg3 13.Qxe3? Rxc6 14.dxc6 Re8 and the queen is lost. Even 14... Bxg3 13.Qd3? loses in magnificent fashion: 13...Rxc6! 14.dxc6? Bb4+ 15.Kf1? Qxd3! 16.cxd3 e2 17.Kg1 e1=R+ Every line is so tactically rich! I can't possibly exhaustively cover them here, so check the tactics chapter for more. } ) 13... e3 { danger is imminent. } * 

