ortunately, ...e4 doesn't work out as well as it does in the lines where White has already captured on c6. } 8. O-O $2 { A common blunder. Black already is much better if we spot the right idea. } 8... e4 $1 { [%cal Bd6h2,Yf6g4,Rd8h4,Rh4h2][%csl Rh2,Rf3]Removing the defender of h2. A kingside invasion is imminent. } 9. Ng5 ( 9. Nfd4 $2 $146 { doesn't improve White's situation. Then they suffer the classic Greek gift! } 9... Bxh2+ 10. Kxh2 Ng4+ $146 11. Kg3 h5 { White's activity on our queenside is just background noise. } 12. Nxc6 $146 h4+ 13. Kh3 bxc6 14. Bxc6+ Kf8 { Black is winning. } ) 9... Ng4 { [%cal Bg4h2,Bd6h2][%csl Rh2][%cal Bd8g5][%csl Rg5]Threatening both ...Bxh2+ and ...Qxg5. If we issue the Greek gift here, White survives because the knight on g5 blocks our queen from landing on h4 after } ( 9... Bxh2+ 10. Kxh2 Ng4+ $146 11. Kg1 { , and White ends up 'equalizing' with } 11... Qxg5 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. f3 exf3 14. Qxf3 O-O 15. d3 { While this is technically equal, Black's position looks quite appealing. In any case, 9...Ng4 is even stronger. } ) 10. d4 { White must protect the knight somehow. Here are a few other ways White might attempt to fight back: White's best alternative is probably } ( 10. h3 $2 { just outright loses. } 10... Qxg5 11. hxg4 $2 Bxg4 12. Qe1 $2 Bf3 ) ( 10. Nh3 $2 $146 { This looks terrible. } 10... Nxh2 $146 11. Re1 O-O { Black is winning. There are tons of tactics in this line. } ) ( 10. d3 { , but Black still has the advantage after } 10... Bxh2+ 11. Kh1 h6 12. Nh3 $146 Bc7 13. Re1 O-O 14. Rxe4 f5 15. Re2 f4 { This looks quite miserable for White. } ) 10... Bxh2+ 11. Kh1 h6 12. Nh3 O-O $17 { We can stop here and conclude that the opening has been a disaster for White. While Black does not have an immediate checkmating attack, White will be unable to secure the king in the long term. Let's suppose White tries to lock Black's bishop in: } 13. g3 $2 a6 14. Be2 { Here it seems as though White is unravelling Black's attack. Now is the opportune moment for a sacrifice: } 14... Nxf2+ $146 15. Nxf2 $146 Bxg3 16. Kg2 Bc7 { White's kingside has been torn apart. The position gets seriously complicated after } 17. Rh1 Qd6 18. Qg1 e3 19. Nd3 $146 Re8 { Black has a significant advantage here, but the position is such that conversion requires careful calculation. I would recommend that my readers independently analyze these positions. } * 

