1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Ne5 $5 Qd6 { Ne5 is a rare move, but not one altogether without merit. As will be seen in chapter 12 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), we always respond to an early Ne5 with ...Qd6, putting pressure on the knight and forcing White to commit to a plan. } 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Ba4 { Dropping the bishop to a4 enables White to sustain the pin. } 7... Nf6 { Black will attempt to hold on to the extra pawn, at least for a little while. } 8. Qe2 Bf5 9. O-O h5 { [%cal Bf6g4,Bd6h2][%csl Rh2]Shutting down g4 ideas and preparing the eventual ...Ng4. } 10. Re1 { A couple of interesting alternatives: At this stage, if White tries } ( 10. f3 { or 10... h5 10.d3 Black should not immediately capture. After 10.d3, White's queen comes to f3 and Black's queen quickly becomes a target. 10...exd3? 11.Qf3! Bd7 12.Bf4! Qd4 13.Rad1 White has a remarkable initiative. This should not be allowed. First, with 10.d3 we need to play the intermediate move 10. f3 10...Ng4! 11.g3 and now we can take. 11...exd3 12.Qf3 Bd7 With the knight on g4, White no longer has 13.Bf4? due to 13...e5! Otherwise, if White manages to spot the insane looking 10. f3 13.Nb5!? , the position flies off the rails. 13...Qb8 is forced, pushing the knight back. 14.Nc3 Ne5 15.Qg2 g5!? The resulting position offers unclear complications, as usual. ...Ng4 is obviously not available after 10... h5 10.f3 , so naturally Black should just return the pawn and add some support to c6 with 10...Rc8 Once the f-pawn no longer controls g4 11.fxe4 our knight can jump in! 11...Ng4! g3 would weaken the kingside too much, so 12.e5 instead makes sense. 12...Qd4+ 13.Kh1 g6 Black is slightly better. } ) 10... Rc8 $13 { [%cal Bf6g4,Be7e6,Bf8e7,Yg7g6,Yf8g7]Black has a slight edge here. We have a space advantage and are currently up a pawn. We can proceed with ...Ng4 to induce light-squared weaknesses around White's king, ...e6 & ...Bg7, or ...g6 & ...Bg7, etc. White will probably need to commit to the sacrifice with d3 at some point to open up the center. Overall, this position looks preferable to play from the black side. } * 

