1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Nc3 { White turns the tables! exd5 is threatened. If Black should attempt to resolve the conflict by capturing on e4 with } 4... dxe4 $5 ( 4... dxe4 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. Nxe4 $146 { White suddenly has a tremendous lead in development! Admittedly, my analysis failed to produce anything better than ...dxe4. For instance, 4. Nc3 4...d4?! 5.Na4! e6 6.Bxc6+ bxc6 7.d3 looks quite miserable. The upcoming positional middlegame would not be pleasant. Or, 4. Nc3 4...e6 will land you in a position one might encounter in both the French variation of the Sicilian and the Closed Sicilian. In any case, White is in excellent shape after 5.exd5 exd5 6.d4 Nf6 7.O-O Bd6 8.Bg5 O-O 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 10.Nxd5! Instead with 4...dxe4 Black is avoiding typical Sicilian positions and is immediately opening up central lines. We are playing for dynamics, after all. While 4.Nc3 is incredibly rare, it is certainly one of the most testing responses to 3...d5. My former attitude towards Nc3 was that it simply amounted to a practical refutation of 3...d5, but after extensive analysis I began to falter in my convictions. As it turns out, Black has a number of extraordinarily aggressive resources available to him, many of which are no menial task to adequately parry. Granted, White is able to avoid our chaotic complications entirely by quickly simplifying to an endgame (this tends to be a recurring pattern), and often Black has nothing better than to cooperate in this reductive scheme, but whenever Black is permitted to pursue chaotic complications and sacrifice, he will have superior practical chances! Such is the condition of chess. } ) 5. Ne5 { Ne5 is a rare move, but not one altogether without merit. As will be seen in chapter 12 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), we always respond to an early Ne5 with ...Qd6, putting pressure on the knight and forcing White to commit to a plan. } 5... Qd6 6. Nc4 Qg6 { [%cal Bg6g2]Black immediately eyes White's weak kingside. } 7. O-O { The only feasible way of defending g2. } 7... Bh3 { Keeping the pace. We want White to be the one on the defense. } 8. Bxc6+ { If White retreats with } ( 8. Ne3 $146 { , the threat on g2 has been defused and Black can just drop the bishop back to d7 } 8... Bd7 { , preventing White from doubling the pawns. The knight is less active on e3, so this ...Bh3-d7 maneuver makes more sense than simply starting with ...Bd7 on move seven. } ) 8... bxc6 9. Ne3 Nf6 10. Kh1 { White legitimizes gxh3. } 10... Bc8 { [%cal Bc8a6][%csl Rf1][%cal Ba6f1]Our bishop might be much better suited to snipe from the queenside, discouraging ideas of d3, etc. If White's knight ever steps away from e3, then g4 would be a good place to relocate the bishop to as well. } 11. Qe2 { [%cal Be2a6][%csl Ra6]Stopping ...Ba6 for now. Instead, if } ( 11. f3 e5 12. fxe4 Nxe4 $146 { We don't mind clarifying things in the center. } 13. Nxe4 $146 Qxe4 14. d3 Qg6 15. Nc4 $146 f6 16. Qf3 Bd7 { Black is holding everything together. and if 11... Bc8 11.d3 , Black has 11...Ba6! 12.Nc4 Bxc4 13.dxc4 Rd8 14.Qe2 e6 and is slightly better. } ) 11... e5 12. Nc4 Bg4 $13 { [%cal Be2e3,Bf6d5]It might seem silly moving the bishop back, but White is delaying our ...Ba6 ideas and their knight no longer covers g4, so this is fine. A game could continue with } 13. Qe3 Nd5 $146 14. Nxd5 $146 cxd5 15. Nxe5 $146 Qa6 { Black returns the pawn, but maintains the center. } 16. Re1 Be6 17. d3 f6 18. Nf3 $146 Bd6 { With a rich game for both sides ahead. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.e5 with 5.h3 / 7.O-O"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
