[White "4.e5 with 5.h3 / 7.O-O"]
[Black "9) Sidelines 1 of 6 | 4.e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing Blitz against experts and advanced players, both here and with Bxc6+ first. } 4... Bg4 { [%cal Be7e6][%csl Rd4,Bf7,Be6,Bd5,Bc5,Re5][%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3]This is congruous with my previous recommendation in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where White plays e5 after Bxc6+. Here ...Bg4 makes a great deal of sense too. Black would like to play ...e6 to enable easy kingside development and establish the central pawn chain, but to do so prematurely would be to sentence our light squared bishop to the miserable fate of the infamous 'bad French' bishop. Such would not be advantageous to Black. Therefore, we should migrate the bishop to the kingside before committing to ...e6. As an aside, this exact position has already been analyzed by IM John Bartholomew in his Chessable course on the Scandinavian Defense. The same position can be arrived at with 1... e4 1.e4 d5 2.e5!? c5 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.Bb5 Bg4! It's worth mentioning that if my recommendations here aren't agreeable to your tastes, you might benefit from checking his course out. } 5. h3 Bxf3 { This is where Bartholomew and I diverge. In his course, he recommends } ( 5... Bh5 { with the idea of tempting White into } 6. g4 $2 { to loosen up the kingside. After } 6... Bg6 7. e6 Nf6 $146 { Black is fine, but I am not particularly fond of playing these positions from the Black side. I find it awkward and uncomfortable whenever White is able to play e6 in these structures. Instead, ...Bxf3 affords Black simple and easy play and is congruous with my previous recommendation from chapter 5. } ) 6. Qxf3 e6 7. O-O ( 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 { is likely to transpose to 5.e5 with 6.h3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 7... Ne7 8. Re1 a6 $15 { Black has no issues. We have better control of the center and e5 is a long term target. From here I assume White might try to contend for the center, so the game might continue with } 9. Bxc6+ Nxc6 $146 10. c3 { but Black now has } 10... Qh4 { d4 is no longer an option, so let's suppose White continues with } 11. d3 { Now Black has } 11... g5 $3 12. Nd2 $146 Rg8 13. Qg4 { Removing the queens from the board will not rescue White's position. } 13... Qxg4 14. hxg4 Bg7 15. Nf3 $146 h5 16. gxh5 g4 { White is much worse. It's so easy for White to go wrong in these positions. } * 

