1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing Blitz against experts and advanced players, both here and with Bxc6+ first. } 4... Bg4 { [%csl Bf7,Be6,Bd5,Bc5][%cal Be7e6][%csl Re5][%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3]This is congruous with my previous recommendation in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where White plays e5 after Bxc6+. Here ...Bg4 makes a great deal of sense too. Black would like to play ...e6 to enable easy kingside development and establish the central pawn chain, but to do so prematurely would be to sentence our light squared bishop to the miserable fate of the infamous 'bad French' bishop. Such would not be advantageous to Black. Therefore, we should migrate the bishop to the kingside before committing to ...e6. As an aside, this exact position has already been analyzed by IM John Bartholomew in his Chessable course on the Scandinavian Defense. The same position can be arrived at with 1... e4 1.e4 d5 2.e5!? c5 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.Bb5 Bg4! It's worth mentioning that if my recommendations here aren't agreeable to your tastes, you might benefit from checking his course out. } 5. O-O Qc7 { If White neglects to immediately repel our bishop, Black has the opportunity to target the unstable e5. } 6. Re1 ( 6. h3 $2 { Drops a pawn. } 6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Qxe5 { There are some nuances to navigating this continuation. Black's advantage is not decisive by any means. For instance, White has } 8. d4 $2 cxd4 9. Bf4 Qe4 10. Qg3 Nf6 $146 11. Nd2 $146 Qf5 12. Be5 { where White will likely regain the pawn soon. Black is slightly better in these positions, but they can still be tricky to navigate. } ) 6... e6 7. h3 Bxf3 { [%cal Bh7h5,Bg7g5,Bg5g4,Rg4f3,Rg4h3][%csl Rh3,Rf3]For those insistent on preserving the bishop pair, } ( 7... Bh5 { is perfectly acceptable too. My motivation for immediately capturing on f3 is simple: I want to generate a kingside attack. With the queen and pawn resting on f3 and h3 respectively, an eventual ...h5 \+ ...g5-...g4! would arrive with deadly effect, opening up the kingside files and casting the game into chaos once again! } ) 8. Qxf3 Ne7 { A kingside pawn storm is on the agenda, but Black must address the queenside situation first. } 9. c3 a6 10. Bxc6+ { White must exchange on c6 otherwise e5 will fall. } 10... Nxc6 11. Qg3 { [%csl Re5,Rg7][%cal Bg3g7,Bg3e5]White defends e5 and eyes g7 simultaneously. } 11... f5 { [%cal Rc7g3,Re5f6,Bh7h6,Bg7g5,Bh8g8][%csl Rg3]Black gains space on the king side, inviting White to capture en passant if they should so wish! If White elects not to, Black will aim for ...g5 with ...h6 and ...Rg8. } 12. d3 Rg8 $1 13. f4 { To allow ...g5 would be extremely dangerous. For instance: } ( 13. Nd2 $2 $146 g5 14. Nf3 $146 h6 15. h4 Qf7 16. hxg5 Be7 17. Qh4 O-O-O { This looks terrible for White. Stockfish thinks White's king is untenable where he currently stands and recommends running to the center. } ) 13... h6 { [%cal Bg7g5]...g5 is incoming! } 14. Qg6+ { White should not allow ...g5. } ( 14. h4 $2 { would be another interesting attempt. } 14... d4 15. Nd2 $2 $146 { With the knight blocking the bishop in } 15... g5 { becomes possible again! } 16. fxg5 hxg5 17. hxg5 O-O-O 18. Nc4 $146 Rg6 { Black can continue with ...Be7, ...Rdg8, ...Nd8-Nf7, etc. White cannot defend g5. } ) 14... Qf7 $17 { [%cal Bg7g5,Bb7b5,Bd5d4,Rg6f7,Re8f7][%csl Rf7][%cal Yf8e7,Ya8d8]Black is a bit better here. Once the queens are exchanged, Black can follow up with ...d4 to restrict White's center and has excellent play on all sides of the board. } * 

