1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing Blitz against experts and advanced players, both here and with Bxc6+ first. } 4... Bg4 { [%csl Bf7,Be6,Bd5,Bc5][%cal Be7e6][%csl Re5,Rd4][%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3]This is congruous with my previous recommendation in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where White plays e5 after Bxc6+. Here ...Bg4 makes a great deal of sense too. Black would like to play ...e6 to enable easy kingside development and establish the central pawn chain, but to do so prematurely would be to sentence our light squared bishop to the miserable fate of the infamous 'bad French' bishop. Such would not be advantageous to Black. Therefore, we should migrate the bishop to the kingside before committing to ...e6. As an aside, this exact position has already been analyzed by IM John Bartholomew in his Chessable course on the Scandinavian Defense. The same position can be arrived at with 1... e4 1.e4 d5 2.e5!? c5 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.Bb5 Bg4! It's worth mentioning that if my recommendations here aren't agreeable to your tastes, you might benefit from checking his course out. } 5. O-O Qc7 { If White neglects to immediately repel our bishop, Black has the opportunity to target the unstable e5. } 6. Re1 ( 6. h3 $2 { Drops a pawn. } 6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Qxe5 { There are some nuances to navigating this continuation. Black's advantage is not decisive by any means. For instance, White has } 8. d4 $2 cxd4 9. Bf4 Qe4 10. Qg3 Nf6 $146 11. Nd2 $146 Qf5 12. Be5 { where White will likely regain the pawn soon. Black is slightly better in these positions, but they can still be tricky to navigate. } ) 6... e6 7. h3 Bxf3 { [%cal Bh7h5,Bg7g5,Bg5g4,Rg4f3,Rg4h3][%csl Rg4][%cal Bd1f3]For those insistent on preserving the bishop pair, } ( 7... Bh5 { is perfectly acceptable too. My motivation for immediately capturing on f3 is simple: I want to generate a kingside attack. With the queen and pawn resting on f3 and h3 respectively, an eventual ...h5 \+ ...g5-...g4! would arrive with deadly effect, opening up the kingside files and casting the game into chaos once again! } ) 8. Qxf3 Ne7 { A kingside pawn storm is on the agenda, but Black must address the queenside situation first. } 9. d3 a6 10. Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. Bf4 { [%csl Re5]Defending e5. } 11... Be7 { [%cal Rg7g5][%csl Rf4,Rf3][%cal Bc6d4,Bh7h5,Bd4f3,Rg5g4]Black prepares ...g5! 11.Bf4 looks enormously risky for this reason. } 12. Nd2 g5 $1 13. Bh2 ( 13. Bg3 $2 { gives Black free tempi. } 13... Nd4 $146 14. Qd1 h5 15. c3 Nf5 $146 { White's position is in a dismal state. Black will simply castle to the queenside and steamroll White on the g and h-files. } ) 13... h5 { [%cal Bg5g4][%csl Rf3,Rh3]Naturally, Black should try to open up the kingside files. One theme to keep in mind is that Black should be careful about moving his king while the white queen eyes f7. Once she has been distracted, that typically marks the opportune moment to for either ...O-O-O or ...Kd7. } 14. c3 { [%cal Bc6d4]White has to play this sooner or later to prevent ...Nd4-f5. Allow me to illustrate what happens if White doesn't see this idea in time. Let's suppose White anticipates the incoming ...g4 by starting with } ( 14. Qd1 $2 O-O-O 15. Kh1 Nd4 $146 { Now } 16. c3 { comes a little too late. } 16... Nf5 $146 17. Rb1 g4 18. Nf1 $146 gxh3 19. gxh3 Qc6 { This is the point. Now the queen can occupy c6 and make threats along the long diagonal. White might try to close down the center with } 20. d4 { , but then their center falls apart. } 20... cxd4 21. cxd4 Qb6 { White cannot defend d4. } ) 14... g4 $1 15. hxg4 { Or, } ( 15. Qe2 { can be met with } 15... O-O-O { where Black has strong play on the g-file. } ) 15... hxg4 16. Qxg4 f5 $3 { [%cal Re5f6,Bc7h2][%csl Rh2]A brilliant tactical shot! White cannot capture en passant due to ...Qxh2+! } 17. Qg6+ { This is just desperation. But let's suppose White has a little more composure and tries } ( 17. Qd1 O-O-O 18. Bf4 Rdg8 19. Nf3 $146 Bf8 { Black makes room for the queen to swing over. Trading bishops on h6 would also be favorable. White is in trouble. } ) 17... Kd7 $1 { [%cal Ba8g8]Threatening to trap the queen! } 18. Qg3 Rag8 19. Qe3 d4 $19 { White is lost. After } 20. cxd4 $2 Nxd4 $146 21. Rac1 Qc6 22. Qxd4+ { White doesn't have much better than to go into an endgame an exchange down. } 22... cxd4 23. Rxc6 Kxc6 24. Nf3 $146 Rg4 25. Rc1+ Kd7 26. Rc4 Rc8 27. Rxc8 Kxc8 { Black's king will walk up to d5 to protect d4 and then the rook can swing around to the queenside with ...Rg8-...Rc8-...Rc2. This is winning. } * 

