1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing Blitz against experts and advanced players, both here and with Bxc6+ first. } 4... Bg4 { [%csl Bf7,Be6,Bd5,Bc5,Re5,Rd4][%cal Be7e6,Bg4d1][%csl Rf3]This is congruous with my previous recommendation in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where White plays e5 after Bxc6+. Here ...Bg4 makes a great deal of sense too. Black would like to play ...e6 to enable easy kingside development and establish the central pawn chain, but to do so prematurely would be to sentence our light squared bishop to the miserable fate of the infamous 'bad French' bishop. Such would not be advantageous to Black. Therefore, we should migrate the bishop to the kingside before committing to ...e6. As an aside, this exact position has already been analyzed by IM John Bartholomew in his Chessable course on the Scandinavian Defense. The same position can be arrived at with 1... e4 1.e4 d5 2.e5!? c5 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.Bb5 Bg4! It's worth mentioning that if my recommendations here aren't agreeable to your tastes, you might benefit from checking his course out. } 5. O-O Qc7 { If White neglects to immediately repel our bishop, Black has the opportunity to target the unstable e5. } 6. Bxc6+ { This is one way to relieve the pressure on e5. } 6... Qxc6 7. h3 h5 $5 { [%cal Bh8h1,Bc6h6]Harry makes an aggressive advance! White certainly won't be keeping the piece if they take on g4. } 8. hxg4 hxg4 9. d3 { White must return the piece. Any knight move allows ...Qh6. } 9... gxf3 10. Qxf3 O-O-O $5 { [%cal Bf3f7][%csl Rf7]Black sacrifices f7 for a kingside initiative! } 11. Qxf7 { White need not accept Black's gambit. } ( 11. Qf5+ Kb8 12. e6 { is perhaps the trickiest alternative we should be aware of. Black can continue with } 12... Nh6 $146 13. Qe5+ Ka8 14. Bf4 fxe6 { and will eventually attempt to coordinate his pieces to the kingside. For instance, after } 15. Re1 Rd6 16. Qe2 $2 e5 { Black returns the pawn! The position is rife with tactics. } 17. Bxe5 Nf5 $3 $146 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 { Finding a defense for White is not easy. } 19. g3 $2 Qh6 20. Qf3 Qh2+ 21. Kf1 Nd4 $146 22. Qg2 Qh1+ 23. Qg1 Qxg1+ 24. Kxg1 Nf3+ $146 25. Kf1 Rh1+ { This is game over. } ) 11... Nh6 12. Qf3 { It might be worth examining some other ways White might respond. } ( 12. Bxh6 { Might look ridiculous at first, but White manages to prevent Black's attack after } 12... Qxh6 { 13.gxh3 Rxh3 White might have survived, but Black is still significantly better. } 13. Qf5+ Kb8 14. Qh3 Qxh3 ) 12... g5 $1 { [%cal Bc6g6,Bg5g4,Bh6f5,Bf5d4][%csl Rf3]Black gambits another pawn! It's important to keep the pace in such positions. If White rejects this one, Black will swing the queen over to g6, lob Gary down the board, and relocate our knight to a more promising position. } 13. Bxg5 Qg6 14. Bxh6 { White doesn't have anything better. } ( 14. Qh3+ Kb8 15. f4 { Might seem more promising, but after } 15... Bg7 { White's bishop is stuck and the e-pawn is hanging. White dare not try to defend e5. } 16. Re1 $2 Nf5 $146 17. Qf3 Bh6 { White's position is falling apart. Once White's bishop has been removed White's position will crumble along the h and g-files. } ) 14... Bxh6 $17 { [%cal Be7e6,Bd8f8]Black should consolidate the center with ...e6 and then try to thrash White on the kingside. Be sure to avoid } ( 14... Qxh6 $2 { This allows White to get off the hook. } 15. Qh3+ Qxh3 16. gxh3 Rxh3 { White has survived and reduced the position into a roughly equal endgame. Instead, ...Bxh6 keeps the attack alive and forces White to defend a miserable position. } ) * 

