1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing Blitz against experts and advanced players, both here and with Bxc6+ first. } 4... Bg4 { [%csl Bf7,Be6,Bd5,Bc5][%cal Be7e6][%csl Re5,Rd4][%cal Bg4d1][%csl Rf3]This is congruous with my previous recommendation in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where White plays e5 after Bxc6+. Here ...Bg4 makes a great deal of sense too. Black would like to play ...e6 to enable easy kingside development and establish the central pawn chain, but to do so prematurely would be to sentence our light squared bishop to the miserable fate of the infamous 'bad French' bishop. Such would not be advantageous to Black. Therefore, we should migrate the bishop to the kingside before committing to ...e6. As an aside, this exact position has already been analyzed by IM John Bartholomew in his Chessable course on the Scandinavian Defense. The same position can be arrived at with 1... e4 1.e4 d5 2.e5!? c5 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.Bb5 Bg4! It's worth mentioning that if my recommendations here aren't agreeable to your tastes, you might benefit from checking his course out. } 5. O-O Qc7 { If White neglects to immediately repel our bishop, Black has the opportunity to target the unstable e5. } 6. Bxc6+ { This is one way to relieve the pressure on e5. } 6... Qxc6 7. h3 h5 $5 { Harry makes an aggressive advance! White certainly won't be keeping the piece if they take on g4. } 8. c3 Bxf3 { [%cal Bd1f3,Bg7g5][%csl Rc1]With c3, White prepares d4. We've seen a similar idea in chapter 5 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). In this case, Black can follow up ...Bxf3 with ...g5-g4!. } 9. Qxf3 g5 $1 { [%cal Bg5g4][%csl Rh3,Rf3]Thematic! Black intends to eventually open up the kingside files. } 10. d4 g4 $1 11. hxg4 { If } ( 11. Qd3 { , Black can close the center down with } 11... c4 12. Qe2 gxh3 13. gxh3 O-O-O { where Black has good play on the open g-file. } ) 11... hxg4 12. Qxg4 Nh6 13. Qh5 { If } ( 13. Qf3 { Black gets typical complications after } 13... O-O-O 14. Nd2 $146 Qg6 15. Qg3 { White might insist on taking this into an endgame, but after } 15... Qe6 16. Qh3 Qxh3 17. gxh3 cxd4 18. cxd4 Nf5 $146 19. Nb3 $146 Rxh3 { Black emerges with the better position. } ) 13... Qe6 $13 { [%cal Bf8g7,Bc5d4,Be8c8,Ba8d8,Bh6f5]Black prepares ...Bg7 followed by ...Nf5. The game might continue with } 14. Nd2 $146 cxd4 15. cxd4 Bg7 16. Nb3 $146 Nf5 $146 17. Qf3 O-O-O { Black fearlessly castles onto open lines! Of course, the king will eventually land on b8. Black should also be cautious of any Nc5 ideas. } 18. Bf4 Bh6 { The bishop is no longer needed on g7 and exchanging it would be favorable to Black. } 19. Rac1+ Kb8 20. Nc5 $2 $146 Nxd4 $146 21. Qd1 Qf5 22. Qxd4 Bxf4 { White is doomed. } * 

