1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension rings high! Chaos and confusion abounds! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White almost assuredly will be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. e5 { It might be surprising to hear, but I encounter this amateurish-looking move routinely while playing Blitz against experts and advanced players, both here and with Bxc6+ first. } 4... Bg4 { This is congruous with my previous recommendation in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where White plays e5 after Bxc6+. Here ...Bg4 makes a great deal of sense too. Black would like to play ...e6 to enable easy kingside development and establish the central pawn chain, but to do so prematurely would be to sentence our light squared bishop to the miserable fate of the infamous 'bad French' bishop. Such would not be advantageous to Black. Therefore, we should migrate the bishop to the kingside before committing to ...e6. As an aside, this exact position has already been analyzed by IM John Bartholomew in his Chessable course on the Scandinavian Defense. The same position can be arrived at with 1... e4 1.e4 d5 2.e5!? c5 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.Bb5 Bg4! It's worth mentioning that if my recommendations here aren't agreeable to your tastes, you might benefit from checking his course out. } 5. O-O Qc7 { If White neglects to immediately repel our bishop, Black has the opportunity to target the unstable e5. } 6. Bxc6+ { This is one way to relieve the pressure on e5. } 6... Qxc6 7. h3 h5 $5 { Harry makes an aggressive advance! White certainly won't be keeping the piece if they take on g4. } 8. d3 $1 { The best move. Similar to this line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), Black now has to take on f3. } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 { [%cal Bg8e7,Yc6d7,Be7c6,Ge7f5,Yf8e7]The h5 pawn is a bit out of place in these positions because Black isn't easily able to push for the standard ...g5-g4 break with the queen on c6 instead of d8. We can still pursue an eventual ...g5-g4, but it will take some time to coordinate our pieces in the proper configuration. } 10. Nc3 ( 10. Re1 { is what the computer likes, but nobody is playing this. More people have endeavored to start developing the queenside. } 10... Ne7 $146 { This is how we proceed against basically any move on move ten. } 11. Bg5 Nf5 $146 12. Nd2 $146 Qd7 $13 { With typical complications. } ) 10... Ne7 11. Bg5 { White could play } ( 11. Re1 { here too. } 11... Nf5 $146 { Black would love to play ...Be7 and ...g5, going into typical dynamic shenanigans. For instance, } 12. Rb1 $2 Be7 13. Bd2 g5 { Black get's a typical initiative. Hence, 12... Nf5 12.Bg5 is the best move. Stopping ...Be7. 12...Nd4 13.Qd1 Qd7! Black intends ...Be7 and also makes room for the knight to drop back to c6. 14.Ne2 Nc6 We shouldn't trade knights. Instead dropping back and targeting ...e5 looks stronger. 15.Ng3 Be7 16.Bxe7 Qxe7 17.Nxh5 White can win the h-pawn, but White would then be inviting Black to attack them. Moreover, they wouldn't even be able to retain the extra pawn. 17...Qg5! Double attack! 18.Ng3 Nxe5 19.d4 cxd4 20.Qxd4 Nc6⩱ With a double-edged middlegame. } ) 11... Qd7 $5 { [%cal Ge7c6,Gf8e7,Gc6d4]I like this move. The idea is to make room for the knight to head to c6 and then d4. After the knight leaves e7 Black also has ...Be7 ideas, where if White choses to trade we don't have to recapture on e7 with the king. } 12. Rfe1 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gc3e2]I prefer ...Nc6 to ...Nf5. While both squares are avenues that the knight can utilize to access the d4 square, from c6 the knight hits e5. Now White doesn't have Ne2 yet, and so c3-d4 will be delayed. } 13. Qg3 { Anticipating ...Nd4 and protecting e5. } 13... Nd4 { [%cal Gd4c2]White now has to address the threat on c2. } 14. Rac1 Be7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 $13 { [%cal Be8c8,Ba8d8]Black is in great shape here. Ideally, we would like to queenside castle and play for ...g5-g4. It's worth noting that we should avoid trading knights in this line, at least until we can break out with ...g5. It's worth explaining what should be done if White takes g7 while they can. } 16. Ne2 $146 ( 16. Qxg7 Kd7 { This is slightly more accurate than ...O-O-O. The reason why is that after } 17. Qf6 Qxf6 18. exf6 ( 18. Kf1 Rh6 19. Ne2 $146 Nxe2 $146 20. Rxe2 { Kd6 Black has a slight advantage. } ) 18... Rag8 { Black's king is more active on d7 than he would be on c8. The game might continue with } ) 16... Nf5 $146 { Keeping the pieces on the board offers better dynamic chances. } 17. Qf4 O-O-O { We castle here to avoid Qa4+. If White instead retreats the queen to f3, Black can strike with ...g5! immediately. } 18. Ng3 $146 { Careful not to be too eager with ...g5. Black would be wise to avoid the trade of knights. } 18... Nd4 $146 19. c3 g5 { Now is the appropriate time to strike. } 20. Qe3 Nc6 $146 21. d4 g4 { Black has the advantage. } * 

