eable to your tastes, you might benefit from checking his course out. } 5. O-O Qc7 { If White neglects to immediately repel our bishop, Black has the opportunity to target the unstable e5. } 6. c3 a6 { Black might also consider } ( 6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Qxe5 { , but White secures some initiative after } 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Qd6 10. Bf4 Qd7 { Black is fine here, but White's lead in development looks intimidating. } ) 7. Bxc6+ ( 7. Be2 $2 { hangs the e-pawn. } 7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Qxe5 { White doesn't have the activity to exploit Black's lack in development. Black should be better. } ) 7... Qxc6 8. d4 e6 $15 { Black has a promising French structure with the bishop pair, a head start on the fight for the queen side, and an active light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. While the middlegame is likely to turn on how each player attends to the queenside, there is attacking potential here, as usual. White also has been deprived of the key light-squared bishop! While this is close to equal, I would take Black any day. The game might continue with: } 9. h3 Bh5 { In this instance Black might be wise to preserve our bishop, as with the queen not on e8 our typical ...h5 & ...g5-g4 pushes become cumbersome to forcefully achieve. Moreover, take notice of the light-squared holes in White's position. } 10. Be3 c4 { Since White no longer has their light-squared bishop, closing down the center and positioning our bishop on g6 would be quite strong. } 11. b3 Ne7 $146 12. Nbd2 $146 Bg6 { The middlegame will now likely be a fight over the queenside. } * 

