1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. d4 { White sacrifices e4 to open the center. } 4... dxe4 5. Ne5 { White has to play this immediately. For instance } ( 5. Bxc6+ $2 bxc6 6. Ne5 $146 { White will lose valuable time throwing their knight around. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxc6 $146 Qd5 { 8.Nb3 Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 f5! Black's advantage is nearly decisive, having the bishop pair in a wide open position and a strong central pawn mass. } 8. Nxd4 $146 e5 ) ( 5. d5 $2 { won't cut it either. Black has time for } 5... a6 ) 5... a6 { It's important to remember the following sequence, otherwise Black probably will not survive. } 6. Nxc6 { The most popular choice by far. } 6... Qc7 $3 { The key move to remember. } 7. Na7+ $5 { We have to be a bit careful if we see this move. This line is rather concrete. } 7... axb5 8. Nxb5 Qa5+ 9. N1c3 Bd7 $7 { Careful. Any other move loses. } 10. Qe2 { If Naturally, } ( 10. a4 $2 { White takes a great risk and will be lost after } 10... Bxb5 { if they do not spot } 11. b4 $3 { In any case, after } 11... cxb4 12. Nxb5 $146 Nf6 $146 { Black has an advantage due to White's queenside weaknesses. } ) ( 10. Na3 $2 $146 { simply will not do. Black secures a potent initiative with } 10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 e5 { White cannot capture e4 due to the threat of ...Bxa3. } 12. Qe3 Bxa3 13. bxa3 Nf6 $146 14. O-O Bc6 { Resignation may be imminent. } ) 10... cxd4 { Every move forces the issue. } 11. Nxd4 e5 $1 12. Qxe4 { Humans will probably be attracted to this move, though it is slightly inaccurate. } ( 12. Nb3 $146 { is also quite natural. } 12... Qc7 13. Nxe4 $146 Nf6 $146 { Black threatens ...Nxe4 \+ ...Ra4, hence an exchange is expected. } 14. Nxf6+ $146 gxf6 15. O-O Rg8 16. Kh1 Be7 { With unclear complications. } ) 12... Nf6 13. Qe2 Bb4 { Keeping the pace. } 14. Bd2 O-O $15 { [%cal Bd4b3,Ba5b6,Ye1g1,Yh1f1,Yd7b5][%csl Re2,Rf1]Black has the favorable position, with the bishops and rooks easily able to capitalize on the open position. We can meet Nb3 with ...Qb6. White needs to be careful of kingside castling, as ...Bxc3 \+ ...Bb5 is something which could easily snatch Black an exchange. } * 

