1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. d4 { White sacrifices e4 to open the center. } 4... dxe4 5. Ne5 { White has to play this immediately. For instance } ( 5. Bxc6+ $2 bxc6 6. Ne5 $146 { White will lose valuable time throwing their knight around. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxc6 $146 Qd5 { 8.Nb3 Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 f5! Black's advantage is nearly decisive, having the bishop pair in a wide open position and a strong central pawn mass. } 8. Nxd4 $146 e5 ) ( 5. d5 $2 { won't cut it either. Black has time for } 5... a6 ) 5... a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Nxc6 $4 { This immediately loses the game. } 7... Qd5 8. Ne5 cxd4 { Tring to hold on to the knight will supply Black with a crushing initiative. For instance: } 9. Bf4 ( 9. Ng4 $2 $146 e5 { Black can easily convert by simply developing and increasing control over the center with ...f5. White's position is miserable. Any attempt to challenge the center with c3 /c4 or f3 /f4 will just gift Black a passed pawn. } ) 9... f6 $1 10. c4 { The best White has is to play for tricks. Again, trying to hold onto the knight with } ( 10. Ng4 $146 { doesn't work. } 10... Bb7 { Black stops any Ne3 tricks. ...h5 is coming next. } 11. h4 { might allow the knight to drop back safely, but after } 11... h5 12. Nh2 $146 e5 { White is just getting crushed. } ) 10... Qa5+ 11. b4 Qxb4+ 12. Bd2 Qb7 { I should emphasize the importance of dropping back to b7 specifically. If } ( 12... Qb6 $2 13. Qa4+ { Black is lost. b7 and d6 are the only squares the queen can retreat to without forfeiting the game, however b7 is the better square of the two. The upcoming line illustrates precisely why b7 is to be preferred over d6. } ) 13. Qh5+ { The surprising thing is that Black can allow all of this and is still completely winning. White might instead try } ( 13. Qa4+ Bd7 ) ( 13. Nd7 $146 Qxd7 { 14.Qxd7+ Kxd7 , but this is clearly still winning for Black. } ) 13... g6 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Qxh8 { Be careful of } ( 15. Qxg6+ { where you should play } 15... Kd7 { instead of ...Kd8 to avoid the potential bishop check. Black has a significant material advantage and should win this easy. } ) 15... Kf7 16. O-O Qb2 $19 { [%csl Ra1,Rd2,Rh8][%cal Bf8g7,Bf6f5,Bc8g4,Bb7b2]From b7 Black's queen can invade. This would be impossible if we had previously retreated the queen to d6. White is simply lost. White's queen is possibly in danger of being trapped in the corner, the rook is hanging, Black has the center, a passed pawn, and our king is totally safe. } * 

