1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension rings high! Chaos and confusion abounds! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White almost assuredly will be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. d4 { White sacrifices e4 to open the center. } 4... dxe4 5. Ne5 { White has to play this immediately. For instance } ( 5. Bxc6+ $2 bxc6 6. Ne5 $146 { White will lose valuable time throwing their knight around. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxc6 $146 Qd5 { 8.Nb3 Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 f5! Black's advantage is nearly decisive, having the bishop pair in a wide open position and a strong central pawn mass. } 8. Nxd4 $146 e5 ) ( 5. d5 $2 { won't cut it either. Black has time for } 5... a6 ) 5... a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. dxc5 { [%cal Bd1d8][%csl Rd8][%cal Be8d8]White dreams of tactical ideas. Such fantasies are mere illusions. } 7... Qd5 { Targeting White's poorly placed knight. } 8. Qxd5 $7 { Fortunately for us, this is forced. For instance, if White tries to save the knight: Or, Also, } ( 8. Ng4 $2 $146 { Black wins with } 8... Qxd1+ { followed by 9...Bxg4 } ) ( 8. Bf4 f6 9. Qxd5 cxd5 10. Nc6 $146 e5 11. Bg3 Bxc5 { White's position is hopeless. } ) ( 8. f4 { just gives us a passed pawn for free } 8... f6 { Black wins with similar ideas. } ) 8... cxd5 9. c4 e6 10. Nc3 { If } ( 10. b4 { Black can respond with } 10... Ne7 $146 11. Nc3 $146 f6 12. Ng4 $146 d4 13. Nxe4 $146 { Black prepares either ...f5 or h5 with } 13... Nc6 $146 { where White will lose a piece. } ) 10... Bxc5 11. cxd5 Nf6 { [%cal Bc8e6]White can restore material balance by capturing the pawn, but doing so will contribute to Black's development. } 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. O-O Rc8 $1 { [%cal Be5c6][%csl Rc6,Re5]Stopping any Nc6 ideas. White's knight is now beginning to look stuck. } 14. Re1 $6 { If White is targeting e4 like this, they clearly fail to perceive the current danger that their knight is in. } ( 14. Rd1 { would be more in tune with the demands of the position. e5 May still be a target, so Black can follow up by preventing Bg5 with } 14... h6 15. Bf4 O-O 16. h3 Rfe8 17. Rac1 g5 18. Be3 Kg7 { Black is in excellent shape here. White's knight is still at risk of being trapped. } ) 14... Bd4 $1 15. Bf4 g5 $1 { Black surges forth with ...g5! once again! White endeavoring to secure the precariously positioned knight only enables Black to obtain an initiative on the kingside. } 16. Bg3 h5 $17 { Black is dangerously close to winning. Let's suppose White continues with the sensible looking Alternatively, } 17. h3 { to see what sort of position we can expect to result from such complications. } ( 17. h4 { might also be attempted. } 17... gxh4 18. Bf4 Bxc3 19. bxc3 h3 { Black's initiative looks intimidating. White might try to close up the kingside with } 20. g3 { , but after } 20... O-O 21. Bg5 Ng4 $146 22. Nxg4 $146 hxg4 23. Rxe4 Rxc3 24. Rd1 Rb8 { Black's advantage is nearly decisive. White's king will probably never find the opportunity to withdraw from his miserable post, otherwise White risks allowing Harry to promote. Black should consider trying to exchange a single rook and then use the king to go pursue White's a-pawn. } ) 17... h4 18. Bh2 O-O { Trading e4 for b2 looks favorable to Black. } 19. Nxe4 $146 Nxe4 $146 20. Rxe4 Bxb2 21. Rd1 Rfd8 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 { Now White has to worry about the back rank. } 23. Re1 Bxa2 { With accurate play, Black should win this. } * 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.Qe2 - What Makes This Variation Troubling?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Qe2 - What Makes This Variation Troubling?"]
[Black "11) Sidelines 3 of 6 | 4.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

3... d5 4. Qe2 $1 { After extensive analysis, I have concluded that Qe2 is possibly the greatest annoyance Black might encounter after 3...d5. After Qe2, Black has little chance of introducing promising dynamic complications. This approach is a direct antidote to the strategic outlook we've adopted from the outset. Of course, it might be asked: What is it specifically about 4.Qe2 which precludes Black from introducing the sort of chaos which we have so ardently pursued up to this point? Well, with White's queen now blocking the e-file, the exigent threat of exd5 is one which Black simply cannot ignore. In the 4.exd5 lines (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), Black complicates matters after 4... d5 4.exd5 Qxd5 5.Nc3 Qe6+ , but with the queen on e2 Black no longer has recourse to the essential ...Qe6+, which in the corresponding variations grants Black the time required to complicate the position and obfuscate the evaluation. With White's threat of exd5, suddenly Black is the one who must scrounge up defensive resources to hold the position together. One might think to exchange on e4, but 3. d5 4...dxe4?! is rightly met with 5.Bxc6+ bxc6 Qxe4 , where White's advantage would be universally acknowledged. Therefore, if White understands the nature of the position and proceeds accordingly, Black has nothing better than to defensively react to the mounting pressure on d5. My recommendation, 3. d5 4...Bg4 , numbs the sting from the immediate 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Nc3 , as now Black has 6...Bxf3! or ...Qd7, and emerges with an equal position. But because Black must address the exd5 threat, nothing can be done to prevent White from fragmenting the queenside structure. Looking back, 3. d5 the immediate 5.Nc3 renews the exd5 threat, and after 5...Nf6 6.exd5 Nxd5 7.h3 Bxf3 8.Qxf3 e6 9.Bxc6+ bxc6 we arrive at a simple position where White has an edge due to the damaged queenside structure. What concerns me is that if these are the sorts of positions we can expect to result from Qe2, Black is going to be quite bored! White is probably going to try to exchange everything and slowly play against Black's queenside weaknesses. I have managed to scrounge up some interesting dynamic counterplay in some lines but in others the positions are quite dry. Here are some other positions we might encounter after Qe2: 4. Qe2 \-- 4\. Qe2 \-- etc. Of course, it might be astutely noted that there are other continuations scattered throughout the course which resemble these positions and which are equally as boring. This I readily concede. What troubles me about the 4.Qe2 variations specifically is that almost every variation rapidly simplifies into alike positions. I endeavored to find continuations which lead to dynamic play, but for the most part was unable to produce anything noteworthy. This chapter is most certainly the least interesting of the entire course. Anyways, though 4.Qe2 might be regarded in this way to be somewhat troubling, perhaps it is within reason to suggest that on a practical level its mere existence is insufficient to warrant the concern of those who proudly brandish our beloved cannon. At the time of writing, the Lichess database indicates that 4.Qe2 is seen in a vanishingly small percentage of games. My experience certainly attests to the paucity of this line too; I have not once encountered this move in my hundreds of games experimenting with the Ferguson's Cannon variation. This metric is most certainly liable to change, and perhaps will do so as a result of publishing this course, but as it currently stands the infrequency with which Qe2 is chosen should allay our misgivings about this response, at least to some extent. } * 

