1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Qe2 { 4...-- 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Nc3 , where Black doesn't have the check on e6 due to the fortunate position of White's queen. 4. Qe2 4...Bg4! reduces the sting of 5.exd5 , as now 5...Qxd5 6.Nc3 can be met with 6...Bxf3 , or even ...Qd7. } 4... Bg4 { As stated in the introductory notice to this chapter, 4.Qe2 is an exceptionally annoying move to encounter. It's extremely easy for White to simplify the position from here and the upcoming continuations certainly don't have much dynamic merit, at least relative to what can be found in the rest of this course. Anyways, after Qe2 White was threatening to secure a remarkable initiative with } 5. O-O Rc8 { If White doesn't capitalize on the opportunity to fragment our queenside structure, we disallow them from doing so altogether. } 6. d3 { Or if } ( 6. h3 { , Black is doing fine after } 6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 dxe4 8. Qxe4 Nf6 $10 $146 ) 6... e6 7. c4 dxe4 { Taking on c4 is fine too. } 8. dxe4 Bd6 9. Rd1 Qc7 10. h3 Bxf3 { As usual, we exchange the bishop on f3 when prompted by h3. Deciding to keep the bishop would be a grave error. } ( 10... Bh5 $2 11. g4 Bg6 12. e5 Be7 { Black's army is cramped and has no play. White's advantage is decisive. } ) 11. Qxf3 Ne7 $10 { [%cal Ba7a6,Yb5c6,Ye7c6][%csl Rc6][%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8,Bf8d8][%csl Rd4,Yb5]Black will play ...a6, castle, and challenge White on the d-file. Black should also try to maintain control over e5. White does indeed have a space advantage, but d4 is a positional weakness and the bishop is awkwardly placed. Black has a slight edge here. } * 

