1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Qe2 { 4...-- 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Nc3 , where Black doesn't have the check on e6 due to the fortunate position of White's queen. 4. Qe2 4...Bg4! reduces the sting of 5.exd5 , as now 5...Qxd5 6.Nc3 can be met with 6...Bxf3 , or even ...Qd7. } 4... Bg4 { As stated in the introductory notice to this chapter, 4.Qe2 is an exceptionally annoying move to encounter. It's extremely easy for White to simplify the position from here and the upcoming continuations certainly don't have much dynamic merit, at least relative to what can be found in the rest of this course. Anyways, after Qe2 White was threatening to secure a remarkable initiative with } 5. h3 { White immediately challenges our pin. } 5... Bxf3 { As usual, we exchange the bishop on f3 when prompted by h3. Being efficient with our time is crucial. } 6. Qxf3 e6 7. Nc3 { One might also encounter } ( 7. Bxc6+ { , and after } 7... bxc6 8. O-O Bd6 9. d3 Ne7 $146 { Black is fine. If Black manages to eventually land ...e5, ...f5, or both, dynamic opportunities may just start to emerge. Still, it seems like a somewhat worse version of the positions found in chapter 4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 7... Nf6 8. exd5 { If White tries something slower like } ( 8. d3 { or O-O, Black has time for ...Rc8. } ) ( 8. e5 { might also be encountered, but we've already seen that White often gets into trouble after e5 in these structures. } 8... Nd7 $146 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Qg3 g5 { Black stops f4. If White insists on this after } 11. d3 Be7 12. f4 $2 gxf4 { , now } 13. Qxf4 { is forced. White will subsequently lose e5 after } 13... Qc7 { followed by ...Nxe5. } ) 8... exd5 9. O-O Be7 10. d3 O-O $13 { Black has superior control of the center and slightly better development. Additionally, White would be wise to tread with caution. A decent amount of players have landed themselves in a lost position after } 11. Bg5 $2 Nd4 $146 12. Qf4 a6 { The bishop is getting trapped. } 13. Ba4 b5 14. Bb3 Ne6 $146 { an important intermezzo! } 15. Qh4 Nxg5 $146 16. Qxg5 c4 { White has permission to resign. } * 

