ent with our time is crucial. } 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxf3 Nxe4 { [%cal Bc3e4,Bd5e4,Bf3e4,Rd8d5][%csl Re4]Black seeks compensation for the dismal state of his ruinous queenside structure. After ...Nxe4, Black can try to induce similar structural deficiencies upon White's kingside. One might also consider } ( 8... e6 9. d3 Bd6 10. O-O O-O { if you prefer more typical looking middlegames. } ) 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Qxe4 Qd5 11. d3 { Alternatively, if White tries } ( 11. f3 $2 { the kingside becomes riddled with dark squared holes. } 11... g6 12. O-O Bg7 { Black's bishop is a magnificent piece. Both the queen and bishop exert great pressure on White's queenside. } 13. Re1 e6 14. Rb1 c4 { Black has sufficient play in these lines. } ) 11... f5 $1 { [%cal Bd5g2][%csl Rg2]If the queen moves anywhere apart from f3, g2 drops. Now White must choose between either repairing Black's structure with } 12. Qxd5 cxd5 { , or allowing their structure to suffer as ours has with 12... f5 12.Qf3 Qxf3 13.gxf3 In either case, Black's situation is acceptable. } * 

