1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Qe2 { 4...-- 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Nc3 , where Black doesn't have the check on e6 due to the fortunate position of White's queen. 4. Qe2 4...Bg4! reduces the sting of 5.exd5 , as now 5...Qxd5 6.Nc3 can be met with 6...Bxf3 , or even ...Qd7. } 4... Bg4 { As stated in the introductory notice to this chapter, 4.Qe2 is an exceptionally annoying move to encounter. It's extremely easy for White to simplify the position from here and the upcoming continuations certainly don't have much dynamic merit, at least relative to what can be found in the rest of this course. Anyways, after Qe2 White was threatening to secure a remarkable initiative with } 5. Nc3 Nf6 { Black must respond to the renewed threat on d5. } ( 5... d4 $2 { doesn't offer promising results. } 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Na4 $146 { White can play b3 \+ Ba3 and has a much better version of the 6.O-O with 7.b3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) variations. } ) 6. h3 Bxf3 { As usual, we exchange the bishop on f3 when prompted by h3. Being efficient with our time is crucial. } 7. Qxf3 Nxe4 { With the queen on f3, exd5 becomes a live threat again. } 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Qxe4 Rc8 $10 { [%cal Bc8c6,Ba7a6,Be7e6,Bd8d4,Bd4a1][%csl Ra1]If White doesn't capitalize on the opportunity to fragment our queenside structure, we disallow them from doing so altogether. Needless to say, this position is not very exciting. Black is doing fine though and has the typical ...a6 \+ ...e6 ideas. One might also consider ...Qd4 at the right moment. } * 

