1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Qe2 { 4...-- 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Nc3 , where Black doesn't have the check on e6 due to the fortunate position of White's queen. 4. Qe2 4...Bg4! reduces the sting of 5.exd5 , as now 5...Qxd5 6.Nc3 can be met with 6...Bxf3 , or even ...Qd7. } 4... Bg4 { As stated in the introductory notice to this chapter, 4.Qe2 is an exceptionally annoying move to encounter. It's extremely easy for White to simplify the position from here and the upcoming continuations certainly don't have much dynamic merit, at least relative to what can be found in the rest of this course. Anyways, after Qe2 White was threatening to secure a remarkable initiative with } 5. Nc3 Nf6 { Black must respond to the renewed threat on d5. } ( 5... d4 $2 { doesn't offer promising results. } 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Na4 $146 { White can play b3 \+ Ba3 and has a much better version of the 6.O-O with 7.b3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) variations. } ) 6. exd5 { This is one way White can simplify the position. Unfortunately, there isn't much to say about these lines. All the moves just follow naturally from those which precede, resulting in quiet and somewhat dry positions. } 6... Nxd5 7. h3 Bxf3 { As usual, we exchange the bishop on f3 when prompted by h3. Being efficient with our time is crucial. It's worth noting that previously White could play 7... Nxd5 7.Qe4 instead of h3. Black response does not change. 7...Bxf3 8.Qxf3 e6 This doesn't alter the evaluation at all and the resulting positions are identical in all respects apart from inclusion of the pawn sitting on h3. } 8. Qxf3 e6 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Qxd5 exd5 $10 { [%cal Be8c8,Ba8d8,Bf8d6,Bf7f5,Yc8c7]We've arrived at a position which resembles 4.Qe2 with 5.h3 #1 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), only with less pieces on the board. White has the bishops but Black has a space advantage and better control over the center. The evaluation is equal. } * 

