1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Qe2 Bg4 { As stated in the introductory notice to this chapter, 4.Qe2 is an exceptionally annoying move to encounter. It's extremely easy for White to simplify the position from here and the upcoming continuations certainly don't have much dynamic merit, at least relative to what can be found in the rest of this course. White threatens to take d5, where after exd5 ...Qxd5 Nc3, Black doesn't have Qe6+ because White's queen blocks e file. } 5. Nc3 Nf6 { Black must respond to the renewed threat on d5. } 6. exd5 { This is one way White can simplify the position. Unfortunately, there isn't much to say about these lines. All the moves just follow naturally from those which precede, resulting in quiet and somewhat dry positions. } 6... Nxd5 7. h3 Bxf3 { As usual, we exchange the bishop on f3 when prompted by h3. Being efficient with our time is crucial. } 8. Qxf3 e6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 { Unfortunately, in keeping up with the pressure on d5 Black has allowed the queenside structure to suffer. White is usually slightly better in these positions, but Black is still somewhat solid. On another note, if Black can eventually land ...e5, ...f5, and a well-timed ...c4, dynamic opportunities just might start to appear on the horizon. } 10. O-O Bd6 11. Ne4 Bc7 { It's important to keep pieces on the board while we have weaknesses which can be easily exploited in a simpler position. } 12. c4 { [%cal Bd5e7,Be7f5]Apparently this is the best move. However, now d4 is a positional hole. One idea is to try to reroute our knight there via e7-f5 at the right moment. } ( 12. d3 { leads to more typical positions. } 12... O-O { ...f5 is a possibility, but involves a high degree of precision. It might benefit Black to avoid it if possible. } 13. Bg5 f6 14. Bh4 Rb8 $10 { Apparently this is equal. Black should have sufficient play. } ) ( 12. Nxc5 $2 $146 { The c-pawn is untouchable for now. } 12... Qd6 $19 { White loses a piece, at least. } ) ( 12. b3 { allows } 12... f5 13. Ng3 $146 O-O 14. Ba3 Bd6 15. Rae1 e5 $15 { Suddenly Black is slightly better. } ) 12... Ne7 13. d3 ( 13. b3 f5 { Seems like this move is the common denominator in all these lines. Black probably will end up being significantly worse without it. } 14. Ng5 $146 Qd6 { With the knight gone from e4, our queen can contribute to the battery! The position is about to get messy. } 15. Re1 e5 { This move is the only one which saves Black. The upcoming line is extremely double-edged. } 16. Qh5+ Ng6 $146 17. Bb2 Qf6 18. Nxh7 $2 $146 Qf7 19. Qf3 { This is all very computer-ish. Don't expect to encounter this. It's a fun line though. } 19... O-O-O 20. Qxc6 Rxh7 21. Bxe5 Nxe5 $146 22. Rxe5 Kb8 $13 { There's probably a repetition on the horizon. } ) 13... O-O { [%cal Yf7f5]Don't be too hasty with ...Nf5. Breaking with ...f5 is crucial in some positions. } 14. Be3 { White targets c5. } 14... f5 $1 { Black doesn't have a viable means of defending c5, so lunging forth with ...f5 is a necessity. The computer's idea here is quite ingenious actually. } 15. Nxc5 Qd6 { [%cal Gc7h2]With the knight no longer covering d6, Black can produce a battery. } 16. g3 f4 $1 { [%cal Gf7f5,Gf5f4]The point. Black is finally getting some dynamic counterplay! } 17. gxf4 Ng6 $13 { [%csl Rd3,Rc5,Rf4,Rh3]The position has been transformed! Suddenly White also has a number of positional pressure points! Black threatens ...Nxf4, which would be crushing if allowed. White has a number of resources to counter this threat though. For instance, with } 18. Qg4 { White issues their own threat. } 18... Rae8 19. d4 Nxf4 $146 20. Kh1 { These positions are extremely sharp. White is up a pawn, but their king is weak. Black seems to be getting good play in this line. } * 

