s is to bring the bishop to d6, the knight to e7, and to expand with ...f5 after getting castled. } 8. d3 Bd6 9. O-O Ne7 10. c4 O-O 11. Nd2 ( 11. Nc3 $146 { instead allows } 11... d4 12. Na4 $146 Ng6 $146 { , where Black gets some quality kingside counterplay. ...f5 is incoming. ...e5 has some merit to it too. } ) 11... f5 $13 { [%cal Bd8d7,Ba8e8,Rf5e4,Ye6e5,Ye7g6]Black is now threatening ...fxe4. Naturally, White might respond with One tricky idea to be aware of is } 12. Qe2 { , where } ( 12. e5 $2 Bxe5 13. Qe2 { White goes straight for our weak e-pawn. Black can try to hold on to the pawn, but the defense won't last long. } 13... Qd6 14. Re1 Ng6 $146 15. Nf3 $146 { and now Black is forced to return the pawn. } 15... Bf4 16. Qxe6+ Qxe6 17. Rxe6 Bxc1 18. Rxc1 Nf4 $146 { The key move. White doesn't have Rxc6 due to ...Ne2+ and therefore the rook must remain on the e-file. } 19. Re7 Rf7 20. Rxf7 Kxf7 $10 ) 12... e5 { would be a sensible rejoinder. Black's setup should be familiar to those already acquainted with the positions analyzed in chapter four (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Black might consider ...Ng6 at some point to allow some imbalances to creep into the position. Also worth noting is a well-timed ...fxe4 followed by ...d4 might be beneficial to Black. The passed pawn can be a valuable asset in certain positions. } * 

