1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Qe2 { 4...-- 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Nc3 , where Black doesn't have the check on e6 due to the fortunate position of White's queen. 4. Qe2 4...Bg4! reduces the sting of 5.exd5 , as now 5...Qxd5 6.Nc3 can be met with 6...Bxf3 , or even ...Qd7. } 4... Bg4 { As stated in the introductory notice to this chapter, 4.Qe2 is an exceptionally annoying move to encounter. It's extremely easy for White to simplify the position from here and the upcoming continuations certainly don't have much dynamic merit, at least relative to what can be found in the rest of this course. Anyways, after Qe2 White was threatening to secure a remarkable initiative with } 5. Bxc6+ { The exchange on c6 is always a resource White can avail themselves of. } 5... bxc6 6. d3 { Simply defending the center and opening up the path for the queenside pieces to develop. White is now able to play Nbd2 before hitting the bishop with h3. } 6... Nf6 { Sensible development. A simple alternative is ...Bxf3, capturing the knight before White has a chance to play Nbd2. There is some practical merit to this idea, so I will offer it as an alternative. White can acquire both a theoretical and practical advantage after ...Bxf3 if they know what they're doing, so ...Nf6 is the objectively preferable move. I don't particularly like either option in all honesty, largely because I dislike much of the 4.Qe2 lines more generally, but it's extremely unlikely that this variation will be encountered in the wild, so I'm not really worried. } 7. Nbd2 { [%cal Bh2h3]If } ( 7. h3 { Black will exchange, as per usual, } 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 { and should eventually play for ...e5, for instance: } 8... e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Qc7 11. Nd2 $146 O-O 12. Qe2 Nd7 $146 13. Nf3 $146 f6 14. Bd2 Rae8 { White has a slight edge. If 9... e6 9.Bg5 Black can get by sacrificing a pawn 9...Qb8! 10.Bxf6 gxf6 11.Qxf6 Rg8 Black has ...Bg7 and ...Rg6/Rxg2 in the cards and has sufficient play. } ) 7... e5 { This is probably the only line after 6.d3 where Black can get away with an early ...e5, though it may come at the expense of a pawn. } 8. h3 { Don't be afraid to give up the pawn if instead White opts for } ( 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Qxe5+ Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Bd6 $10 { Black's activity makes up for the pawn. } ) 8... Bxf3 { Typical. } 9. Nxf3 { Or, } ( 9. Qxf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Qd6 { with a slight advantage to White. } ) 9... Bd6 { [%cal Be8g8,Bh8f8]Defending e5 and preparing ...O-O. Once again, don't fear the sacrifice. } 10. O-O ( 10. exd5 cxd5 11. Nxe5 $146 ( 11. O-O Qe7 { 12.f4 Nd7 } 12. Re1 { Rfe8 14.Qf2 Nxe5 15.fxe5 Bxe5= On top of the restoration of material equality, notice that the queenside structure has also been repaired. } ) 11... O-O { Black will eventually get the pawn back. } ) 10... O-O 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 Qe7 $13 { [%cal Be7e6,Gf6d7,Yf8e8,Yf7f6,Gd7f8,Ya8b8]Black's idea is to play ...Qe6 to break the pin and then ...Rfe8 and ...Nd7 to support the center. With the f-pawn freed, we might consider ...f6 to support e5 even further, at which point we could slowly maneuver the knight to e6 via ...Nd7-f8-e6. Black is slightly worse, but can secure solidity with an appropriate approach. } * 

