1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Qe2 { 4...-- 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Nc3 , where Black doesn't have the check on e6 due to the fortunate position of White's queen. 4. Qe2 4...Bg4! reduces the sting of 5.exd5 , as now 5...Qxd5 6.Nc3 can be met with 6...Bxf3 , or even ...Qd7. } 4... Bg4 { As stated in the introductory notice to this chapter, 4.Qe2 is an exceptionally annoying move to encounter. It's extremely easy for White to simplify the position from here and the upcoming continuations certainly don't have much dynamic merit, at least relative to what can be found in the rest of this course. Anyways, after Qe2 White was threatening to secure a remarkable initiative with } 5. Bxc6+ { The exchange on c6 is always a resource White can avail themselves of. } 5... bxc6 6. d3 { Simply defending the center and opening up the path for the queenside pieces to develop. White is now able to play Nbd2 before hitting the bishop with h3. } 6... Bxf3 { [%csl Re5]Unlike most other circumstances, here Black might benefit from capturing the knight without being prompted to do so by h3. If we don't take now White can cover f3 with Nbd2, which would allow them to recapture on f3 with the knight rather than the queen once an exchange is induced with h3. With the knight on f3, White would be able to control the critical e5 square with much greater ease. These lines aren't so great for us. Next we will lock the pawn chain with ...e6, develop our kingside, and get castled. } 7. Qxf3 e6 8. O-O Bd6 { [%cal Bg8e7,Bf7f5,Ye7g6]The setup I tend to like in these positions is with the bishop on d6 and with the knight on e7. With the knight not blocking the f-pawn, Black will eventually break with ...f5. The knight might come to g6. Generally, White is simply a bit better after 6.d3. Fair enough. Nobody denies that 3...d5 is questionable, so there will be holes. The following line will stand as a sample continuation on what one might encounter from here. } 9. Nc3 { The most common move. Probably the most testing line is } ( 9. Qe2 { aiming for a quick f4. I'm thinking this won't be very common though. } 9... Ne7 $146 10. f4 O-O 11. Nd2 $146 { The best move, but everyone is playing Nc3 instead. Nd2 is better because it doesn't clog up the long diagonal, so White leaves open the possibility of continuing with b3 and Bb2. } 11... Ng6 $146 12. g3 f5 13. e5 Bc7 { Black is just worse, make no bones about it! } ) 9... Ne7 10. Bf4 { If White attempts to play for e5 with Or, after } ( 10. Qe2 { Black has } 10... e5 { Of course, White can still try to push for an advantage with } 11. exd5 cxd5 12. f4 { , but once again our favorite } 12... f6 { adds an unclear twist to the position. } ) ( 10. Re1 { Black doesn't have e5 right away due to the pressure on d5, so instead Black should simply respond with } 10... O-O { White could now play } 11. e5 { , but after } 11... Bc7 12. Na4 $146 Ng6 $146 13. Qh5 Qb8 { White has no viable way of keeping e5 alive. } ) 10... Bxf4 { [%cal Be7g6][%csl Rf4]Exchanging bishops and following up with ..Ng6 seems like a sensible plan. } 11. Qxf4 Ng6 12. Qg3 O-O 13. f4 f5 $1 { [%cal Ba8b8,Bd8a5,Rc5c4]Both sides seem to have decent play in this middlegame. When the central tension has been resolved, or if the center happens to close down, playing on the queenside looks like a natural way to continue. We have the b-file for one of our rooks and might look to play ...c4 at an opportune moment. } * 

