1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. Ne5 { Ne5 is not played often, but isn't a bad move by any means. } 4... Qd6 { I find that this is Black's best option. We force White to make a decision. } 5. Nxc6 $6 { In my estimation, the possible capture on c6 with the knight is a risky move to make, especially considering the vulnerability of the e4 pawn. } 5... bxc6 6. Ba4 { [%cal Ba4e8]Giving up e4 but maintaining the pin. } 6... dxe4 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. O-O $5 Ng4 $1 { And White is already forced to make positional concessions. } 9. g3 Ne5 { [%cal Be5f3,Bc8g4,Bg4d1]Now we can direct our forces to begin to exploit White's weaknesses. Practically speaking, I like Black's attacking chances here. Stockfish judges that White's best defense is to attempt to open the center with d3, effectively allowing the intrusion of Black's army, which is good news for us. } 10. d3 { Note that } ( 10. Nxe4 $2 $146 { loses to } 10... Qd4 11. Nc3 $2 $146 Bg4 { where White will lose the queen. } ) 10... Nf3+ 11. Kh1 ( 11. Kg2 $2 { is met by } 11... Qe6 { where White cannot prevent us from entering on h3 } 12. Nxe4 $2 $146 Qh3+ 13. Kxf3 Bg4+ { and White has permission to resign. } ) 11... Bg4 { [%cal Bd6g6,Bg6h5,Bh5h2,Ba8d8,Bd8d1,Be7e5]Black is now threatening ...Qg6-h5. White is on the defense. } 12. dxe4 Qg6 13. h3 h5 { Black has excellent attacking prospects from here. I'll give the following line as an example of the sort of sharp attack one can expect from this variation. } 14. Qd5 { If White doesn't do something active, Black can just stabilize his position with ...Rc8 and then crush White with ideas of ...h4 or even ...Bxh3 if White ever moves the queen. } 14... Bd7 15. Qxc5 e5 { [%cal Bf8c5]} 16. Qe3 Qg4 $5 { Quite a move, this! Positioning our beloved queen right at the tip of our opponent's blade! White has no choice but to take, which makes it all the more devious. Although, arguably stronger is } ( 16... Bxh3 17. Qxf3 Bxf1 18. Be3 Bh3 { where the bishop will return to g4 and Harry will run down the board. Both are excellent, but ...Qg4 is more startling. } ) 17. hxg4 ( 17. Kg2 $2 { results in mate. } 17... Qxh3+ 18. Kxf3 Bg4# ) 17... hxg4+ 18. Qh6 $7 gxh6 19. Be3 h5 $19 { [%cal Bh5h4,Bf8h6,Be8e7]This position is horrible for White and the attack isn't even over yet. } * 

