1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. d3 Qa5+ { [%cal Ba5b5,Ba5e1][%csl Rb5]While it certainly appears as though Black will emerge up a piece after ...Qa5+, and although White often prematurely buys into this deception, White has a crafty way to escape certain doom. There is some venom to this 4.d3 line. } 5. Nc3 d4 6. b4 $7 { [%csl Gc3,Gb5][%cal Bb4a5][%csl Ra5]The only move! White has to complicate matters to gain the time required to adequately attend to the exigent circumstances. } 6... cxb4 { Avoid taking with the queen. White gets too strong an initiative after } ( 6... Qxb4 $2 7. Rb1 Qa5 8. Ne5 $146 { Now Black is the one in danger. } 8... Bd7 9. Nc4 $146 Qd8 10. Nd5 $146 { This looks pretty miserable. } ) 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Ne2 e5 $15 { [%cal Bf8d6,Bf7f6,Bg8e7,Be7g6,Bg6f4,Bc6c5]Black has a space advantage, the bishop pair, and is up a pawn. } * 

