1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. d3 Qa5+ { [%cal Ba5b5][%csl Rb5][%cal Ba5e1]While it certainly appears as though Black will emerge up a piece after ...Qa5+, and although White often prematurely buys into this deception, White has a crafty way to escape certain doom. There is some venom to this 4.d3 line. } 5. Nc3 d4 6. b4 $7 { The only move! White has to complicate matters to gain the time required to adequately attend to the exigent circumstances. } 6... cxb4 { Avoid taking with the queen. White gets too strong an initiative after } ( 6... Qxb4 $2 7. Rb1 Qa5 8. Ne5 $146 { Now Black is the one in danger. } 8... Bd7 9. Nc4 $146 Qd8 10. Nd5 $146 { This looks pretty miserable. } ) 7. Ne5 { [%cal Bb5e8]I doubt you'll encounter this move, but might as well be prepared for it given that it's the whole point of b4. White now has the time to introduce threats. } 7... b3 $5 { Chaos ensues once again! I assume you're wondering about why Black isn't playing the more natural looking } ( 7... bxc3 $2 { This was my initial preference, but Black's position begins to look grim after } 8. Qh5 $3 g6 9. Nxc6 $146 gxh5 10. Nxa5+ $146 Bd7 { Black might be able to hold this, but it doesn't look promising. } ) 8. Nxc6 { The following sequence is pretty much forced. } 8... bxc6 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Bxa8 Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 bxc2 $1 { [%cal Rd1c1,Rc3d3][%csl Rd3]An essential addition which simplifies the position. Now the defender of d3 has been eliminated. White can keep queens on the board, but at the cost of another pawn. Alternatively, allowing the queen trade results in a favorable exchange for Black. } 12. Bxc3 cxd1=Q+ 13. Kxd1 dxc3 14. Rb1 { This is a must. Other moves allow the immediate ...e5 followed by ...Bd6, where the White rook no longer can invade on the back rank. } 14... e6 15. Rb8+ Ke7 16. Kc2 g5 $13 { [%cal Bf8g7,Bg8f6]While White does have some pressure, Black has emerged with two minor pieces for the rook. Both sides have chances here. } * 

