1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. d3 Qa5+ { [%cal Ba5b5][%csl Rb5][%cal Ba5e1]While it certainly appears as though Black will emerge up a piece after ...Qa5+, and although White often prematurely buys into this deception, White has a crafty way to escape certain doom. There is some venom to this 4.d3 line. } 5. Nc3 d4 6. b4 $7 { The only move! White has to complicate matters to gain the time required to adequately attend to the exigent circumstances. } 6... cxb4 { Avoid taking with the queen. White gets too strong an initiative after } ( 6... Qxb4 $2 7. Rb1 Qa5 8. Ne5 $146 { Now Black is the one in danger. } 8... Bd7 9. Nc4 $146 Qd8 10. Nd5 $146 { This looks pretty miserable. } ) 7. Ne5 { I doubt you'll encounter this move, but might as well be prepared for it given that it's the whole point of b4. White now has the time to introduce threats. } 7... b3 $5 { Chaos ensues once again! I assume you're wondering about why Black isn't playing the more natural looking } ( 7... bxc3 $2 { This was my initial preference, but Black's position begins to look grim after } 8. Qh5 $3 g6 9. Nxc6 $146 gxh5 10. Nxa5+ $146 Bd7 { Black might be able to hold this, but it doesn't look promising. } ) 8. Nxc6 { The following sequence is pretty much forced. } 8... bxc6 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Bxa8 Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 bxc2 { [%cal Rc3d3][%csl Rd3][%cal Rd1c1][%csl Rc1]An essential addition which simplifies the position. Now the defender of d3 has been eliminated. White can keep queens on the board, but at the cost of another pawn. Alternatively, allowing the queen trade results in a favorable exchange for Black. } 12. Qc1 Qxd3 13. a4 $7 { a4 is effectively forced. Black was threatening ...Bb5, which if allowed would likely end the game on the spot. } ( 13. e5 $2 { technically keeps White alive too, but after } 13... e6 { the bishops will fly in. } ) 13... e5 $13 { [%cal Bf8d6,Bg8f6][%csl Rd2,Re1,Rc1,Ra1,Ra8]While it's true that Black is an exchange down, we have some some notable compensation. The game might continue with } 14. Ra2 Nf6 $146 15. Qxc2 { Maybe White's advantage will be directly apparent once the endgame arrives. Maybe not. Black has a passed pawn. } 15... Qxc2 16. Rxc2 Bd6 17. Ke2 Ke7 18. Bc6 Bxc6 19. Rxc6 Nxe4 $146 20. Rb1 Ke6 { Black's center is quite formidable here. It doesn't look easy for White to break through. } 21. Rb5 Nxd2 $146 22. Kxd2 e4 { Black prevents Kd3. This endgame is unclear. White probably is slightly better with perfect play, but Black's central potential certainly should not be neglected either. I could see this going either way. } * 

