1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. O-O dxe4 { White gambits e4. The themes are the same between this variation and the ones in chapter eight and chapter twelve. } 5. Ne5 Qd6 { We almost always play ...Qd6 in response to an early Ne5. } 6. Nc4 ( 6. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 { will most probably transpose to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Of course the key difference is that Bc4 is available to White. After } 7. Bc4 Nf6 $146 8. Nc3 $146 Ng4 $146 { Black induces light-squared weaknesses. This is still quite similar to the line in the previous link. } 9. g3 Ne5 $146 10. Be2 Bf5 { Black's position is more than acceptable. } ) ( 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Nc4 $146 Qg6 { will most probably transpose to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 6... Qg6 7. d3 { [%cal Be4d3,Rb5c6,Bg6c6,Rd1d3]White breaks in the center. The idea is to draw Black into taking on d3 as a means of opening up the center, then to pull Black's queen away from her kingside post with Bxc6+ to delay potential kingside dangers involving ...Bh3 and to enable the recapture on d3 without having the queenside structure pulled apart. A clever idea. } 7... exd3 8. Bxc6+ Qxc6 9. Qxd3 Nf6 { [%cal Bg7g6,Be8g8,Bf8g7,Bh8f8]With the open center Black should focus on getting the king castled. } 10. Rd1 Be6 11. Ne5 Qc8 $5 { [%cal Bc5c4]The queen remains on the c-file so that we can play ...c4. } 12. Nc3 { We shouldn't be worried about any checks on b5. } ( 12. Qb5+ $2 Nd7 $146 13. Nxd7 $146 Bxd7 { This is slightly better for Black. } ) 12... c4 13. Qf3 g6 $15 { [%cal Be8g8,Bf8g7,Bh8f8,Bf6h5,Bb7b5,Bc8b7]Black has a small edge here. We have the bishops and slightly more space, plus White's knight on e5 is a little bit awkward. It could get trapped if White is not careful. Black will continue with ...Bg7, castle, and might throw in ...Nh5 to force White to come up with a way to address the threat on their knight. Black might also consider ...b5 and ...Qb7 soon to gain space and open up the queenside. } * 

