1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 { Boom! Ferguson's Cannon discharges! Lines have opened up! Tension runs high! Chaos and confusion abound! As I've always passionately maintained, one surprisingly effective route to securing victory in chess is to establish an advantage in the psychological domain. With 3...d5, White will almost assuredly be out of book. Dispossessed of the comforts afforded by those familiar positions they've grown accustomed to playing over the years, White will be forced to improvise in dangerous and foreign positions! Doing so with success is not so easy, especially when such positions teem with tactics and require careful calculation to safely navigate. No doubt, White's composure will be distressed upon encountering the enigmatic 3...d5. Consequently, Black will have secured a psychological advantage right from move three, bringing us one step closer to checkmate before a mere semblance of the middlegame can even be detected! } 4. O-O dxe4 { White gambits e4. The themes are the same between this variation and the ones in chapter eight and chapter twelve. } 5. Ne5 Qd6 { We almost always play ...Qd6 in response to an early Ne5. } 6. Nc4 ( 6. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 { will most probably transpose to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Of course the key difference is that Bc4 is available to White. After } 7. Bc4 Nf6 $146 8. Nc3 $146 Ng4 $146 { Black induces light-squared weaknesses. This is still quite similar to the line in the previous link. } 9. g3 Ne5 $146 10. Be2 Bf5 { Black's position is more than acceptable. } ) ( 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Nc4 $146 Qg6 { will most probably transpose to this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 6... Qg6 7. Re1 { Anticipating ...Bh3. } ( 7. Nc3 $146 { transposes to this line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) ( 7. f4 $2 { would be interesting. Black can respond with } 7... Bf5 8. Ne5 $146 Qd6 9. Nc3 $146 Nf6 $146 10. Qe2 h5 { etc., resulting in typical complications. } ) 7... Bh3 8. Ne3 { This defense looks more human than what the engine is suggesting. Stockfish thinks that White would be better off trying } ( 8. Bxc6+ $2 bxc6 9. g3 $2 { , but I can't imagine that a human would find this desirable. First White gives up the key light-squared bishop and then weakens the kingside light squares beyond repair? This looks like something a patzer would play, yet somehow it is 'best'. } ) 8... Nh6 $1 { [%cal Bh6f5,Bh6g4,Yf7f5,Yf5f4]The optimal square to develop the knight to. Here it won't obstruct our f-pawn in case we would like to go for ...f5-f4. The knight also now has access to f5 to challenge the e3 knight. } 9. Nc3 { White needs to address Black's threat of ...Nf5. Something like } ( 9. d3 { would be much too slow. } 9... Nf5 $146 { The engine looking sequence of } 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. g3 { is pretty much forced at this stage. } 11... Rd8 { d3 clearly causes nothing but trouble for White. } ) 9... Nf5 10. Ncd5 { [%cal Bd5e3,Bd5c7,Bd5f4][%csl Re8,Ra8,Rg6,Rh3]The point of Nc3. White defends e3 and also threatens multiple forks. It's starting to look like Black might be under some serious pressure here. } 10... e5 $1 { Black should not allow Nf4. Nc7+ is permissible though! } 11. Nc7+ { If White instead steps the king to the side with } ( 11. Kh1 { Black should immediately capture on e3 and drop the bishop back: } 11... Nxe3 $146 12. Nxe3 $146 Bd7 { This is a bit better for Black. These positions have so many moving parts. Precision is very important. } ) 11... Kd7 { d7 is the natural square for the king, producing contact with c6 in case White immediately blunders with } 12. Nxa8 ( 12. Bxc6+ $2 Kxc6 13. Ncd5 $146 { It's worth mentioning that when White doesn't have their light-squared bishop they need to watch out for } 13... Nh4 $146 { If White had Bf1 this would be a different story, but here Black has a decisive advantage. } ) 12... Bxg2 $1 13. Qg4 { White's best defense here is be to get the queens off the board immediately. Fortunately, with the state of White's kingside even this may not be enough to survive. Instead, capturing g2 would be a sizable mistake! } ( 13. Nxg2 $2 $146 Nh4 $146 14. Bf1 Nf3+ $146 15. Kh1 Qh5 $19 { White must surrender the queen to keep the king alive. } ) 13... Bf3 { Careful. } ( 13... Qxg4 $2 { actually just loses. } 14. Nxg4 $146 Bf3 15. Nxe5+ $146 ) 14. Qxg6 hxg6 $17 { [%cal Bf5d4,Bf8d6,Bh8a8]After the dust settles, the evaluation weighs in favor of Black. Material is equal, or will be once we execute the cornered knight, but our pieces are much more active. Additionally, White's light squares are disastrous and they have some serious catching up to do to adequately situate their queenside pieces. Black can continue with ...Nd5 to target b2 and ...Bd6 to enable the rook to access a8. } * 

