.. Ng6 $146 { It's hard to see how White will defend h4. Even if White starts with d3 on move eight, enabling the bishop to land on g5, the evaluation doesn't budge: 8... Ne7 7.d3 a6 8.Bc4 h5 9.h4 Ng6 10.Bg5 Be7! White's kingside defenses are simply too scant for such an idea to make sense. 11.Qd2 f4! 12.Ne4 Bxg5 13.hxg5 b5! The pawn on g5 will fall once the knight has been eliminated, which we can do in due time. This is winning. } ) 10... h4 11. Nf1 Qd6 { [%cal Bb7b5,Bc8b7,Ye8c8,Ya8d8]Simply improving the queen. Black might queenside castle at some point soon. } 12. d3 b5 13. Bb3 Bb7 $17 { [%cal Bg7g5,Bg5g4,Be8c8,Ba8d8][%csl Rf1,Re1,Rd1,Rc1,Rb1,Ra1][%cal Ba2a4]This position looks fun! Black owns half of the board and most of White's pieces haven't yet advanced off of the back rank. Black is better. ...g5-g4 and maybe even ...O-O-O are on the agenda. A game might continue with } 14. a4 b4 15. Nbd2 $146 O-O-O 16. Nc4 $146 Qf6 17. c3 g5 { These positions are rich with dynamic potential. Black has an impressive initiative here. } * 

