1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Qe2 { Not very ambitious, but logical enough. Foreign positions are easier to navigate when simplified. White's best attempt to play for an advantage is with } ( 6. Be2 { , which has been analyzed in depth in chapter one (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 6... Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 8. d4 Nf6 $1 { Black has come prepared! White is invited to capture c5. Trying to hold on to the extra material is tempting, but risky! } 9. dxc5 e6 10. Be3 Nd5 $1 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Bd4 $6 f6 $1 { White walks right into Black's preparation. The bishop won't be on d4 for long! ...e5 is incoming. You can learn more about this position here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 13. O-O-O $5 e5 14. Be3 $6 { A typical error! White thinks they can hold onto the c-pawn after Be3, but Black will simply capture on e3 with the knight and then pick up c5! Moreover, after fxe3 ...Bxc5, White will be unable to defend e3. White's position is already horrendous! } 14... Nxe3 15. fxe3 Bxc5 { e3 is doomed. } 16. Nc3 Bxe3+ 17. Kb1 O-O { Black is just winning. He's up two pawns, has a passed pawn, and has extremely strong bishops. This is a great example of how White can go wrong early on, even in the more tame Qe2 variations. The rest is merely a matter of technique. } 18. Rhe1 Bb6 19. Nd5 Ba5 20. c3 Rad8 21. Ne7+ Kf7 22. Nxc6 bxc6 23. Kc2 Bb6 24. Rf1 Ke6 25. Rde1 Rd7 { Whoops! It's easy to err in blitz. Now } 26. Nh4 ( 26. Nxe5 $3 $146 { is winning for White! White missed the win in this game. } ) 26... g6 27. Nf3 Rfd8 28. g4 Bc7 29. g5 f5 { The pawns will now march unopposed. White fought on, but one might argue resignation would have been the more rational move. } 30. Nd4+ Kd5 31. Nb3 Bb6 32. Nd2 Ke6 33. Nc4 e4 34. a4 Rd3 35. a5 Bc7 36. Re2 R8d7 37. b4 Bd8 38. Kb3 Bxg5 39. a6 Bf6 40. Rc1 Rh3 41. Na5 Rdd3 42. Rec2 Kd6 43. Nc4+ Kc7 44. Na5 f4 45. Nc4 g5 46. Nd2 e3 47. Ne4 Be7 48. Kc4 Rd7 49. Rg1 h6 50. b5 f3 51. bxc6 Kxc6 52. Rf1 Rh4 53. Rxf3 Rxe4+ 54. Kb3 e2 0-1 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
