1. e4 c5 2. Be2 { This game will transpose in a few moves to the position after 6.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) in the mainline. } 2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qd7 6. Bb5 Qe6+ { And it has transposed. Enjoy the rest of the game. } 7. Qe2 Qxe2+ 8. Nxe2 Bd7 9. d4 e6 { Our move here is } ( 9... Nf6 $146 { enticing White to take c5. Although here Black starts with ...e6, the c5 pawn is gambited all the same. } ) 10. Be3 Nf6 11. dxc5 Nd5 12. Bd2 Bxc5 { White returns the pawn without resistance. While this is the safe route, now Black has a very comfortable position with slightly superior activity. } 13. a3 a6 14. Bd3 b5 { Black begins his minority attack. These middlegames are usually a battle over the queenside, so this makes sense. } 15. O-O O-O 16. b4 Be7 $5 { Black takes notice of the fact that b4 has permanently weakened the queenside's dark squares. The bishop is headed to f6 where it will exert great pressures on White's queenside. } 17. c4 bxc4 18. Bxc4 Rfc8 19. Rfc1 Bf6 $1 { Improving the bishop. I mentioned somewhere in this course that the better player will often be the one with the advantage. This sentiment especially rings true in the early queen-exchange middlegames where the positions are equal, but imbalanced. } 20. Rab1 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. Ng3 Bb5 23. Bb3 Bd3 $1 { Hitting the rook, but also preventing Ne4. It would be unwise to allow the knight to navigate to c5. Black is slowly outplaying White. } 24. Rxc8+ Rxc8 25. Re1 Bb2 26. a4 Bc2 27. Bxc2 $2 ( 27. Bxd5 { is the only way to maintain the balance. } 27... exd5 28. b5 axb5 29. axb5 f6 $13 ) 27... Rxc2 28. Rd1 f5 29. Nf1 Bc3 30. b5 axb5 31. axb5 Rb2 32. Bxc3 Nxc3 33. Rd7 $4 { The losing move! } ( 33. Rd8+ { would have at least kept White alive. } 33... Kf7 34. g3 Rxb5 $15 ) 33... Ne2+ $1 34. Kh1 Rb1 { The knight falls, but also the possibility of a mating net looms in the air. } 35. g4 Rxf1+ 36. Kg2 Rb1 37. gxf5 exf5 38. Rb7 Nd4 39. b6 h5 40. Kg3 g5 41. h4 { Checkmate is unstoppable. } 41... f4+ ( 41... Rg1+ 42. Kh2 Nf3+ $146 43. Kh3 g4# ) 42. Kg2 g4 43. Rd7 Nf3 44. Rd8+ Kg7 45. Rd7+ Kf6 46. Rd6+ Ke7 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1 

