1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Nxe2 Bd7 8. d3 { The slow approach. White already surrenders a slight advantage to Black. } 8... Nf6 9. h3 e6 10. Bf4 a6 { [%cal Gb7b5,Gc6a5,Ga5b3,Rb5a4,Ra4b3]One of the upshots of d3 is that Black can easily secure the bishop pair via a swift ...a6-b5 and ...Na5 once the bishop is pushed back to b3. } 11. Ba4 b5 12. Bb3 Na5 13. O-O Nxb3 { Chopping off the bishop. } 14. axb3 Nd5 15. Bd2 g6 $2 ( 15... Nb4 $146 { Black should waste no time targeting White's weakened queenside. } 16. Bxb4 cxb4 17. Ra5 Bc6 18. Rfa1 Bb7 19. c4 bxc3 20. bxc3 Rc8 $15 ) 16. Ne5 Bg7 17. Nxd7 { Black doesn't mind giving up the bishop pair. Almost all of his pawns are on light squares and exchanging on d7 helps Black activate his king. } 17... Kxd7 18. c3 Rhd8 19. Rfd1 a5 20. Nf4 Kc6 21. Kf1 b4 { White's queenside is full of pressure points. Black begins to tickle the dark squares. } 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Ra4 Rdb8 $1 { White is in a tricky spot now! Black intends ...bxc3 followed by an eventual capture on b3, with threats to secure a material advantage. } 24. c4 $4 { White tries to keep the queenside closed, forgetting about Black's sniper bishop posted on g7! } ( 24. Rb1 { with this White can stay in the game. Now if Black captures c3, White can recapture with the b-pawn and b3 will be protected by the rook. } ) 24... Bxb2 $1 { This was already game over. The rest was simply a matter of technique. } 25. Bf4 Re8 26. g4 Bc3 27. Bd2 Bd4 28. Bf4 dxc4 29. dxc4 Kb6 30. Rd2 Re4 31. Bg3 Rae8 32. Rda2 Re1+ 33. Kg2 Ra8 34. f4 Rb1 $19 { b3 is untenable. Once the pawn falls, White's queenside collapses. } 35. Bf2 Rxb3 36. Bxd4 cxd4 37. Rd2 Kc5 38. Rda2 Kxc4 39. Rxa5 Rxa5 40. Rxa5 Rb2+ 41. Kf3 b3 { 0-1 Black wins on time. } 0-1 

