1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Be2 $1 { White finds the best move! } 6... Nd4 $1 7. O-O Nf6 8. Re1 $1 { This is the critical test. This position is discussed in-depth in chapter one. } 8... Qb6 9. d3 { You can read more about 9.d3 here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 9... e6 10. b3 $5 { A sign that White intends to place their bishop on b2. Therefore, Black can develop the dark-squared bishop to d6 without worrying about facing episcopal opposition on the h2-b8 diagonal. } 10... Bd6 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Nxd4 { White finally gets impatient and whips off Black's knight. } 12... cxd4 13. Na4 Qc7 { [%cal Gc7h2][%csl Rh2]Lining up on h2. } 14. Bxd4 $1 ( 14. h3 $2 { Whether they like it or not, White is unable to save h2. } 14... b5 $19 { The knight gets trapped! } ) 14... Bxh2+ 15. Kh1 Bd6 { Black secures the bishop. } 16. Bf3 e5 $1 { Freeing the light-squared bishop. } 17. Bb2 Bf5 18. Nc3 a6 19. Ne4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Be6 { [%cal Gf7f5,Bf8f6,Bf6h6]Keeping pieces on the board. Black plans ...f5 and a rook lift. } 21. Qf3 Rae8 $6 { This was Black's one slip-up. More precise was } ( 21... f5 { Black should fearlessly march forward! b7 is untouchable due to the threat of ...e4. } 22. Bd5 Rae8 23. Bxe5 Bxe5 24. d4 Bxd4 25. Rxe6 Rxe6 26. Bxe6+ Kh8 $13 ) 22. Rac1 b5 23. d4 f5 $1 24. Bd5 $4 ( 24. dxe5 { was the only move. } 24... Bb4 25. Bc6 Bxe1 26. Bxe8 Rxe8 27. Rxe1 Qxc2 $15 ) 24... e4 $1 25. Bxe6+ Rxe6 26. Qh3 { White fails to take into account ...Rh6. Even so, White is lost wherever the queen goes. White's kingside lacks the defensive resources required to survive. For instance: } ( 26. Qc3 Qe7 27. Kg1 Rg6 { Black will stack up on the g-file. g2 is a critical weakness which should be exploited. } 28. Kf1 Qg5 29. Qh3 Rh6 $19 { White is out of luck. g2 is simply untenable, that is unless White surrenders the queen. } ) 26... Rh6 $19 { White resigns. Black played a great game. } 0-1 

