1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Bxc6+ $2 { Even mistakes as simple as this happen frequently. White often has no clue how to play these positions! } 5... Qxc6 6. d4 Nf6 7. Ne5 $4 { Whoops! This is premature. Please note that often White's g-pawn hangs when White plays Ne5 too early in the 4.exd5 lines! I want to accentuate this point because more often than not Black simply misses the free pawn. White basically hands you the game with this error; be prepared to meet it. } 7... Qxg2 $1 8. Qf3 ( 8. Rf1 { is not much better. } 8... Bh3 9. Nd2 $146 cxd4 $19 { White has permission to resign. } ) 8... Qxf3 9. Nxf3 Bg4 10. Ne5 cxd4 { Very clean performance from Black. } 11. Nxg4 Nxg4 12. h3 Ne5 13. f4 Nc6 $19 { White is down two pawns and has zero compensation in return. Black is already winning. These games can end rather quickly if caution is neglected! } 14. Rg1 e6 15. Rg5 f6 16. Rb5 O-O-O 17. Na3 a6 18. Rb6 e5 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. Nc4 Bc5 21. Rb3 h6 22. Bd2 Rhf8 23. O-O-O e4 24. Re1 b5 ( 24... e3 { is simpler, but everything is completely crushing here. } 25. Ba5 b5 26. Bxd8 bxc4 27. Rb6 Nxd8 $19 $146 ) 25. Na5 Nxa5 26. Bxa5 Rde8 27. Rg3 g5 28. h4 Bd6 29. Rg4 Bf4+ $1 { White's position is miserable. Black played an excellent game and converted quite cleanly. } 30. Kd1 Kd7 31. hxg5 hxg5 32. Rh1 Ke6 33. Rh6+ Kf5 34. Rg1 Re6 35. Bb4 Rfe8 36. Rh7 e3 37. Ke2 Ke4 38. Rf7 Rc8 39. c3 d3+ 40. Kd1 e2+ 41. Ke1 Ke3 42. Rf5 d2# { Checkmate with a pawn! Absolutely brutal. } 0-1 

