1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 { Always glad to see this move. Now Black quickly can snap up the bishop pair. } 6... a6 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. O-O Nf6 9. d4 e6 10. Re1 Be7 $5 { Waiting to see if White wants to play c4. I usually like to avoid capturing on d4 until they commit in this way, as they will be unable to bring their knight back into the game by recapturing on d4 due to the hanging c-pawn. } ( 10... cxd4 { is always possible too, if we're in search of an evaluation with flat 0s. Of course, the tale the engine tells is not so simple in actual fact. } 11. Nexd4 $146 Qc7 12. Nf5 $2 $146 { This is why we might consider avoiding the capture on d4. White gets quick, aggressive play. Black should be fine if we quickly castle to the queenside, but still. } 12... Bd7 { This would probably be tricky to navigate if we had not seen the position before. } 13. Bg5 O-O-O { ⩱ It might be worth taking note of this queenside castling idea if you plan to capture on d4 early in your games. } ) 11. c4 { Precisely what Black has been waiting for. } 11... cxd4 $1 { Notice that White cannot play Nexd4 due to ...Qxc4. } 12. Qxd4 b6 $5 { An interesting and tricky move introduced in chapter one. Black aims to quickly construct a battery on the long diagonal and will also swing the rook over to d8 to hit White's queen on her central post. } 13. Nc3 Bb7 14. b3 Rd8 { Boom. } 15. Qh4 ( 15. Nd5 $3 $146 { White must find this ridiculous move in order to avoid a significantly worse position. The threat is Nxe7 followed by Ba3. This wasn't played in the game, but Black needs to be precise in order to meet this. These positions are rich with dynamic potential! } 15... Qc5 16. Qxc5 Bxc5 17. Nxf6+ $146 gxf6 $15 ) 15... h5 $2 { Black already had a win, but missed it. } ( 15... Rd3 { would have sealed the deal. Black threatens both knights! For instance: } 16. Re3 Rxc3 $3 17. Rxc3 Ne4 $19 $146 ) 16. Qg3 $4 { [%cal Bg3g7][%csl Rg7]A strategic oversight. Black does not care about the g-pawn. Have it! } 16... h4 $1 { Simple chess. White once again is lost. } 17. Qh3 Rd3 $1 { Black finally spots this key idea. } 18. Ne5 $4 ( 18. Re3 { would have been a much more resilient defense. Still, Black's is not out of tactical resources. } 18... Qd7 { Threatening Rxc3. } 19. Rxd3 Qxd3 20. Bb2 { and White is lost. For instance: } 20... Qc2 21. Rb1 $2 Ne4 $19 $146 ) 18... Rxh3 19. Nxc6 Rxc3 { The game is already over, but Black finishes this one with a beautiful tactical sequence. } 20. Ne5 Rh5 21. f3 h3 22. g4 Bc5+ $1 23. Kf1 Rxe5 24. Rxe5 Rxf3+ 25. Ke2 Bd4 $19 { White resigned. A swift execution. White never stood a chance. } 0-1 

[Event "Blast the Rossolimo: Ferguson's Cannon Variation"]
[Site "4.exd5 & 5.Nc3 Model Game | LichessBlitz2550 vs. LichesBlitz2800 "]
