1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Ne2 { White elects to keep the queens on the board, but now Black now has time for ...a6! This is a typical theme in the exd5 variations: Have the queen stay in contact with the knight on c6 until we can induce a trade or repel the bishop with ...a6. More information about this line can be found here (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 6... a6 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. d4 Nf6 9. O-O e6 { This is all fairly typical so far. } 10. c4 { [%cal Bc6c4][%csl Rc4]White gains central space, but because the c-pawn is loose Black can capture on d4 and White will be unable to recapture with a knight. Moreover, recapturing with the queen allows ...Bc5 with tempo, and so this is not a particularly pressing continuation. } 10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc5 { In the theory in chapter one we recommend ...b6 instead. What follows in the next few moves is a great illustration as to why we should be cautious to immediately hit the queen with ...Bc5. } 12. Qh4 O-O 13. Bg5 { White's pieces fly in! Perhaps Black shouldn't have been so eager to castle. } 13... Be7 { [%cal Be2g3,Bg3h5,Bh4e7][%csl Rf6,Re7]Retreating to defend the knight doesn't look particularly compelling. More interesting would be } ( 13... Nd7 $146 { with the idea of ...f6 to repel the bishop and then to advance with the eventual ...e5. This would not only resolve the pressure White exerts on f6, but also creates an avenue of development for Black's light squared bishop. As you can tell, already it is not such an easy game for Black. White has heavy kingside pressure which can be tricky to navigate around. Additionally, Black has already used two moves on the dark-squared bishop and his position has hardly improved as a consequence. } ) 14. Ne5 { 14...f6! was the way to go. Now White has 35.c6! Black is in trouble. } 14... Qb6 $2 { Black slips up here. As we have learned from chapter one (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), under most conditions Black should meet Ne5 with ...Qc7. Here's another example from the same chapter (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) illustrating this theme. Even when Ne5 doesn't come with tempo on our queen, repositioning to c7 might be the best move. Here } ( 14... Qc7 { would clearly be much more effective. White doesn't have a good way of supporting the knight on e5, so they're best off just trading it with } 15. Ng4 $146 Nxg4 $146 16. Bxe7 Re8 17. Bg5 e5 $10 { This game is also a great example of how White can take the reigns quickly if Black doesn't respond properly to these key ideas, e.g. Ne5. Be sure to remember this ...Qc7 response to Ne5, as it applies in many different sort of positions. } ) 15. b3 $2 { Obsessively fixating over material is never a good idea. Instead, simply Nf4-Nh5 would have secured White a significant advantage. Now Black has time for ...h6. } 15... h6 16. Be3 Qc7 { Black finally finds the right idea. } 17. Nf3 Nd5 $1 18. Qe4 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 b5 $5 { An interesting idea from Black. More sensible to me is ...Bc5 and ...Bd7-Bc6 to keep the queenside locked down and put the bishops on the prime diagonals. } 20. Rfc1 Qa7 21. c5 b4 22. Ne5 Bf6 23. Nd4 Qc7 24. f4 Rd8 25. Ndc6 Rd5 26. Nxb4 Rxe5 $1 { [%cal Be5h2,Be5a1][%csl Rh2,Ra1,Rc1][%cal Bf4c1]Black temporarily sacrifices the exchange! } 27. fxe5 Bxe5 28. Rab1 Bxh2+ 29. Kh1 Bf4 30. Qe4 $1 { White finds the correct idea. Now best for Black is to take c1. After } 30... Rb8 $2 { Both players are getting pressed for time. Mistakes start to become ubiquitous. } ( 30... Bxc1 31. Qxa8 Qxc5 32. Nd3 $146 Qh5+ { Black has a draw. There are ways to attempt to play for a win, but they look risky. In those lines White has a passed pawn and is up an exchange. } ) 31. Nd3 $2 Bxc1 32. Rxc1 Bb7 33. Qe5 Qxe5 34. Nxe5 Rc8 $2 35. c6 Ba8 { [%csl Gf7,Gg7,Gh6,Ge6]White is completely winning here, but somehow manages to screw it up. Black's kingside pawns save the game! } 36. c7 Kf8 37. Nd7+ Ke7 38. Nb6 Bb7 39. Nxc8+ Bxc8 40. b4 Kd7 41. a4 e5 42. b5 axb5 43. axb5 f5 44. b6 e4 45. Rd1+ Kc6 46. Rd8 Kb7 47. Kg1 g5 48. Kf2 f4 49. g3 h5 { White needed give up hope of promoting on the queenside and use the rook to go after Black's kingside pawns. Allowing the rook to sit idle while Black steamrolls White on the kingside enabled Black to secure the draw. } 50. gxf4 gxf4 51. Rf8 h4 52. Rxf4 e3+ 53. Kxe3 Kxb6 54. Rxh4 Kxc7 55. Rc4+ Kd8 56. Rxc8+ Kxc8 1/2-1/2 

