1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. O-O Bg4 6. Nc3 Bxf3 7. Nxd5 Bxd1 8. Nc7+ Kd7 9. Nxa8 { White is playing a dangerous game. Unless White knows to meet } 9... Bh5 ( 9... Bh5 { with } 10. a4 { this will probably not end well for them. } ) 10. d3 $4 e6 11. Bf4 Bd6 { Black is already winning! This line is covered in chapter two (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 12. Bxd6 Kxd6 { White can do nothing to save the knight. Black will have two minor pieces for the rook. This is game over. } 13. Bxc6 Kxc6 14. b4 { Trying to spice up the position, but White just has no counterplay at all here. } 14... cxb4 15. Rfb1 Ne7 16. Nb6 axb6 17. Rxb4 Nd5 18. Rc4+ Kd6 19. a4 Ra8 20. Rb1 f5 21. h3 Be8 22. Rh4 h6 23. c4 Nc3 24. Rxb6+ Bc6 25. Rb3 Nxa4 26. Ra3 Ra6 27. d4 Nb2 28. Rxa6 bxa6 29. c5+ Kd5 30. g4 a5 31. gxf5 exf5 { A textbook victory from Black. It's quite easy for White to misstep after Nc7+! } 0-1 

