1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. O-O Bg4 6. Nc3 Bxf3 7. Nxd5 Bxd1 8. Nc7+ { Another instance of the risky Nc7+. As it so happens this is the most common response to ...Bxd1, yet White almost always fails to identify the correct continuation. } 8... Kd7 9. Nxa8 Bh5 10. d4 { White, as expected, exerts some effort to rescue the cornered steed. } 10... cxd4 11. Bf4 Nf6 12. Nc7 a6 $1 13. Ba4 e6 { Black has succeeded in ensuring that the knight won't escape. } 14. f3 $2 { The idea to block off Black's bishop is actually not so bad in these variations, but it must be done at the appropriate time. White has more pressing issues to deal at present, hence it is inaccurate here. } ( 14. Rfe1 { This is the move we discuss in the theory section, and in response we play } 14... Bc5 { rather than ...Bd6 to avoid pinning ourselves if White takes on c6 and then sacrifices the knight on e6 after our king recaptures on c6. Take note of the fact that if White doesn't spot 14.Re1, we can probably just default to the intuitive 14...Bd6 instead. } ) 14... Bd6 $1 { Black cashes in. } 15. Bxd6 Kxd6 16. Nxa6 { Trying to secure as much material for the piece as possible. Nonetheless, Black's advantage is already decisive. } 16... bxa6 17. Rad1 e5 18. c3 Rd8 19. cxd4 Nxd4 20. Rd2 Nd5 { Black's minor pieces are monstrously powerful. The knights exert so much pressure from their strong position in the center! White's position looks pretty hopeless. } 21. f4 f6 22. fxe5+ fxe5 23. Rc1 Ne2+ $1 { It was only a matter of time before White slipped up yet again. } 24. Rxe2 Bxe2 { Black is up a piece. The rest is merely a matter of technique. } 25. Rc6+ Ke7 26. Bb3 Bb5 27. Rc5 Ke6 28. a4 Be8 29. Kf2 e4 30. Ra5 Rd6 31. Bxd5+ Rxd5 32. Rxa6+ Ke5 33. Ra7 Rd2+ 34. Kg3 Rxb2 35. Rxg7 Bxa4 36. Rxh7 e3 37. Re7+ Kd4 38. h4 Bc6 39. h5 Rxg2+ 40. Kh3 Rg1 41. Re6 Bd5 42. Re7 Kd3 { 0-1 White resigns. White got outplayed at every turn. Well played by Black. } 0-1 

