1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. O-O Bg4 6. Be2 { White retreats the bishop. Surprising as it is, this is played quite often. } 6... e6 7. h3 Bh5 8. Nc3 Qd7 { This game has been following the theory in chapter two. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } 9. g4 $6 { Overextending here is not wise. } 9... Bg6 10. Re1 Bd6 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nb5 h5 $2 { Apparently, ...h5 is a mistake here. } ( 12... O-O-O { is the engine's choice, which is sensible enough. } 13. Nbxd4 $146 h5 14. g5 Nge7 $146 15. Nb5 $146 Bb8 16. Qxd7+ Rxd7 17. c3 Bf5 18. Bf1 $17 { Black has a lead. } ) 13. g5 $4 e5 $5 { [%cal Gd7h3,Ge5d4,Gf7f6,Ge8c8,Ga8d8]Black protects d4 and open lines up for the queen. ...f6 is an idea here, as is ...O-O-O. } 14. Nxd6+ Qxd6 15. Bd3 $2 { Opening up the e-file. While this looks somewhat natural, it is a serious mistake. Turns out that White's only move to maintain the balance is } ( 15. b4 { with the idea to get active on the queenside. } 15... Qxb4 16. Bd2 Qd6 17. Bb5 e4 $17 { White is still much worse, however. } ) 15... Nge7 16. a3 O-O-O 17. Qe2 f6 { [%csl Gg7,Gf6,Ge5,Gd4,Rg5,Rh3,Rf2]Black's pawns are superb. White's kingside is a mess. White's opening play has been an unmitigated disaster! } 18. Bd2 Rhe8 19. Rad1 Bxd3 20. cxd3 Nd5 21. Rc1 Kb8 22. Kh1 Nf4 $4 { Time pressure took a toll. Instead, after } ( 22... Qd7 { Black is just completely winning. The center is rock solid and White's kingside weaknesses are finally under seige. } 23. Kh2 f5 { ...e4 is the threat. } 24. Rxc6 Qxc6 $19 ) 23. Bxf4 exf4 24. Qxe8 $1 { White sacrifices the queen! This is the only way to survive. } 24... Rxe8 25. Rxe8+ Kc7 26. Kh2 $6 { Suddenly White is lost again! They had to take on f6. } 26... fxg5 27. Nxg5 $2 Qg6 { [%cal Gg6g5,Gg6e8,Gg6d3]White's scattered pieces give Black an easy means of converting. The clock is running out, so it will be easy to slip up and drop more material. } 28. Re5 Kb8 29. Rd5 Qxd3 30. Ne6 $4 Qd2 31. Rf1 f3 $6 ( 31... Qe2 { Would pick up a piece. } ) 32. Kg3 $2 Qe2 33. Rxd4 { [%cal Ge2f1,Ge2e6,Bc6d4][%csl Rd4,Re6,Rf1]Seeing that material was about to drop, White resigned. With the exception of the ...Nf4 slip up earlier, Black had a stellar game. } 0-1 

