1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. O-O Bg4 6. Nc3 Bxf3 7. Nxd5 Bxd1 8. Rxd1 { White finds the safe continuation. } 8... Rc8 $1 9. d4 { The difference on the clock in this game is already remarkable. This was a three minute blitz game with no increment. White's clock: 1:58 \- Black's clock: 2:54 This is a great example of why this opening is well suited for blitz! White so often burns up their time early in the game to safely navigate into the middlegame. } 9... e6 10. Nf4 cxd4 11. Rxd4 a6 12. Bxc6+ Rxc6 { Once again, I want to emphasize the time difference. White's clock: 1:28 \- Black's clock: 2:46 White has used a little more than half of their total time to secure an equal middlegame. Quite the investment. } 13. Nd3 $2 Nf6 { c2 was hanging! Black should simply capture, but development is fine too. } 14. Be3 Be7 15. Ne5 Rxc2 $1 { The pawn finally falls. White has no compensation for sacrificing the material and is nearly out of time. It is clear that Black's choice of opening has successfully thrown White off guard. } 16. b3 O-O 17. a4 h6 { Black can just play safe moves which put the ball back in White's court. They need to come up with a plan, but don't have the time to do it. } 18. h3 Rfc8 19. Rad1 R8c3 20. b4 Nd5 $1 21. Rxd5 exd5 22. Rxd5 Bxb4 23. Rd8+ Kh7 24. Nxf7 Rc8 25. Rd7 R2c7 26. Rxc7 Rxc7 27. Ne5 Bd6 28. Nd3 Rc3 { Black wins on time. White ran out of time, but Black was completely winning anyways. Clearly even masters run into trouble against 3...d5! } 0-1 

