1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 f6 6. c4 e5 7. Nc3 Be6 { This is an error. As specified in chapter four (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), I recommend here that Black close the center down for now with } ( 7... d4 { The reasoning is that with c4 \+ Nc3 White has serious pressure on d5. We would prefer it if they didn't complicate matters in the center before we can generate an attack on the kingside, so closing the center makes sense. Consult the linked variation for more information. } ) 8. b3 { A missed opportunity. White had } ( 8. exd5 cxd5 9. cxd5 Bxd5 10. Qa4+ Kf7 11. Be3 { , which would result in a worse position for Black. The c-pawn is a weakness and White is ahead in development. } ) 8... Ne7 9. O-O Ng6 10. Na4 { White intends on targeting c5. Black should ignore White's avaricious endeavors and focus on generating a kingside attack. } 10... Bd6 11. Be3 Qe7 { Not a bad move by any means but ...d4 would be much better, releasing the pressure on d5 and forcing the bishop back. } 12. Qe1 O-O 13. Qa5 d4 14. Bc1 f5 { Black's onslaught on the kingside begins! } 15. Ng5 Bd7 { Black's initiative is already monstrous! White's pieces on the queenside are unable to substantively contribute to a defense. } 16. Re1 $4 f4 $1 17. Nf3 Bg4 18. Nd2 $2 f3 { White's position is hopeless. This is the sort of attack Black can get when White foolishly fixates on the weak c5 pawn. } 19. g3 Nf4 $3 { [%cal Be7g5,Bg5h5,Bh5h2,Yf4h3,Yh3f2,Rg1f2][%csl Rf2]A brilliant idea! Black threatens to invade with ...Nh3+, swing the queen over to h5, and then sacrifice on f2! } 20. gxf4 { This just makes it easy for Black. } 20... Qh4 21. Kh1 Qxf2 22. Rg1 Bh3 { With mate being ineluctable, White resigned. What an incredible finish! } 0-1 

