1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 f6 6. h3 { White probably was interested in preventing ...Bg4, but that wasn't even Black's idea. White came to regret this waste of a tempo. } 6... e5 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. b3 O-O 10. Na4 { White intends on going after c5! } 10... Ng6 11. Ba3 { This position is very similar to this position from chapter four (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). The difference here being that White has wasted time playing h3. Needless to say, this is just a much worse version of that line for White. Black's typical kingside attack will effectively start one tempo up. } 11... f5 $1 { Thematic! Black neglects to attend to White's irrelevant queenside activities. } 12. Bxc5 Nf4 $1 13. Re1 fxe4 14. dxe4 d4 { Black missed a tactic here. } ( 14... Bxh3 15. gxh3 Bxc5 16. Nxc5 $146 Qd6 $19 { The knight will drop if White intends on preserving their king's safety! } ) 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. c3 c5 { Black need not worry about the center. Instead, } ( 16... Qg6 $3 { would be crushing! } ) 17. cxd4 cxd4 18. Nb2 Qg6 19. Nh4 Qg5 20. g3 Nxh3+ $19 { White capitalized on the opportunity to resign. Another textbook victory. } 0-1 

