1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. d3 f6 6. e5 { A rare sighting of the critical continuation! Few people have the strategic acumen to identify e5 as the most critical move. } 6... g5 $5 7. exf6 $2 { Dazed and confused by the threat of ...g4, White already fell victim to the pressure! ...exf6 is a serious mistake. } 7... exf6 8. O-O { White probably assumed they could drum up counterplay on the open e-file and target Black's king. Unfortunately for White, this plan just doesn't work. Black's king will head to f7 and will not be able to be targeted so easily. } 8... Ne7 9. Re1 Kf7 10. Nc3 { Up until this point the game has followed the theory found in chapter four (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Nc3 is not a particularly concerning move and doesn't modify the dynamic of the position enough to warrant altering Black's default plan to play ...Ng6 followed by ...g4. } 10... Ng6 11. b3 g4 12. Nd2 h5 $1 { Harry is marches on! White can do nothing to stop his trek to h3! } 13. Bb2 h4 14. f3 { An interesting attempt! White tries to bait Black into trading on f3. The kingside storm would surely subside if Black were to exchange, but ...g3 instead will be met with h3 closing down the position. White probably thought this was a clever way to stop Black's belligerent rush! } 14... g3 { [%cal Bg6f4,Bc8h3,Rh2h3][%csl Rh3]Black doesn't buy that White's king will be safe after White closes down the kingside with h3! The idea evidently is to sacrifice at the right moment. } 15. h3 Nf4 16. Ne2 Nxh3+ { Apparently } ( 16... Nxg2 $3 $146 { works too! } 17. Kxg2 Bxh3+ 18. Kxh3 Qd7+ 19. Kg2 Bd6 { This would be crushing! } ) 17. gxh3 Bxh3 18. Nf4 Bf5 ( 18... Qd7 { would have been a bit more precise. Black could then continue with ...Bd6. White's defense would be entirely suppressed. } ) 19. Qe2 { Apparently White had chances of coming back if instead they found: } ( 19. Ne4 $2 $146 { Black should not take the bait. If } 19... dxe4 $2 20. fxe4 Bd6 21. exf5 Bxf4 22. Qg4 { Suddenly White is back in the game. Instead, 19. Ne4 19...Rh6! preserves Black's advantage. } ) 19... Bd6 20. Qe3 $4 d4 { This is just game over. } 21. Qe2 Bxf4 22. Kh1 h3 23. Rg1 g2+ 24. Rxg2 hxg2+ 25. Kxg2 Qg8+ 26. Kf1 Rh1+ 27. Kf2 Qg3# { A textbook victory from Black! } 0-1 

