1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. e5 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 8. d3 h5 { [%cal Bg8e7,Be7f5,Bg7g5,Bg5g4]This position is discussed in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). This game is a great example of what can happen if White carelessly allows Black to execute the plan outlined there. } 9. O-O Ne7 10. Bf4 { This move is understandable. White want's to protect the e5 pawn. However, given that Black is playing for ...g5-g4 this just gives Black everything he could ask for. } 10... Nf5 11. c3 g5 $1 12. Bc1 Be7 { This is a bit slow. Black should instead continue with the aggressive } ( 12... g4 13. hxg4 Nh4 $146 { An important intermezzo. The idea is to free the f-pawn. } 14. Qf4 hxg4 15. Qxg4 Kd7 16. g3 f5 17. Qd1 f4 $3 { Stopping White from playing f4 themselves. There's a lot of nuance to these positions. } 18. Bxf4 Be7 19. Nd2 $146 Qg8 20. Re1 Rf8 { Black would have been winning if they found this! Generally, it's better to break with ...g4 sooner than later. } ) 13. Qe2 g4 14. Kh2 gxh3 { This was a bit premature. Black should start with } ( 14... Kd7 { to get the queen and rook over to the g-file before releasing the tension. } ) 15. gxh3 Kd7 16. Na3 Bg5 17. Bd2 Rb8 18. b3 Bxd2 19. Qxd2 Qh4 20. Rg1 Rbg8 21. Nc2 Nh6 { [%cal Bh6g4]A clever idea! Black intends ...Ng4+. White's only defense here is Rg3. } 22. f3 $4 { [%csl Rg3,Re3,Rf2]This is no good. White has permanently weakened the dark squares. } 22... Nf5 $1 23. Qe1 Qf4+ 24. Kh1 h4 25. Rg4 Qxf3+ 26. Kh2 Rxg4 27. hxg4 Qxg4 28. Ne3 Qf4+ 29. Kh3 Qxe3+ 0-1 

