1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5. e5 Bg4 6. h3 { This game is a great example of the sort of attack Black can expect if White carelessly walks into this variation (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 8. O-O h5 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4]As is typical, Black exchanged on f3 so that the ...g5-g4 push will arrive with extreme force. The objective of these positions is to tear open White's kingside and execute the king along the h and g-files. } 9. c3 { White aims for a quick d4. } 9... g5 { Wasting no time. } 10. d4 g4 $1 { The point! The engine thinks that White's best attempt is to take on g4, eventually opening the h-file for Black's rook. White is in a tough spot already and Black's play comes entirely naturally. } 11. Qg3 $2 Ne7 12. hxg4 hxg4 13. Qxg4 Nf5 14. Bg5 $4 Qb8 $2 ( 14... Be7 { would have ended the game on the spot due to } 15. Bf4 Kd7 $3 { with ...Rh5 and ...Qh8 coming. Resignation would be prompted. } ) 15. b3 ( 15. Be7 { Would bode even worse. 15...Qxe7 16.Nd2 O-O-O The other rook is coming to g8. White can resign. } ) 15... Be7 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. Qg5+ Kd7 18. Qf6 Qg8 { Boom. White is getting absolutely crushed. ...Rh6 and ...Qh7 are both threats. This is game over. } 19. g4 $4 { White offers a resignation in the form of a free checkmate. Good game! } 19... Qxg4# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } 0-1 

