1. e4 d5 { The Scandinavian actually can transpose if White continues with a specific line. } 2. e5 c5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bb5 Bg4 { This position is discussed in more detail in chapter nine (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Chapter nine covers the continuations in which White elects not to capture c6. Those lines which include the c6 exchange are analyzed in chapter five (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 5. h3 Bxf3 { [%cal Be7e6,Bh7h5,Bg7g5,Bg5g4]I am a proponent of exchanging on f3 upon being prompted by h3. After the queen recaptures Black can try for an eventual ...h5 \+ ...g5-g4 after White has castled. This game takes a different but perfectly viable approach to the middlegame. } 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Qxf3 e6 8. O-O Ne7 9. c4 { [%csl Rd4,Rd3]This attempt to challenge Black's center is not particularly effective. Taking on d5 would just repair Black's structure and its's not clear that the pawn serves any other purpose on c4 other than to exchange. } 9... Qc7 10. Re1 Ng6 { [%cal Bc7e5][%csl Re5][%cal Bg6e5]Black sensibly targets e5. One bonus of taking on f3 after White hits the bishop with h3 is that White's queen blocks the f-pawn from advancing to protect e5, so this plan makes a lot of sense. } 11. Qg3 h5 $1 { [%cal Bh5h4,Bh8h5,Bh5e5][%csl Re5]A cute idea. Black will hit the queen with ...h4 next and lift the rook to h5 to build even more pressure on e5. } 12. b3 h4 13. Qe3 Rh5 14. Bb2 $2 { This just runs into ...d4. More resilient would have been } ( 14. f4 { , but then f4 becomes weak and Black can simply refocus the attack. } 14... Rf5 15. Rf1 Be7 { Black now has ...Nxf4 followed by ...Bg5. This is still much better for Black, but White isn't getting demolished like he is after Bb2. } ) 14... d4 $1 15. Qe2 Rxe5 16. Qf1 Rxe1 17. Qxe1 Qf4 18. Na3 Bd6 { There is no defense! White has permission to resign. } 19. Kf1 Qh2 20. Qe4 Kd7 $1 21. Re1 Nf4 { White finally suffered enough and succumbed to the temptation to resign. This game is a great example of the sort of flexibility Black has in the 5.e5 lines (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Targeting e5 is a perfectly reasonable approach, as is storming the kingside with ...h5 \+ ....g5-g4. } 0-1 

