1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d5 4. Nc3 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ gxf6 7. O-O Qb6 { White no longer has the opportunity to double Black's pawns. This position is analyzed in depth in chapter seven (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 8. Qe2 $2 { This is already not so great for White. The queen is not particularly well placed on e2. } 8... Rg8 9. d4 cxd4 10. Bxc6+ $2 { White clearly demonstrates that they don't understand how to approach the position. White's kingside light squares will be under siege soon! Exchanging on c6 not only relieves White of their light squared defender, but also accelerates Black's rampage. } 10... Qxc6 11. g3 { White is just falling off the board. I bet they didn't expect to play this sort of position when they played Bb5! } 11... Bg4 12. Kg2 e5 13. Re1 O-O-O { Simpler is } ( 13... Bb4 14. c3 dxc3 { , but castling works too. } ) 14. h3 Bh5 ( 14... Bf5 { would have been stronger. White wouldn't have Qe4 in that case. } ) 15. Qe4 Qxe4 { Black's advantage is already decisive, with queens or without. } 16. Rxe4 Bg6 17. Re1 Bxc2 18. Bd2 Kb8 19. Rac1 d3 20. Re4 Be7 21. Rh4 Rd5 22. Ne1 Ba4 $4 { [%cal Rh4a4]Whoops! The bishop is hanging! Instead, } ( 22... Rb5 23. b3 Rc8 24. Nxc2 $146 dxc2 25. Rxh7 Ba3 { would have been a clean way to end the game. } ) 23. Rxh7 { White misses the free piece! } 23... Bc6 24. Kh2 Rf8 25. Rc3 e4 26. Be3 f5 27. Bd2 { White is just shuffling the bishop around. They've given up hope already, but don't want to resign. } 27... Bf6 28. Ra3 Bxb2 29. Rb3 Bd4 30. Ng2 Bxf2 { Now that the f pawn has been eliminated Black can pursue a promotion. White has no hope of coming back now. } 31. Nf4 Rc5 32. Kg2 Bd4 33. Kf1 e3 34. Bxe3 Bxe3 35. Rb1 d2 36. Rd1 Rc1 37. Ke2 Bf3+ 38. Kxf3 Rxd1 39. Nd5 Bb6 40. Nc3 Ra1 41. Ke2 Rd8 42. Nd1 Rxa2 43. Rxf7 Rc8 44. Rxf5 Ba5 45. Rd5 Rc1 46. Ne3 d1=Q# { Black got a crushing position out of the opening and finished White with style! } 0-1 

